<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugBusts     05-18 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Busts,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocaine Seized From Airplane and Speed Boat, Pot From Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities seized more than two tons of cocaine in the Florida
Keys, cut off a drug supply line to a New York resort and charged
four people with possession of 1{ tons of marijuana in Alabama in
three separate actions Wednesday.
   Customs agents said a patrol vessel chased down a high-speed
boat running without lights in the Florida Keys just before dawn
Wednesday, and found more than two tons of cocaine aboard. Three
Florida men and a Colombian national were arrested and their
38-foot boat confiscated, said Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   Authorities had not determined the value or exact weight of the
cocaine, which they said was in 50 bales weighing from up to 75
pounds each.
   Federal authorities in Mobile, Ala., charged four people,
including a West German couple, with possession of 1{ tons of
marijuana and 236 pounds of a substance believed to be hashish oil,
worth a combined street value of more than $20 million.
   A supply line that would have brought nearly eight tons of
cocaine into the Hamptons on New York's Long Island for the resort
season was cut off by undercover agents who confiscated the first
shipment, faked a delivery and made nine arrests, officials said
Wednesday in Farmingdale, N.Y.
   The 1,200-pound shipment _ and the plane it was coming in on _
were seized in Miami because the plane, which was under
surveillance on its journey, had engine trouble and put down there
on its way from Colombia to Suffolk County Airport in Westhampton
Beach, N.Y.
   The 1,200 pounds of cocaine, divided into small packets, could
have been sold for $80 million, state police Capt. Walter Heesch
estimated.
   Special Customs Agent Arthur Stiffel said the import ring had
planned to bring in 1,000 pounds of cocaine every 48 hours for 30
days to sell in the Hamptons, the group of villages that have
become a swanky New York summer retreat.
   ``We got them on their first run,'' said Stiffel. ``They were
just gearing up so they had enough supplies during the peak sale
period of the summer.''
   Eight men, including two Columbian nationals, were charged with
conspiracy to import and distribute cocaine.
   In the pre-dawn raid Wednesday on a secluded Alabama waterfront
home, a motorcycle, a 1988 Mercedes car, a 1986 Ford pickup,
$28,000 in cash, two sailboats, a motorboat and two life rafts,
were confiscated, U.S. Customs agent Gary Wright said.
   Wright said the drugs were smuggled into the Gulf Coast from a
foreign distribution point apparently aboard a 35-foot sailboat.
</TEXT>
