<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonRiots-Atlanta     05-18 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Riots-Atlanta,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Repairs Continue at Prison Scarred by Riot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Prison Riots-Aftermath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These days, a visitor can drive directly through
wide-open iron gates and park within 20 yards of the U.S.
Penitentiary's front steps.
   Those are the same steps descended by 89 hostages when they
poured out of the prison last Dec. 4, ending an 11-day uprising by
more than 1,100 Cuban inmates.
   The penitentiary then was less a prison than a badly damaged
fortress under siege. The front steps, patrolled constantly by
armed federal officers, led to a building only partly controlled by
authorities. The rest was in the hands of Cuban detainees, who
rioted at word of a deportation agreement with Fidel Castro.
   When it was all over, the prison was emptied of all inmates for
the first time since it opened in 1902 and officials began cleaning
up the damage. Officials estimated the damage here and in Oakdale,
La., where Cuban inmates staged a similar uprising, at $64 million.
   Now, 600 inmates, all Americans, are housed at the prison,
compared with about 200 Americans and 1,400 Cuban inmates at the
time of the takeover. In two years, the number is to reach 800 to
850. So far, there are no plans to bring Cuban detainees to
Atlanta, said Mike Caltabiano, executive assistant to Warden Joseph
Petrovsky.
   The riot interrupted a $63 million, five-year renovation
project, but many of the areas damaged were to be razed in the
renovation anyway, Caltabiano said.
   The only real loss, he said, was the burned-out prison
industries building.
   A temporary industries unit has been set up in a former
gymnasium. There, inmates repairing mailbags and making mattresses
and meteorological parachutes earned $500,000 for the prison in
April, Caltabiano said.
   A 20-foot-high chain link fence is being erected to cut the
prison almost in half. Behind it, most of the construction will go
on. The first phase of the renovation project is to be completed
next year.
   Elsewhere, vandalism in the dining hall and chapel has been
repaired.
   ``It's been the positive attitude of the staff that's made it,
by putting this kind of thing behind them and saying, `OK, we're
going to see how we can rebuild Atlanta,''' Caltabiano said.
   The prison is ``Atlanta'' or ``USP (U.S. Penitentiary) Atlanta''
to its employees. It was known as the ``Big A'' to decades of
inmates, including the famous and the infamous.
   At the dawn of the 1920s, the ``Big A'' was home to Socialist
presidential candidate Eugene V. Debs, who was imprisoned for a
speech condemning war in World War I. It held Al Capone in the
1930s, Soviet spy Rudolph Able in the 1950s and Mafia informant Joe
Valachi in the 1960s.
   In the late 1970s, there were 16 slayings at the prison, many
described as professional ``hits'' related to drug sales. By 1978,
a report by the U.S. Bureau of Prisons suggested closing the
penitentiary because its old design and deteriorating structures
made security impossible.
   The prison was to have been closed by the fall of 1984.
   But the number of Cuban inmates, detained during the Mariel
boatlift because of their records in Cuba or imprisoned later for
offenses in the United States, mounted.
   Violence again was a problem. The Bureau of Prisons reported the
Atlanta pen had less than 10 percent of all federal prisoners, but
almost 20 percent of all assaults on inmates or guards.
   The Cubans frequently protested prison conditions but more often
complained that they were being detained at all. The final uprising
was triggered by word that deportations to Cuba would resume.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
