<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     05-18 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perry Mason Solves Nielsens for NBC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Perry Mason won another case and helped NBC win
the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings last week, part of the important May
sweeps period.
   NBC's average, prime-time rating for the week that ended Sunday
was 14.7 and its share was 26. ABC was second with a 12.8 and 22
share. CBS had an 11.4 average rating and 20 share. NBC's
season-to-date rating average is 15.8. ABC has 13.5 and CBS 13.3.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   Raymond Burr's latest stint as the ever-victorious defense
attorney topped the Nielsens. Not far behind were a Barbara Walters
special on ABC and ABC's miniseries ``The Bourne Identity''
starring Richard Chamberlain.
   May is one of four months when local stations' ratings are
measured for use in negotiating advertising rates, so the networks
put on a lot of special programming to draw viewers to affiliates.
   ``Perry Mason: The Case of the Lady in the Lake'' was the No.
1-rated prime-time network show of the week with a rating of 22.6
and a 35 share. NBC said it was the network's best Sunday movie
rating all season.
   In addition to ``Bourne'' and the usual series, ABC also made
the top 10 with the theatrical film ``Beverly Hills Cop,'' and NBC
added to the top 10 part two of its sci-fi miniseries ``Something
Is Out There.''
   CBS, shut out of the top 10, came in 11th with the season-ending
episode of ``Knots Landing.'' But part one of its big miniseries of
the week, ``Beryl Markham: A Shadow on the Sun,'' fared poorly
against ``Perry Mason'' and came in 43rd with a rating of 10.4.
   The top 10-rated shows were: ``Perry Mason'' NBC, ``The Cosby
Show'' NBC, ``Cheers'' NBC, ``Beverly Hills Cop'' ABC, ``Barbara
Walters Special'' ABC, ``Night Court'' NBC, ``Golden Girls'' NBC,
``Something Is Out There, Part 2'' NBC, ``The Bourne Identity, Part
2'' ABC and ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC.
   The lowest-rated prime-time shows of the week were: ``I Married
Dora,'' ``Tour of Duty,'' ``Uncommon Valor,'' ``West 57th,'' ``High
Mountain Rangers,'' ``48 Hours,'' ``Aaron's Way,'' ``Houston
Knights,'' ``Ohara'' and ``Supercarrier.''
   For the week that ended Friday, ABC's ``World News Tonight'' was
first in the ratings for the third week in a row. It had a 9.4
rating and a 20 share. The ``CBS Evening News'' was second with 9.1
and 20. ``NBC Nightly News'' continued to trail with an 8.0 and 17
share.
   ABC said that it had calculated an 11 percent share increase for
``World News'' this quarter compared to the period last year. CBS
was down 9 percent in share, and NBC down 18 percent, ABC said.
</TEXT>
