<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NBCSeason     05-18 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBC Season,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Leaves Lineup Largely in Place for Fall Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-place NBC is not making wholesale changes
in its prime-time lineup for the fall, but is adding eight new
shows, including a promising series set in a sophisticated New York
restaurant from the producers of the critically acclaimed ``St.
Elsewhere.''
   Besides ``St. Elsewhere,'' which the producers chose to end
after this season, NBC is eliminating eight series: ``The Facts of
Life,'' ``Crime Story,'' ``A Year in the Life,'' ``Our House,''
``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd,'' ``Beverly Hills Buntz,''
``The Bronx Zoo'' and ``Aaron's Way.''
   Replacement series ``Day by Day'' and ``In the Heat of the
Night'' made the cut. So did the 4-season-old ``Miami Vice,'' which
had been a question mark.
   ``Highway to Heaven'' and ``My Two Dads'' are not on the fall
schedule, but are still in production and will return as specials
or replacement series, according to NBC.
   NBC plans to start the season on Sept. 19 despite the strike by
the Writers Guild of America, which already has forced CBS to
announce it will start late. NBC opens with prime-time coverage of
the Summer Olympics, followed soon thereafter by the World Series.
ABC also is expected to announce it will delay the start of its
season. ABC and CBS are expected to announce their fall lineups
later this month.
   NBC is adding these new shows:
   _``Tattinger's,'' starring Stephen Collins as a popular New York
restaurant owner who moves in powerful circles. It co-stars Blythe
Danner, Mary Beth Hurt and Jerry Stiller.
   _``Something Is Out There,'' based on the the high-rated recent
sci-fi miniseries, starring Joe Cortese as a cop and Maryam D'Abo
as the extraterrestrial who helps him track down a killer from
outer space.
   _``Midnight Caller,'' starring Gary Cole as an ex-cop cult hero
with a late-night radio talk show.
   _``Unsolved Mysteries,'' which has been a series of specials
this season. Real-life crimes or mysteries are re-enacted.
   _``Baby Boom,'' based on the movie of the same name in which a
high-powered career woman suddenly finds herself saddled with an
infant. Kate Jackson stars.
   _``Dear John,'' starring Judd Hirsch as a married man suddenly
abandoned by his wife, based on the BBC series of the same name.
   _``Empty Nest,'' the semi-spinoff of ``Golden Girls,'' starring
Richard Mulligan as a recently widowed pediatrician living in the
``Girls''' neighborhood in Miami.
   _``The Magic World of Disney,'' a rotation series based on
Disney movie projects, including ``The Absent-Minded Professor,''
starring Harry Anderson, ``Davy Crockett,'' and an action-adventure
series to be announced.
   Here is the NBC prime-time lineup for next season:
   Monday: ``ALF,'' ``The Hogan Family'' (formerly ``Valerie's
Family''), ``NBC Monday Night at the Movies.''
   Tuesday: ``Matlock,'' ``In the Heat of the Night,'' ``Midnight
Caller.''
   Wednesday: ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' ``Night Court,'' ``Baby
Boom,'' ``Tattinger's.''
   Thursday: ``The Cosby Show,'' ``A Different World,'' ``Cheers,''
``Dear John,'' ``L.A. Law.''
   Friday: ``Sonny Spoon,'' ``Something Is Out There,'' ``Miami
Vice.''
   Saturday: ``227,'' ``Amen,'' ``Golden Girls,'' ``Empty Nest,''
``Hunter.''
   Sunday: ``The Magical World of Disney,'' ``Family Ties,'' ``Day
by Day,'' ``NBC Sunday Night at the Movies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
