<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Mozambique     05-18 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Mozambique,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mozambique President Meets Deng Xiaoping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping today told President
Joaquim Alberto Chissano of Mozambique that China went through a
20-year period of stagnation before leftist mistakes were corrected
in the late 1970s.
   Deng, 83, in opening remarks to Chissano, said China's troubles
began in 1957, the year Mao Tse-tung launched a repressive
anti-rightist movement and the Great Leap Forward, a disastrous
experiment in rapid industrialization.
   He said those mistakes led to the ultra-leftist 1966-76 Cultural
Revolution, when the nation was torn apart by purges and violent
battles between rival leftist groups.
   Deng, who was purged three times during those two decades, rose
to power in the late 1970s. He has introduced pragmatic political
policies and market-oriented economic reforms which have
dramatically improved the living conditions of most Chinese.
   Chissano arrived in China on Monday for a four-day state visit,
his first since assuming office in 1986.
</TEXT>
