<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Rasmussen; A separate moved for AMs on Duggan as a0644.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Duggan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Duggan, whose distinctive face, voice
and bearing brought characters to life on screen, stage and TV
since the close of World War II, died Sunday of cancer. He was 64.
   Duggan played on Broadway in ``Rose Tattoo'' and ``Paint Your
Wagon.'' He did live TV shows in New York City during the 1950s,
played Dwight Eisenhower in the 1979 miniseries ``Backstairs at the
White House,'' and portrayed Col. Deiner in ``Rich Man, Poor Man.''
He also played Gen. Ed Britt in the 1965-67 series ``Twelve O'Clock
High.''
   Duggan's movies include ``Three Brave Men,'' ``Merrill's
Marauders,'' ``Seven Days In May,'' ``In Like Flint,'' and ``Doctor
Detroit.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Louis Fields</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis Glenn Fields Jr., a retired U.S.
ambassador appointed by President Reagan in 1981 to the Conference
on Disarmament at the United Nations in Geneva, died Tuesday of
cancer at age 58.
   Fields joined the Virginia Bar Association and was named state
coordinator in 1965 for the re-election bid of the late Sen. A.
Willis Robertson. He served as a consultant in economic warfare to
the Vietnam bureau of the Agency for International Development from
1967 to 1969. From 1969 to 1981, Fields worked in the legal
adviser's office of the State Department.
   Following his appointment by Reagan, he served in the rank of
ambassador until his retirement in 1985.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joseph Tomlin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph J. Tomlin, the founder of ``Pop
Warner'' football for youths, died Monday. He was 85.
   Tomlin guided the Pop Warner program as it grew from a local
junior football league in Philadelphia in 1929 to a far-reaching
organization sponsoring ``midget football'' in 40 states, Mexico
and the United Kingdom with 200,000 participants annually.
   Tomlin and Philadelphia restaurateur Frank Palumbo held the
first ``Santa Claus Bowl'' in 1947 with the help of Palumbo's
friend, entertainer Frank Sinatra, to bring national attention to
the conference.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Telek</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Rep. William Telek, a Republican from
Johnstown, was beaten to death in an apparent robbery early
Tuesday. He was 64.
   Telek, a former college professor, high school teacher and
guidance counselor, had been in the House since 1979.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Martin Rasmussen</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUYALLUP, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Nielsen Rasmussen, an engineer and
machinist who built the ``Junkyard Telescope'' on display at the
Smithsonian Institution, died Saturday at age 92.
   Rasmussen, whose telescope was donated by his family to the
Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American History in
Washington, D.C., in 1982, built the telescope out of 30 automobile
flywheels purchased for 25 cents each. It had a maximum
magnificaton of 1,300 times.
   Rasmussen worked as a machinist at Globe Machine Manufacturing
Co. in Tacoma, was a 50-year member of the International
Association of Machinists and a 50-year charter member of the
Tacoma Astronomical Society.
</TEXT>
