<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ShipFire 4thLd-Writethru a0404 05-18 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ship Fire, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0404,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship Fire Kills 10 People, Injures 35</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with five grafs to UPDATE with 10th fatality. Pickup
7th graf pvs, ``The cause...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSAKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire swept through a Soviet passenger ship
in this western Japanese port early Wednesday, killing 10 people
and injuring 35, the fire bureau said. Many of those aboard were
Soviet students and workers.
   Ten bodies were recovered from the docked 4,870-ton Priamurye,
most from a still smoldering section of a passenger cabin, the last
about 10 hours after the blaze broke out, said Toshio Yabuno of the
Osaka City Fire Bureau.
   He said the victims' identities and nationalities were not known.
   White smoke billowed from the ship as fire squads pumped water
into the lower decks. Firefighters wearing oxygen masks plunged
through the smoke to rescue people trapped aboard the ship.
   Thirty-five people were injured in the pre-dawn blaze, most from
smoke inhalation, said Yabuno. He said 28 of the injured were taken
to hospitals and the seven others were treated at the port area for
minor burns or bruises.
   The cause of the fire was not known, said Yoshiaki Kataoka of
the Maritime Safety Agency's regional headquarters in Okobe. The
agency was informed of the blaze about 1:50 a.m. (12:50 p.m. EDT
Tuesday), he said.
   Kataoka said many of the passengers were Soviet students and
workers visiting Japan on a tour organized by the Communist Youth
League.
   The ship was carrying 295 passengers and 129 crew members when
it arrived Tuesday at Osaka, 255 miles west of Tokyo, Kataoka said.
   Firefighters temporarily stopped battling the blaze at one point
because water pumped into the lower decks had caused the ship to
list. The extra water was removed.
   Police cordoned off the area and ambulences sped to the dock.
   The Priamurye left Vladivostok on May 7 and made stops at Otaru,
on Japan's northern island of Hokkaido, and in Tokyo. On Thursday,
it was to have left for Hiroshima, the official said.
   Soviet consular officials took most passengers to a junior high
school gymnasium.
   The worst ship disaster in recent years involving a Soviet
cruise vessel occurred on Aug. 31, 1986, when the Admiral Nakhimov
sank in the Black Sea after colliding with the freighter Pyotr
Vasyev, with the loss of 398 lives.
   Both captains were sentenced to 15-year prison terms.
   On Feb. 16, 1986, the 20,000-ton Soviet cruise liner Mikhail
Lermonov slammed into rocks off New Zealand and sank. But although
the liner was carrying more than 700 passengers and crew, there was
only one fatality, a Soviet crew member.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Israel-ClusterBomb     05-18 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Cluster Bomb,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sanctions Possible Over Alleged Attempt To Acquire Bomb Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Israel are negotiating a
settlement after a two-year investigation into allegations Israel
tried to acquire U.S. technology illegally for cluster bombs, U.S.
officials say.
   ``We will not prosecute criminally,'' Justice Department
spokesman John Russell said Tuesday. ``We are in negotiations with
Israel,'' he said.
   Because the case is still open, Russell would not comment on why
the department has decided to forgo criminal prosecution. He also
refused to divulge the nature of the negotiations.
   But an official of the U.S. Customs Service, speaking on
condition he not be named, said this week there was a proposal to
issue administrative sanctions against Israel, possibly civil fines.
   An official at the Israeli Embassy did not return a telephone
call to discuss the case.
   The probe centered on allegations that Israel tried to obtain
from private American contractors the technology to produce cluster
bombs, which are canisters containing hundreds of smaller
high-explosive bomblets.
   The United States banned the export of cluster bombs to Israel
in 1982 after reports that Israel had used them in the invasion of
Lebanon, violating the stipulation that Israel use the bombs only
for self-defense.
   Specifically, investigators sought to determine if there were
any violations of the Arms Export Control Act, which stipulates
that certain military items can only be exported from the United
States with a license.
   U.S. officials said Israelis had approached Vector Corp. of
Marion, Iowa, with the proposal that the company's description of
technology be relabeled so it would not appear to be used in
producing explosive devices.
   Vector's high-speed machinery compresses and seals the hundreds
of little bombs in cluster bombs.
   Israeli officials denied any violations had occurred. They said
they developed their own ``minibombs'' placed in artillery shells,
and any American technology had been imported with valid licenses,
they said.
   In July 1986, subpoenas and search warrants were served at
Israel Military Industries in New York, whose 200 employees
negotiate military contracts with U.S. companies in spending $1.8
billion in military aid grants.
   The Justice Department withdrew the subpoenas after the Israeli
government said some of the officials were covered by diplomatic
immunity. In exchange, the Israelis agreed to cooperate with the
investigation.
   Subpoenas were also served on Vector Corp.; Bexco International
of Cedar Rapids, Iowa; and Assembly Machines Inc. of Erie, Pa.
Grand juries were impaneled in Erie and Cedar Rapids.
   Dan Schwartz, a lawyer for Vector, said he had no information
about the Justice Department's negotiations. ``We have received no
word for a fairly long period of time,'' he said.
   Officials at Assembly Machines, a manufacturing company, and
Bexco, an export-import firm, also said they had no information
about the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     05-18 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Opt For Healthier Diet, Almost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new Agriculture Department report says there
have been some dramatic changes in the mix of foods consumed by
Americans since 1970 but some inconsistencies, too.
   Of all the meat consumed in 1986, two-thirds was red meat,
mostly beef, pork and lamb, compared with three-fourths in the
early 1970s.
   ``Instead, we ate more poultry, fish, grains and cereal
products,'' the report said Tuesday. ``We also cut back on whole
milk, while consuming more low-fat milk and yogurt. Fresh fruit and
vegetable consumption rose as well.''
   But the report added: ``While there was a general shift toward
foods perceived as low in fat or calories, our cheese consumption
increased during the period. In addition, consumption rose for fats
and oils, frozen potatoes, and corn sweeteners and soft drinks.''
   And families ate fewer eggs and fresh potatoes and drank less
coffee during the 16-year period.
   Overall, the consumers responded to higher incomes, new food
production and marketing techniques, and changes in lifestyles.
   Consumption of red meat declined, but poultry more than took up
the slack. Total meat consumption, which includes poultry,
gradually crept higher.
   The report was prepared by a team in the department's Economic
Research Service and was included in the agency's quarterly
National Food Review.
   In the early '70s, the report said, Americans ate an average of
151 pounds of red meat annually per person, and about 49 pounds of
poultry. In 1986, red meat dropped to 140 pounds while poultry
averaged 72 pounds.
   ``Poultry's rise stemmed largely from retail prices that
remained well below those for red meats, primarily because of
savings passed on from the farm and processing levels,'' the report
said. ``As a result, poultry was used to a greater extent in frozen
entrees and convenience foods than red meats were.''
   But poultry's price advantage was not the only factor that
affected consumers. Cut-up birds and heavily advertised branded
items such as those of Holly Farms, Perdue, Louis Rich and Tysons
Foods gained popularity.
   Pan-ready or pre-cooked items, along with upscale raw products
such as boneless breast fillets, also attracted consumers.
Processors began offering chicken and turkey franks, turkey
breakfast sausages, and turkey ham and salami in an effort to cater
to consumer concerns about fat.
   ``Other food processors and retailers joined the move toward
value-added items,'' the report said. ``Dairy processors introduced
fresh and microwave pizzas, a variety of flavored and textured
yogurts, Mexican-flavored cheeses, fruit and onion-flavored cream
cheeses, upscale frozen dairy products, and ready-to-make quiche
mixtures.''
   Frozen vegetable processors developed new combinations, sauce
selections and single-serving products in microwave containers. And
supermarkets now have a wider variety of fresh produce than they
had in the '70s, and have become more convenenience oriented with
salad bars and soup kettles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng has
reported outside earnings of at least $119,500 last year, virtually
unchanged since he joined the Reagan Cabinet in March 1986.
   The outside earnings were in addition to his annual Cabinet
salary, which was raised to $99,500 in February 1987.
   In fact, Lyng's Cabinet salary has increased at a faster clip
than his outside income indicated by the disclosure report, which
doesn't reveal specific financial figures.
   Lyng's salary when he took over USDA 26 months ago was $86,200 a
year. In January 1987, he and other federal workers got a 3 percent
cost-of-living increase, which boosted his salary to about $88,800
a year.
   A month later, in February 1987, Cabinet salaries were boosted
to their present level, $99,500 a year.
   According to the statement released on Tuesday, Lyng owns assets
worth at least $775,000, primarily in real estate investments and a
family seed business in Modesto, Calif. His 1987 outside income was
in the range of $119,500 to $260,000.
   Lyng's liabilities, secured by mortgages and home equity, are at
least $300,000, according to the report.
   Income, assets and liabilities are reported only in broad ranges
by the financial disclosure reports.
   When Lyng underwent Senate confirmation proceedings in March
1986, he reported 1985 assets of at least $775,000 and an income in
the range of $205,000 to $344,000. The 1985 income included $82,500
salary from his private consulting firm, which he sold after being
chosen for the USDA post.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers have indicated they will plant fewer
total acres of feed grains this spring, but an Agriculture
Department report says that total 1988 production may increase
because of greater corn acreage in high-yielding states.
   ``Production of feed grains is forecast at 219 million metric
tons, 2 percent above 1987's 215 million,'' the department's
Economic Research Service said Tuesday.
   Besides corn, other feed grains include sorghum, oats and
barley. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4
bushels of corn.
   In a related report, the government's Joint Agricultural Weather
Facility said that by mid-May corn planting had advanced rapidly to
about 88 percent completed in the major producing states, matching
the fast pace of a year ago. Normally, only 66 percent of the
acreage is planted by May 15.
</TEXT>
