<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Threat     05-18 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Threat,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Student Charged With Threatening President Reagan's Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury indicted an Iranian
graduate student Tuesday on charges he threatened the life of
President Reagan and other public officials in letters and
telephone calls.
   Mohammed Farhad Khorrami, 37, a student at Indiana University in
Bloomington, was indicted on four counts of threatening injury to
the president and two counts of telephone harassment.
   Khorrami is accused of threatening the Jewish National Fund
office in New York City during January and February. He also
allegedly threatened former Secretary of Defense Caspar Weinberger,
Israeli officials and Jews in general.
   Khorrami is a doctoral student in economics and held a graduate
student teaching position in Bloomington from 1982-84, said
Gretchen Wolfram of the news bureau at Indiana University-Purdue
University at Indianapolis. He has taught in a joint program of the
universities since 1985, she said.
   Khorrami has applied for legal alien status under the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's amnesty program. He faces
penalties of more than five years in prison and up to $275,000 if
convicted, officials said.
</TEXT>
