<1ST_LINE>r w PM-McFarlane-StarWars Bjt   05-18 0854</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-McFarlane-Star Wars, Bjt,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McFarlane Says Reagan's Own Advisers Faulted Star Wars Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's decision to pursue an
ambitious space shield against nuclear weapons came despite his own
top advisers' belief that the Star Wars system wouldn't work, says
former national security adviser Robert C. McFarlane.
   McFarlane, giving his first public account of the origins of
Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative, told a congressional
committee Tuesday that the president apparently came up with the
idea on his own against the advice of McFarlane and other top
military officials.
   The idea that any technological system ``could so devalue the
nuclear threat'' from additional and more accurate Soviet
intercontinental missiles as to produce ``a no-nuclear world ... is
infeasible,'' he told the House Armed Services Committee.
   But McFarlane said the idea already has served the purpose he
originally saw for it _ forcing the Soviets to reconsider their
offensive missile buildup and to add to the pressures that brought
perestroika, Mikhail S. Gorbachev's restructuring of the Soviet
economy.
   McFarlane later told a reporter he had chosen to speak out on
the subject after remaining silent for five years because ``I've
become more despairing about the responsiveness of government to
people, and it's not going to get better until we put aside the
notion that the American people are too dumb to understand.''
   He said he feels ``guilty as a member of a community ... that
has not been very candid with the American people about their
safety.''
   McFarlane said he directed the military Joint Chiefs of Staff in
late 1982 to develop the idea of using U.S. technological
superiority for some kind of anti-missile defense. The idea was
``to demonstrate to the Soviet Union that we intended to redirect
our investment strategy to an area where we had the comparative
advantage,'' he said.
   The military chiefs came up with a proposal for a limited,
ground-based system, McFarlane said, but Reagan turned that limited
concept into a much more ambitious system which McFarlane had
recommended against.
   He said the president had been thoroughly briefed on the
problems of such a system: the risks of technical failure, the
suspicions that would be aroused among allies that the United
States was seeking only its own security, Soviet suspicions of U.S.
preparation for a first nuclear strike and the ``fiscal
extravagance'' involved.
   ``My approach was one ... based on a rather sober, conservative
judgment about technological risk, fiscal realities and traditional
allied strategy,'' he said in a brief interview. ``I was paid to
deal in the real world. Presidents are paid to inspire, to lead, to
have a vision that goes beyond the status quo.''
   When Reagan announced his idea for a space-based missile shield
in a March 1983 speech, members of the military establishment,
including then-Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger and the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, were flabbergasted because it so differed from
anything previously discussed.
   McFarlane, who now is at work on a book while at Georgetown
University's Center for Strategic and International Studies, said
the original idea for a defense system came in late 1982 from Adm.
James Watkins, then chief of Naval operations.
   ``The president never directed me to develop an SDI program,''
McFarlane said. ``I never heard from anyone (in the White House)
the guidance to do this,'' although he was aware Reagan had some
interest in anti-ballistic missile defense dating from before his
1980 election.
   In late 1982, the administration had lost several battles in
Congress over what kind of basing mode to use in deploying the MX
missile and was concerned that the United States was losing ground
to the Soviets in offensive weapons, he said.
   Adm. John M. Poindexter, then a National Security Council
deputy, came to him with Watkins' idea, and McFarlane told the
Joint Chiefs to develop the idea further, he said. The chiefs met
several times in January 1983, then at a Feb. 11 meeting summarized
their findings in a meeting with Reagan.
   ``The president interrupted, and said, `Are you telling me that
you believe as a body that we should consider whether defense could
make a greater contribution (to the strategic balance)?' And each,
in turn, answered yes,'' McFarlane recounted.
   ``But the military was talking about missiles,'' McFarlane said.
   ``How did that get changed into an Astrodome to protect the
population?'' asked committee chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis.
   ``Basically, the president wanted to change it, Mr. Chairman,''
McFarlane answered. ``He said, `You must deal in the traditional
threat we have faced, and in military terms. My job is to lead, and
to try to evaluate what may be feasible technologically, and be
responsive to human beings.'... I don't fault him for it.''
   Estimates of the long-term cost of Reagan's space-based defense,
which could use a combination of orbiting satellites, space fired
rockets and laser beams to knock out Soviet missiles, range up to
as much as $1 trillion. Some $25 billion in research and
development money already has been approved. Deployment of a
rudimentary version to protect a few limited military targets is
envisioned as early as the mid 1990s.
</TEXT>
