<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Hungary-Collide     05-18 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Hungary-Collide,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Military Vehicle Collides With Passenger Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet military vehicle collided with
a passenger train in northwestern Hungary and two people were
reported injured.
   The official news agency MTI said the accident happened Tuesday
at a railway-crossing near the city of Gyoer, causing ``major
disturbances'' on train lines connecting Budapest with Vienna and
Bratislava.
   The brief MTI communique did not say what time the accident took
place, but Vienna's train information service said the Orient
Express train which was scheduled to leave Budapest at 9:45 a.m.
was delayed five hours.
   MTI said train traffic was restored on one track by 3:30 p.m.
   According to the news agency report, two people suffered slight
injuries in the accident, and damage was ``considerable.'' MTI did
not say what type of military vehicle was involved and gave no
further details of the accident.
</TEXT>
