<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     05-18 0946</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0993</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENDHAM TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks in this quiet, wealthy
community say they don't mind having a wealthy celebrity like
Whitney Houston as a neighbor. But they do mind her home
improvement plan.
   Houston, who was born in Newark about 30 miles away, bought the
5-acre estate in the heart of fox-hunting country last summer and
began installing a swimming pool, sound studio and tennis courts in
the fall, said township officials.
   Residents are complaining that the construction trucks have
caused disruptions by being parked illegally, said Ruth Kollmer,
who lives four houses away.
   However, police have gone to the site several times and found no
parking violations, Police Chief F. Herbert Herron said Tuesday.
   The 24-year-old singer has missed much of the flap because she's
been on a European tour since mid-April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Judge Reinhold says people
shouldn't worry about the beating he gets at the hands of a girl in
a music video being taped this week with country music singer Jo-El
Sonnier.
   The video, which will accompany Sonnier's song ``Tear-Stained
Letter,'' is meant as a lighthearted version of the serious movie
``Fatal Attraction,'' Reinhold says.
   ``It's a comic look at how violent romance can be. I'm pretty
much brutalized and beat up and victimized by a beautiful girl,''
Reinhold said.
   Reinhold is best known for his appearances in the movie comedies
``Ruthless People,'' ``Beverly Hills Cop'' and ``Fast Times at
Ridgemont High.''
   Sonnier's song ``No More One More Time'' from the album
``Jo-El'' is in the top 10 of the country music charts.
   The two became friends in Los Angeles several years ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PINSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Camera in hand, singer Eddy Arnold paid a
surprise visit to the elementary school he attended more than half
a century ago.
   Arnold, who grew up in the area, appeared in principal Robert
Morrison's office and introduced himself, then toured the school
and took snapshots.
   ``He stayed about an hour and related a lot of stories from when
he went to school here,'' Morrison said.
   The principal said the 70-year-old singer got teary-eyed Friday
when he peeked into the sixth-grade classroom where he'd been a
student.
   ``We had a real nice visit,'' Morrison said. ``We felt honored.
It makes you feel good to know somebody famous like that has such
good memories of your school.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg was among 380
students honored during a pre-commencement ceremony at the Columbia
University School of Law.
   President Kennedy's daughter, whose diploma reads Caroline
Bouvier Kennedy, was among the graduates who shook the hand of Dean
Barbara Aronstein Black during a ceremony Tuesday marking
completion of their law studies.
   Her mother, Jacqueline Onassis; her brother, John Kennedy; her
husband, Edwin Schlossberg; and other family members were in the
audience.
   Ms. Kennedy was not expected to attend today's official
university commencement ceremony.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DUNCAN, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Beatrix of the Netherlands
isn't one to take ax in hand, but she seemed intrigued watching a
900-year-old Douglas fir topple on the last day of her nine-day
visit to Canada.
   The queen and Prince Claus, her husband, visited a logging site
and sawmill Tuesday before returning to Vancouver in mid-afternoon
for a flight back to Amsterdam.
   The 50-year-old queen lived in Ottawa as a child with her sister
and mother, then-Crown Princess Juliana, during the Nazi occupation
of the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Kathy Forester of the
award-winning Forester Sisters has announced she is expecting a
child in July.
   She and husband Terry Adkins are the parents of a 4-year-old
daughter, Amonie.
   The singer will continue with her sisters on a concert tour
through June. The Foresters were voted group of the year in 1987 by
the Academy of Country Music.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Versions of the following items moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Yankees General Manager Lou
Piniella didn't want to admit it, but when pressed by a crowd of
400 students he told them his favorite player is veteran second
baseman Willie Randolph.
   Piniella confessed his preference after a speech Tuesday at a
Drug Awareness Rally at the Annunciation School here. He told the
cheering students to say no to drugs because ``drugs have no place,
anywhere.''
   ``I've seen athletes send entire careers down the drain with
drugs,'' Piniella said.
   Urged by the crowd to name his favorite player, the former
Yankees batting star and manager reluctantly said, ``Willie
Randolph. How's that?'' Randolph is the team's co-captain.
   Piniella also presented autographed baseballs to winners of a
community-wide ``Just Say No to Drugs'' poster contest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bill Armstrong, putting his pony
where his mouth is, has paid off a Super Bowl bet with Virginia
Sen. John Warner by donating a wild bronco pony to a local Boy
Scout troop.
   The senator from Colorado had backed the hapless Denver Broncos
in January's National Football League championship, while fellow
Republican Warner wagered on the Washington Redskins, who won 42-10.
   Warner put up a supply of Virginia ham and peanuts for his side
of the bet, while Armstrong ventured a wild bronco, to be donated
to a Colorado troop in Warner's name.
   ``As it turns out, Senator Warner was right about the outcome of
the Super Bowl ... this time around, anyway,'' Armstrong said
Tuesday.
   The bronco was brought from the Western rangelands by the
federal Bureau of Land Management. Armstrong paid a $125 ``adoption
fee'' for the pony, which will be the responsibility of the scouts
at Hutchinson Elementary School to train and care for as a troop
project.
