<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Carlton     05-18 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Carlton,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazz Musician Suffered Nerve Damage, Expects To Resume Career</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grammy Award-winning jazz guitarist Larry
Carlton says he's in a lot of pain and suffered nerve damage as a
result of a gunshot wound to the neck, but expects his career to be
``grooving'' by this time next year.
   Carlton, 40, said in a recent interview he has a clear memory of
the April 6 shooting by two young assailants in the doorway of his
office at his Hollywood Hills home.
   Carlton spoke in a whisper during the interview, the result of
permanent nerve damage to his left vocal cord suffered in the
attack.
   He said he is depressed, but looks forward to resuming the
career that has made him one of the industry's busiest studio
musicians. His doctor said it was impossible to say how long it
would take to recover.
   ``The fact is that I'm just a really thankful guy right now,''
Carlton said. ``I'm recovering fine, in a lot of pain, true, but
this time next year I ought to be grooving, thank God.''
   Surgery has repaired damage to his carotid artery, but the
trauma suffered by the nerves in his left side will be slow in
healing, said his physician, Dr. Eric Schlesinger.
   Schlesinger said Carlton ``was extraordinarily lucky.
Considering where the bullet was, the velocity and the high
caliber, the fact that he's alive is astounding.''
   No suspects have been identified, and police still don't have a
clear motive for the attack other than robbery or an interrupted
burglary.
   A $20,000 reward has been offered for information leading to an
arrest.
   Carlton won a Grammy this year for best pop instrumental for his
version of the Doobie Brothers' ``Minute By Minute.'' In 1981, he
shared a Grammy with pianist Mike Post for the theme to ``Hill
Street Blues.''
</TEXT>
