<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TheFinalRound Bjt   05-18 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-The Final Round, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Trying To Edge Its Way Into The Spotlight With
California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the final push of the primary season, it's
California that seems to get all the attention. But New Jersey is
also looking for a little respect.
   The two states hold primaries on the same day _ June 7 _ along
with Montana and New Mexico.
   California, with its prize of 314 delegates and its importance
in the general election, naturally finds its way into the campaign
spotlight.
   Democrat Jesse Jackson, for one, is throwing nearly all of his
remaining resources, both time and money, into his California
campaign.
   Vice President George Bush, the GOP nominee-to-be, is
campaigning as intensely as if he still had active primary
opponents and needed California's 175 Republican delegates. Bush is
clearly looking to the fall campaign, in which California's 47
electoral votes could be pivotal.
   But New Jersey wants a share of the limelight too.
   Though offering only about a third of the delegates at stake in
Calfornia, New Jersey is still the nation's eighth-largest primary,
with 109 Democratic delegates and 64 Republican delegates at stake.
   The candidates can't really afford to turn their their backs on
those kind of numbers, despite the headaches of simultaneously
running campaigns on both sides of the country.
   Even if jet lag is the price to be paid, they're taking the New
Jersey primary seriously.
   Both Jackson and Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis were in
New Jersey on Sunday, and Jackson will be back next week.
   Dukakis was scheduled to campaign in New Jersey on Wednesday and
Thursday before heading to Los Angeles.
   Newark Mayor Sharpe James, chairman of the Jackson campaign in
New Jersey, says even if the candidate can't be in two places at
once, he'll make his presence felt in New Jersey.
   ``He's everywhere you have to go to get votes,'' said James.
   Observers are already predicting Jackson will do well in New
Jersey's cities and among minority voters, but Dukakis seen as
likely to win the state by a sizable margin.
   Rep. James Florio of New Jersey, a Dukakis backer, says even
though the Massachusetts governor is favored in the state, he
doesn't intend to get complacent and slight New Jersey.
   ``The combination of New Jersey and California are very
important,'' Florio said. Aides to Dukakis are hoping the
combination of contests on June 7 will give their candidate the
number of delegates he needs to clinch the Democratic nomination.
   In past elections, New Jersey has demonstrated some clout.
   In 1984, Walter Mondale racked up a comfortable win over Gary
Hart and Jackson in New Jersey, a victory that did much to nail
down the nomination. The same day, Hart scored a 2-1 triumph over
Mondale in California, but it was too little, too late.
   Still, some New Jersey politicians long for a place in the sun _
without having to compete with California.
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, a Republican, has attempted
unsucessfully to have the date of the state's primary moved up.
   ``I worry that New Jersey is getting lost in the presidential
primary shuffle,'' Kean said in a speech to the state Legislature.
   A bipartisan commission suggested holding the primary a week
earlier this year, but the proposal was not acted upon.
   ``They were only attempting to get it out from the shadow of
California,'' said Kean spokesman Carl Golden.
</TEXT>
