<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-18 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Scores Another Primary Win, Looks Ahead To Fall Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, who added Oregon to his growing
list of primary wins is talking more and more like a man who fully
expects to win the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Dukakis has been at pains in recent weeks to avoid sounding
overconfident, but in his victory statement Tuesday night he was
looking ahead to a fall faceoff with Republican nominee-to-be
George Bush following the final round of primaries.
   ``We will campaign hard for victories in California, New Jersey,
Montana and New Mexico on June 7 and for the White House next
fall,'' he said.
   The people of Oregon, he said, ``voted for a candiate who can
win the presidency.''
   A day earlier, at the Statehouse, Dukakis made some lighthearted
remarks that also reflected confidence.
   ``This state will be blessed with a great new governor,'' Dukaks
said Tuesday night at a birthday party for Massachusetts Lt. Gov.
Evelyn Murphy. She would succeed Dukakis if he assumes the
presidency in January.
   Dukakis drew laughs from the friendly crowd by delivering a
standard joke _ that if he moves to the White House, he will have
``an opportunity to live in public housing for the first time in my
life.''
   Dukakis was tending to state business today before leaving
tonight for campaign appearances in New York and in New Jersey,
which holds its primary June 7. Dukakis won the New York primary
last month but, with an eye on the fall, already has returned there
several times for fund-raisers and other events.
   His loss to Jesse Jackson in the District of Columbia primary
was the only Dukakis defeat in the last 10 primaries.
   The governor was to spend Thursday morning in New Jersey before
heading to California for a weekend of campaigning in advance of
that delegate-rich state's primary, also June 7, the final day of
the primary season.
   Before heading to Murphy's birthday party, Dukakis met at the
Statehouse for 90 minutes with Rep. Mel Levine of California, a
member of the House Foreign Affairs Committee and an expert on
U.S.-Israeli relations.
   Dukakis has been holding a series of meetings with congressional
leaders aimed at bolstering his standing in foreign policy matters.
   ``It was a very productive meeting,'' Levine said as he left the
governor's office. ``I found the governor's questions to be to the
point, reflecting a substantive background in the area, a great
deal of sympathy for our concerns and a real inquisitive mind and
interest in finding solutions to very difficult problems'' in the
Middle East.
   Levine also said Dukakis is in ``terrific shape'' to win the
California primary.
   Dukakis aides say they expect the contests in California and New
Jersey to push the governor over the 2,081-delegate mark needed to
secure the nomination.
</TEXT>
