<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpeedTrapFlap     05-18 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Speed Trap Flap,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Wants to Rid Town of Speed-Trap Reputation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATTON VILLAGE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new mayor says he wants to
shake this town's speed-trap reputation by giving a free ride out
of court to traffic violators, but the former sheriff retorted,
``The man is a stone-cold idiot.''
   ``I envision a police department that is not a cash register on
(Highway) 59,'' Mayor Robert Devaney said Tuesday after his first
council meeting. Devaney, a 66-year-old accountant, took office
Friday.
   Patton Village's new council members agreed to research
Devaney's proposed ``amnesty program'' for those cited as traffic
violators to determine if it would be legal.
   ``It's a parasitical situation. We're mooching off citizens of
East Texas by writing up citations and abusing people, according to
reports I've heard,'' Devaney said. ``It's my intent and desire to
remit all these fines, wipe them out and dismiss them.''
   However, Alan E. Hall, who last week announced his resignation
as police chief, warned that Devaney's action would trigger
liability problems and lawsuits for false arrest.
   ``He's going to shut down court, padlock the doors and open up
this whole town to lawsuits,'' said Hall, who has been told to
vacate his office immediately. ``It don't take an Einstein to
figure it out from a liability standpoint. The man is a stone-cold
idiot.''
   For years, Patton Village has been a notorious speed trap where
police strictly enforced a 55 mph limit. U.S. 59 is a major divided
highway a few miles east of Interstate 45, the main route between
Dallas and Houston.
   Devaney and three new council members ran on a platform that
supported giving voters the option of disincorporating the town of
1,300 residents.
   The Municipal Court will remain closed and a constable from
Mongtomery County will investigate warrants issued by the police
department to see if they were executed properly, Devaney said
following Tuesday's council meeting, which was attended by an
applauding crowd of about 20 people.
   City secretary Linda Cayton, who resigned in protest Tuesday
after the council meeting, said 90 percent of the town's 1987
fiscal budget of $435,000 came from traffic tickets and other
municipal court fines. From August through March, the court
generated $180,502 in town income, she said.
   The Texas Commission on Judicial Conduct recently issued a
warning to the town's municipal court, ordering officers to stop
arresting out-of-county residents without taking them before a
magistrate.
   Floyd Duval, Patton Village's municipal judge, was suspended by
the commission pending the outcome of an official oppression charge
against him. He is accused of offering to pay a woman's traffic
ticket in exchange for sex.
   The 20-member police department remains in operation, but
officials said the officers won't be out on the highway setting up
a speed trap.
   ``The officers may be out there periodically, but they won't be
citing people for going two miles over the speed limit or other
things like that,'' said the new police chief, J.D. Broussard Jr.
   Devaney said the court will be closed for about 30 days and then
reopened ``hopefully with a different focus, not getting money
we're not entitled to.''
</TEXT>
