<HEAD>Former Temptations Singer Jailed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Ruffin, former lead singer of the
Temptations, was jailed after failing to show up for his trial on
cocaine possession charges, his court-appointed lawyer said.
   Detroit Recorder's Court Judge John P. O'Brien issued a bench
warrant for Ruffin's arrest Tuesday morning, several hours after
the singer's nonjury trial was to resume, attorney Jeffrey Collins
said.
   Ruffin, 47, of South Lyon arrived in court in the afternoon,
Collins said. O'Brien had adjourned the case and left instructions
for Ruffin to be held in Wayne County jail if he appeared ``pending
final resolution of the case,'' the attorney said.
   Collins said he planned to ask O'Brien today to reconsider his
order that Ruffin be jailed.
   Police arrested Ruffin on charges of possessing less than 50
grams of cocaine during a raid at a Detroit home last July. Ruffin,
a member of the soul music group from 1963 to 1968, could receive
up to four years in prison if convicted.
