<DOCNO> AP880518-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     05-18 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Seems More And More Like An Underdog As He Campaigns In
California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As George Bush said, ``It hasn't been a good
day.''
   The Republican nominee-to-be did win another uncontested primary
victory Tuesday in Oregon. But he also had to face polls suggesting
his standing is slipping in a hypothetical fall matchup with
Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   A Los Angeles Times poll out today indicated Bush trails Dukakis
in California, a key battleground in November.
   The vice president concedes that his problem might stem in part
from troubles that have dogged the Reagan administration _
controversies about Attorney General Edwin Meese, Panamanian
military leader Manuel Noriega and the Iran-Contra affair.
   ``It could an accumulation of current events, but I don't worry
about it. I've learned not to live on these polls,'' Bush said,
talking to police officers battling gangs in Los Angeles on Tuesday.
   Stopping drug traffic is Bush's topic today, as he visits a
house where crack was sold and visits a school fighting its own
drug problem.
   But Bush's woes all but drowned out his talk of agriculture and
drugs on Tuesday.
   ``It's hasn't been too good a day,'' he said in Los Angeles.
``But it will turn around, it will turn around.''
   Part of the problem is the combination of the Democratic and
Republican nomination fights at this point, Bush aides said.
   ``Dukakis is in a very enviable position _ he is scoring a knock
every Tuesday, while we have no opponents ... and we have suffered
in the polls,'' said spokesman Pete Teeley.
   Teeley admitted the administration's problems are Bush's:
``Whatever happens to the administration rubs off on the vice
president.''
   Bush has refused to talk about Meese's problems, but he stepped
a slight distance away from the Reagan administration on the furor
over a proposed deal with Noriega, admitting a deal is unpopular.
   Asked about a Senate resolution condemning any deal, he said:
``I think it expresses a lot of the strong feeling out there across
the country on that matter, very strong.''
   But despite repeated questions, Bush refused to give his opinion
on whether Noriega should be allowed to escape drug-running charges
in exchange for stepping down.
   Bush took the offensive on the Iran-Contra affair, accusing
Democrats of leaking ``scurrilous allegations'' against him that
aren't true.
   ``You've had endless investigations _ each one with a lot of
Democrats slavering, trying to find something wrong and they
haven't,'' Bush told reporters in Fresno. ``The American people are
fair. They know when someone is telling the truth.''
   The vice president professed not to be concerned about a CBS
News-New York Times poll putting him 10 points behind Dukakis. The
poll put Bush at 39 percent and Dukakis at 49 percent in a fall
matchup.
   In another poll, limited to California, Dukakis' lead was even
wider. A Los Angeles Times survey suggested Dukakis had a 17-point
lead over Bush in the state _ 53 percent to 36 percent, with 11
percent undecided. The Times poll questioned 2,202 Californians by
telephone in six days, ending Monday night. The margin of error was
3 percentage points.
   Bush acknowledged those kind of numbers were not good news.
   ``No, they weren't,'' he said. But he quickly pointed to polls
indicating he trailed in New Hampshire, a primary he went on to win.
   Bush argued that the fall campaign has not really begun, so
hypothetical matchups at this point don't prove much.
   ``The thing hasn't really started in terms of Democrats versus
Republicans and we haven't gotten any of that in focus and it won't
be until after the convention,'' Bush said, adding he will ``not
try to join every issue with the Democrats or start jumping all
over them right now.''
   Bush's negative ratings were high in the CBS-Times poll.
Thirty-three percent said they had a favorable view of Bush, but
even more _ 35 percent _ said they had an unfavorable view. While
voters are less familiar with Dukakis, his favorable rating stood
at 38 percent and unfavorable at 14 percent.
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said that the negative ratings
can change quickly in a presidential campaign.
   ``Positive and negatives can turn around overnight,'' Atwater
said.
</TEXT>
