<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Terrorists-Vermont     05-18 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Terrorists-Vermont,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Says Bomb Importers Had Terrorist Link</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men who smuggled a bomb from Canada
into Vermont belong to a Syrian terrorist group that assassinated
Lebanese President-elect Bashir Gemayel, officials said in asking
for maximum sentences.
   U.S. Attorney George Terwilliger III said Tuesday he was aware
of the association within 48 hours of the Oct. 23, 1987, arrests.
   ``We deliberately kept the association out of our case because
it was not relevant to any of the charges,'' Terwilliger said. ``We
came away from the trial without any possible taint to our case
that premature disclosure of this association might have caused.''
   U.S. District Judge Albert Coffrin has not set a sentencing date
for the three Lebanese-born Canadians.
   ``Acts of terrorism such as suicide bombings, kidnappings and
murder have become all too commonplace as instrumentalities of
political operations in some parts of the world,'' Terwilliger said.
   ``What this case is about is an attempt to import those
techniques into the territory of the United States.''
   That charge drew an immedate rebuke from a lawyer for one of the
men, who said the FBI had failed to produce any proof that three
are members of the Syrian Social National Party.
   ``They're going to have to prove it,'' said Mark Keller, a
lawyer for defendant Walid Kabbani. ``We can say no, he's not a
member of the party. Is that enough?''
   Floyd Clarke, head of the FBI's criminal investigation division,
said sources and channels of information on which the allegation
was based are confidential.
   The three were arrested Oct. 23, 1987, in Richford after the
town police chief spotted them behaving suspiciously near the
international border. A search of their van turned up explosives,
authorities said.
   It is believed to be the first time Middle Eastern terrorists
have been arrested in the United States carrying explosives, said
Justice Department spokesman John Russell.
   ``Based on the information known by the FBI, it is our judgment
that the crimes committed by the defendants in Vermont were
undertaken in furtherance of the defendants' SSNP activities,''
Clarke said in an affidavit.
   Clarke's affidavit said the FBI does not have enough information
to state conclusively the intended bomb target.
   The affidavit was submitted with a sentencing memo and filed by
Terwilliger in U.S. District Court in Burlington.
   Walid Mourad pleaded guilty Jan. 26 to conspiring to transport
explosives and an immigration violation, and faces up to 10 years
in prison.
   George Younan and Kabbani were found guilty by a jury of several
explosives violations and an immigration violation. Younan faces up
to 35 years in prison and Kabbani up to 30 years and six months.
   All three are in custody awaiting sentencing.
   The SSNP is responsible for car bombings in Lebanon in 1985 and
1986 that killed 105 people and injured 378, as well as the 1982
assassination of Gemayel, Clarke's affidavit said.
   The group began in the 1930s as a fascist paramilitary
organization opposing the French Mandate Regime in Lebanon and
espousing ``Greater Syria,'' which envisioned Syrian control of
Lebanon and what was then Palestine, the affidavit said.
</TEXT>
