<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Reno,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Star of Black Stallion Movies Likes Ranching</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kelly Reno, the young star of the rustic
``Black Stallion'' movies, says he's at home on the range and won't
regret it if he never does another movie.
   ``If I really wanted to be an actor, I wouldn't have gotten
married,'' said Reno, a 21-year-old 6-footer who operates a ranch
for a living in Pueblo County. ``I would have gone to Hollywood and
taken any role available.''
   Reno is best known for his starring roles in the 1979 ``The
Black Stallion'' and 1983's ``The Black Stallion Returns.'' He also
appeared in the movie ``Blade's Escape,'' and starred in a 1985
episode of Steven Spielberg's ``Amazing Stories.''
   Reno said recently he would like to do classic westerns, but he
quickly added, ``If I never do another one (movie) again, I'll
never regret it.''
   He and his wife, Lynette, were married in August 1986. They own
40 acres, lease another 4,000 acres of grazing land and run 200
head of cattle on their spread south of Pueblo.
