<2ND_LINE>AM-Transit Bus Crash, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0486,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, About 20 Injured In Bus Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS final two grafs with two grafs to UPDATE with details on
injuries sustained by boy and bus driver.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city bus crashed into a utility pole near
downtown Tuesday night, killing a 14-year-old boy and injuring
about 20 other people, authorities said.
   Witnesses indicated that a car may have caused the accident and
sped away, said Sgt. Lou Narducci of the Greater Cleveland Regional
Transit Authority police.
   Narducci said about 16 people were on board the bus when it hit
the pole and a chain-link fence, but Cleveland police officer Emil
Cielec said 20 people were taken to four hospitals.
   ``We've heard a lot of different versions of what happened, and
it's up to the city police to figure it out,'' Narducci said. ``We
know that the bus hit a utility pole and the fence and that another
car was involved.''
   Anthony Hardaway, a resident in a nearby YMCA building, said he
was in his room when there was a ``boom and a flash that made me
jump.''
   He said he ran outside and saw that a bus was involved in the
accident.
   ``There was nobody around, and me and some other guys tried to
help,'' he said. ``I went in the bus, but I don't want to talk
about what I saw because it was bad. I knew one boy had it.''
   The front of the bus was demolished. Another car nearby also was
damaged on the front end, and part of the utility pole was on the
car. Police were questioning the driver of that car.
   The boy, who was not immediately identified, was dead on arrival
at St. Vincent Charity Hospital and Health Center, said Dr. Carla
Streep O'Day, director of emergency services. She said it appeared
that a post from a metal fence pierced him in his side.
   The bus driver, Audrey Simmons, was admitted in fair condition
with a broken leg, hospital spokeswoman Maria Tayek said.
</TEXT>
