<DOCNO> AP880518-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SteelPlant     05-18 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steel Plant,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint U.S.-Japanese Steel Venture Dedicated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FOLLANSBEE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees at a new Japanese-American
steel plant in this Ohio River town are diligent and hard workers,
says the mill's top executive. But they have one flaw.
   ``There is a very bad habit _ spitting,'' Takamasa Yamamura,
chairman and chief executive officer of Wheeling-Nisshin Inc., said
at dedication ceremonies Tuesday. ``I asked the employees, `Please
stop the spitting. This is my house.'''
   Spitting is ubiquitous in West Virginia, as is chewing tobacco.
But it's not welcome in the spotless, state-of-the-art
steel-coating plant.
   Company officials and politicians hope the plant will ignite an
economic recovery in the upper Ohio River Valley, where idle steel
mills sit rusting.
   ``This project is very important because it is coming at a very
difficult time in the American steel industry,'' said Yuzuru Abe,
chairman and chief executive officer of Japan's Nisshin Steel Co.
Ltd. Nisshin co-owns the plant in a joint venture with
Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp., which operated a steel plant at
the site before it closed.
   Politicians, workers and townspeople joined company officials in
dedicating the $65 million, computer-controled mill. Even the
refreshments reflected the cross-cultural marriage _ sushi and
chicken were served while a high school band played standards of
the 1940s.
   ``This has to be the happiest day of my life, believe me,'' said
Mayor Adam Dalessio. ``In a short time, we have come from what was
a very gray future to one bright with opportunities.''
   As proof of the town's rebound, the mayor, who worked at the
former Wheeling-Pitt plant for more than 40 years, cited the
opening of a new fast-food restaurant and a bank. A new supermarket
and drug store are scheduled to open within a month in the town of
3,900 people.
   Wheeling-Pitt provided the land along the Ohio River where the
3-block-long plant sits. The plant was built with the help of $55
million in loans from Sanwa Bank of Japan and an $8.75 million
federal urban development grant.
   Follansbee was selected over towns in Pennsylvania and Ohio that
sought the mill, which employs about 90 and will grow to 100
workers when it enters full production in July.
   The aluminized and galvanized steel the plant produces resists
rust and is used in construction, automobiles and appliances.
Coated, flat-rolled steel is considered one of the most profitable
sectors in the highly competitive steel industry.
   Wheeling-Pitt, which supplies about 80 percent of the steel used
by the plant, will receive a third of the profits generated at
Follansbee. Nisshin Steel, Japan's sixth-largest steel-maker, will
get the rest.
   Among the difficulties faced by the American plant employees,
who will work alongside a few Japanese workers, was adapting to the
Japanese style of management. Everyone at the plant, including
company executives, wears a powder-blue shirt and dark blue
trousers while on the job, and employees will have a say in company
operations.
   Wheeling-Nisshin spent $3 million training the workers,
including sending many to Japan.
   ``I'd like to say thanks for our training,'' said plant employee
John Thompson. ``Not only has it been invaluable, nothing like it
has ever happened to me in my lifetime.''
</TEXT>
