<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorldBank     05-18 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Bank,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Urge Transfer of World Bank Funding Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve senators have suggested that proposed
U.S. funding increases for the World Bank be used instead to make
American industries more competitive.
   In letter released Tuesday to Sen. John Stennis, chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Committee, the senators said they are deeply
concerned about the Reagan administration's request to increase
U.S. funding to the World Bank by $70.1 million annually for the
next six years.
   ``The World Bank continues to subsidize the building of unneeded
foreign production facilities while U.S. plants close and workers
lose their jobs,'' the senators said in their letter.
   The group cited a recent decision by the World Bank to approve a
$400 million loan to Mexico to modernize its steel making
facilities.
   ``Until the World Bank reverses its policy of funding foreign
economic development at the expense of the American worker and
vital U.S. industries, we believe that the taxpayers' money can be
better spent on programs to develop efficient technologies which
make American industries more competitive and put Americans back to
work,'' they said.
   The group suggested the additional $70.1 million proposed for
fiscal 1989 instead be directed to programs that will assist
struggling U.S. industries regain their competitive edge in
international trade.
   The letter was signed by Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah; Howell
Heflin, D-Ala.; Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio;
Barbara Mikulski, D-Md.; Donald Riegle, D-Mich.; Richard Shelby,
D-Ala.; Arlen Specter, R-Pa.; and Steven Symms, R-Idaho.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
