<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NursingHomeStudy     05-18 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nursing Home Study,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Suggests Payroll Tax To Fund Federal Insurance For Long-Term
Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private study calls for a new federal
insurance program financed by additional payroll taxes to pay
nursing home bills and other costs of long-term care for the
elderly.
   The report issued Tuesday by the Brookings Institution also says
there should be an expansion of private insurance to help cover
such costs.
   Alice M. Rivlin, former head of the Congressional Budget Office
and a lead author of the report, stopped short of saying its
primary recommendation is for a new government program.
   She said the main purpose of the 318-page report was to compile
extensive data for Congress to debate in shaping a national policy.
   However, Ms. Rivlin acknowledged the report envisions the
private insurance as supplementing a government program. For
example, the private insurance would cover co-payments required of
beneficiaries under a Medicare-like plan, or the government role
would be limited to kicking in only after privately financed
benefits are exhausted.
   Long-term care is shaping up as a major issue in 1989, much the
same way catastrophic coverage for acute illness was an overriding
Medicare issue this year. The central question of that 1989 debate
will be over the extent to which payment of long-term care expenses
_ at nursing homes and at home _ should be a federal responsibility.
   No matter what program evolves, Ms. Rivlin said provisions would
have to remain to care for the poor elderly who do not have the
resources to pay for any of their own care.
   The Brookings report says the cost of a new social insurance
program would range between $33 billion and $42 billion, compared
with the $20 billion spent on long-term care under current policies.
   That money could be raised, it said, by a payroll tax of from
2.2 percent to 2.9 percent _ half on employers and half on
employees _ with no cap on the level of wages subject to
withholding.
   Medicare currently is financed by a similar tax, but with a cap
on the income subject to taxation.
   Pending legislation by Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., would remove
the cap to provide open-ended home health care for any disabled
person _ young or old.
   Under questioning, Ms. Rivlin said that is a laudable goal,
``but it's also a very tricky problem.''
   ``We're concerned that the Pepper bill does not have adequate
safeguards against escalating costs,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
