<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Finances,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Got More than $120,000 in Income from Trust, Petroleum
Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush received more than
$100,000 in income from a qualified trust and $20,773 in a
distributions from a limited petroleum partnership in 1987,
according to papers filed with the government.
   The vice president's office on Tuesday distributed copies of
Bush's 1987 financial disclosure report, filed with the Office of
Government Ethics in accordance with law.
   In addition to the income from the trust, it shows the amount of
Bush's ``distributive share'' from Hollywood L.P.G. No. 2 Limited
Partnership, or his share in the partnership.
   Stephen Hart, the vice president's press secretary, said the
partnership could not be put into the blind trust with Bush's other
assets because the trust covers only shares or other items listed
for trading.
   Other income included a book royalty of $1,575 from Doubleday,
publisher of the vice president's recent book of memoirs.
   Bush had loans of $10,000 to $15,000 from Connecticut General
Life Insurance Co. and $50,000 to $100,000 each from Massachusetts
Mutual and Guardian Life Insurance, all taken out in 1979 at 5 per
cent interest.
   The report showed assets valued at from $73,000 to $160,000 in
bank accounts, credit union and similar investments. It did not
include the home the vice president owns in Kennebunkport, Maine.
   Items are required in most cases to be valued only by a range,
rather than the specific figure, in the reports.
   The vice president listed receipt of gifts ranging from a number
of items valued at $100 each to a television set valued at $1,999,
which he received from Dr. and Mrs. Charles Neblett of Houston.
   Hart said the Nebletts are very close friends of the vice
president and his wife.
   Neblett's office in Houston said the doctor was in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
