<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Finances,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Discloses Holdings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson has disclosed he and his wife
have stock and bank account holdings worth at least $345,000 and
possibly more than $510,000.
   The figures were contained in a personal financial statement
presidential candidates are required to file with the Federal
Election Commission. But since the forms require only that a range
of value be stated, the exact amount of the assets cannot be pinned
down.
   Jackson listed stocks and bank accounts collectively worth
between $95,000 and $260,000, plus his wife's stock in Inner City
Broadcasting Corp. valued at more than $250,000.
   The head of the New York-based entertainment company, Percy
Sutton, also made a loan to Jackson this year, and Jackson listed
under liabilities a promissory note for between $15,000 and $50,000.
   Sutton did not return a call seeking an explanation of the loan.
Jackson's campaign referred calls to his attorney, John Bustamante
of Cleveland. Bustamante did not return a message Tuesday.
   The Democratic candidate reported salary and wages $166,933 for
the past 15{ months, plus interest and dividends totaling between
$4,300 and $15,500.
   A family company headed by Jackson's wife, Jacqueline, provided
most of Jackson's wages, $105,000. The firm, Personalities
International, Inc., handles most of Jackson's speaking fees, and
he listed himself as an employee of the firm until last September.
   In addition, he reported $30,500 in honoraria paid directly to
him. The financial statement does not reflect specific wages of
Jackson's wife, Jacqueline, as their joint 1987 tax statement did.
   On their tax return they reported $159,000 in salary and wages
together, which an aide said was from Personalities International.
   The financial statement filed this week covered all of 1987 and
through April 13 this year. It said Mrs. Jackson and one of the
couple's children received salary of between $100,000 and $250,000
from Personalities International.
   Jackson reported earning $12,750 from the Rainbow Coalition, a
voter education organization he founded and headed until he began
running for president last fall.
   He also listed $2,000 in earnings for TV appearance compensation
from Talent and Residuals, Inc. of Chicago, and $16,683 in book
advance royalties from Fortress Press which published ``Straight
From the Heart,'' a collection of Jackson speeches.
   The financial reports do not include candidates' personal
residences. Jackson owns homes in Chicago and Washington, and his
mother's home in South Carolina.
   Jackson reported dividends for holdings in: Prudential-Bache
Money Mart Assets of Chicago, Calvert Social Investment Fund of
Washington and Commonwealth Edison, Common, of Chicago, plus
interest on accounts in seven banks and savings and loan
institutions.
   The honoraria Jackson received for speaking at various churches,
campuses and other organizations ranged from $100 to $5,000.
</TEXT>
