<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Contras-Drugs     05-18 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras-Drugs,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Probe Developing Evidence Of Drug Deals Permitted To Help
Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration may have sanctioned
and in some cases recruited convicted drug traffickers in its
secret effort to aid the Nicaraguan Contras, a House subcommittee
chairman says.
   Rep. William Hughes, D-N.J., who chairs the House crime
subcommittee, said Tuesday the panel has uncovered ``a substantial
amount of evidence'' suggesting that the administration used known
drug criminals to secure guns for the rebels.
   He said there is no proof so far, but that he will air the issue
at public hearings next month.
   President Reagan said Tuesday he knows nothing about the alleged
operations. ``No one ever received or could get any evidence to
substantiate those rumors,'' Reagan said.
   Asked if he planned to check out the reports, Reagan said,
``Yes, we are.''
   Hughes said his subcommittee has examined a 3{-year period in
which administration officials either ignored or encouraged
criminal activity on behalf of the Contra rebels.
   ``There is distinct evidence of a pattern,'' Hughes said.
   He said the crime panel has uncovered repeated allegations of
federal agents recruiting or coercing criminals to work on behalf
of the Contras, who are trying to overthrow Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government. Sometimes, Hughes said, the criminals may
have been recruited as part of a plea bargain.
   Hughes said the allegations range from poor supervision of
federal drug cases to the ``possible use or abuse of the criminal
justice system '' in the Contras' behalf.
   Hughes said some operatives involved had ties to the Medellin
drug cartel of Colombia.
   Asked if administration officials had direct knowledge of the
illegal operations, Hughes replied: ``There would appear to be a
substantial amount of evidence to suggest that.'' He declined to
give specifics.
   While Hughes also declined to name names, he said, ``There is
some evidence that the (retired Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L.) North
operation had some knowledge.'' North, a former Reagan national
security aide, has been charged with conspiring to divert Iran arms
sale profits to the Contras at a time when Congress banned such aid.
   Hughes also said the role of Attorney General Edwin Meese III
remains an ``open question.'' Meese has denied that he usurped
local jurisdiction in Contra-related investigations.
   Newsweek magazine on Sunday suggested that Vice President George
Bush's foreign policy aide, Donald Gregg, was the Washington
contact for an arms operation supplying the Contras with links to
drug dealers.
   Bush lashed out at the report Monday as ``old news ... not even
news.''
   White House and Justice Department spokesmen have denied
repeatedly any interference by the administration in local
investigations.
   Hughes said congressional investigators have interviewed
hundreds of witnesses, and served 30 or more subpoenas. The crime
panel has coordinated its activities with Lawrence E. Walsh, the
independent council in the Iran-Contra criminal investigation,
Hughes said.
   Among those compelled to testify was Jeffery Feldman, an
assistant U.S. attorney in Miami.
   Feldman met with subcommittee investigators in closed session in
July of last year. He also was questioned by investigators of the
congressional Iran-Contra committees.
   Feldman was the lead prosecutor in a 1985 case involving an
alleged gun running operation for the Contras.
   According to crime subcommittee records, Feldman and his
superior, Leon Kellner, the U.S. attorney in Miami, may have been
persuaded to delay the case on instructions from the Justice
Department. Meese has acknowledged discussing the case with
Kellner, but denies any attempt to sidetrack the investigation.
   There have been numerous allegations that the Contras have
helped support their war effort through drug running, and the
Reagan administration also has said the Sandinistas have done the
same.
   The crime subcommittee also is investigating possible
mishandling of the case of Barry Seal, an American who Hughes said
was involved in selling drugs to the Nicaraguan government.
   Reagan in 1986 used a photo taken by Seal to show what he
described as Sandinista officials involved in drug dealing. The
photo allegedly showed officials in the capital city of Managua
loading drugs onto an airplane bound for the United States.
   Hughes said a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration investigation
of Seal, who was later murdered in this country, may also have been
slowed deliberately.
   Reagan, in answering questions Tuesday about the overall
allegations, referred to the case.
   ``The only thing I knew is when we operated a sting operation
and found that the Sandinistas were shipping out drugs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
