<1ST_LINE>r a PM-China-Oxen     05-18 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Oxen,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Heads For China To Present Musk Oxen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Time of departure is uncertain.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOULTRIE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two rare musk oxen donated to China as
replacements for a pair that had been presented by Richard Nixon
but have since died are ready for a presentation ceremony, says the
woman organized the gift.
   The oxen ``had to stay in quarantine a month before we would
have the presentation ceremonies,'' Helen Miller said Tuesday as
she packed for her trip to the dedication at the Beijing Zoo.
``They've been over there a month and they've passed their tests.
   ``The ceremony is on the 23rd,'' she added, ``but I don't know
whether it's our 23rd or theirs. It's a day later going in that
direction.''
   Mrs. Miller, who planned to depart for China today, began a
campaign to replace the two oxen, which were presented to China in
1972 by then-President Nixon, after she learned in 1980 of their
deaths.
   The oxen, Milton and Matilda, were given to China in exchange
for two pandas, Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing, that have become popular
attractions at the National Zoo in Washington.
   As part of her project, the Moultrie resident visited the
University of Alaska to view a herd of musk oxen, which are found
only in Greenland and arctic regions of North America. The oxen,
which have heavy fur coats and horns that curl below their heads
and then upward, were hunted relentlessly for years and are
considered an endangered species.
   Mrs. Miller, a retired construction company employee, persuaded
university officials to donate the oxen, named Koyuk and Tanana, to
China under a new U.S.-China bilateral agreement for the exchange
and preservation of rare and endangered plants and animals.
   ``This is going to be the first gift under this agreement,''
said Mrs. Miller. ``I've been working on this project for 7{ years,
so this agreement came along at just the perfect time.''
</TEXT>
