<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     05-18 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Charges U.S.-Backed Plot To Encourage Guerrilla Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH NAVARRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian intelligence officials
charged that the United States may have been behind a plot to
encourage anti-government guerrilla violence aimed at ousting Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The accusation came during a news conference on Tuesday where
Eduardo Sanchez, one of the alleged conspirators, was presented to
reporters.
   Sanchez described the plot in a brief statement, then was
removed from the room. Reporters were not allowed to ask him
questions.
   In another development, the pro-Noriega newspaper La Republica
said on Tuesday the Treasury Ministry has prepared charges against
Panamanian consulate officials in London and four U.S. cities who
have remained loyal to Delvalle.
   According to Sanchez, another co-conspirator was Eduardo
Herrera, a lieutenant colonel in the Panamanian Defense Forces.
Herrera was retired in April when he refused orders to return home
from Israel, where he had been the Panamanian ambassador.
   Sanchez said he had spoken by telephone with Herrera to receive
instructions on a plan to oust Noriega, head of the 15,000-member
Defense Forces and Panama's de facto leader. Noriega was indicted
in Florida in February on federal drug-trafficking charges.
   Lucinio Miranda, secretary general of the National Department of
Investigations, told reporters at the news conference that Sanchez
and three others were arrested last week in connection with the
conspiracy.
   Miranda said that during the arrests, authorities seized a cache
of weapons including pistols, grenades, rifles and machine guns.
   ``We don't know what kind of support they had,'' Miranda said,
and added: ``They could be backed by Washington.''
   ``Absurd,'' U.S. Embassy spokesman Terence Kneebone told The
Associated Press about the alleged conspiracy. Kneebone said the
purported plot appeared ``to have been manufactured out of whole
cloth.''
   The Reagan administration imposed economic sanctions on Panama
after the Noriega-dominated National Assembly on Feb. 26 ousted
President Eric Arturo Delvalle. The previous day Delvalle had tried
to fire Noriega. The United States still recognizes Delvalle as
Panama's legitimate president.
   La Republica said the diplomats that will be charged with
withholding from the government hundreds of thousands of dollars in
fees paid to them by people doing business with Panama. The
U.S.-imposed sanctions prohibit such people from transferring funds
to the Panamanian government.
   The newspaper said charges of embezzlement have been prepared
against the following consular officials: Alberto Garcia de
Paredes, New York; Jaime Trujillo, Atlanta; Santiago Torrijos
Lopez, Los Angeles; Alberto Dominguez, Miami, and Eduardo Arango,
London.
   Officials at the Treasury and Foreign ministries were
unavailable for comment on the report. Many Panamanian diplomats
abroad have remained loyal to Delvalle, who is in hiding in Panama.
Other diplomatic missions have been taken over by officials
representing the acting chief executive, Manuel Solis Palma.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
