<DOCNO> AP880518-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LieDetectors     05-18 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lie Detectors,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ban on Private Lie Detector Tests Cleared for Final Passage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most lie detector tests for private employees
and job applicants would be prohibited under compromise legislation
approved unanimously by House and Senate negotiators.
   Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., on Tuesday predicted swift,
overwhelming House approval of a measure he said would ``stop the
explosion, the epidemic of lie detector tests'' administered
annually to about 2 million private employees and job applicants.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor
and Human Resources Committee, said the bill effectively would
prohibit as much as 85 percent of private polygraph tests. He
called the tests ``inaccurate instruments of intimidation.''
   The bill would not cover federal, state or local government
employees. It also would exempt private contractors involved in
government intelligence or national security work.
   Williams and other House negotiators accepted without dissent a
Senate amendment, sought by business interests and drafted in
consultation with organized labor, that would cover instances of
``economic loss or injury'' suffered by an employer.
   The amendment would allow employers to administer carefully
controlled lie detector tests as part of a theft investigation
within the company.
   The conditions for such tests are that the employee had access
to the stolen property, that the employer had a ``reasonable
suspicion'' that the worker was involved and that the employer give
details of the incident and evidence supporting the suspicions in a
written statement.
   Senate negotiators accepted a House provision allowing employers
to give polygraph tests to guards and other security personnel, as
well as employees handling certain controlled drugs, as long as
strict standards are met and the results are not the sole basis for
adverse action against an employee.
   Permissible tests would have to be administered under stringent
guidelines to be developed by the Labor Department which would
require that each test take at least 90 minutes and be conducted by
a licensed examiner.
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, said business executives'
opposition to the bill was overcome when they ``realized that these
quickie polygraph tests are inaccurate, unfair and very detrimental
to their employees.''
   The House approved the original bill, 254-158, last Nov. 4.
Williams said the House will act soon on the compromise measure and
send it to the Senate, which passed its version on March 3 by a
69-27 vote.
   At the time, Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., said that denying
employers the chance to screen job applicants will increase
workplace thefts and consumer costs.
   Judy Goldberg of the American Civil Liberties Union said the
compromise measure is ``an important step forward'' and will have
its biggest impact in the 28 states that either do not regulate
polygraph tests or only have licensing laws for examiners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoosterFiring     05-18 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Booster Firing,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Officials Say Test Firing Appears Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most severe test firing yet of a
redesigned space shuttle booster rocket appears to have been a
success, but NASA officials say they won't be certain until the
booster is disassembled.
   ``Everything we've seen in the whole program is looking very
positive,'' John McCarty, head of the Marshall Space Flight
Center's propulsion lab, said after Tuesday's test. ``It gives us a
lot of confidence.''
   The booster was redesigned after the space shuttle Challenger
exploded shortly after liftoff Jan. 28, 1986, when exhaust burned
through a joint in one of the segmented boosters. The test, which
included intentionally flawed booster joints, had been postponed
from last week.
   Jim Thomas, technical assistant in the Marshall motor project
office, said the absence of bubbles in a bead of grease placed
outside the redesigned joints indicated they did not leak during
the test.
   The old joint design probably would have failed such a test,
McCarty said.
   The test was the fourth of 10 being conducted on the redesigned
rocket in preparation for August's shuttle launching. It was the
final test firing of a shortened version of the redesigned booster.
   Shuttle managers said the firing of the 52-foot-long booster at
Marshall was the most severe test yet of the redesigned joints.
   Two joints, the case-to-nozzle joint and the igniter joints,
were intentially flawed through as many as three layers of
insulation and seals, including the last seal intended to keep hot
exhaust gas from escaping.
   ``It shows the redesigned joints will seal even though we had
some pretty severe flaws,'' said Thomas.
   The firing, which lasted less than a second, generated 960
pounds of pressure and a temperature of more than 5,000 degrees
Fahrenheit inside the case. The nozzle end of the stack was plugged
for two minutes to allow gas to reach the joints.
   Thomas said the test was ``unprecedented in the solid rocket
motor industry.'' But he added the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration probably won't test-fire a full-length booster the
same way.
   The abbreviated booster tests show the design is ``tolerant to
flaws of this type,'' Thomas said.
   The fifth test of the redesigned booster is planned for the last
week of July, officials said. The tests began in November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
