<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up A Bit, Stocks Down After Two Days Of Record Highs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAORI KITAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained ground today against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo, while stock prices fell back for the first time in
five trading days following an overnight downswing on Wall Street.
   The dollar closed at 125.53 yen, up 0.71 yen from Tuesday's
finish, but slightly lower than its opening level of 125.60 yen.
   ``Trading was scattered throughout the day as market
participants stayed on the sidelines,'' said a dealer with a major
commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   A sense of disappointment that the dollar did not rise high
enough in overseas markets, despite the dramatically improved U.S.
trade performance in March, prevented participants from placing
major orders, he said.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the nation's
trade deficit fell more than $4 billion in March to $9.7 billion,
the lowest monthly finish since March 1985.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 60.11 points Tuesday to close at a
record high, shed 52.40 points, or 0.18 percent, finishing the
day's session at 27,767.58.
   ``The overnight slump on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones
Average of 30 industrials slipped back below the $2,000 level, and
fears over rising inflation in the U.S. pulled back the Tokyo
market,'' said one brokerage official, also speaking anonymously.
   It is also time for the market to adjust itself after rising
almost 660 points over the past four trading days, he said.
   The Nikkei index, the market's key barometer, closed at Tuesday
27,819.98 points, surpassing the previous record closing of
27,759.87 points registered Monday.
   Investors are concerned that rapid economic growth in the United
States could lead to higher interest rates, which in turn could
lead to declines in New York stocks, traders said.
   Popular issues included steels, non-ferrous metals and trading
houses. Drugs, precision machineries, papers, and certain
foodstuffs and electricals lost ground.
   Trading was moderately active with volume in the first section
of trading estimated at 1.2 billion shares, up from the 1.1 billion
shares which changed hands Tuesday.
</TEXT>
