<HEAD>Congress Enters Dispute Between AIDS Victim, Justice Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS victim fired from his clerk-typist job
at the Justice Department is turning down a one-year temporary
position offered to him in the wake of publicity about the incident.
   ``I'm not going to accept,'' Mark Gregory said at a
congressional hearing Tuesday. ``They owe me my job back. They
fired me because I had AIDS.''
   Gregory said he has taken 30 days off since learning last
October that he has AIDS-related complex, a precursor to full-blown
AIDS _ nearly half of the time to participate in a treatment study
at the National Institutes of Health. Gregory was fired April 25 on
the grounds that his absences made him incapable of performing his
job.
   The firing came several weeks after the Office of Personnel
Management had instituted a policy saying federal workers with AIDS
had to be treated like those with other serious medical problems
and could not be discriminated against.
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., chairman of the House civil
service subcommittee, said ``a newly stated, enlightened policy ...
appears to have been thrown overboard within the first month.''
   ``We will not let this go,'' she said. ``We want to make sure
that federal policy is leading the way and not catching up.''
</TEXT>
