<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>FAA Report: Military-Civilian Use of Scott AFB is Feasible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Federal Aviation Administration report says
Scott Air Force Base in Illinois could be expanded to permit
civilian use, but the Defense Department is expressing doubts about
the findings.
   ``Joint use offers a practical solution to congestion in the St.
Louis air traffic hub, which otherwise threatens to become a
bottleneck, constraining the flow of air traffic across the
nation,'' the FAA said.
   The study said in a study it would be feasible to expand the
base for joint military-civilian use by adding a 10,000-foot runway
and a civilian terminal.
   It estimated the cost at $250 million and said the project would
take about three to five years to complete.
   In a response to the civilian agency's study, the Department of
Defense said it ``is not opposed to the principle of joint use of
its airfields. However, the decision for or against joint use must
be a deliberate and comprehensive process, not just an evaluation
of `technical feasibility.'''
   The base, located 20 miles east of downtown St. Louis near
Belleville, Ill., is headquarters for the U.S. Transportation
Command, Military Airlift Command and Air Force Communications
Command.
