<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp     05-18 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese-Owned Tanker Set Ablaze By Iranian Gunboats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Iranian speedboats attacked a
Japanese-owned chemical carrier in the Strait of Hormuz today,
setting it ablaze and forcing its crew to abandon the vessel,
shipping sources said.
   The 6,730-ton craft, the Panamanian-flagged Ace Chemi, put out a
distress signal at 8 a.m. (midnight EDT Tuesday), according to the
gulf-based shipping executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``May Day! May Day! We are under attack. We are being approached
by four gunboats,'' radio monitors heard a voice from the Ace Chemi
shouting, the executives said. Only three of the gunboats attacked,
the executives said.
   A salvage tugboat that was in the vicinity picked up the seamen
and brought the fire aboard the carrier under control, they said.
The tugboat then began towing the vessel through the strait, into
the gulf, they said. It was not immediately clear what chemical, if
any, the ship was carrying.
   Iran had not attacked neutral ships in the gulf since
Washington's new policy went into effect May 3, allowing the U.S.
Navy to help merchant vessels attacked by Iran even if they were
not sailing under the Stars and Stripes. Before the policy, the
Navy only protected U.S.-flagged ships.
   It was unclear if any American or other warship was near Hormuz,
the gulf's only outlet, when the Iranians struck today.
   Washington's get-tough policy was adopted after the Navy's most
serious clash with the Iranians in the gulf on April 18.
   During that engagement, the Navy sank or damaged six Iranian
gunboats and destroyed two oil platforms. The action was meant as
punishment for a mine explosion in the gulf the previous week that
injured 10 U.S. sailors and blew a hole in a Navy frigate. The
United States charged that Iran planted the mine.
   The last victim of Iranian gunboat attacks on neutral shipping
in the gulf was the Saudi Arabian-owned Sea Trader. After that
attack, Saudi Arabia broke relations with Tehran on April 26.
   Iran generally retaliates for Iraqi air raid attacks on its own
tankers on a ship-for-ship basis. Since April 29, Iraq has hit at
least 10 vessels owned by or doing business with Iran in an
escalated campaign to throttle its gulf enemy's oil-based economy.
   On Tuesday, explosions tore through a crippled Spanish
supertanker at Iran's Larak island oil terminal, and an unknown
number of tugboat crewmen battling fires on the ship were reported
killed or missing and feared dead.
   The blast partially sank the 235,000-ton Barcelona, one of five
ships damaged in a devastating, long-distance raid on the terminal
by Iraqi warplanes at the weekend. The toll of dead and missing
stood unofficially at 22.
   Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit in London said four tugs were
attending the stricken Barcelona at the time of the blast.
   It reported ``all crew lost'' aboard the tugboat Scan Force and
three dead on the tug Beaufort, while the tugs Safir and Ferdinand
Verbiest were damaged.
</TEXT>
