<1ST_LINE>r a PM-USIACensorship     05-18 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USIA Censorship,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documentary Export Rules Held Invalid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court's ruling that affirms the
tax-free export of documentary films is a victory for free speech
and for makers of movies on controversial topics such as nuclear
arms and Nicaragua, filmmakers' lawyers say.
   The government's attempt to ban the tax-free export of films
that advocate a cause or seek to influence government policy was
struck down Tuesday by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which
called the restriction a ``virtual license to engage in
censorship.''
   The court ruled 3-0 that U.S. Information Agency regulations
governing the worldwide distribution of thousands of films each
year violate the constitutional right of freedom of speech by
discriminating on the basis of content.
   ``This is a great victory for the First Amendment and obviously
important for filmmakers, many of whom have lost significant
amounts of money'' because of the export restrictions, said David
Lerner, spokesman for the Center for Constitutional Rights, which
represented the filmmakers.
   The ruling was the second victory in less than a week for
independent filmmakers, who need the agency's approval to qualify
for an exemption from foreign nations' import taxes.
   U.S. District Judge A. Wallace Tashima of Los Angeles declared
last Friday that rewritten rules allowing the agency to label some
exported films ``propaganda'' also were unconstitutional. Tashima's
1986 ruling invalidating the agency's original labeling regulations
was upheld by Tuesday's ruling.
   Tashima ordered the USIA to draft a third set of rules that do
not discriminate on the basis of content and to grant approval to
six films whose producers had filed the suit.
   The films include ``From the Ashes,'' a sympathetic portrayal of
the 1979 Nicaraguan revolution; ``In Our Own Backyards,'' on the
dangers of uranium mining, and ``Whatever Happened to Childhood?,''
on drug problems among children.
   The USIA and the Justice Department declined to comment on both
rulings.
   The USIA regulations implement a 1954 treaty, signed by about 60
nations, that exempts films from import fees if both the exporting
and importing nation certify the film's educational content.
   ``The USIA forces filmmakers to choose between exercising their
right to free speech and foregoing benefits ... or curtailing their
speech and obtaining the benefits,'' said Tuesday's opinion by
Judge Cecil Poole.
   Noting that the USIA has approved a pro-nuclear power film while
rejecting the film on the dangers of uranium mining, Poole said
both the regulations and the agency's practices ``seem to
disapprove materials that criticize and approve those that accept
the prevailing state of affairs.''
   He rejected the USIA's argument that the court should defer to
the government on decisions that involve ``the delicate area of
foreign relations.'' Constitutional protections apply equally to
speech that is directed abroad, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BodySearch     05-18 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Body Search,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Plan To Resume Digging At Suspected Mob Burial Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators hope the discovery of a burial
ground they believe was used by mob hit men will lead to an
egg-sized diamond once owned by the family of Sir Winston Churchill
and stolen eight years ago, a newspaper reported today.
   Joseph Scalise, an underworld jack-of-all-trades imprisoned in
Great Britain, was convicted of stealing the $960,000 Marlborough
diamond, a 45-carat gem, and authorities believe he mailed it from
London to the United States, the Chicago Tribune reported, quoting
unidentified sources.
   His home sits about 50 yards from the site where investigators
dug up one body Monday. Authorities plan to resume digging today.
   The search for the diamond led investigators to the secret
burial ground in rural Du Page County west of Chicago, the
newspaper said.
   Forensic experts from the FBI crime lab in Washington arrived
Tuesday to help identify the badly decomposed remains unearthed
from a grave after excavations began Monday, said FBI spokesman Bob
Long.
   Digging was suspended Tuesday until the team and officials from
the county coroner's office finished examining the gravesite for
evidence and removed the remains.
   Scalise, 48, is serving a 16-year sentence for the 1980 London
jewel store heist in which the Marlborough diamond and $2.6 million
worth of other jewelry were taken.
   FBI agents recently traveled to Britain to question Scalise and
another reputed Chicago mobster, Arthur Rachel, who is imprisoned
there, the Tribune reported.
   Investigators suspect the deserted field near the Argonne
National Laboratory was used as a graveyard by mob hit men during
the city's chop-shop wars of the 1970s, when the mob seized control
of the stolen auto-parts trade.
   Several scrap dealers suspected of trying to deal independently
in stolen auto parts disappeared at the time and investigators
believe the skeleton found Monday may be one of them, the Tribune
reported.
   Unidentified police sources told the newspaper they discovered
clues pointing to the makeshift graveyard's existence during their
search for the Marlborough diamond.
   British police learned that on the day of the robbery, Scalise,
a reputed crime-syndicate enforcer, mailed a package from a London
post office. Authorities believe it contained the stolen jewelry,
but have never discovered to whom the package was addressed.
   When Scalise and his accomplice, Rachel, went to prison without
revealing what they did with the loot, authorities interviewed
their associates, including underworld informers, the newspaper
said.
   None had much to say about the diamond, but several provided
information about the burial ground, the newspaper reported.
   On Tuesday, investigators sifted the soil around the gravesite
for fragmentary evidence and used metal detectors. They also took
soil samples to determine where else the ground might have been dug
up.
   Long said investigators would continue digging through the end
of the week.
</TEXT>
