<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Despite Loss, Oregon Vote Share Was `Mandate For
Change'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson brushed aside a primary loss to Michael Dukakis in Oregon,
concentrating instead on the improvement over his showing in the
state four years ago.
   Although he trailed the Massachusetts governor by nearly 20
percentage points in Oregon, Jackson expressed satisfaction with
his showing.
   ``We have done 3{ times better than in 1984,'' he told
supporters at a Hollywood hotel. ``For us, it's a mandate for
change.''
   Jackson, who has slipped far behind Dukakis in the delegate
race, implied that his rival is being prematurely crowned the
victor in the fight for the nomination.
   Asked why Dukakis did so well in Oregon when he himself spent
much more time and money in the state, he replied tartly: ``I would
assume he is riding right now on the crest of his hidden assets ...
the assessment of the pundits of the inevitability (of winning the
nomination.)''
   Jackson's aides have indicated he will make an all-out effort in
the campaign leading up to California's primary, less than three
weeks away. But polls are suggesting he has an uphill fight on his
hands.
   A Los Angeles Times poll published today indicated Dukakis led
Jackson 2-1. According to the poll of 713 Democrats questioned by
telephone over six days ending Monday, Dukakis was favored by 61
percent, Jackson 30 percent, with 5 percent undecided. The margin
of error was 5 percentage points either way, the newspaper said.
   Nonetheless, Jackson told backers: ``We look forward to
California,'' and added, ``Though we struggle against the odds, we
will not surrender.''
   Jackson, asked if he had any realistic chance of stopping
Dukakis, replied: ``We'll all know standing right here the night of
June 7.''
   New Jersey, Montana and New Mexico hold primaries along with
California that day, wrapping up the Democratic primary season.
   Jackson, whose relations with the Jewish community have
sometimes been strained, was meeting with Jewish leaders today.
   Jackson offended many Jews in 1984 with his reference to New
York as ``Hymietown'' and his association with Muslim leader Louis
Farrakhan. Jewish groups have also expressed concern over what they
see as Jackson's tilt toward the Arabs.
   Today's session at a Hollywood hotel was being attended by about
40 people, organizers said. But some Jewish leaders boycotted the
session, with some complaining that the meeting would be closed.
</TEXT>
