<HEAD>Former President Says Dukakis `Will Do Well' Against Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELLIJAY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter described Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis as ``highly competent'' on Tuesday and
said Dukakis would fare well against Republican George Bush in the
Nov. 8 presidential election.
   ``I know him well. He and I were governors together,'' said
Carter, who was governor of Georgia from 1971 to 1975 and won the
presidency in 1976.
   ``I think among all the governors, he would be voted one of the
top ones in administrative ability, in vision and competence and
sound judgment,'' Carter said Tuesday.
   Carter said Dukakis ``he will do well'' against Bush.
   As a former Democratic president, Carter is a delegate to the
convention in Atlanta this summer. He said he plans to go to the
convention as an uncommitted delegate because he told the
candidates earlier that he would not choose among them until the
convention.
