<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Earthquake     05-18 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Earthquake,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Island Rocked By Earthquake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake today shook floors and
rattled dishes in homes on the western island of Cefalonia, but
authorities said there were no immediate reports of damage or
injuries.
   The Athens Seismological Institute said the tremor measured 5.8
on the Richter scale and occurred at 8:17 a.m. (1:17 a.m. EDT). Its
epicenter was in the Ionian seabed 190 miles west of Athens and
just off Cefalonia.
   The quake was felt throughout the Ionian island chain off
western Greece and along the coast, a police spokesman in the port
city of Patras said.
   ``It felt really strong and there were three or four
after-shocks,'' said a police officer in Cefalonia who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. An earthquake measuring 6 on the scale can cause
severe damage.
</TEXT>
