<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cambodia     05-18 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Struggle For Villages Seen As Life and Death of Revolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's pro-Vietnamese government
has convened an unprecedented national congress to rally local
leaders in its struggle to keep villages and communes from falling
into the hands of guerrillas.
   The official Communist Party newspaper Pracheachon (The People)
said cadres of about 500 model communes across Cambodia opened the
congress in Phnom Penh Monday to discuss how to strengthen local
defenses.
   The paper said the party's ruling Politburo, ``considers the
localities as a matter of life or death to the revolution ... as
the core battlefield, and the work of building and consolidating
localities, villages, communes, units and army bases as the key
task in 1988.''
   A text of the editorial, which was quoted by the official
domestic radio Tuesday, was obtained from a Western embassy in
Bangkok today.
   The paper said the government continues to have problems
countering the propaganda war the guerrillas mounted after
Vietnamese forces backing Phnom Penh overran all major guerrilla
bases along the Thai border in 1984-85.
   Vietnam invaded the country in late 1978 and is regarded with
deep-seated enmity by many Cambodians. But people also fear the
return of the Khmer Rouge, who comprise the largest guerrilla group
in the Cambodian resistance.
   The Vietnamese ousted the Khmer Rouge, which killed hundreds of
thousands of people during its three-year rule.
   On May 10, Khmer Rouge radio claimed guerrillas smashed the
Vietnamese administrative network in more than 4,000 villages and
200 communes during the seven-month dry season that ended in April.
   Claims by the Khmer Rouge, however, are widely regarded as
exaggerated.
   Pracheachon said the guerrillas were planting ``secret agents''
and preparing for 1990, when Vietnam has said it will withdraw the
last of its troops from Cambodia.
   ``The militia and police forces in a number of localities do not
act as a real support for the people in attacks against the
enemy,'' it said.
   ``The people's living conditions there remain primitive (and)
have not improved ... The party and state policy has not reached
the people, causing a number of them to be misguided by enemy
propaganda. Many of them are even helping in enemy maneuvers.''
   Khmer Rouge radio has said the guerrillas, working in small
groups, use villagers' homes as support bases and hiding places.
   Phnom Penh has been trying with its propaganda to lure
guerrillas and their supporters back into the fold with promises of
amnesty, jobs and rewards.
</TEXT>
