<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Olympics     05-18 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Olympics,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leaders Urge Talks To Bring North Into Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of South Korea's three
main opposition parties today urged the government of Roh Tae-woo
to resume talks aimed at persuading North Korea to enter the Summer
Olympics.
   They made the call in a meeting to discuss a common
parliamentary strategy for dealing with the Roh government, a joint
announcement said.
   Leading dissidents and anti-government students also have called
for talks to bring the north into the Seoul games, which begin
Sept. 17.
   There was no immediate government reaction to the opposition
call.
   But on Monday, Park Seh-jik, president of the Seoul Olympic
Organizing Committee, expressed a willingness to allow North Korean
participation ``if the International Olympic Committee, other
Olympic families and the Korean people want to do so.'' He said he
would even go to Pyongyang for such talks.
   Today's meeting among Kim Dae-jung of the largest opposition
Peace and Democracy party, Kim Young-sam of the Reunification
Democratic Party and Kim Jong-pil of the New Democratic Republican
Party, was their first since the opposition won an unprecedented
majority in the National Assembly on April 26.
   The three Kims urged the government to ``make utmost efforts and
show generosity'' in negotiating with the north for its entry in
the Olympics. They said the games should be made ``a new turning
point'' for reunification of the communist north and capitalist
south, which have been divided for 43 years.
   After several rounds of unsuccessful talks with South Korea and
the International Olympic Committee, the north decided to boycott
the games unless it was made co-host.
   Despite fears by some that the north might try to sabotage the
games, a record 161 countries, including North Korean allies China
and the Soviet Union, have accepted invitations to enter.
   The International Olympic Committee, with the south's consent,
offered to let the north stage some events while rejecting the
co-host demand. Pyongyang claims that making Seoul the exclusive
host would hinder Korean reunification.
   Kim Dae-jung today urged that efforts be made, in the interests
of north-south reconciliation, to form a unified Korean Olympic
team and suggested considering offering the north virtual co-host
status, his aides said.
   On other major domestic issues, the three Kims agreed to push
for the formation of several special committees in the legislature
to investigate corruption and the government's violent suppression
of the 1980 Kwangju civil uprising, their statement said.
   They also urged the government to release all political
prisoners and pledged anew to work for parliamentary democracy
through dialogue and compromise.
</TEXT>
