<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Rattle Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms boomed over the central High Plains today after
unleashing a tornado and hail as big as golf balls in Nebraska,
while rain fell from Florida to New England.
   Strong thunderstorms developed in the Nebraska Panhandle as
showers and thunderstorms continued over southern Nebraska and
northern and western Kansas.
   Showers were scattered over the southern Rockies and the
northern High Plains.
   Showers lingered from New England to Virginia, and showers and a
few thunderstorms fell along the East Coast from North Carolina to
northeast Florida. Cloudy skies and scattered showers dampened
Washingon state and Oregon. Fair skies prevailed across the rest of
the nation.
   In Nebraska on Tuesday, the storms produced a tornado that
touched down a mile or two southeast of Harrisburg in the
Panhandle, but no damage was reported. Golf ball-size hail fell in
Oconto in the central section of the state.
   Winds gusted to 49 mph in Goodland in northwest Kansas.
Thunderstorms dropped large hail on the Carolinas.
   High-temperature records were set in seven Southern or
Midwestern cities and tied in four.
   It was 94 degrees in Texarkana, Ark., where the old record of 93
was set in 1913. Records were also set in New Orleans, Mobile,
Ala.; Monroe, La.; Pensacola, Fla.; Rapid City, S.D.; and Fort
Smith, Ark. Records were tied in Apalachicola, Fla.; Baton Rouge,
La.; El Dorado, Ark.; and Lake Charles, La.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over central and southern Florida, from New England to the Middle
Atlantic states and from the central Appalachians to the Carolinas;
thunderstorms from the Dakotas and western portions of the central
and southern Plains to the central and southern Rockies, Utah and
parts of Arizona; and showers over parts of Idaho and the Pacific
Northwest.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 70s or 80s over
much of the nation; in the 60s in the Pacific Northwest and the
northern Rockies, and from the eastern Great Lakes to Pennsylvania,
northern West Virginia and the northern Atlantic Coast; and the 90s
in the desert Southwest and from the central Gulf Coast to parts of
the central and southern Plains.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 79 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 63 fair; Boston 53 cloudy; Buffalo 49 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 66 cloudy; Cincinnati 57 fair; Cleveland 53
foggy; Detroit 49 fair; Miami 70 fair; New York 58 foggy;
Philadelphia 60 showery; Pittsburgh 54 partly cloudy; Portland,
Maine, 55 foggy; Washington 62 drizzle.
   _Central: Bismarck 72 windy; Chicago 48 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
75 fair; Denver 64 partly cloudy; Des Moines 60 fair; Indianapolis
57 fair; Kansas City 63 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 55 fair;
Nashville 60 fair; New Orleans 73 partly cloudy; St. Louis 62 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 61 windy; Anchorage 47 cloudy; Las Vegas 67
fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 81 cloudy; Salt Lake City 53
cloudy; San Diego 60 partly cloudy; San Francisco 53 windy; Seattle
48 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 50 partly cloudy; Toronto 48 fair.
</TEXT>
