<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-18 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Stronger, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged higher in light European
trading early today, with traders predicting restrained activity a
day after the dollar's sharp gains. Gold prices fell.
   While a sharply improved U.S. trade performance in March boosted
the dollar on Tuesday, dealers predicted the dollar was unlikely to
gain much more ground and said its downward trend had not been
reversed.
   ``If you calculate an average of the last two U.S. (trade)
deficits, you get $11.75 billion,'' said a senior trader in Milan,
Italy. ``That's still a nasty figure.''
   The dollar surged Tuesday after the U.S. Commerce Department
said the nation's trade deficit dropped to $9.7 billion from $13.8
billion in February.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose to a closing 125.53 Japanese yen from 124.82 yen at
Tuesday's close. Later, in London, it dipped to 125.50 yen.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8586 from $1.8630 late
Tuesday. The pound dropped 3 cents on Tuesday after the Bank of
England signaled a cut of half a percentage point in the commercial
banks' base lending rate to 7.5 percent to force down the surging
currency.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday:
   --1.7053 West German marks, up from 1.7045
   --1.4215 Swiss francs, up from 1.4190
   --5.7717 French francs, up from 5.7710
   --1.9093 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9060
   --1,265.75 Italian lire, up from 1,264.00
   --1.2373 Canadian dollart, up from 1.2358
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $453 a troy ounce, down
from $453.50 bid late Tuesday. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $452.70.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $453, down from $455 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell to a closing bid of $454.54
from $454.67 bid at Tuesday's close.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $6.55 a troy ounce, down
from $6.59 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
