<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vanuatu     05-18 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vanuatu,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australian Prime Minister Blames Libya For Riots In Vanuatu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke today blamed
Libya for a riot in Vanuatu that left one person dead and nine
injured in the capital of that tiny South Pacific island nation.
   A New Zealand military aircraft that took riot gear to Vanuatu
returned home today with more than 25 New Zealanders aboard. The
government of Prime Minister David Lange said it would keep
monitoring the situation in Vanuatu.
   ``There is no doubt about a Libyan connection in Vanuatu,'' said
Hawke, following reports in the Australian media that
Libyan-trained activists were involved in Monday's riots in the
capital of Port Vila.
   Police said 30 people were arrested after a march by 2,000
villagers in Port Vila became a riot, with protesters looting shops
and smashing store windows.
   Australia also airlifted supplies of riot control gear at the
request of the Vanuatu government, headed by Prime Minister Walter
Lini, who also is an Anglican priest.
   ``Lini is the democratically elected head of a government of a
friendly country ... and Australia can't stand idly by if there are
attempts to undermine by non-democratic process that government,''
Hawke told reporters.
   He presented no evidence to back up his charge against Libya.
   Vanuatu, formerly the Anglo-French New Hebrides, was
administered jointly by Britain and France from 1906 until 1980,
when it achieved independence. The island group is 1,200 miles
northeast of the Australian city of Brisbane and has a population
of 130,000.
   Vanuatu sent shockwaves through the generally pro-Western South
Pacific when it decided in 1986 to establish diplomatic relations
with Libya and the Soviet Union.
   Villagers from three tribes decided to march on Lini's office
following last week's closure of the Vila Urban Land Corp. The
government agency administered leases for land on which Port Vila,
a town of 15,000 people, is built and which the tribes say belong
to them by tradition.
   The official Radio Vanuatu said today that life was slowly
``trickling back'' despite injuries and extensive damage to shops
and offices. It said Lini requested civil servants to return to
work and help repair the damage.
</TEXT>
