<HEAD>Singers Perform For Unusual Audience</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, `One of ...,' to CORRECT that theme of
musical, not song, is triumph of poor.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 900 residents of homeless shelters,
nursing homes and centers for the mentally ill and handicapped
attended a Broadway spectacular featuring songs from a show close
to their hearts, ``Les Miserables.''
   One of the stars of that show, Randy Graff, sang her big number,
``I Dreamed a Dream.'' The theme of the musical is the triumph of
people regarded as society's outcasts.
   ``It kind of gives you a view of what everyone else considers
reality,'' said Mignon Bowe, who said she became homeless after she
fractured an ankle and lost her job.
   Seventeen singing stars, including cast members from other hit
shows like ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' belted out their hits
Tuesday at a Manhattan auditorium.
   ``This is the first time I've ever been to a place like this,''
said 77-year-old Martha Sicilia, who lives in Cliffside Nursing
Home in Queens.
   ``This is doing what normal people do,'' said Susan Nayowith, a
social worker at a shelter run by the Lenox Hill Neighborhood
Association. ``Most of all, it helps their self-esteem.''
   Also performing were two-time Tony award-winner Dorothy Loudon
and cabaret singer Julie Wilson.
   The event was organized by Hospital Associates Inc., a
non-profit group that stages about 3,500 cultural programs annually
throughout the city.
</TEXT>
