<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudentBurglars 1stLd-Writethru a0641 05-18 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Burglars, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Allegedly Broke Into Cars With Tools Made In Shop Class</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to recast. Picks up in 3rd graf,
`Authorities contend ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One teen-ager pleaded guilty and four others
pleaded innocent to charges they broke into at least 33 vehicles in
what police called a high school burglary ring operation.
   Police said the students, using tools they made in shop class,
sold the stereos, radar detectors and other items they pilfered.
   Authorities contend the boys used tools made in metal shop or
bent coat hangers to break into the vehicles in Peoria. They were
arrested after an anonymous tip to police.
   The stolen items were sold to fellow students and other
residents in Metamora, a community of about 2,500 people 17 miles
northeast of here, police said.
   The five youths remain under house arrest. Since they were
charged late last month, they have been prohibited from leaving
their homes for any reason except to attend school.
   Three other boys charged a week later remain in their parents'
custody while their cases are pending. They are expected to enter
pleas Thursday to one count each of vehicle burglary.
   Assistant Peoria County State's Attorney Kim Nuss said two girls
also took part in one burglary but probably will not be charged
because police can't find the owner of the car they allegedly
burglarized.
   The youth who pleaded guilty Tuesday did so under a plea-bargain
arrangement, Ms. Nuss said. She said the 16-year-old pleaded guilty
to three counts of vehicle burglary, and another three counts were
dropped.
   The four others, ages 15 to 17, pleaded innocent to multiple
counts of vehicle burglary in Peoria Juvenile Court.
</TEXT>
