<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0495 05-18 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs, Peres comments today; picks up 4th graf
pvs, Until now.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said
today he believes there is a ``fair chance'' the Soviet Union will
move towards taking a role within the U.S. framework for peace in
the Middle East.
   Peres, a strong backer of the American peace plan, made his
comments after meeting in Washington Tuesday with the Soviet
ambassador to the United States.
   ``I think that there is a fair chance that the Russians will
make some moves in the direction of the United States proposal,''
said Peres, interviewed from Toronto on NBC-TV's ``Today'' program.
   ``I'm not sure they will be able to reach a conclusion, but even
if they will reach some progress it will be of importance and great
meaning,'' he said.
   Soviet ambassador Yuri Dubinin expressed ``significant
differences'' in the Soviet position at the meeting, saying the
Kremlin no longer insists on a dominant role for an international
conference in Arab-Israeli peace talks, according to an Israel
source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Peres said today he welcomed the participation of Kremlin leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, but insisted the Soviets would have to work
within the American blueprint.
   ``The problem is not his participation, but the nature of his
participation,'' Peres said. ``It depends very much on the the
Russian policy. ... If there will be the slightest attempt to try
to teach us a lesson or to impose a solution, I think all parties
will refuse.''
   Until now, the United States and Israel rejected Soviet demands
that the superpowers be given an active role in Arab-Israeli talks.
The U.S. peace plan envisions the superpowers only as overseers
devoid of any power to impose.
   Earlier, Assistant Secretary of State Rozanne Ridgway told
reporters the Soviets remain ambiguous about their position on the
peace plan. The Soviets have ``made some hints. We will keep
plugging away at them, and the whole notion of the peace process
will be on the ... summit agenda,'' she said.
   The meeting with Dubinin follows contacts Peres held last week
with Soviet officials in Europe. Based on those contacts, Peres
said he expects the Soviet Union will tell President Reagan at the
superpower summit in Moscow later this month that they are backing
a U.S.-sponsored Mideast peace plan.
   ``I think the occasion will really be in the summit meeting to
have the Russians adopt the needs of the Middle East and not the
Middle East submitting to ideas that were born in Moscow,'' Peres
told reporters following a 30-minute meeting with Reagan.
   Peres and Secretary of State George P. Shultz both hope Soviet
backing will draw Jordan and the Palestinians into the stalled
peace process, thereby forcing Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir to join too. Shamir has rejected the international auspices
the plan envisions for Arab-Israeli talks.
   In a clear reference to Shamir, the White House said:
   ``Those leaders who are negative, consistently reject new ideas
and fail to exploit realistic opportunities to bring about
negotiations, make progress impossible. In the end they will have
to answer to their own people for the suffering that will
inevitably result.''
   The statement praised Peres, saying he ``is creative and has the
courage and wisdom to say yes when real opportunities arise.''
   Shultz, in a prepared statement following three meetings with
Peres, praised his ``commitment and resolve'' toward finding peace
formulas, giving the foreign minister a boost on which he intends
to capitalize when he runs against Shamir in November's general
elections.
   But Peres, asked by reporters whether he viewed the praise as a
political endorsement, said Israel and the United States do not
interfere in each others' politics.
   The White House, asked whether its statement could be construed
as tilting toward Peres in his competition with Shamir for Israel's
leadership, said only: ``Our statement stands on its own.''
   Shultz said he was embarking on another Mideast shuttle mission
June 3 because he believes the U.S. plan is the only workable
alternative to the violence there.
   But he conceded ``the odds against a breakthrough are high.
Pessimism and cynicism run deep.''
</TEXT>
