<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EconomicMeeting     05-18 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economic Meeting,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Says World Economic Outlook Bright</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III said
today the world economic outlook was bright but that U.S. trading
partners needed to move faster with economic reforms.
   He said South Korea, Taiwan and other rapidly growing Asian
economies were hurting efforts to correct world trade imbalances by
failing to deregulate their domestic markets and make them more
open to foreign exporters and investors.
   ``Their (trade) surpluses, particularly in the case of Korea and
Taiwan, are impeding the adjustment of global imbalances and adding
to protectionist pressures,'' Baker told trade and finance
ministers from 24 leading industrial nations.
   Citing the Commerce Department's report Tuesday of an
unexpectedly large drop in the U.S. March trade deficit, Baker said
prospects were good for keeping the world economy on an even keel.
   ``While the near-term economic situation looks encouraging, we
need to maintain this momentum in the medium-term,'' he told the
opening session of a two-day ministerial meeting of the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
   Baker praised Japan, West Germany and Britain for making
economic adjustments that have helped to prevent last October's
stock market crash from pushing the world economy into a recession.
   He added, however, that the European natios need to reduce their
high unemployment and promote faster economic growth, while Japan
should ensure greater foreign access to its financial markets.
   Baker said the administration of President Reagan had
contributed to helping the world economy by cutting its budget
deficit last year, boosting exports and increasing the consumer
savings rate.
   He said the U.S. general budget deficit _ including state and
local governments _ had fallen to a level lower than the average
for the OECD nations as a group.
   European and Japanese officials struck a similarly upbeat tone,
but they stressed that the Reagan administration should do more to
reduce the federal budget gap.
   ``Efforts by the United States to reduce its budget deficit and
by the European countries to attain robust economic growth are
indispensable,'' said Sousuke Uno, the Japanese foreign minister.
   Uno echoed Baker's call for South Korea and other newly
industrialized nations to play a greater role in efforts to
coordinate world economic policies.
   None of the emerging economic powers in Southeast Asia, which
also include Singapore and Hong Kong, was represented at the OECD
ministerial meeting.
   Jacques Delors, chief executive of the European Economic
Community, told the meeting these Asian nations, which he called
``the four Asian tigers,'' must be encouraged to ``join the club''
of rich nations seeking to coordinate policies.
   Delors also said that while the American economy remained
buoyant, U.S. consumer demand ``at some stage'' will slow down,
presenting a challenge to Europe to pick up the slack in economic
growth.
   The OECD meeting was expected to focus also on efforts to reduce
government subsidies to farmers and to cut down on the accumulation
of farm product surpluses.
   Baker said the best way to coordinate reforms in agriculture was
through the global trade liberalization talks, known as the Uruguay
Round, now getting under way in Geneva.
   ``All countries, however, are responsible for the ultimate
success of the round, not simply the industrial nations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
