<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Tests,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit to Begin Random Drug Tests on Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city will begin random drug testing for its
5,000 police officers next week, Mayor Coleman Young says.
   The mayor said Tuesday about 100 officers could be tested a day,
and the testing would begin in the department's narcotics
department.
   ``It will be fair. It will be thorough. But it will be given,''
Young said.
   If a police officer fails the urinalysis, there will be up to
three more tests before any disciplinary action is taken.
   Drug tests are performed only on police recruits and officers
transferring to the narcotics division, winning a promotion or
suspected of drug abuse.
   Police union officials withheld immediate comment on the
program. The Detroit Police Officers Association and the
Lieutenants and Sergeants Association have filed lawsuits to block
drug testing.
</TEXT>
