<HEAD>Former Choral Singer Pleads Guilty to Thefts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former singer in the Chicago Symphony Orchestra
Chorus has pleaded guilty to charges he stole $47,000 from the
chorus director, a choral foundation and a fellowship fund.
   Christopher Graves, a tenor in the chorus since 1974, entered a
guilty plea to theft and forgery charges Tuesday and was ordered to
pay full restitution and to perform 400 hours of community service.
   Prosecutors say Graves, 40, was an administrative assistant of
the American Choral Foundation, headed by chorus director Margaret
Hillis, when the thefts occurred. He was also administrative
assistant of the Hillis Fellowship Fund, which helps pay for choral
members' voice lessons.
   He was accused of illegally diverting money from the fellowship
fund, the foundation and Hillis's personal account between August
1984 and November 1986, when Hillis discovered funds missing.
