<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Donovan-Meese     05-18 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Donovan-Meese,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Labor Secretary Donovan Says Meese Should Remain in Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Labor Secretary Raymond Donovan said
today that embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III should remain
in office to ensure that the constitutional right of innocence
until proven guilty is not further weakened.
   ``If the leading law enforcement officer of this country, Ed
Meese, is drummed from that office and run out of that town
(Washington) and presumption of innocence is further eroded, that's
a danger to the people,'' Donovan said in an interview from New
York on the CBS ``This Morning'' program.
   Donovan, the first sitting Cabinet member to be indicted, was
found innocent in May 1987 of larceny and fraud charges that forced
him from office in 1985.
   Criminal investigations of Meese have led to unrest and
resignations at the Justice Department.
   President Reagan, who Donovan said stood by him during his legal
problems, on Tuesday reaffirmed his faith in Meese, comparing the
attorney general's situation to that of Donovan.
   The former labor secretary noted the similarities between
himself and Meese.
   ``Those who believed in me, just as those who believe in Ed
Meese, know us to be the honorable people that we are, but there's
a certain segment that you can never convince,'' he said.
   Donovan said Reagan is a ``true friend (who) doesn't believe in
shooting his wounded like many others do in that city of
Washington.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
