<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-Embezzlement 1stLd-Writethru a04phisticatedcriminalenterprise.''spokesmanfortheparolecommissioninWashington
05-18 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Embezzlement, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deceased Jewish Leader Suspected of Embezzling Holocaust Survivor
Funds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with Nachmann's lawyer
confirming suspicion, saying he discovered the funds were missing.
Picks up ``13th graf pvs, `Galinski said ...
^By TERRENCE PETTY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before he died this year, the
long-time head of the nation's Jewish community apparently
embezzled millions of dollars in government funds earmarked for
Holocaust survivors, his successor said.
   A family lawyer said today that he believed Werner Nachmann, the
former president of the Jewish Council of West Germany, stole the
money to bankroll his troubled business. The lawyer said Nachmann's
heirs have filed for bankruptcy.
   ``I am shocked, horrified and furious that such a thing could be
even possible,'' Heinz Galinski, Nachmann's successor as council
president, said Tuesday.
   Hessicher Rundfunk radio in Frankfurt reported that the council
believes Nachmann, who died in January, embezzled about $19 million
in Holocaust reparations from 1980 to 1987.
   Galinski confirmed that an investigation had been launched and
said Nachmann was suspected of having stolen more than $6 million
in interest accumulated from Holocaust survivor funds.
   He called the radio's figure ``pure speculation.''
   Lawyer Peter Paepcke, who said he had worked for Nachmann for a
decade, claimed he discovered the irregularities and estimated
Nachmann had embezzled as much as $15.6 million.
   ``I'm afraid that what has been said by the Jewish Council is by
and large correct,'' he said by telephone from Karlsruhe, where
Nachmann lived and owned a textile and raw materials wholesale
business.
   Nachmann, president of the council since 1965 until his death at
age 62 of a heart attack, was in charge of disbursing the funds to
Holocaust survivors around the world and had unlimited access to
them, the radio report said.
   About $236 million was appropriated by the government in 1980
for Holocaust survivors who had not previously made reparations
claims. The funds were in addition to $47 billion already paid by
West Germany to Holocaust survivors or victims' families.
   The radio report said Nachmann was suspected of taking interest
accumulated from the funds and transferring it to ``among others,
his own company accounts.''
   ``Learning of this surprised and dismayed the council's
directorate, which immediately informed government leaders,''
Galinski said in a telephone interview from his Berlin office.
   ``This has presented me with the most serious problem I have
ever faced in my 40 years of working for the Jewish community,'' he
added.
   Galinski said the Jewish Council ``has contracted with financial
experts to look into the accusations'' and the investigation is
expected to take two to three weeks.
   ``I'm afraid he was getting too overworked and used the money to
keep the company going. He was also under great stress in his job
as head of the Jewish community, and the whole thing just overtook
him,'' Paepcke said of Nachmann, whose company employed 26 people.
   He said he had recently filed for bankruptcy for the family
company and expected the case to be heard in the next week or two.
   Galinski said the council had asked a civil court in Karlsruhe
to freeze money from Nachmann's estate pending an investigation
into the allegations.
   A court spokesman, Alfred Mueller, told the AP that no action
has yet been taken on the council's application.
   Nachmann had been active in trying to help heal wounds in West
Germany left by the Holocaust, in which about 6 million Jews were
killed during Nazi rule.
   Nachmann's family fled Nazi Germany to France in 1938. He
returned to Karlsruhe in 1945 and began working toward
re-establishing Jewish communities in the country.
   About 525,000 Jews lived in Germany when the Nazis took power in
1933. West Germany has about 30,000 Jewish residents today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
