<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RightsRap 1stLd-Writethru a0618 05-18 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rights Rap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Civil Rights Rap' Makes History Lesson Hard To Beat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 14th graf, `The ``Civil...' to restore dropped word
`material.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Civil Rights Rap,'' a six-minute rap and
video excursion into the civil rights movement, makes the history
lesson a whole new song and dance.
   The video, starring 30 high school students from Massachusetts
and aimed at a young audience, covers some of the major events of
the civil rights movement, setting to rap prose the stories of the
Montgomery bus boycott, the Supreme Court decision which ended
school segregation and the 1960s sit-ins.
   The video, to be shown at the 12th Atlanta Film & Video
Festival, which opens tonight, begins with the rappers from
Lincoln-Sudbury Regional High School moonwalking to a driving beat
and offering historical raps such as this verse about the 1956 bus
boycott in Montgomery, Ala., which propelled the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr. to national prominence:
   ``This short rap tells of Rosa Parks,
   ``Who caused some friction, set off some sparks.
   ``Rosa wasn't gonna moan, she wasn't gonna fuss.
   ``She just sat down at the front of the bus.
   ``Cops they came and threw her off the line.
   ``Rosa was told that she had to pay a fine.
   ``Blacks all said, `We refuse to ride.'
   ``They had their dignity, they had their pride.
   ``It took a while but after a time,
   ``Blacks up front was no longer a crime.''
   The ``Civil Rights Rap'' is the product of Rapping Up History, a
non-profit project devoted to developing innovative educational
material to make history more attractive to a new generation.
   The video shows the young actors portraying the events in the
song, and includes shots of the rappers performing and documentary
footage from the 1963 March on Washington. It ends with King's ``I
Have A Dream'' speech.
   History teacher Thom Thacker conceived te idea out of his desire
to involve students in learning, said Richard DeLaura, a friend of
Thacker who put the teacher's words to music and produced the song.
   The students, including six rappers who call themselves the Go
Ill Crew, recorded audiocassettes of the song and sold them to
raise money to produce the video.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0661 05-18 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0661,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Mediator Says End To Militia Fighting Would `Solve'
Hostage Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 12-15, bgng, `Syria massed...' to UPDATE with
quotes from Kenaan. Pick up 16th pvs, `An Amal...' Edits thereafter
to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian mediator seeking to end 13
days of fighting between rival Shiite Moslem militias said today
the problem of foreign hostages in Lebanon would be solved if the
combat stopped.
   Ali Mohammed Besharati, Iran's acting foreign minister, told
reporters: ``The case of kidnapping (of foreigners) in Lebanon is
part of the crisis which Lebanon is passing through. I believe that
if we could end the state of war currently prevailing, then
definitely the other case would be solved too.''
   He made the statement in response to reporters' questions after
a meeting with Salim Hoss, Lebanon's acting prime minister.
Besharati would not elaborate on the issue of the hostages, most of
whom are believed held by extremists loyal to Iran.
   Most of the 18 hostages, including nine Americans, are believed
held in Beirut's southern slums, where fighting between the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the Syrian-backed Amal
has raged since May 6.
   Lebanese security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said that during the meeting with Hoss, Besharati sought support
for an Iranian proposal to end the militia battles.
   One source said Besharati proposed a compromise agreement for
partial deployment of the Syrian army in south Beirut to halt the
bloodshed that has killed 243 people and wounded 762.
   The plan under consideration envisages a Syrian deployment in
the northern districts of the southern slums, where Amal still
holds positions after being dislodged from 90 percent of the
16-square-mile enclave, the source said. The source spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   He said the Syrians ``will not deploy'' in the southern sector
of the disputed area, where Hezbollah has its main bases.
   Besharati would not comment on the report. But he said Iran was
seeking the ``formation of a force to preserve security in south
Beirut.''
   Asked if the Syrians would be represented in this force,
Besharati said: ``We and our Syrian brothers would guarantee this
force.
   ``It is neither in Syria's interest to deploy in south Beirut
nor does the whole population want Syria to enter south Beirut,'''
Besharati said.
   Syria has massed 7,500 troops and 500 tanks on the southern,
western and northern edges of the zone since the weekend.
   On Tuesday, Besharati told Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, Syria's
military intelligence chief in Lebanon, that Iran did not want
Syrian troops deployed in south Beirut. The two met again today.
   ``We are giving political efforts a chance to solve the problem
and stop the bleeding in south Beirut,'' Kenaan said after today's
meeting. ``But it seems that this effort is not leading to a
tangible outcome.''
   He said Syrian troops were prepared to storm the slums, adding:
``The population has requested the deployment of the Syrian forces
to end their ordeal. We cannot but meet the people's pleas.''
   An Amal spokesman said the militia's chief, Nabih Berri, met
Syrian President Hafez Assad in Damascus on Tuesday and returned to
Beirut after Assad ``assured him that Syrian forces will enter the
suburbs.''
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, also is Iran's main
Arab ally. But Assad's government has recently been alarmed by
Tehran's efforts through Hezbollah to dominate Lebanon's 1.2
million Shiites, the country's largest single sect.
   Local news media have reported that the hostages were moved
since the fighting began.
   One report said they were taken to the basement of the Iranian
Embassy, out of the embattled region. The embassy denied that.
   Another report said they were moved from an exposed Hezbollah
barracks to the home of the militia's spokesman on the fringes of
the zone. That could not be verified.
</TEXT>
