<HEAD>Three Hurt When Explosion Rips Special Effects Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fireworks explosion during testing of
movie special effects tore through a chemical supply house,
injuring three people, one critically, officials said.
   No fire was reported after the blast Tuesday afternoon at
TRI-ESS Sciences, said police Lt. Joe Latta.
   One of the employees injured, Leroy Thomas Hage, 23, underwent
surgery for an abdominal cut and today was in serious condition and
improving, said hospital spokeswoman Norka Manning.
   The other, Fernan Fernandez, 29, was in serious condition with
stomach wounds, Ms. Manning said. Tri-ESS owner Ira Katz, who
suffered cuts and a hand injury, was treated at a hospital and
released.
   ``We were testing pyrotechnics _ special effects for a motion
picture,'' Katz said after returning to his business later Tuesday.
   Fire Chief Ken Whittekind said the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
bomb squad determined that the explosion was caused by the mixture
of two, still undetermined, chemicals.
   Damage to the building was estimated at less than $500,
Whittekind said.
   A spokeswoman for Tri-ESS said the company sells chemical
supplies to industry and schools and a smoke-producing product to
the entertainment industry.
