<HEAD>Tree Warden Race Draws Unusual Crowd</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This town of about 250 registered voters
was puzzled when it found itself with four candidates for the job
of tree warden.
   The root of the problem?
   The candidates didn't know anyone else was running.
   This Berkshire Hills town often has trouble getting enough
candidates to fill out its ballot, let alone more than one hopeful
for each office. Tree warden was the only contested office out of
17 on Tuesday's ballot.
   Helene Morandi, the wife of the election winner, John Morandi,
said her husband is retired and decided to run because he thought
no one else would.
   ``I don't know how there got to be so many of us,'' said another
candidate, Louise G. Dellea, a former tree warden who was drafted
because he thought no one was seeking the job.
   A second former tree warden, David Germain, said he also ran
believing there were no other candidates.
   Election runner-up Louise Hardy had simply said: ``If elected,
I'll find out what the job entails.''
