<2ND_LINE>PM-Brick Punishment,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Orders Texas School To Stop Practice of Brick Punishment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NACOGDOCHES, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State education officials ordered a
school district to stop hanging bricks around youngsters' necks to
make them remember to bring supplies to school.
   Four elementary school pupils were required to carry bricks in
their hands or around their necks last month, said James Bogue,
superintendent of the 400-student Central Heights School District
in Nacogdoches County.
   ``I want to tell you it sounds worse than it was,'' Bogue said
Tuesday.
   The practice was ``something short of punishment, a way to
remind students to bring their materials to class,'' he said.
Pupils could carry the brick in their hands, he said, although some
chose to wear it around the neck.
   Bogue said the district schools will no longer use the bricks.
   Spokeswoman Terri Moore said the Texas Education Agency received
a telephone complaint May 9 and told Bogue to discontinue the
practice. No written complaints, which would lead to a formal
investigation, were received.
   Houston firefighter James Barclay said his 13-year-old son, who
lives with a grandmother in Nacogoches, had to wear a brick bearing
the words, ``I forgot my pencil.''
   Bogue said teachers had discipline problems with the boy. ``It's
on the record that he was sent to the principal's office 49
times,'' he said.
</TEXT>
