<HEAD>Police Battle 5,000 Marcos Supporters In Philippines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with protesters clashing with police, four
women injured. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today fired tear gas and smoke
bombs to disperse 5,000 supporters of deposed President Ferdinand
Marcos who rallied to protest the government's refusal to allow him
to attend his mother's funeral.
   At least four women suffered injuries from the tear gas during
the confrontation, according to rally leader Salvador Panelo.
   The Marcos supporters staged a rally in central Bonifacio Square
to demand the return of Marcos for the funeral of his mother,
Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4.
   A breakaway group of 2,000 demonstrators later marched toward
the U.S. Embassy and were blocked near Manila City Hall by 50
policemen, reporters at the scene said.
   A police spokesman said the demonstrators were dispersed when
they started throwing stones at the officers, who fought back with
truncheons. Police used tear gas and smoke bombs to disperse the
marchers.
   Panelo said the police intervention ``only demonstrates the
weakness of this government because it is afraid of the people's
voice.''
   The protesters scattered in various directions but tried to
regroup in Bonifacio Square, where they held the earlier rally.
   Col. Emiliano Templo, deputy chief of the Capital Command,
appealed to the marchers to stay calm. He said he would allow an
overnight vigil by the protesters, but police blocked access to
road leading to the presidential palace.
   Rally leaders want President Corazon Aquino to reconsider her
refusal to allow Marcos to return to the Philippines for his
mother's funeral. Marcos lives in Hawaii, where he fled after the
February 1986 revolt which toppled his 20-year regime.
</TEXT>
