<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Indelicato-Freedman     05-18 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indelicato-Freedman,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mistrial Declared in Fraud and Conspiracy Trial of Indelicato Ally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mistrial was declared in the fraud and
conspiracy trial of a man accused of participating in a kickback
scheme with the former top education adviser to Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis.
   A 12-member jury deliberated 3{ days on one count of conspiracy
and one of mail fraud against Michael Freedman. On Tuesday, the
panel said it could not reach a unanimous verdict.
   The key stumbling block appeared to be whether the prosecution
had proved willfulness on Freedman's part in accepting kickback
money. After the jury raised that question Tuesday morning, U.S.
District Judge Douglas Woodlock again charged the jury on legal
issues.
   Woodlock set a new trial July 11. A new jury will be chosen.
   Gerard Indelicato, who became the governor's education adviser
in March 1983, headed the state's adult education program at the
time the alleged scheme got under way.
   He pleaded guilty last month to participating in the alleged
scheme and testified against Freedman. He is to be sentenced July
8. Assistant U.S. Attorney Ralph Gants declined to say whether
Indelicato would testify in Freedman's new trial.
   Indelicato won a recommendation from prosecutors for a reduced
sentence in exchange for his cooperation in what Gants called an
``ongoing investigation.''
   Indelicato testified that the scheme involved skimming $80,000
from two adult education programs from 1979 to 1983. The money, he
testified, was shared among Freedman, Indelicato, his brother
Joseph and a fourth conspirator, Antonio Perrotta.
   All but Freedman have pleaded guilty.
   Prosecutors agreed to recommend to Woodlock that Indelicato
receive a five-year prison term and pay an $80,000 fine. Woodlock
could exceed that if he chose.
   Indelicato became Dukakis' education adviser two months after
the conspiracy alleged by the government ended. He testified that
while he worked for Dukakis' election bid in 1982, he was receiving
kickbacks of hundreds of dollars per month from the adult education
program.
   ``It was a regular income, if you will, for all of us,''
Indelicato said.
   Indelicato said Freedman accepted his share and was aware of the
source of the money. But he did not depict Freedman as an architect
of the scheme.
   Freedman's attorney, John Burns, did not return telephone calls
seeking comment.
</TEXT>
