<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessHotel     05-18 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Hotel,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Aid Society: High-Priced Cubicles Violate Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hotel that's home to 455 homeless families is
charging the city as much as $1,160 a month for 9-by-12-foot
cubicles without bathrooms, according to advocates for the homeless.
   The Martinique Hotel has subdivided existing rooms to obtain at
least 80 of the cubicles, in violation of state regulations,
according to lawyers for the Legal Aid Society.
   A state hearing officer who ordered the city to stop using such
a room last month found that it ``fails to even minimally conform
to the standards set forth in department regulations.''
   The officer noted in his decision that Room 1127 was too small
to accommodate a table and chairs, lacked a private bathroom and
was infested with roaches. A mother and two young children occupied
the room.
   ``The state has a role to perform _ enforcing its regulations _
and it's not doing that,'' said Steven Banks, an attorney with the
society's Homeless Family Rights project.
   Suzanne Trazoff, a spokeswoman for the city's Human Resources
Administration, admitted that the room violates state regulations,
but said the state knows the city is trying to end the practice of
housing families in hotels.
   A woman who answered the telephone at the hotel and refused to
identify herself said there was no one available to speak to the
press. She said the hotel manager would be in ``sometime this
afternoon.''
</TEXT>
