<HEAD>Two Killed, One Critically Hurt in Domino's Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with victims shot in head, money missing
from store, ages of victims, quotes from police chief. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A management trainee and his wife were
shot to death in the head and another man was critically wounded
during a possible robbery at a Domino's Pizza, Police Chief James
Gabbard said today.
   The trainee, Bill Edwards, 27, and his wife, Frances, 29, a
driver for the chain, were killed late Tuesday night, Gabbard said.
   Matthew Boornoosh, another Domino's employee, and the couple
were each shot in the head in a back room, he said, adding that
none of the victims was bound.
   The Edwards were the parents of a 2-year-old daughter, Tiffany,
who was home with a baby sitter when they were killed.
   ``We're investigating robbery as the probable motive, but we
don't have any conclusive evidence at this time,'' Gabbard said.
Police have no witnesses, he added.
   Police have been unable to interview Boornoosh, 27, who
underwent emergency surgery and was listed in critical condition
early today at Indian River Memorial Hospital.
   An undisclosed amount of money was missing from the cash
register, Gabbard said.
   ``The store was open at the time. There was no signs of forced
entry,'' he said. ``The way they were shot leads us to believe more
than one person was involved.''
   The victims, were discovered about midnight when a customer
drove to the store because his pizza hadn't been delivered.
   ``The lights were out, and he knew something was wrong,''
Gabbard said.
