<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ZeroTolerance     05-18 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zero Tolerance,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Monkey Business' Released With No Fine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0680 to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Monkey Business, the yacht that
took Gary Hart on a cruise with Donna Rice, was released without
fines or punishment after having been seized under the
controversial new ``zero tolerance'' drug policy.
   The yacht was boarded by the U.S. Coast Guard Saturday near
Bimini, and searchers discovered a marijuana cigarette aboard.
About eight ounces more of pot was found when the boat docked in
Miami Beach, the Coast Guard said.
   However, no one was charged, and the U.S. Customs Service, which
usually takes over such cases, refused jurisdiction over the boat.
   ``After reviewing the case of the Monkey Business, the Customs
Service feels the matter can be handled best by the Coast Guard,''
said Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   The Coast Guard, in turn, decided the case did not merit
administrative forfeiture or a fine, and released the yacht Tuesday
to its Turnberry Isle owners, said spokesman Joe Dye.
   The zero tolerance program allows confiscation of any vehicle,
plane or vessel carrying even small amounts of drugs.
   The 82-foot yacht was made famous last year by Hart, then a
candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination, who took a
trip to Bimini with model Rice on the vessel. Hart's liaison with
Rice led to his withdrawal from the 1988 presidential race.
   The Monkey Business, which rents for $2,500 a day, sports a hot
tub and a bar adorned with an Oriental rug. Elizabeth Taylor, Jack
Nicholson, Elton John and other personalities have sailed it.
</TEXT>
