<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea-Kwangju 2ndLd-Writethru a0666 05-18 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Kwangju, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0666,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Clash With Police On Anniversary Of Uprising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 7 grafs to UPDATE with nationwide protests; firebombs,
rocks thrown in Seoul clashes; pickup 4th pvs, `Punish Roh ...'
DELETES grafs 11-12 pvs, `In the ...' to CONFORM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KWANGJU, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters called for the overthrow
of President Roh Tae-woo and clashed with police today in
nationwide demonstrations mourning victims of a 1980 uprising.
   Police headquarters in Seoul reported that 43,000 students and
others joined in demonstrations or sit-ins at 106 places across the
nation. The number included 39,000 students demonstrating at 103
colleges, police said.
   In Seoul, fierce clashes erupted after riot police hurling tear
gas grenades broke up a march in the streets near City Hall. Waves
of screaming students charged riot police near Myongdong Cathedral,
blocking streets and hurling rocks, bricks and firebombs.
   ``Down with the military dictatorship which committed the
Kwangju massacre!'' the protesters yelled. ``Drive out the Roh
murder regime!''
   Clashes also broke out in the provincial cities of Sunchon,
Pusan, Chungju and Chongju where students and police fought running
battles in the streets after rallies marking the eighth anniversary
of the Kwangju uprising.
   Police declined to release any figures on injuries or arrests.
   In Kwangju, long lines of mourners, many wearing black ribbons,
filed through Mangwoldong Cemetery as prayers were offered at
altars bearing pictures of people killed in the uprising.
   ``Punish Roh Tae-woo, punish (former president) Chun Doo-hwan,''
some protesters shouted during the services in the city 165 miles
southwest of Seoul.
   About 10,000 people, mostly students, later marched from the
cemetery to the plaza in front of the downtown provincial
government office.
   No police were in sight along the route, but police inside the
office fired tear gas, scattering the protesters.
   When the protesters regrouped, some throwing empty cans at the
police, one officer used a loudspeaker to apologize for what he
called a mistaken firing of tear gas.
   The rally then proceeded peacefully, swelling at one point to an
estimated 50,000 people, with another 20,000 to 30,000 spectators.
   Protesters called for daily demonstrations for the rest of the
week.
   The Korean news agency Yonhap reported that a student angered
because a campus festival was going ahead on the Kwangju
anniversary set himself on fire in Chonan, about 30 miles south of
Seoul. It said he suffered serious burns.
   Police were on nationwide alert, with about 50,000 riot police
deployed in Seoul and other cities and security around government
offices was stepped up.
   The leaders of the three main opposition parties agreed today to
push for formation of a legislative committee to investigate the
Kwangju uprising. The meeting among Kim Dae-jung, Kim Young-sam and
Kim Jong-pil was their first since the combined opposition defeated
Roh's party in National Assembly elections on April 26.
   At the cemetery, relatives of the dead wept at the gravesides
and put up placards denouncing the Roh government and calling for
retribution. Mourning prayers were chanted and incense burned on
the altars.
   ``We must overcome our anguish and sorrow to drive out the
military dictatorship,'' said Chun Ky-ryang, a leader of the
relatives' of those killed in the uprising.
   Roh and Chun were top generals who had just seized power in 1980
when students and citizens took control of Kwangju during protests
in the traditional anti-government stronghold.
   The government says 191 people were killed when troops ended the
uprising, but dissidents claim hundreds died.
   Roh, who took office in February after winning election in
December, has attempted to defuse lingering resentment over Kwangju
by honoring those killed and offering compensation to victims.
</TEXT>
