<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ForeignTrade-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a04</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Trade-Markets, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0428,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good News on Trade Deficit Means Bad News for Stocks, Bonds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with today's activity in the
dollar and on Wall Street; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `Inflation erodes
...'; A version moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After seeing the stock and bond markets take a
tumble over reports of the best U.S. trade performance in three
years, investors and traders may be wondering how much more good
news the markets can stand.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the trade deficit
shrank more than $4 billion in March to $9.7 billion _ the lowest
monthly deficit since March 1985 _ largely on a boom in exports.
   The news was good for the dollar, which surged against other
major currencies Tuesday. The dollar's long-term decline apparently
has paid off by making U.S. exports more attractive, and currency
dealers widely believe monetary authorities aren't likely to
depress its value further.
   The dollar retreated today, however, slipping to around 125.43
Japanese yen in midmorning trading in New York from 125.75 yen late
Tuesday. The U.S. currency also declined to around 1.7046 West
German marks from 1.7065 marks.
   To traders on Wall Street and in the bond market, the trade news
confirmed their recent fears that growing exports reflected strong
economic growth that could ignite high inflation.
   After a brief rally Tuesday, stock prices slumped. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials, which had risen late Monday on
expectations the trade shortfall would narrow, fell 21.22 points to
close at 1,986.41.
   Bond interest rates jumped after initially receding. The yield
on the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond jumped to 9.22
percent from 9.11 percent late Monday.
   Wall Street continued its decline in early trading today. The
Dow average was down 3.15 points at 1,983.26 at 10:30 a.m. EDT.
   Interest rates crept still higher, as the yield on the key
30-year bond edged up to 9.23 percent at around midmorning.
   Inflation erodes the value of fixed-income investments such as
bonds, and tends to depress bond prices and drive interest rates
higher.
   Stock and bond traders saw the 23 percent jump in exports in
March _ to an all-time high of $28.97 billion _ as another sign
that the U.S. economy may be overheating dangerously.
   The markets fear the surge in output of export goods could
aggravate inflation by tightening factory capacity, putting more
spending money into workers' pockets and driving up wage costs due
to shrinking labor pools. That could move the Federal Reserve to
push interest rates even higher to try to curb growth.
   Many traders are so worried about inflation that ``they'd take
almost any (economic) number at this point and put a negative cast
to it,'' said Gary Schlossberg, senior economist for Wells Fargo
Bank in San Francisco.
   The last big dose of good economic news also knocked the wind
out of the markets, when the Labor Department reported that the
nation's unemployment rate in April had dropped to a 14-year low.
   Following the employment report, the Fed nudged short-term
interest rates higher, and major U.S. banks responded by raising
their prime lending rates by half a percentage point to 9 percent.
   As a result, the ``good news is bad news'' syndrome that has
gripped the financial markets made even an improved trade
performance cause for alarm.
   Some economists also were quick to punch holes in the March
trade report.
   The trade deficit for March normally shows a seasonal decline of
around $1 billion anyway, and much of the apparent improvement in
the latest report was due to transitory factors, said John Paulus,
chief economist for the investment firm Morgan Stanley & Co.
   Although total imports rose only 3.6 percent, to $38.7 billion,
imports of goods other than oil increased more than 5 percent, he
noted. On the export side, $600 million of the improvement
reflected sales of gold bullion to Taiwan, which has come under
heavy pressure to reduce its large trade surplus with the United
States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
