<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs 4thLd-Writethru a0686 05-18 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0686,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>46 Sikhs Surrender, Ending 10-Day Siege at Golden Temple</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with officials saying all
militants out of temple, police in control. CORRECTS total death
figure to 37, not including suicides. Pick up 9th pvs, `The
government...' Edits thereafter to trim and conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last 46 Sikh extremists holed up in
the Golden Temple surrendered today and emerged with their hands
up, ending a 10-day siege of Sikhism's holiest shrine, officials
said.
   Police shot and killed one extremist when he tried to flee
during the surrender, and three others committed suicide by
swallowing cyanide capsules.
   ``All of them have come out. No terrorist is inside the
complex,'' said Punjab state police commander K.P.S. Gill.
   Sarabjeet Singh, administrator of the Amritsar district, said,
``The temple is in control of the security forces.''
   At least 37 people, mostly Sikh militants, were killed during
the siege of the 400-year-old Golden Temple, the spiritual and
military stronghold of Sikhs waging a campaign of violence for a
separate Sikh nation in Punjab state.
   The figure does not include the three suicides today and another
militant who swallowed cyanide when 146 other Sikhs surrendered
Sunday.
   Police searched the surrendering militants, including one woman,
and removed and unwound the turbans worn by devout male Sikhs, who
do not cut their hair and coil it in a knot under the headgear.
   Commandos surrounded the extremists, who were given water and
snacks and ordered to sit on the ground in a tin shed near the
temple complex.
   Earlier in the day, police had said about 60 extremists remained
in the temple complex, but that figure was only an estimate.
   Since Sunday, police, commandos and paramilitary troops had kept
up pressure on the complex with burst of machine-gun fire,
incendiary bullets and smoke bombs.
   The government forces had rooftop bunkers on most buildings
overlooking the complex. Commandos had moved inside the walls and
occupied a dining hall and two brick towers that had been used as
lookout posts by the militants.
   The surrender followed escalating attacks by Sikh militants
elsewhere in Punjab. In the past 24 hours, Sikh radicals killed at
least 38 people, including 31 migrant Hindu workers late Tuesday
night, in revenge for the siege.
   About 2,800 policemen, commandos and paramilitary troops
surrounded the Golden Temple complex May 9 after Sikh extremists
fired at police officers who were making an inspection just outside
the walls.
   The Indian army raided the Golden Temple in June 1984 to drive
out militants, and some 1,200 people, most of them Sikhs, were
killed. Five months later, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was
assassinated by her Sikh bodyguards to avenge the attack on the
temple.
   Sikhism was formed 500 years ago as an alternative to Hinduism
and Islam. Sikhs form less than 2 percent of India's 800 million
people, but they are a majority in Punjab. Sikhs say they are
discriminated against by the Hindus, who account for 82 percent of
the population.
   In the Tuesday night attack, about 15 Sikh extremists attacked
Hindu canal workers at a camp near Kharar village, 12 miles from
the state capital of Chandigarh, police said.
   Thirty-one workers were killed and 20 injured. Survivors said
the gunmen repeatedly shouted that they were taking revenge for the
Golden Temple siege.
   Police Superintendent Chander Shekhar said a note found at the
scene claimed responsibility for the Khalistan Commando Force, one
of a dozen Sikh separatist groups. The note said the attack was in
retaliation for the siege, Shekhar reported.
   Seven other slayings Tuesday raised to 97 the number of people
killed by Sihk extremists in Punjab in the past three days.
   About 1,060 people have been slain by Sikh militants in Punjab
this year. In all of 1987, the radicals killed 1,030 people.
</TEXT>
