<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan-Explosion     05-18 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Explosion,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Arabs Confess to Attacks That Killed 7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH ZARROUG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Arab suspects confessed to attacks
that killed seven people and declared they were waging a terror
campaign against Britain and the United States, a senior police
officer said today.
   The Arabs, who carry Lebanese passports, told investigators they
trained in an Arab country for the Sunday night attacks on a hotel
and a club, said Police Inspector Gen. Ibrahim Ahmed Abdel-Karim.
   Abdel-Karim, whose remarks were carried by the official Sudan
News Agency, did not identify the suspects or the country.
   Abdel-Karim said the three told police that one man set off
explosions at the Acropol Hotel and the other two sprayed the
nearby Sudan Club with automatic weapons.
   Five Britons, including a family of four, and two Sudanese died
at the Acropol. Twenty-one people were injured in the hotel and the
club, including three Americans and an unspecified number of
French, British, Dutch and Swedes.
   Abdel-Karim said the suspects told interrogators that the
attacks were directed ``against American and British interests.''
   The hotel is a favorite haunt of foreign relief workers and
journalists, and the club is frequented by British and other
Commonwealth nationals.
   Abdel-Karim said the suspects told police they acted on their
own and had no accomplices. He said police believe others were
involved, but he did not say where they are.
   ``The group is bigger than (the three in custody) and it has
international and regional branches,'' Abdel-Karim said.
   Information Minister Abdullah Mohammed Ahmed told reporters the
three got visas to enter Sudan from the embassy in Kuwait and came
to Khartoum a few months ago after a stop in West Germany. He said
they posed as businessmen.
   Ahmed said preliminary investigations showed the attackers
planned to set off the Acropol explosions halfway through
dinnertime, when the restaurant would be full.
   They planned a simultaneous bombing at the Sudan Club, where a
party was supposed to be held, ``but for some reason the bomb at
the hotel exploded before its scheduled time,'' he said.
   He said the premature explosion ``alerted people at the Sudan
Club and made possible a partial evacuation ... before the
attackers arrived there, threw grenades and opened fire with
submachine guns.''
   ``If it were not for the premature explosion at the hotel, a
great massacre would have taken place,'' he said.
   Ahmed said police discovered the three suspects had worn three
layers of clothing for the attacks: the traditional flowing
Sudanese robe, topped by a safari suit and then a sports training
suit.
   He said two attackers were seen throwing away their top garments
and two submachine guns near the attack site. Police dogs were used
to sniff the discarded clothes and track down the two men, he
added. The third suspect was apprehended later as he entered a
rented apartment where the attackers lived, the minister said.
   A government source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
attackers claimed foreign relief workers staying at the Acropol
were using their humanitarian work as a cover for espionage.
   The source also said the three men intended to carry out other
terrorist attacks in the capital but refused to give details.
</TEXT>
