<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Guatemala, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0648,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MOSCOW</HEAD>
<HEAD>Grenades Thrown At Tass Correspondent's Residence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated PRess Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two grenades exploded early today at the
home of the correspondent for the Soviet news agency Tass after a
threat by a right-wing terrorist squad, the correspondent said.
   Alejandro Trouchine said the blast damaged his vehicle and the
door of the house and broke windows, but no one was injured.
Windows also shattered in neighboring homes, he said.
   Trouchine, who opened the Tass office here in January, has his
office at his home.
   Trouchine said he and his wife Elena were at home when the
blast, heard in a large part of the southern part of the city,
occurred at 2:20 a.m.
   Their 12-year-old son Eugenio left two weeks ago for Moscow, he
said.
   He said that on May 9 he had received in the mail a communique
from ``Mano Blanca,'' Spanish for White Hand, which said in part:
   ``The Mano Blanca rises again in the combative life of
Guatemala, raises its flags of western Christian civilization
against the new Marxist avalanche that keeps company with two
Communist espionage agencies, Tass and Prensa Latina, for whom we
have a surprise at the right oportunity,'' the communique said.
   Prensa Latina is the Cuban government news agency.
   The communique, dated April 14, also threatened representatives
of an exile opposition organization who visited the country a few
days later. Parts of it were published in local newspapers at the
time.
   In a dispatch from Moscow, Tass said the explosion gutted the
Tass office but said it happened Tuesday night. Violent attacks on
Soviets and their facilities were seldom reported by the state-run
media in the past, but the current ``glasnost'' campaign, which
encourages openness, has resulted in quicker acknowledgement of
some such incidents.
   The attack came a week after a failed coup attempt that the
government of President Vinicio Cerezo blamed on civilians, former
military officials and dissident officers.
   Cerezo took office Jan. 14, 1986, as the first civilian
president since 1970. He was the second civilian to take office in
more than 30 years of military and military-dominated rule.
   Mano Blanca was most active from the mid-1960s until about 1980,
claiming responsibility for bombing and assassinations of people it
claimed were communists.
</TEXT>
