<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearWaste     05-18 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Waste,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Groups Propose Principles to Improve Cleanup of Nuclear Weapons
Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen environmental, peace and anti-nuclear
groups proposed today a set of principles they said should guide
efforts to improve cleanup of the Energy Department's nuclear
weapons plants.
   They called for, among other things, independent oversight of
safety activites at the department's plants, as provided for in
some of the five different bills on the subject being considered by
Congress.
   The groups did not collectively endorse any of the bills.
``There are bits and pieces of each'' that deserve support, said
Tim Connor of the Hanford Education Action League in Washington
state.
   The groups said they would cooperate in lobbying efforts, but
were not forming any umbrella organization.
   The Energy Department is expected to propose in July a new
reactor to produce tritium, which decays rapidly and must be
renewed in stored weapons from time to time.
   The groups' proposal called for a public demonstration that
additional nuclear weapons materials are needed; independent
licensing of new plants and safety regulation; provisions for
public participation in licensing; compliance with all federal and
state environmental laws; a federal commitment to pay all clenaup
costs; long-term health studies of nearby residents and job
retraining for displaced workers when plants close.
   ``This is not a ban-the-bomb statement,'' said Connor.
   Groups participating were the Environmental Policy Institute;
Greenpeace; American Friends Service Committee; Puget Sound SANE,
Seattle; Palouse Clearwater Hanford Watch, Moscow, Idaho; Ohio
Public Interest Campaign, Cincinnati; Northwest Nuclear Safety
Campaign, Seattle; Snake River Alliance, Ketchum, Idaho; Hanford
Education Action League, Spokane, Wash.; Fernald Residents for
Environmental Safety and Health, Harrison, Ohio; Energy Research
Foundation, Columbia, S.C.; Colorado Peace Network, Denver;
Coalition for Safe Power, Portland, Ore., and Citizens Against
Rocky Flats Contamination, Denver.
</TEXT>
