<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Sets Hearing In Sailor's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds.: SUBS grafs 3-4 pvs, `Meanwhile, Adm. ...,' with 4 grafs to
reflect navy confirmation of New York Times report. Picks up 5th
graf, `Mirecki of ...' Adds three grafs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of Navy training has ordered a
thorough review of procedures involving risk after five instructors
were accused of forcing a recruit underwater in a pool and
unintentionally causing his death.
   A preliminary hearing will be held next week to determine
whether the five instructors and the officer-in-charge, Lt. Thomas
A. Torchia, should be court- martialed or whether the charges
should be dropped, a Navy spokesman said Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, Vice Admiral N.R. Thunman, the chief of Navy
training, has instructed commanders of training programs to review
all their safety procedures, said Lt. Brian Cullin, a Navy
spokesman in Washington.
   Thunman told The New York Times he wanted to know, ``Are we
training too close to the edge, are we too close to the margin?''
   ``The admiral has ordered an in-depth look at all the training
schools,'' added Cullin, noting Thunman's command covers basic
training as well as various technical, aviation and special
operations schools.
   Nonetheless, the air-sea rescue course in which Airman Recruit
Lee Mirecki died would be resumed next month, the Times quoted
Thunman as saying. Since it began in 1983, the course has graduated
1,573 sailors.
   Mirecki of Appleton, Wis., died March 2 after being pulled from
a pool at the Navy Rescue Swimmer School of the Naval Aviation
Schools Command.
   Initially, the Navy said Mirecki died of cardiopulmonary failure
during the program, which trains Navy air crew personnel for search
and rescue missions.
   But Mirecki's fellow students contacted news media and his
family to say he was treated unusually harshly the day he died.
   Instructors forced Mirecki into the pool against his will, held
his head under water and broke his grip on a rack and safety rope
before he died, according to Navy charges.
   The defendants are Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, who was
officer-in-charge, charged with dereliction of duty; Petty Officers
Richard E. Blevins, David J. Smith, Michael W. Combe, Frankie E.
Deaton and John W. Zelenock, who were instructors, were charged
with involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy to commit battery in
Mirecki's death.
   Navy Cmdr. Daniel J. D'Alesio Jr. has been appointed by Rear
Adm. David Morris, chief of naval air training, to preside over the
hearing set for May 25 at Pensacola  ...
   All the defendants are on temporary leave from their duties, and
the rescue swimmer school has been suspended indefinitely, Saunders
said.
   If convicted, Torchia faces a maximum penalty of punitive
dismissal from the Navy and three months confinement. The
instructors face a maximum penalty of dismissal and three years
confinement.
   A Navy official who asked not to be named said today the
service's inspector-general had just completed an independent
assessment of training procedures at various schools and concluded
they were inadequate.
   Although the final report has not been completed, ``the
inspector general found with regard to the rescue swimmer school
that safety procedures either didn't exist or were out of date,''
said the official.
   The inspector general also concluded instructors had not been
taught proper teaching methods or how to handle emergencies, the
source said.
</TEXT>
