<DOCNO> AP880518-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope Bjt 1stLd-Writethru 05-18 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope, Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Birthday, Trumpets Democracy In Anti-Stroessner
Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with pope's birthday,
departure for Encarnacion. PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `Last week...'
EDITS thereafter to trim and conform</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II was serenaded by a
crowd of 1,000 young well-wishers when he got up today, his 68th
birthday and the last day of his four-nation tour to South America.
   ``I still feel young, especially when I'm with young people,''
the pontiff told the singers.
   The young people gathered at 8 a.m. outside the Vatican envoy's
residence, where John Paul spent the night. Following a chorus of
``Happy Birthday,'' the pope came out to greet the crowd.
   John Paul later departed by plane for the Parana River port of
Encarnacion, birthplace of President Alfredo Stroessner, 234 miles
southwest of Asuncion on the border with Argentina.
   The schedule for today, final day of his South American tour,
also included a Mass in Caacupe, site of the national religious
shrine, about 34 miles east of Asuncion. The pontiff returns to the
capital for a youth rally before departing for Rome at the end of
his tour, which began in Uruguay on May 7 and also took him to
Bolivia and Peru.
   At a meeting with prominent citizens Tuesday night that
Paraguay's authoritarian government initially tried to prevent, the
pope told a cheering, chanting crowd of 3,800 that democracy is
impossible without real participation by all citizens.
   Responding to Paraguayans' complaints of political oppression,
the pontiff spoke of human rights and fundamental civil liberties
in this landlocked country that Stroessner, a general, has ruled
for 33 years in what is widely regarded as a dictatorship.
   The crowd interrupted the Roman Catholic leader 18 times with
applause.
   A block of 60 chairs reserved for officials of Stroessner's
rightist government and governing Colorado Party sat empty during
the hour-long gathering in a government-owned sports stadium.
   Last week, the government abruptly canceled John Paul's
scheduled meeting in the stadium with the ``Builders of Society,''
a church-picked collection of cultural, business, education and
political leaders that includes opposition figures.
   It later backed down after the Vatican protested. Such a
government ban would have been unprecedented in this pontiff's 37
foreign tours.
   As the stadium filled in the hours leading up to the pope's
arrival, an hour late, people chanted anti-government slogans and
sang folk songs. Several speakers addressed the exuberant crowd,
denouncing repression.
   ``It is impossible to speak of true liberty, and even less of
democracy, where there is no real participation by all citizens in
making the great decisions that affect the life and future of the
nation,'' he told the crowd.
   A small group sat through the speech wearing mock handcuffs and
gags.
   Among those attending was Domingo Laino, leader of the
center-left Authentic Liberal Radical Party, one of four political
groups the government does not allow to participate in elections.
   Laino drew wild cheers when he was greeted and embraced by local
bishops.
   As the pope departed, the crowd broke into the chant, ``Dear
John Paul, the people are banned.''
   On Monday, Stroessner told the pope that Paraguay enjoys full
democracy and that its citizens flourish under his law-and-order
policies.
   Stroessner, 75, took power in a 1954 coup and last February was
elected to an eighth straight term as head of this nation of 3.8
million in balloting opppositon leaders called rigged.
   On Tuesday, the pope met with about 5,000 native Indians in
Mariscal Estigarribia, 340 miles northwest of Asuncion.
   White ranchers have ``taken away our land, burned our houses and
divided our communities,'' said Rene Ramirez of the Maskoy tribe.
``Cattle are more important than we are.''
   The pontiff on Tuesday also said Mass in Villarrica, a farm
center 100 miles southeast of Asuncion. He denounced the
exploitation of Latin America's peasant farmers, telling 350,000
``campesinos'' not to be resigned to poverty.
   Paraguay's authoritarian government has harshly repressed
attempts by peasant farmers to organize.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
