<DOCNO> AP880518-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   05-18 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0906</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   May 16
   Baltimore Sun on the INF treaty:
   Having cleared away obstacles to the INF treaty in negotiations
with the Soviet Union, the Reagan administration now faces even
tougher bargaining with the United States Senate. ...
   The administration deserves to lose this face-off with the
Senate for two key reasons: First, its attempt to reinterpret the
1972 Anit-Ballistic Missile treaty in order to promote the
Strategic Defense Initiative is so obviously contrary to law and
custom that it cannot bear close scrutiny. Second, the Senate's
need to reassert its constitutional treaty powers so obviously
outweighs President Reagan's desire for a pro forma diplomatic
ceremony with Soviet General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev that the
White House is bound to blink.
   Humiliation of the president is hardly a wise gesture before the
summit. Therefore, American citizens have a right to expect the
executive and legislative branches to work out some face-saving
language to cover an administration retreat on the ABM issue.
   At no point should the Senate withdraw from its insistence that
treaty testimony offered by an incumbent administration is binding
on future administrations.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 16
   The Long Beach (Calif.) Press-Telegram on presidential aides'
memoirs:
   Now that Larry Speakes and Don Regan have sullied the
administration with books about their White House experiences, some
argue that such kiss-and-tell revelations should be delayed until a
president has left office.
   Regan's response to that is that Nancy Reagan didn't wait that
long to have him fired.
   His tone is petulant, but Regan has a point.
   And that suggests that this president and future presidents
ought to have a friendly chat with key appointees in the future. It
seems fair enough to ask them to delay any potentially damaging
revelations until the president has left office.
   Presidential appointees _ including Don Regan _ are almost
without exception decent men and women who would honor such a
request unless strong considerations of conscience or national
security were involved. ...
   Friendly agreements for the duration of a president's time in
office ought to allow the chief executive to go about the job
without fear that associates will stab him in the back before it's
done.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 14
   The Columbia (Mo.) Daily Tribune on George Bush:
   George Bush is emerging from the vice presidency as the
quintessential faithful dog who never even barks, let alone bites,
his master.
   Judging from the public comments Bush has made over the past 7{
years, you would think (President) Reagan has never uttered a word
or had a thought that was not 100 percent in keeping with Bush's
own feelings. ...
   However, it's a well-known political fact that personal
popularity does not transfer. Just because Candidate Two might say
he will do everything precisely as his popular predecessor would,
Candidate One's voter strength will never be passed along intact.
...
   The only way for Bush to shed this image is to assert himself.
Instead of depending on the actions of others ... Bush will have to
prove by his actions and words what he is. ...
   We know George Bush is a nice man with good experience in
government. We believe he is a good organizer of administrative
affairs. But after all this time in public office and on the
campaign trail, he has yet to show us what he really stands for.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 13
   Westerly (R.I.) Sun on raising the speed limit from 55 mph to 65
mph:
   To those who think the 65 (mph) law is a killer, Transportation
Secretary Jim Burnley must look like a devil's advocate. He says
the traffic death rate has not been worsened.
   This flies in the face of the National Safety Council's ... view
that higher speeds are causing more deaths.
   (Burnley) promises supportive data in a forthcoming report to
Congress. We shall see.
   Meanwhile, he does make one excellent point _ that enforcement
of speed limits is of crucial importance in holding down fatalities.
   But ... there is this House testimony by Judith Stone of the
National Safety Council to think about: ``We have a very strong and
clear indication from across the nation that average speeds have
increased and more people are dying and sustaining more severe
injuries on these roads.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 13
   The Huntington (W.Va.) Herald-Dispatch on airplane safety:
   The two Aloha Airlines pilots who safely landed a Boeing 737
after a large section of fuselage blew away ... were honored in
ceremonies at the White House ... _ and rightly so. ...
   But while the pilots garner their well-deserved praise, federal
investigators are working behind the scenes to figure out the
bizarre mishap's cause. And their initial findings are far from
reassuring.
   The Federal Aviation Administration has disclosed that Aloha
received warnings months ago that its aging planes needed better
maintenance.
   Obviously, not only Aloha but all the nation's airlines need to
pay closer attention to the FAA's warnings of potential problems.
   And it well may be that airlines _ worried about their
profit-loss statements _ are trying to squeeze too much life out of
their older planes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   05-18 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: that's intolerable.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 16
   Dallas Times Herald on outlawing plastic weapons:
   The Senate Judiciary Committee took a reasonable, necessary and
courageous stand in unanimously approving legislation that would
ban plastic guns and any other firearms that elude metal detectors
and X-ray machines.
   This nation cannot afford to permit the manufacture or sale of
these kinds of weapons.
   The committee's voice vote clears the ban for action on the
Senate floor. Congress should waste no time in protecting Americans
from lethal guns that could be easily smuggled aboard airlines.
Terrorists do not deserve to have any friends in Washington. ...
   We hope that the willingness of congressional leaders to take a
stand in the case of plastic guns, despite threats of a political
retaliation at the polls, will lead to a candid and courageous
review of a whole series of gun-control regulations.
   There must be a balance between sanity and total surrender.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 14
   Worthington (Minn.) Daily Globe on President Reagan's
endorsement of George Bush:
   That was some endorsement President Reagan gave Vice President
George Bush. ...
   For an opener, the president waited until Pat Robertson
terminated his candidacy and there was no one but Bush remaining in
the Republican race.
   The president didn't devote his remarks primarily to the Bush
candidacy. He talked on other subjects for 15 minutes and then
appended a three-sentence comment on Bush at the end of his address.
   To top it all off, Reagan said ``George Bosh'' in one of the
three references he made to the vice president during the course of
his speech. ...
   It's an expansive endorsement and a glowing tribute in the
context of what the president has said in support of other
candidates _ Jesse Jackson, or Michael Dukakis.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 13
   Philadelphia Inquirer on books about President Reagan:
   Who needs enemies? President Reagan has his old inner circle
circling like sharks in the water, gnawing on what's left of him
like so much chum.
   They helped breathe life into the Reagan ethos. Now they're
rushing to suck the blood out.
   Seldom, if ever, has a president been so ill-served by the men
who served him.
   But whose fault is that? Well, its the fellow upon whose carcass
the sharks are feeding. He's harvesting what he has sown.
   But it is a sad and shameful harvest, nonetheless.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 16
   Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal editorial on Panama's Gen. Noriega:
   Offering to trade U.S. criminal charges for an agreement that
Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega would relinquish control of
his government puts U.S. justice up for sale or trade.
   The Reagan administration has been discussing a deal that could
result in the dropping of drug trafficking charges against Noriega
if the general gives up his power by August.
   The administration describes its plan to coax Noriega to step
down as ``diplomatic plea bargaining,'' thus devaluing U.S. justice
and telling criminals that criminal charges can be negotiated away
in the embassy back room.
   Criminal charges should not be political nor negotiable outside
the context of official court proceedings, not even by the White
House.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 13
   Honolulu Star-Bulletin on first anniversary of the Fiji coup:
   Whatever the reasoning, Fiji's dumping of an elected government
and replacing it with one that puts a majority of the nation's
people in limbo is not happy a result.
   It appears to have been a large step backward on the road toward
representative government.
   Until Fiji resumes the democratic institutions that it seemed on
the way to developing up until a year ago, it will be viewed as an
island nation that has broken the promise of its hopeful future.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 12
   New Jersey Herald, Newton, N.J., on new boxing regulations:
   The sport of boxing is safer and its integrity less susceptible,
thanks to a bill signed into law that affords participants
increased medical protection and mandates them and their staffs to
undergo background checks to ensure there are no ties with
organized crime. ...
   The law requires two physicians be present at ringside and all
boxers undergo a physical examination after every bout. In
addition, fighters are required to carry medical insurance
coverage. ...
   Currently only promoters sponsoring bouts in casinos are
checked. The new law requires that all promoters, managers and
trainers submit to annual background checks.
   The reforms are a step in the right direction to ensure boxing
is safer and not tainted by people who might want to control the
outcomes of bouts.
</TEXT>
