<HEAD>Weicker Proclaims Dislike for Meese</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Language in grafs 1,3 may be offensive to some.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lowell Weicker, traveling to
Connecticut with President Reagan, today labeled Attorney General
Edwin Meese III ``a son of a bitch.''
   Taking advantage of the chance to present his views to the small
pool of reporters who accompany Reagan on the presidential jet,
Weicker said:
   ``I've been battling the son-of-a-bitch ever since he became
attorney general. I don't like him.''
   Weicker's comments came in the context of his answer to
reporters' questions about whether Meese should resign.
   The Connecticut Republican, who long has been at odds with the
administration on a variety of issues, said, ``I want to see the
report of the special prosecutor first.''
   Reagan often invites members of Congress to accompany him on
trips to their states and districts as a matter of presidential
courtesy. Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., also traveled on the
presidential aircraft today.
   For his part, Reagan, said that critics of his embattled
attorney general were ``trying to make a fuss over him'' but that
none of the charges against him had been substantiated.
   Reagan commented on Meese's troubles as he sat down to lunch
with cadets on the Coast Guard cutter ``Vigorous'' at the service's
New London, Conn., academy before making a speech about illegal
drug trafficking.
   Reagan toured the cutter and inspecting goods seized in drug
raids, including sawed-off shotguns, automatic weapons and
five-kilogram of cocaine.
   When he sat down to lunch with the cadets, a reporter said there
appeared to be a rebellion within conservative ranks about Meese
and the attorney general's firing of his spokesman, Terry Eastland,
a favorite of the right wing.
   ``I think some will keep on trying to make a fuss over him,''
Reagan said of Meese. ``So far they're all empty charges.''
