<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PortlandMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0581 05-18 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Portland Mayor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0581,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portland Mayor Bud Clark Wins Primary; Runoff Uncertain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with final unofficial returns,
absentee ballots to be counted by Friday. Picks up in 4th graf, `A
runoff ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Bud Clark easily defeated 10
challengers for his job, but uncounted absentee ballots may decide
whether the eccentric tavern owner will face a runoff in his bid
for a second term.
   Clark needed one vote more than 50 percent of the total votes
cast Tuesday to win re-election outright, but final unofficial
results today showed he had only 49.8 percent.
   Clark, with 59,810 votes, was followed by former Police Chief
Ron Still with 40,960, or 33.5 percent, and former City
Commissioner Lloyd Anderson with 12,693, or 10.6 percent. Former
Police Chief Jim Davis was a distant fourth, with 4,832, or 4
percent.
   Jim Dodson, a spokesman for the Multnomah County elections
office, said absentee ballots would be counted by Friday. He said
he had no idea how many people had cast absentee votes.
   A runoff in November would be between the top two vote-getters.
   Also Tuesday, voters statewide approved a law requiring drivers
and passengers of motorcycles and mopeds to wear helmets. With
1,959 of the state's 2,338 precincts reported, the helmet proposal
was ahead by 381,488, or 68 percent, to 178,827, or 32 percent.
   Clark shocked the city four years ago by unseating incumbent
Frank Ivancie. Despite a series of crises that plagued the first
half of his term, polls showed him far ahead of the other
candidates in the non-partisan race.
   Clark decided to wait for complete returns before making a
victory speech.
   ``We led the way in showing you could upset an incumbent, and
now it looks like everyone wants to do the same thing,'' Clark said
in a telephone interview. ``I just want to get back to running the
city.''
   Still said he was confident there would be a runoff. The last
runoff in a Portland mayoral race was in 1956 when Terry Schrunk
defeated incumbent Fred Peterson.
   During Clark's first two years in office, Still and another
police chief resigned and Davis was fired in a dispute over a
Police Bureau audit.
   The other chief to resign was Penny Harrington, who left after
16 months as the first female chief of a big-city police department
in the United States. Her resignation came a day after a commission
that Clark appointed issued a report that criticized her management
and recommended that she be replaced.
   Portland's crime rate was the major issue in the mayor's race,
but Clark's opponents apparently were unable to convince voters
that he was directly responsible for the crime problem. Clark said
lowering the crime rate would be the top priority of his second
term.
   Clark, 57, has been criticized for his eccentricities, but there
were few campaign attacks on his personality. His trademark
``whoop, whoop'' cry is a staple of civic functions, and the
bicycling mayor has chronicled his political career with an
ever-present camera.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Hastings-Impeach 2ndLd-Writethru a0691 05-18 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings-Impeach, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0691,850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with Hastings statement; picks up pvs 5th
graf, Hastings sat. Editing throughout. Note language in graf 6, I
ask you.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Judge Alcee L. Hastings of Miami told
House investigators today that ``I am not guilty but I am not
free,'' and demanded that they drop impeachment proceedings and
clear his name of misconduct charges brought by fellow judges.
   Hastings said he was the first federal judge in U.S. history to
be threatened with impeachment after his acquittal of criminal
charges at a jury trial.
   ``They found me not guilty of crimes I never committed,''
Hastings told the House Judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice,
which opened impeachment hearings today.
   ``Let me make it very, very clear,'' he said in sworn testimony.
``I did not receive a bribe, I did not obstruct justice, I have not
betrayed the integrity of my office. I am not guilty but I am not
free.''
   Hastings denounced a report by a special five-judge panel of the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals accusing him of lying under oath
and manufacturing evidence at his bribery trial in 1983.
   ``I ask you in the name of decency, I ask you in the name of
justice, the American jury system and the American way of life, I
beg you, I beseech you _ hell no, I demand of you, that you set me
free!''
   Hastings, the first black federal judge in Florida, was
acquitted five years ago of conspiring to solicit a $150,000 bribe
from two convicted racketeers.
   Today's hearing began with a review of evidence in the case by
New York lawyer John Doar, a former U.S. assistant attorney general
who supervised the appellate panel's investigation.
   Doar also wrote the panel's voluminous report accusing Hastings
of bribery conspiracy and obstruction of justice after a 3{-year
investigation that he said involved 2,800 documents and testimony
from 110 witnesses.
   The report was given to the House leadership in March 1987 by
the Judicial Conference of the United States, the chief
policymaking body of the federal judiciary, with the conclusion
that ``consideration of impeachment may be warranted.''
   At the outset of today's hearing, Rep. John Conyers Jr.,
D-Mich., chairman of the subcommittee that has studied the case for
more than a year, said he was deeply troubled that the charges
against Hastings might be racially and politically motivated.
   Conyers said the impeachment proceedings were ``exceedingly
difficult and trying'' because Hastings already has been acquitted
of criminal charges and because he is a black federal judge.
   Hastings sat silently with his lawyers at a side table as
Conyers said the subcommittee had ``taken cognizance of racially
motivated conduct in this country for many, many years,
particularly in the criminal justice system.''
   ``We are not unaware or naive about the troubling matters that
hover over this particular hearing today,'' he said.
   Conyers charged that the federal courts have become
``conservatized and in some instances politicized'' under the
Reagan administration. Referring to the Justice Department, he
added, ``never have we known an administration that has so
politicized the administration of law.''
   Rep. George Gekas of Pennsylvania, ranking Republican on the
panel, declared that ``never has there been a hint ... that any
part of this inquiry was based on racial motivations.''
   He urged his colleagues to keep racial or political
considerations from influencing the proceedings and to concentrate
on its fact-finding mission in the case.
   Last April, the Supreme Court rejected a move by Hastings to
block the impeachment inquiry as unlawful.
   The high court left intact a 1980 law under which Hastings'
fellow judges asked the House to consider impeaching him for
alleged judicial misconduct. The justices also refused to block
release of confidential grand jury documents concerning Hastings to
the Judiciary panel.
   A team of House lawyers has been studying a 381-page report,
prepared by a special five-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta, which concluded there was ``clear and
convincing evidence'' that Hastings conspired with Washington
lawyer William A. Borders Jr. to solicit a bribe from two
racketeers in exchange for a promise of lenient sentences.
   In addition, the panel accused Hastings of trying to conceal the
conspiracy by giving false testimony and fabricating evidence at
his highly publicized trial in Miami four years ago.
   Hastings was acquitted of the bribery-conspiracy charges, but
Borders was convicted at a separate trial in 1982 on charges of
conspiring to arrange the alleged bribe from convicted racketeers
Frank and Tom Romano.
   The judicial panel concluded that Hastings ``attempted to
corruptly use his office for personal gain.'' Its report said
``such conduct cannot be excused or condoned even after Judge
Hastings has been acquitted of the criminal charges.''
   An impeachment resolution against Hastings has been introduced
by Reps. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., and F. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis.
   Hastings, who was nominated by President Carter in 1979, had
claimed previously that his prosecution was racially and
politically motivated. ``If I were white, I wouldn't be facing
impeachment,'' he said.
   If the full House votes impeachment, the Senate would conduct a
trial. Conviction by the Senate would result in Hastings' removal
from the federal bench.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
