<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IslandSale     05-18 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Island Sale,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scottish Island Offered For Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 350-acre Scottish island with
rolling pastures, ruins of a chapel, two four-bedroom farmhouses
and a harbor was offered for sale Wednesday for more than $280,000.
   Savills, an Edinburgh real estate firm, said the island of Pabay
in Scotland's Western Isles is surrounded by seas teeming with
seals, porpoises and otters, was once a refuge for pirates, and has
been inhabited since the 13th century.
   The island is licensed by the Post Office to produce its own
stamps, and because it has no postal workers, its handful of
inhabitants are paid to collect their mail from a post office on
the Isle of Skye two miles away.
   Savills advertised it as ideal for someone seeking a sanctuary
from the pressures of modern life. It asked for offers of more than
$280,000.
   ``For that money you would be lucky to find a one-bedroom flat
in central London,'' said spokesman Andrew Smith. ``But that's the
way the property market is.
   ``There are certain limitations on getting to it, but if you
want a bit of privacy it's the ideal situation,'' he said.
   The island currently is a commercial farm, and the owner's
identity has not been disclosed, Smith said.
   Religious persecution on the mainland brought the island's
earliest settlers seeking sanctuary 700 years ago, he said. By
1549, Scottish writer Dean Munro described it as ``full of woods,
good for fishing, and a main shelter for thieves and cutthroats.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
