<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson     05-18 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Begins Defense Of His Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson said Wednesday that
U.S. intelligence cannot counter his claim there might be Soviet
missiles in Cuba, repeating a never-proven contention from his
failed Republican presidential campaign.
   On the second day of his return to his Christian Broadcasting
Network's ``700 Club'' program, Robertson said he was victimized by
the media that was playing ``gotcha'' with his campaign.
   ``It isn't so much to learn what it is you've got to say, but
sort of can we pick a fact that is erronous and can we play `I
gotcha','' he said of the media's reporting of his statements.
   Robertson stunned his rivals when he said during a February
campaign debate that the Soviets maintained nuclear missiles in
Cuba.
   ``I never claimed to have proof the missiles were there,'' he
said Wednesday.
   During the debate Robertson said, ``Information came to me that
the Soviets, in violation of the so-called Khrushchev-Kennedy
accords, have put some SS-4s and 5s in Cuba.''
   During the televised appearance, Robertson offered pictures and
testimony from unnamed sources that he said led to the conclusion
that there was a possibility that the missiles existed. Asked why
the information was not better publicized, Robertson said the
material was being deliberately withheld to aid in the ratification
of the U.S.-Soviet missile treaty.
   ``The fix is in, that's why. The deal has been signed and
everybody wants it to go through,'' he said.
   Likewise, Robertson said the campaign statement that he knew the
location of American hostages was exaggerated by the media.
Robertson said the statement was a ``throwaway line'' at the end of
an interview, and that CBN knew only the general location of some
hostages.
   Robertson said he would show videotapes on Thursday of
depositions taken in his $33 million libel suit against former Rep.
Pete McCloskey. The former California congressman charged Robertson
evaded combat duty in the Korean War by using his father's
influence, who was a U.S. senator from Virginia.
</TEXT>
