<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     05-18 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Fire Tear Gas, Smoke Bombs To Disperse Pro-Marcos
Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas and smoke bombs
Wednesday to halt a rally and march to the U.S. Embassy by
protesters demanding that deposed President Ferdinand Marcos be
allowed to return for his mother's funeral.
   Organizers said at least four women and two children were hurt.
Police said there were minor injuries to several demonstrators but
did not give a figure.
   About 5,000 demonstrators rallied to urge the government allow
the exiled Marcos to return to attend the funeral of his mother,
Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4.
   A breakaway group of 2,000 demonstrators, chanting ``If you want
trouble, we will give you trouble!'' later marched toward the
embassy and were blocked near City Hall by 50 policemen,
journalists said.
   A police spokesman said the demonstrators were dispersed when
they started throwing stones at the officers, who fought back with
truncheons and later used tear gas and smoke bombs to disperse the
marchers.
   The marchers later regrouped in the central Bonifacio Square to
protest the dispersal.
   Rows of barbed wire and 400 policemen and soldiers backed by
four firetrucks and two water cannons blocked all roads leading to
the presidential palace.
   ``Any dispersal is a curtailment of the people's right to
peaceably assemble and march,'' said rally leader Salvador Panelo.
``It only demonstrates the weakness of this government because it
is afraid of the people's voice.''
   Col. Emiliano Templo, deputy commander of the Capital Command,
allowed protesters to hold a protest vigil Wednesday night.
   About 100 Marcos supporters with red, white and blue balloons
waited for their companions near the main road leading to the
palace, but they peacefully dispersed at sundown after most of the
earlier protesters did not arrive.
   Rally leaders want President Corazon Aquino to reconsider her
refusal to allow Marcos to return for his mother's funeral. Marcos
lives in Hawaii, where he fled after the February 1986 revolt which
toppled his 20-year regime.
   ``We are going to appeal again ... that they allow the return of
President Marcos if only for humanitarian considerations,'' said
Fernando Diaz, president of the Long Live the Filipino Movement.
</TEXT>
