<HEAD>$50,000 Donated For Memorial To Korean War Vets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange is donating $50,000
for a monument to the veterans of the Korean War.
   Stock Exchange Chairman John Phelan presented the money Tuesday
to Mayor Edward I. Koch, who formed the New York Korean Veterans
Memorial Commission to help raise $2 million for a monument to be
built in Battery Park in lower Manhattan.
   Thomas W. Evans, co-chairman of the commission, said the
commission also will establish ``a living memorial'' to provide
social services for Korean War vets.
   About 53,000 Americans lost their lives in the Korean War, which
lasted from 1950 to 1953. The Republic of Korea lost 70,000 in its
armed forces.
   Evans said a competition will be held to design the monument.
