<HEAD>Girls Swipe Doomed Bunnies From Class</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A junior high school principal says
two girls will be given detention for two weeks for stealing a pair
of rabbits to save them from being slaughtered in science class.
   ``There may have been a better way to handle it, to bring it to
the attention of the administration, rather than `rabbitnapping,'''
Comstock Junior High School Principal Rich Rapheal said.
   ``We like brought them to the office. If we didn't do anything,
they would be dead,'' said Wendy, 15, one of the students. The
girls were not identified except as Wendy and Johanna, 14.
   Rapheal said the rabbits were part of an agriculture sciences
class in which the processing of livestock is demonstrated from
birth to slaughter.
   ``They are killed humanely,'' Rapheal said. ``They're hit on the
head _ I know that doesn't sound humane _ with a club designed for
that.''
   ``They could have showed us a film,'' Johanna said.
   The principal said the class was warned days ahead that the
rabbits would be killed Tuesday, and students who objected could
have been excused.
   Still, there will be changes in the class, Rapheal said.
   ``They'll still have the unit on processing of meat and
livestock, but probably not kill them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
