<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--AcidRain     05-18 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Acid Rain,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cloud Experiment Demonstrates Acid Rain Chemistry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have fed a pollutant into a cloud and
demonstrated a chemical reaction involved in acid rain, a report
says.
   Researchers released sulfur dioxide into a cloud that covered
the top of a British hill, and measurements showed it reacted with
natural hydrogen peroxide, according to a report in Thursday's
issue of the British journal Nature.
   The rate of reaction was comparable to that expected from
laboratory experiments, they wrote.
   The reaction produces sulfate, which reacts with atmospheric
moisture to form sulfuric acid, a constituent of acid rain.
   Little sulfate was detected in the experiment, which was
performed in December 1985. But significant levels appeared when
the experiment was done in springtime, when more sun was available
to promote sulfur dioxide reactions, researchers wrote.
   Acid rain also can include nitric acids formed from pollutants
called nitrogen oxides. It can harm vegetation and acquatic life,
and damage buildings and monuments.
</TEXT>
