<HEAD>Bush Visits Site of Drug Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush visited the scene
of a recent drug raid today, saying, ``It's not show business. You
have to learn and understand and then take action.''
   The Republican presidential contender, on a campaign trip to
California, went to a ``rock house,'' the name for locations where
the cocaine derivative crack is sold and used in south central Los
Angeles.
   He spent about 15 minutes in the storefront location and talked
to Det. Mike Brown about a major drug raid and cocaine that police
said was found there on May 2.
   ``I'm talking to the people who are actually out there waging
the battle. You learn from it. It brings it home dramatically,''
Bush said.
   He commended the police who are ``physically coming in to
relieve a neighborhood of this kind of filth.''
   Asked the value of such a visit, Bush said, ``Anybody who has
practical experience, you learn from them. It's not show business.
You have to learn and understand and then take action. That's what
I want to do if I'm elected president. It's been extraordinarily
helpful.''
