<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What else could The Tombstone Epitaph
possibly be but a funeral service publication?
   That's what the folks assumed at ``The Serials Directory,'' an
international reference book which lists publications and their
subjects.
   ``Broke me up,'' says Wallace E. Clayton, editor of the Epitaph,
a nationally circulated monthly journal of Western history.
   Ellen Rice, data-base coordinator for ``The Serials Directory,''
which is based in Birmingham, Ala., said the mixup was ``definitely
our fault.''
   Someone apparently misread classification numbers, and, together
with the name Epitaph, concluded that it was a funeral service
directory, she said.
   ``The Serials Directory,'' consisting of three volumes, is
mailed to libraries, colleges and universities, among other
institutions. It sells for $289.
   Ms. Rice said the error ``is funny,'' but it will be corrected
and the Epitaph will be listed under publications dealing with the
history of North America.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MUNHALL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For some 300 physics students from
Pittsburgh area high schools, this week's amusement park trip
consisted of more than just rides and cotton candy. It also
included a test organized by the High School Physics Teachers
Association.
   The students were asked, for example, to estimate the number of
lights on the Ferris wheel at Kennywood Park, or the amount of
paint it would take to paint all of the tables there.
   ``Know your mass,'' two questions began. ``Estimate the vertical
distance traveled by the left end of the Noah's Ark (ride) since
1950,'' and ``What is the weight of the water in newtons in the
Kennywood Lagoon?''
   Mark Bentsen, 17, a student at Pittsburgh's Shady Side Academy,
stood under the roller coaster and did his best to crack questions
on potential versus kinetic energy.
   ``It would be nice to say I want to be a physicist,'' Bentsen
said, ``but I'm more into financial planning.''
</TEXT>
