<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Awad     05-18 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Awad,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wife Of Palestinian Activist Seeks Help From Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Palestinian-rights activist
Mubarak Awad launched a Capitol Hill lobbying effort Wednesday in
hope of persuading lawmakers to help her husband fight deportation
from Israel.
   Nancy Nye, Awad's wife, said she has not sensed a strong support
of Congress in the matter so far.
   ``I'm presenting this case to congressional members, that they
will look at this case and look at the way the government of Israel
is dealing with Palestinian residents,'' said Ms. Nye.
   She said she intends to visit congressional offices _ including
those of Sens. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and John Glenn, D-Ohio,
and Reps. Michael DeWine, R-Ohio, and Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y. _ on
Wednesday and Thursday before returning to Israel on Friday.
   Ms. Nye said U.S. lawmakers could ask Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir to consider changing his decision to order Awad
deported.
   Awad, 44, a naturalized U.S. citizen who has a home in
Wapakoneta, Ohio, is being held in an Israeli jail pending review
of the deportation order by Israel's supreme court.
   A native of Jerusalem, Awad was arrested May 5 following
government allegations that he had done much to incite the
five-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Ms. Nye said her husband is a moderate who believes that Israel
and Palestine should exist in side-by-side states and that
Palestinians should resist the military occupation of Israel
through non-violent methods.
   She said the court's decision, expected shortly after it hears
the case next Monday, will determine whether Christian and Moslem
residents of Jerusalem can have their residency rights lifted and
be asked to leave their homeland.
   Ms. Nye released copies of a letter she received from her
husband last Sunday. In the letter, Awad said he is willing to
accept the state of Israel and that Palestinians have been using
civil disobedience and non-violent action to deliver a message to
the Israelis and the world.
   ``Let not this chance be gone,'' Awad wrote. ``Don't force us
again to kill.''
   Ms. Nye said she believes Awad meant that many Palestinians have
had to discipline themselves in using non-violent means to send the
message that they are tired of living under military occupation.
   ``But he also understands that a long struggle that seems to be
falling on deaf ears will produce a frustration,'' she said. ``And
I think he fears that that frustration will lead to violence.''
</TEXT>
