<HEAD>GOP Credentials Committee Ousts 800 Delegates From State
Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Georgia Republican Party's credentials
committee has ousted about 800 of the 2,301 delegates from this
weekend's state convention in Albany.
   Richmond County party chairman Larry Colet, whose 63-member
delegation was one of at least 40 county delegations thrown out for
technical reasons, said Tuesday that attorneys for the rejected
delegates may challenge the committee's credentialing authority.
   Colet and other members of his delegation said the committee's
action is a continuation of a months-long battle between party
regulars who want a full slate of George Bush delegates and
counties that allowed Pat Robertson supporters into their
delegations to the state convention.
   The Richmond County group included 38 Robertson supporters and
25 Bush supporters.
   ``It's dumb,'' said state Sen. Frank Albert, a member of the
rejected delegation. ``I'm a Bush supporter, but there are a lot of
people like myself who are disgusted.''
   ``I think they're going to keep us off the floor altogether. We
can sit up in the balcony and throw stuff at 'em.''
