<DOCNO> AP880518-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Sikhs Bjt   05-18 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs, Bjt,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Surrender, Ending Siege</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh radicals surrendered after a 10-day
siege and emerged Wednesday from their revered Golden Temple,
symbol of the dream of an independent nation that propels their
campaign of blood and terror.
   Forty-five men and a woman emerged, hands in the air or clasped
on their heads. About 2,800 police, commandos and paramilitary
troops surrounded the sacred compound, which has walls 20 feet high
and covers the equivalent of five city blocks.
   ``No terrorist is inside the complex,'' said K.P.S. Gill, police
chief of Punjab state. ``All of them have come out.''
   The militants crossed an 8-foot-wide white marble walkway that
provides the only access to the 400-year-old shrine, which sits in
a vast pool where pilgrims bathe in peaceful times. The surrender
took 45 minutes.
   Gill said one radical tried to flee and was shot dead, and three
committed suicide by swallowing cyanide capsules. Another committed
suicide by the same method Sunday.
   Officials say 42 people, most of them militant Sikhs, were
killed during the siege, bringing the death toll to 46 with the
suicides.
   The Golden Temple, Sikhism's holiest site, has been the center
and symbol of Sikh militancy since the separatists began their
terrorist war in 1982.
   Thousands of people have been killed and Wednesday's surrender
does not end their struggle for a Sikh nation in this rich northern
agricultural state. It would be called Khalistan, or Land of the
Pure.
   Elsewhere in Punjab, the only Indian state in which Sikhs are a
majority, Sikh gunmen killed at least 40 people Tuesday and
Wednesday. The victims included 31 itinerant Hindu laborers who
were attacked in their tents late Tuesday night near a canal they
were building near Majjat, a village 120 miles southeast of
Amritsar.
   Militants say Sikhs need a separate homeland to preserve their
faith and avoid discrimination by Hindus.
   They have killed at least 1,063 people in Punjab so far this
year, including entire families. The death toll from their
terrorism in all of 1987 was 1,032.
   Sikhism was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to Hinduism
and Islam. Only 2 percent of India's 800 million people are Sikhs
and 82 percent are Hindus.
   Commandos searched everyone who emerged from the gold-domed
temple Wednesday, even to the point of removing turbans and
unwrapping the yards of fabric that form the traditional headgear
of devout male Sikhs.
   Prisoners were taken to a tin shed, where Red Cross workers gave
them food and water.
   Five bodies were found inside the complex, one identified as
that of Jagir Singh, spokesman for the Panthic Committee, umbrella
group for a dozen separatist groups.
   It was partially burned but there was no word on the cause of
death. Another body, of a woman, was found in the sacred pool.
   During the cease-fire and subsequent surrender, crowds gathered
300 yards from the temple compound. That was as close as they could
get to the shrine, whose immediately vicinity has been sealed off
since the siege began May 9 in Amritsar, a city of 800,000 people.
   ``This is a day of great relief,'' Punjab governor Sidharth
Shankar Ray said Wednesday night, but added: ``It is neither
victory nor defeat.''
   He urged Sikh militants throughout Punjab to turn themselves in
at the nearest police stations and said the temple would be
restored to its religious function as soon as possible.
   Government forces had been careful to avoid storming the temple.
   Prime Minister Indira Gandhi ordered an army assault against
Sikh gunmen in the complex in 1984 in which more than 1,200 people
were killed. Less than five months later, on Oct. 31, two of her
Sikh bodyguards assassinated Mrs. Gandhi.
   Her son and successor, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, said
Wednesday night no one should be allowed to carry arms in the
Golden Temple.
   In his first public statement after the siege ended, he said in
New Delhi he believes most Sikhs in India supported it.
   Sikh militants usually complain of discrimination in general
terms, but one specific complaint is the allegation that Gandhi's
government has tried to weaken Punjab's economy by diverting river
water needed for its agriculture to other states.
   Because of the terror campaign, security officials outside
Punjab scrutinize Sikhs more closely at checkpoints and during
times of crisis. Since devout Sikhs wear turbans, moustaches and
untrimmed beards, they are instantly distinguishable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
