<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FishermenRescued     05-18 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fishermen Rescued,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Helicopter Used To Rescue Fishermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in a helicopter plucked two fishermen
from the Arkansas River _ and then ticketed them for being there.
   A third fisherman waded to safety Tuesday, but did not avoid a
ticket for violating a city ordinance that makes it illegal to swim
or wade in the Zink Lake or low-water dam area, Cpl. G.L. Temple
said.
   Michael Levasseur, 30, said he and two other men waded out about
300 feet.
   Police yelled at them from a pedestrian bridge about six hours
later to get out. The three had planned to wait for the rising
water to recede before leaving, he said.
   ``We just looked at each other and said, `I hope you can
swim,''' said Levasseur, who waded to shore.
   They were loaded down with fishing tackle and their catch.
   ``I just thought, `These fish ain't worth dying over,' so I let
them go,'' Levasseur said.
   Pat Arrington, 27, said he had 20 to 30 pounds of fish strung
around his neck as well as a tackle box. ``The current pulling on
the fish was pulling me down _ I had to lose all my stuff just to
stay alive,'' he said.
   The men were treated for exhaustion once they reached shore.
   The third fisherman was identified as Steve Arrington, 30.
   Of the tickets, which carry a fine up to $500, Officer T.J.
Gresham said, ``We want people to understand how dangerous it is to
be out there.''
</TEXT>
