<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmokingAd     05-18 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking Ad,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Sox Refuse To Hide Smoking Ad During Cancer Benefit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSE MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boston Red Sox have refused to cover a
billboard advertising cigarettes during a charity game to raise
money to fight children's cancer despite complaints by an
anti-smoking group.
   The Boston-based Group Against Smoking Pollution, or GASP, asked
the ballclub to cover a billboard in center field promoting
Marlboro cigarettes during an exhibition game to be played Thursday
between the Red Sox and Cincinnati Reds to benefit cancer research.
   Red Sox management said the billboard, which has an illustration
of a cowboy, could not be covered because of a long-term contract
the team has with the Philip Morris tobacco company.
   ``The Red Sox have entered into a contract that is legally
binding,'' team counsel John Donovan said Wednesday. ``I intend to
honor my contracts.''
   GASP Executive Director Jerry Maldavir said he believes the Red
Sox are sending mixed messages to children by displaying the
billboard.
   ``Since Thursday night's game is for children who have cancer,
the Red Sox should do something to dispel the connection between
smoking and baseball,'' he said.
   Donovan refused to comment on the image projected by the
cigarette ad, but said the team has raised millions of dollars for
the local children's cancer group known as the Jimmy Fund in the
past and will continue to support the charity.
   Steven Weiss, a spokesman for Philip Morris, said he had no
immediate comment on the dispute.
   Mike Andrews, executive director of fund raising for the Jimmy
Fund, said although he does not think attacking the Red Sox is
fair, he could not fault the anti-smoking group for trying. GASP
has been trying for six years to get the ballclub to drop the
tobacco advertisements.
   ``If anything, I think all tobacco advertising, smoking or
smokeless, should be banned, as should smoking itself. Tobacco is a
drug,'' Andrews said.
   ``Kids idolize and emulate sports figures,'' Maldavir said.
``When they see the billboard on television or at the ballpark,
they think baseball and smoking go hand in hand.
   ``The Red Sox project this attractiveness that says, `Wear what
I wear, smoke what I smoke.'''
   In light of the U.S. surgeon general's recent report that
concludes nicotine found in tobacco is as addictive as drugs,
Maldavir said, his group's request is even more urgent.
   ``In 1971, advertising of tobacco products was banned on
television, but every time the TV cameras go across the scoreboard,
there it is,'' Maldavir said.
</TEXT>
