<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Press     05-18 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Press,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Western Publications to be Sold in Soviet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have lifted restrictions on the sale of
American and West European newspapers and magazines and they will
be sold in ordinary press kiosks in the future, the weekly Moscow
News reported Wednesday.
   Viktor Pukalov, head of the Soyuzpechat agency that distributes
Soviet and foreign periodicals, told Moscow News ``the first step
toward extending the sales of Western newspapers and magazines was
the decision to open access to these publications to the general
public.''
   The newspaper did not make clear when the publications would
appear.
   The article specifically mentioned the Times of London, the
International Herald Tribune, Newsweek and the Economist as
examples of Western publications that will be available in Soviet
kiosks.
   Pukalov acknowledged that another barrier to broader circulation
_ the non-convertible ruble _ has not been surmounted.
   Soviet hard-currency reserves are limited, and therefore the
government spends its dollars, pounds and other convertible funds
on priority items like grain and high-technology equipment for
boosting factory output.
   ``I think that our Western partners will be interested in an
exchange of publications,'' Pukalov told the newspaper. ``Interest
in our press is growing along with the interest in our country: for
the first time the single number of export copies of Soviet
newspapers and magazines reached 12.5 million copies.''
   Pukalov said 160,000 issues of publications from 46 foreign
countries reach Moscow each day, but indicated that most go to
hotels frequented by foreigners or to press and foreign trade
offices that need to know what is carried in those publications.
   Western publications are more expensive than Soviet newspapers,
which usually sell for 3 to 5 kopeks (5 to 8 cents), and the price
to Soviet customers would have to be even higher to recover the
cost and transport, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
