<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseSpending     05-18 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Striving To Work Out Of Snarl On Pentagon Budget Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate was still trying to work its way
out of a legislative snarl Wednesday which has blocked final action
on a Pentagon budget bill, while the House voted overwhelming
passage of a military construction measure.
   ``We're trying to work out some type of agreement, but we don't
have one yet. I don't know when it will be done,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   The dispute involves an amendment that would allow drug dealers
convicted of killing people to be sentenced to death.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., sponsor of the amendment, has
refused to withdraw the proposal and opponents have threatened a
filibuster to block a final vote on the provision.
   D'Amato has offered to drop the amendment if Democratic leaders
promise that it will come before the chamber later for a separate
vote, but opponents have not dropped filibuster threats.
   ``I am not willing to let this go until we can be assured of a
vote,'' D'Amato said Wednesday afternoon.
   The amendment is the only unresolved issue in the huge Pentagon
budget bill. Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services
Committee, has pushed for final action by the Democratic-controlled
chamber.
   Approval by the Senate would send the bill to a conference
committee to be reconciled with the separate Pentagon spending
measure passed a week ago by the House.
   Both bills authorize defense spending of $299.5 billion in the
fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, but contain a number of differences
over issues such as arms control, the Star Wars budget, and
ordering the military into the fight against drugs.
   Meanwhile, the House voted 382-26 passage of a bill
appropriating $9 billion for a variety of military construction
programs for the next fiscal year. The Senate has yet to act on its
version of the same measure.
   The bill is different from the authorization legislation, which
allows the Pentagon to go ahead and sign contracts. Appropriation
bills are considered later.
   The House measure includes $77.5 million for the first
construction of hangars at Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri for
the ``stealth'' bomber.
   The plane, known formally as the B-2, is designed to evade
Soviet radar. The Air Force plans to begin deploying it early in
the next decade. The first stealth bombers will be based at
Whiteman.
</TEXT>
