<2ND_LINE>AM-Weicker-Meese,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weicker Uses Expletive To Describe Meese</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Note contents of grafs 1 and 6</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Lowell Weicker said
Wednesday that Attorney General Edwin Meese III is ``a son of a
bitch'' that he doesn't like, but stopped short of saying Meese
should resign.
   Connecticut's other senator, Democrat Christopher Dodd, said
Meese should step down. In taking that position, Dodd said he had
voted against Meese's confirmation in the first place and merely
was being consistent.
   The two lawmakers were guests of President Reagan on Air Force
One en route to New London, Conn., where Reagan delivered the
commencement address at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy.
   Weicker and Dodd made their comments separately, talking with
reporters in the rear cabin of the presidential jet about Reagan's
longtime friend while the president was in his cabin at the front
of the aircraft. A reporter reminded Weicker that his comments were
on the record.
   Weicker, a frequent critic of administration policies who is
seeking a fourth term in office this fall, expressed surprise that
he had been invited aboard Air Force One.
   Meese has been been the target of a criminal investigation by
independent counsel James McKay of possible conflict of interest.
There have been repeated calls for Meese's resignation. When a
reporter asked Weicker if Meese should step down, he said, ``I've
been battling the son of a bitch ever since he became attorney
general. I don't like him.''
   However, Weicker said, ``I want to see the report of the special
prosecutor (McKay)'' before saying whether Meese should leave.
   Later, as Reagan toured a Coast Guard cutter in New London,
television reporters tried to get Weicker to repeat his assessment
of Meese on camera. He said merely that he wanted to see the
special prosecutor's report.
   When pressed on the issue by ABC-TV correspondent Sam Donaldson,
Weicker playfully thrust his hand behind the cameras and raised his
middle finger in the reporter's face.
   Reagan often invites members of Congress to accompany him on
trips to their states and districts as a matter of presidential
courtesy.
   Reagan, eating lunch with members of the cutter's crew, was
asked by a reporter about conservatives' unhappiness over Meese's
firing of Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland.
   ``I think some will keep on trying to make a fuss over him
(Meese),'' Reagan replied. ``So far, they're all empty charges.''
</TEXT>
