<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deputies-Smoking     05-18 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deputies-Smoking,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sheriff's Association Approves Hiring of Non-Smokers Only</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The county Sheriff's Association
overwhelmingly ratified a new contract that would ban the hiring of
smokers.
   The provision does not apply to smokers already employed by the
department, said Ron Komers, director of the Ventura County
Personnel Department.
   The 550-member association, made up of sheriff's deputies,
sergeants and investigators, voted by a 9-1 ratio last week in
favor of the two-year contract. The county Board of Supervisors is
expected to give its final approval next week.
   Under the plan, new employees would be required to sign an
agreement stating they will not smoke, he said. Violators could be
fired.
   No law enforcement agency in California and only a few across
the nation have such a policy, officials said.
   County spokeswoman Lucy Crockett said the contract was modeled
on one instituted by Alexandria, Va., police 11 years ago. That
policy, however, was rescinded in 1986 and replaced with one that
allows smoking in designated areas because the department had
``trouble with enforcement,'' she said.
   The measure is intended to reduce health-care and pension costs,
which, statistics show, can range up to $5,000 more per year for a
smoker than for a non-smoker, Komers said.
</TEXT>
