<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     05-18 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Meets Jewish Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson met Wednesday with Jewish
leaders in what he described as ``a step toward healing the
wounds'' and the beginning of in-depth dialogue with Jewish critics
of his Democratic presidential candidacy.
   A few in the group endorsed him.
   Jackson said after the 90-minute private meeting with a dozen
Los Angeles area rabbis and about 20 other Jewish leaders that he
would have a similar meeting in New York next month _ after
California's June 7 presidential primary.
   His campaign has been troubled by opposition from Jewish voters,
due in part to his 1979 meeting with Palestine Liberation
Organization leader Yasser Arafat, his reference in 1984 to New
York as ``Hymietown'' and his past relationship to Louis Farrakhan,
who has made anti-Jewish statements.
   While about a dozen demonstrators outside Jackson's Hollywood
hotel chanted ``Lose, Jesse, lose,'' ``Jew hater'' and ``Jesse, get
out of town,'' Jackson and about half of the participants in the
closed session praised each other at a joint news conference.
   Jackson described the session as ``a step toward healing the
wounds,'' adding that ``We do live in one global community. ... We
walk together.''
   Rabbi Allen Freehling said that ``the litany of complaints in
the Jewish community with Jesse Jackson has been articulated'' and
that there was ``a reconciliation.''
   ``We are as Jews and blacks united in one respect: We have a
common commitment to justice,'' said Rabbi Leonard Beerman, one of
the few participants in the session to say he was endorsing Jackson.
   Asked by reporters why he didn't have a similar meeting while
campaigning in New York last month, Jackson cited verbal attacks
against him by Edward Koch, New York City's Jewish mayor, and said,
``Here you have a climate that is more conducive'' to healing his
differences with Jewish voters. ``We thought this was the right
place to start.''
   Koch had said during the New York primary campaign that Jewish
voters concerned about the fate of Israel would have to be crazy to
vote for Jackson.
   Jackson said on Wednesday, ``I met with Arafat. So did the pope.
We took him not arms. ... We took to him an appeal for reason, for
justice.''
   On another subject, Jackson said he would not let death threats
deter his campaign.
   Asked if he was changing anything because of the arrests Tuesday
of a St. Louis couple accused of conspiring to harm or kill him,
Jackson replied, ``No, we are not. We know that those who will do
peace must face the hostility of those who are bound to fear.
   ``We will not surrender to the dream-busters. The Secret Service
will handle the dream-busters,'' he said, praising the federal
agents protecting him and other presidential candidates.
   Security spokesmen declined comment on whether Jackson's
security had been increased, but there were no signs of any
significant change in their procedures.
   On politics, Jackson said he was not discouraged by polls
indicating he is trailing Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis by
more than 30 percentage points in California.
   ``All my life has been an uphill battle. We will not
surrender,'' Jackson said.
   Earlier, Jackson had said that the results of the Oregon
primary, where Dukakis defeated him handily, would still give his
campaign a boost in California because his Oregon showing was
better than 1984.
   ``We look forward to California, New Jersey, New Mexico and
Montana as our base of support continues to expand. I'm very
encouraged,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
