<DOCNO> AP880518-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     05-18 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says No Veep Search Started; Dismisses Jackson Letter On
Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis insisted Wednesday that he has not begun looking for a
running mate but said he hoped to choose one before the Democratic
National Convention in July.
   ``Nobody is heading my search for a running mate,'' Dukakis
said. ``The search for a running mate will not begin until the 8th
of June,'' the day after the final primaries.
   The Washington Post reported Wednesday that Dukakis campaign
chairman Paul Brountas was heading the search.
   ``I haven't made that decision,'' Dukakis told a Statehouse news
conference. ``But it will be a thoughtful, and I hope successful,
search.''
   Several Dukakis aides, speaking privately, said they were aware
of no formal search for a running mate but that they expected
Brountas, a law school classmate and close friend of the governor,
to head the effort.
   With prospects of a convention battle with Jackson, Dukakis was
asked if he hoped to choose a running mate before then.
   ``Most nominees do,'' he said. ``If I'm the nominee I would hope
that decision will be made before the convention, sure, or at least
the recommendations.''
   The Massachusetts governor also brushed off the latest challenge
of delegate selection rules from rival Jesse Jackson, whose
campaign on Wednesday said it sent Dukakis a letter indicating
Jackson planned a convention challenge to delegate rules.
   Jackson has been complaining recently that Dukakis has unfairly
been getting the support of the majority of ``super delegates,''
elected officials and party leaders who automatically are
convention delegates.
   ``I don't think we are going to have a fight with Mr. Jackson,''
he said.
   ``I think Jesse has a perfect right to voice criticism of
whatever he chooses to criticize,'' he said, before repeating his
position that Jackson knew the delegate selection rules when he
entered the race.
   Dukakis was leaving Massachusetts Wednesday night for
appearances in New York and New Jersey. He was to attend several
events Thursday morning in New Jersey before heading to California
for several days of campaigning there. California and New Jersey
hold primaries June 7.
   Dukakis held the news conference to announce an executive order
expanding state use of recycled products and banning the state from
purchasing non-recyclable polystyrene products, which have been
linked to damaging the ozone layer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
