<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pandas     05-18 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pandas,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wildlife Group Thwarted in Latest Bid to Block Opening of Panda
Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has turned down a request for
an expedited hearing by a wildlife group, clearing the way for the
Toledo Zoo to begin exhibiting two giant pandas from China,
officials said Wednesday.
   Kenneth Cook, press director of the World Wildlife Fund, said he
had hoped a hearing could be held in U.S. District Court this week
on the group's motion to bar the exhibit, which is scheduled to
open next Tuesday.
   But Cook said Judge Norma Johnson could not schedule a hearing
that soon and asked the parties to file additional briefs in the
case.
   ``I think it happens when the court gets jammed,'' said Cook.
``We're disappointed. We're stuck.''
   But he said the wildlife fund intends to continue its fight and
plans to file its brief on Friday. He said he presumes a hearing
will be set after the reply briefs are filed.
   Ellen Efros, lawyer for the zoo, said rules require that a reply
brief be filed within five working days of the wildlife fund's
filing. She said the judge's decision clears the way for the
exhibit to open.
   Last week Judge Johnson refused to grant a temporary restraining
order sought by the group to prevent the pandas from being shipped
to Toledo from Shanghai.
   The pandas are scheduled to spend at least 100 days at the zoo,
which has spent nearly $3 million preparing for their visit.
   In their suit against the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, the
wildlife fund argued that exhibition of the pandas violates an
international convention that prohibits trafficking in endangered
species for commercial purposes.
   The group says the exhibition would increase the demand for such
transactions from other zoos and hurt the effort to breed pandas.
</TEXT>
