<2ND_LINE>AM-TV-Tartikoff,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC To Experiment with Prime-Time News This Summer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC will devote an hour to prime-time news this
summer, and if the strike by the Writers Guild of America doesn't
end by midsummer, prime-time news could be part of the fall lineup,
NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff said Wednesday.
   Tartikoff told reporters in a satellite news conference that NBC
plans to put news specials and a potential series with Connie Chung
into the Tuesday 10 p.m. EDT time period by the end of June.
   NBC has not had a prime-time news show since ``1986'' was
canceled a year and a half ago. CBS has three prime-time news
hours: ``60 Minutes,'' ``48 Hours'' and ``West 57th.'' ABC has
``20@20.''
   NBC has scored in the ratings this season with lifestyle
documentaries like Chung's ``Life in the Fat Lane'' and Maria
Shriver's ``Women in Prison.''
   NBC starts the season with prime-time coverage of the Summer
Olympics, but Tartikoff said if the writers' strike continues
through the summer, it could delay the start of NBC's series. A
news show, unaffected by the strike, he said, ``may continue out of
that crisis the way (ABC's) `Nightline' continued out of the Iran
hostage crisis.''
   NBC's news writers are members of the National Association of
Broadcast Employees and Technicians rather than of the Writer's
Guild.
</TEXT>
