<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-18 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Convoy Greeted by Music and Cheering Crowd</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TERMEZ, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bands, banners and a cheering crowd on
Wednesday greeted the first Soviet soldiers to cross the border in
the withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   ``The soldiers are leaving, but friendship with the Soviet Union
stays,'' the Afghan defense minister, Mohammad Rafie, told a rally
in this border town. ``And it will keep developing and growing even
stronger.'' His comments were reported by the Soviet news agency
Tass.
   Nikolai Novikov, 21, was the first Soviet soldier to cross the
bridge over the river Amu-Darya that forms the border between
Afghanistan and Soviet Uzbekistan. He was riding on a flower-decked
armored personnel carrier.
   Behind him followed 228 vehicles and about 1,300 soldiers of his
motor rifle unit.
   The convoy was the first significant withdrawal of Soviet forces
under a U.N.-sponsored peace accord that calls for the Kremlin to
remove all of its estimated 115,000 soldiers within nine months.
   The Kremlin sent soldiers over the border into Afghanistan in
December 1979. They replaced one pro-Soviet government with another
and stayed to help fight U.S.-backed Moslem insurgents.
   Tass said Col. Yuri Starov, unit commander, told a rally: ``Our
officers and men have done all they could for peace on Afghan
soil.''
   ``Our best comrades have not laid down their lives there in
vain,'' he said. ``Afghanistan remains free and independent.''
   Rafie said that as a result of Soviet aid, ``Children are going
to school, peasants are cultivating land and workers are operating
their lathes.''
   ``You have helped us to create a battleworthy people's army
which can independently fulfill any assignment to protect the
fatherland,'' he said.
   Reporters flown to Termez saw troops cross the ``Bridge of
Friendship'' from the Afghan village of Khairaton.
   Information about the Soviet withdrawal has been relayed from
Kabul by a Reuters news agency pool report.
   The Associated Press was denied permission to travel to
Afghanistan for the pullout. A Soviet Foreign Ministry official
said recently the exclusion was the result of ``inappropriate
questions'' asked during a previous visit by AP.
   Tass said a band played a march as the convoy crossed the river,
and motorists honked their car horns. The military vehicles honked
their horns in reply.
   Most of the Soviet troops in the initial withdrawal convoy had
left their base in Jalalabad, near the border with Pakistan, early
Sunday.
   The most dangerous stretches of the three-day journey of the
convoy from Kabul to Termez had been expected to be a gorge north
of the capital and the Salang tunnel, in the Hindu Kush mountains,
overrun with rebels.
   But Col. Grigory Bondarev, a senior officer with the convoy,
said there were no major incidents on the journey from Jalalabad,
west to the capital Kabul and north to the Soviet border.
   ``All who left Jalalabad arrived safe and healthy,'' he said.
``I can tell you officially that there was no shooting from
Jalalabad to Kabul and from Kabul to Khairaton.''
   But Soviet TV on Tuesday night showed a correspondent with the
convoy while rifle fire crackled around him. The reporter did not
give his location.
   The Geneva accord was signed last month by Pakistan and
Afghanistan with the Soviet Union and United States as guarantors.
The fundamentalist Moslem guerrillas did not participate in the
negotiations or sign the pact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
