<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Stephens     05-18 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Stephens,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Eisenhower Aide Dies At Age 84</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas E. Stephens, who was appointments
secretary to President Dwight D. Eisenhower during his two terms,
has died. He was 84.
   Stephens died Sunday at Morton Plant Hospital.
   Born in Ireland, Stephens obtained law degrees from Brooklyn Law
School and St. Lawrence College, said Herb Pankratz, a researcher
for the Eisenhower Library in Abilene, Kan.
   Stephens was affiliated with the New York law firm of Lord, Day
and Lord during the 1930s. In 1938, he was an administrative
assistant to Newbold Morris, then president of the City Council.
   He became active in the Republican Party during the 1940s,
serving at one time as the party's director of campaign development.
   In 1949, Stephens took his first job in Washington, D.C., as
administrative assistant to Sen. John Foster Dulles, who became
Secretary of State under Eisenhower. Stephens became Eisenhower's
appointments secretary in 1952.
   Stephens moved to Clearwater in 1973.
   He is survived by his wife of 27 years, Mary. No funeral was
planned.
</TEXT>
