<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czech-Church     05-18 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czech-Church,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names of Three Roman Catholic Bishops Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities released the names
Wednesday of two auxiliary Roman Catholic bishops and an apostolic
administrator who will be appointed in June, state radio reported.
   The two auxiliaries, to serve in Prague, were identified as Jan
Lebeda, now vicar general, and Antonin Liska. They will assist
Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek, the 88-year-old archbishop of Prague
and Czechoslovakia's Catholic primate.
   Jan Sokol, the third appointee, will be apostolic administrator
for the archdiocese of Trnava in Slovakia.
   Keston College, a London-based organization that monitors
religious life in the Soviet bloc, said none of the new three
belongs to Pacem in Terris, a government-sponsored clergy
organization the Vatican does not recognize.
   An apostolic administrator is considered a ``titular bishop,''
ranking below a full resident bishop.
   Church sources in Prague had mentioned the same names earlier
this week. Lengthy negotiations between the government and a
Vatican delegation preceded the appointments.
   Ten of Czechoslovakia's 13 dioceses still lack full bishops and
the three serving bishops are over age 75. No new Czechoslovak
bishops have been appointed since 1973.
</TEXT>
