<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Economy     05-18 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Economy,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic Reform Delayed Again Due To Lack Of Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's latest economic
reforms, scheduled to start May 15, will be postponed until June
because of lack of emergency credits from the West, the state
Tanjug news agency said Wednesday.
   The reform package is aimed at curbing Yugoslavia's 170 percent
inflation rate, Europe's highest, by removing price controls,
liberalizing imports and instituting a foreign exchange market.
   Yugoslavia's six-month partial wage and price freeze, insituted
last fall, was prolonged earlier this month after the government
announced it had failed to secure about $300 million in emergency
loans.
   Yugoslavia must secure the credits in order to receive an
expected $1.4 billion in new loans from the International Monetary
Fund, Western governments and banks, to finance the country's $20
billion foreign debt.
   The new economic program will be delayed for another 10 to 15
days, or until until the initial credits became available to the
National Bank of Yugoslavia, according to the agency.
   Tanjug said Yugoslavia is expected to secure the short-term loan
from the Basel-based Bank for International Settlements only after
a stand-by arrangement for the new loans is approved by the
International Monetary Fund.
   The IMF Board of Directors is scheduled to meet before early
June, when the new Yugoslav economic measures are expected to be
introduced.
</TEXT>
