<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Whistleblowers     05-18 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whistleblowers,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Dismissed Workers Get Awards For Whistleblowing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private foundation gave $10,000 awards
Wednesday to three people who lost their jobs after alleging
wrongdoing by their employers.
   The Cavallo Foundation, set up by Massachusetts money manager
Michael Cavallo, gave its first annual awards to a fired shipyard
inspector, a former Census Bureau worker and an ex-Veterans
Administration employee.
   The awards, presented by Cavallo at a news conference, came on
the eve of a Senate committee vote on a bill that would protect
government employees who disclose abuses. The bill would restrict
the Office of the Special Counsel from acting against
whistleblowers who complain that the agency often ends up
investigating them when they file complaints.
   The Governmental Affairs Committee is to take up the bill, which
would also give additional judicial protection to whistelblowers,
on Thursday.
   ``They probably thought I was a nitpicker and a busybody, but I
didn't care,'' said Leon Bard, 34, who was fired in 1986 as a
quality inspector at Bath Iron Works in Bath, Maine, after he
disclosed that uninspected steel was being used in the construction
of Ticonderoga-class Navy cruisers.
   The company has denied that it used uninspected materials in its
shipbuilding. Bard, who is suing to get his job back, said he now
does seasonal excavation work and odd jobs in Bath.
   John Barter, 39, said he was fired as security chief at the
Cincinnati Veterans Administration Medical Center for reporting
alleged brutality to patients by a VA police chief.
   ``I hope my suffering will lead to real free speech rights for
other employees,'' said Barter, who works part-time for a halfway
house in Cincinnati but said he has been unable to find a full-time
job since he was fired.
   The other award winner, Billie Pirner Garde, 35, got a law
degree after she was fired for speaking out eight years ago against
corruption and sexual harassment in the Muskogee, Okla., district
office of the Census Bureau. Now, she works in Appleton, Wis., with
the Government Accountability Project, defending whistleblowers in
the nuclear industry.
   She referred to whistleblowers' stories as ``bureaucratic
profiles in courage.''
   In addition to the annual awards, the foundation gave a special
award and $3,000 to long-time whistleblower A. Ernest Fitzgerald,
61, who has become well-known for disclosing corruption and
mismanagement in the Defense Department, where he has worked for 23
years.
   Fitzgerald praised Cavallo for setting up the awards, saying,
``I just hope you don't run out of money, because the other side
has lots more.''
   Cavallo, 35, who said he contributed $300,000 to set up the
foundation last year, described the award as a reward for people
``who risk their jobs and risk having their lives turned upside
down for doing the right thing.'
   He said the awardees were chosen by a panel from among 25 people
nominated by public interest groups, investigative reporters and
others.
</TEXT>
