<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GraveSearch     05-18 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grave Search,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Development Delayed Over Search For Ancient Graves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the lives of Arthur Vinal Jr. and
Edward Wanton are separated by nearly three centuries, their names
both appear on a lawsuit seeking to stop the construction of four
houses.
   One of Wanton's descendants has gone to to court seeking to
block Vinal's proposed building project until a more thorough
search is made for a 17th-century burial ground believed to contain
the remains of Wanton and other early Quaker colonists.
   A hearing is scheduled next week in Plymouth County Superior
Court on Sally Sanford's request for an injunction.
   Sanford, a New York musician and Wanton's
great-great-great-great-great-great-great-granddaughter, obtained a
temporary restraining order against the development Tuesday.
Historical burial grounds are protected by state law.
   But Vinal, himself a descendant of 17th century settlers, said
an extensive search was made and two old headstones were discovered
outside the site proposed for four single-family homes.
   ``I've read a lot of stories about the North River and knew
about the burial ground. That's why we looked around before we made
any plans,'' said Vinal.
   ``I'm convinced we will not be disturbing any burial site with
the four homes,'' he said.
   The town planning board last June approved construction of four
houses on 16 of the 80 acres owned by Vinal for about 20 years.
   ``We've done what is expected of a developer,'' said Vinal's
attorney, Peter Puciloski. ``The suit is simply without merit.''
   Sanford said Wanton fled the Massachusetts Bay Colony in the
mid-1600s and settled on the North River, where he worked as a
teacher, village leader and shipwright.
   He set aside land near his house where he and other Quakers were
buried. Quakers are a Christian sect founded in England about 1650
based on a rejection of violence.
   Sanford maintains the full 16 acres should be surveyed more
carefully. Her suit says Norwell planners did not consider
affidavits from long-time residents who said they had knowledge of
the location of the burial site.
   Sanford said she became interested in Wanton nine years ago when
researching family roots.
</TEXT>
