<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Switzerland-Bishop     05-18 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Switzerland-Bishop,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope's Nomination of Bishop Stirs Controversy in Swiss Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II's nomination of a conservative
bishop has touched off a controversy that bares deep discontent
among Swiss Roman Catholics over what critics charge is a growing
assertion of Vatican dominance. Wolfgang Haas, 40, is to be
consecrated Sunday as auxiliary bishop in Switzerland's
second-largest diocese, Chur. The title of coadjutor bestowed on
him by the pontiff gives the prelate the automatic right to succeed
Bishop Johannes Vonderach, 72, as head of the Chur Diocese.
   The nomination of Haas, said to hold strongly conservative views
of the church's role in society, has drawn wide criticism in the
lay and religious press of Switzerland.
   The appointment is also being challenged as incompatible with a
special privilege the Vatican granted in 1948 to Chur's ``Cathedral
chapter'' of 24 leading priests, who have the right to elect their
bishop from among three candidates named by the pope.
   ``Catholics feel deeply hurt in their sense of justice,'' said
an editorial this week in Orientierung, a Zurich Roman Catholic
periodical. ``One has the impression that even in Rome, people and
institutions who are thoroughly willing to respect the cultural and
political peculiarities of a country were not consulted.''
   Switzerland is a cradle of Protestantism and the native land of
the Rev. Hans Kueng, a critic of the papacy.
   Reform-minded Catholics are also concerned that Haas'
conservatism will reduce the role of the many lay people who have
become active in parishes since the 1960s.
   Haas, 40, is said to have little sympathy for the increasingly
important role of women in the church in Switzerland.
   ``He has already refused to say Mass in the Chur cathedral
because a woman was supposed to deliver the homily,'' said
theologian Martha Brun.
   Last week, a petition signed by 267 of the Chur Diocese's 550
priests was handed to the representative of the pope in the capital
of Bern. It demanded that Haas renounce his appointment pending
clarification of the special rights of succession in the Chur
Diocese.
   ``The problem is that a vested right was bypassed,'' said the
Rev. Guido Kolb, a member of the Cathedral Chapter, who delivered
the petition to the capital. ``But the tendency in Rome is
centralist again, ignoring the privileges of thelocal churches.''
   Kolb said the non-signers included ``those who felt the petition
was too conciliatory and others who favor dropping the matter.''
   Haas has yet to react to the criticism. He has merely said he
``cannot and will not'' renounce his right of succession.
   But his consecration is not likely to end the debate.
   Theology students have staged protest demonstrations in Chur,
where 50 students mounted a 10-hour vigil in front of the
cathedral, and in the city of Fribourg, which has Switzerland's
largest Roman Catholic university. In Fribourg, a funeral cortege
accompanied a coffin marked ``Second Vatican Council'' _ a
reference to the program of reforms instituted in the 1960s to
modernize the church.
</TEXT>
