<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PaperDoctors     05-18 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paper Doctors,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspended Doctors Rush To Catch Up On Patient Records For
Reinstatement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly half the 290 doctors suspended by
Tampa General Hospital for falling behind in paperwork rushed to
complete patient records Wednesday to win reinstatement, a
spokeswoman said.
   The list of suspensions, which affected admitting privileges
only, stood at 159 doctors by midday Wednesday, a day after it was
posted at the hospital, said Cindy Tanner, spokeswoman at the
hospital.
   Ms. Tanner said that since the hospital's large records section
is open around-the-clock, there has been no crush from doctors
scrambling to fill out forms.
   ``It has been a smooth process,'' she said.
   Of the 331 doctors warned in notices mailed Sunday, 41 complied
before Tuesday. The 290 suspensions represented about one-third of
the staff.
   ``It's no big deal,'' said Tom Clark, executive director of the
Hillsborough County Medical Association. ``Hospitals all over the
country do it.''
   Clark said he hadn't received many complaints from doctors. But
he said Tampa General let too many doctors fall behind with too
many records, causing a budget shortfall.
   Hospital President Newell France noted that patients and
insurance companies can't be billed and Medicare and Medicaid won't
pay until records are completed.
   Bills worth $5.5 million for patients discharged more than a
month ago have been held up because of the problem, France said,
causing a ``definite impact on cash flow.''
   In addition, France said, the Joint Commission on Accreditation
cited Tampa General in its January survey for allowing charts to
fall behind. It gave the hospital until June to get them in order.
   Dr. Edward Spoto, hospital chief of staff, said the number of
suspensions appeared to be ``extrordinary'' because the hospital
and medical staff are ``strictly enforcing staff rules and
regulations'' and a new physician-medical records information and
notification system has been installed.
   The system allows more frequent notification to physicians about
incomplete charts and records. The old system notified them once a
month, and gave the physicians 15 days to complete their charts, he
said.
   In an emezgency, emergency room physicians can admit a patient
even if the person's doctor is suspended. Non-emergency admissions
must wait until the physician is reinstated.
</TEXT>
