<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Post, Newsweek Editors Interview Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Editors from The Washington Post and Newsweek
interviewed Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Wednesday.
   The Soviet news agency Tass reported that the interview took
place, and the evening television news program ``Vremya'' showed a
short film clip of Gorbachev meeting the U.S. journalists.
   Tass said the group included Washington Post Chairman Katharine
Graham; Newsweek Editor Richard Smith; and Washington Post editors
Jimmie Hoagland, Meg Greenfield and Robert Kaiser.
   No details of the interview were released, but the Soviet media
said it would be published in the Soviet press on Monday following
its publication in Sunday's editions of the Post and next week's
issues of Newsweek.
   Gorbachev granted the interview less than two weeks before
President Reagan arrives in Moscow for his fourth meeting with the
Soviet leader.
   Prior to traveling to Washington for their meeting in December,
Gorbachev granted an interview to NBC News.
