<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TVProgramRules 1stLd-Writethru a0749 05-18 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Program Rules, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Exclusivity Ruling May Cut Into Reruns on Superstations, Cable</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: RECASTS lead to clarify; adds new detail, reaction throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Wednesday approved rules that are likely to reduce how often TV
viewers will see reruns of shows like ``The Brady Bunch'' and ``I
Love Lucy.''
   The FCC, voting 3-0 to adopt the rules, said local TV stations
will be able to negotiate exclusive contracts for syndicated
programs. Cable TV systems that broadcast the same programs in a
local station's viewing area will have to black out the shows or
substitute other programs.
   Broadcasters welcomed the rules, but the cable industry
predicted an outcry from angry viewers and said it will challenge
the rules in court. Some critics say the rules could spell the end
of some so-called superstations, whose local signals are carried by
cable systems in other parts of the country.
   FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said he expects the rules will
end the ``reign of reruns'' on TV, and, by giving broadcasters a
measure of protection, will heighten the value of the programs to
advertisers. More ad revenue, in turn, will foster production of
new programs, he said.
   ``The big winners today are consumers. They will benefit by a
smooth transition to a fairer and more competitive market structure
which promises richer and more diverse programming,'' Patrick said.
   It is unlikely cable systems will have to resort to blackouts to
comply with the rules, Patrick said, because of a one-year
transition period, a variety of exceptions that will be allowed and
the amount of substitute programming that is availble.
   ``Blackouts will only occur if cable operators seek to cause
turmoil for short-term political advantage, which I cannot believe
they will do,'' he said.
   Broadcasters have been pushing the FCC to reimpose exclusivity
rules and were happy with the final product, but the National Cable
Television Association said the action ``pulled the plug on the
favorite TV programs of millions of people.''
   NCTA President James Mooney predicted that ``people whose
favorite programs disappear will be angered and bewildered,'' and
the costs of syndicated programming will go up.
   The rules are similar to ones the FCC dropped in 1980. Since
then, cable systems have been able to carry the signals of
out-of-town stations such as WTBS in Atlanta, WWOR in the New York
area and WGN in Chicago, which have become known as superstations,
even when those stations transmit programs whose rights were bought
by a local TV station.
   Ted Turner, chairman of Turner Broadcasting Inc., which owns
WTBS, said in a statement the new rules ``do not give the cable
industry a realistic chance to avoid massive blackouts.''
   Turner held out the possibility of a court appeal, but said that
decision would be made after the FCC issues its written rules.
   Jeff Treeman, senior vice president of United Video, the Tulsa,
Okla.-based cable carrier that distributes superstation signals,
including WGN, said cable systems in some large markets, where
independents can afford to buy exclusive rights to programming, may
have to black out or substitute shows for as much as 40 percent of
a superstation's programming.
   ``That's enough for the cable operator to drop the signal,'' he
said.
   Under the new syndicated programming exclusivity rules, TV
stations will be able to negotiate for exclusive rights to a
syndicated program and will be able to force a cable system to
honor that contract. The rules also allow broadcasters to negotiate
rights with cable systems.
   Superstations also will be able to buy exclusive rights for
syndicated shows on a nationwide basis, under the rules.
   Patrick said the new rules won't go into effect for one year, to
give cable systems time to prepare.
   The rules won't apply to cable systems with fewer than 1,000
subscribers. About half of all cable systems fall into this
category, though they serve only about 5 percent of the nation's 45
million cable subscribers, the FCC said.
   ``You will see more diversity in programs,'' said Edward O.
Fritts, president of the National Association of Broadcasters,
though he added that rules will likely drive up the cost of
syndicated programming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
