<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDSSpots     05-18 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Spots,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Spots Being Readied to Promote AIDS Pamphlets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials are pushing out a
wave of television spots to herald the arrival in the mails next
week of a historic pamphlet on AIDS.
   The first of the 107 million copies being mailed to every
American household are to begin arriving next Thursday, with the
bulk of the deliveries to be completed within two weeks. It marks
the first time the federal government has every mailed a health
message to every household.
   Public Health Service spokesman Jim Brown said Wednesday all the
major networks except NBC, which did not respond, have agreed to
air special spots alerting Americans to be looking for the
eight-page booklet.
   Dr. Robert E. Windom, the No. 2 official in the Department of
Health and Human Services, and Surgeon General C. Everett Koop
wrote letters seeking two minutes of network air time Sunday at
9:58 p.m.
   Brown said the Fox Network and the Cable News Network had agreed
to that request. ABC agreed instead to air a 30-second spot,
featuring Windom and Koop, in four separate slots, including at the
start of its ``Baby M'' movie Saturday night, on ``Good Morning
America'' and during the popular afternoon soap opera ``General
Hospital.''
   Brown said CBS has agreed to broadcast shorter spots promoting
the mailer on 130 occasions during the next two weeks. ``We're
delighted,'' he said.
</TEXT>
