<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     05-18 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says VP Would Lead Anti-Drug War, Declines Noriega-Deal
Comment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush declared Wednesday he
would not ``bargain with drug dealers'' as president, but he still
refused to give his views on reports of a plea-bargain deal with
Panamanian Gen. Manuel Noriega.
   In a day devoted to tough talk on drugs, the vice president
visited a ``rock house'' where the potent cocaine derivative crack
was sold and used, then said in a speech at the Los Angeles Policy
Academy that he would put his vice president in charge of a
``Cabinet-level council of war'' against illegal drugs.
   ``Drug dealers are domestic terrorists, killing kids and cops
and they should be treated as such,'' Bush said. ``I won't bargain
with terrorists and I won't bargain with drug dealers either,
whether they are on U.S. or foreign soil.''
   Bush spokesman Peter Teeley was asked if Bush meant that
statement to apply to Noriega. He said Bush responded that his
statement referred to ``the way I would deal with drug dealers as
president.''
   The Reagan administration has been taking part in negotiations
designed to persuade Noreiga to step down from power. Published
reports have said that the dropping of U.S. drug charges against
Noriega would be part of the deal.
   At an earlier appearance Wednesday, Bush was asked again about
such a deal with Noriega. He refused comment as he has each time he
has been asked.
   As for his proposal that his vice president be in charge of a
Bush administration anti-drug effort, he said, ``I've been involved
as vice president as part of the federal effort against drugs. But
I've concluded that's not enough. If I'm elected, I will put my
vice president in charge of every aspect of federal drug policy.
   ``Together we can coordinate an attack on the drug trade that
will be nothing less than a modern D-Day. ... We have not spent the
last 200 years defending our country from despots and dictators,
only to lose our streets to drug dealers and gangs.''
   Bush said of his visit to the storefront ``rock house,'' which
police raided May 2, ``It's not show business. Anybody who has
practical experience, you learn from them. You try to learn and
understand and then take action. ... It's been extraordinarily
helpful.''
   On the last day of a week-long Western campaign swing, Bush went
to the police academy to deliver a speech praising the
administration's drug enforcement efforts but adding, ``We still
have miles to go and we can't rest.''
   ``I'll demand stronger penalties for drug offenders,'' he said.
``Mike Dukakis and Jesse Jackson criticize our anti-drug efforts _
and I readily concede there's room for improvement _ but I want
them to join me in these tougher penalties. This isn't Democratic
or Republican.''
   ``The message should be clear: If you deal drugs you're going to
do time. I want to see drug dealers behind the iron bars of prison,
not law-abiding citizens behind protective bars at home,'' he said.
   Bush chief of staff Craig Fuller said the speech was the first
in a series on drugs with a major one coming up outlining plans for
reorganizing the nation's effort against drug abuse.
</TEXT>
