<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HarvardUnion     05-18 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvard Union,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Workers Unionize, But Fight Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sometimes bitter labor fight between
Harvard University and 3,300 of its white-collar employees is not
necessarily over now that the workers have voted to unionize, both
sides said Wednesday.
   The day after the narrow union victory, Harvard officials said
they may challenge the results with the National Labor Relations
Board while union representatives accused the university of
violating labor laws and began preparing for contract negotiations
that could last a year or more.
   By a 1,530 to 1,486 vote, the university's clerical and
technical workers, 80 percent of whom are women, approved a bid to
organize under the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
   ``We're all ecstatic,'' said Kristine Rondeau, chief organizer
of the union effort and a former Harvard employee. ``We want to
make this a model for women everywhere.''
   Harvard President Derek Bok, who spent much of his academic
career writing about labor issues and often praised unions, was out
of town Wednesday and unavailable for comment, according to the
university's press office.
   But Anne Taylor, the administrator directing Harvard's response
to the union, said, ``In the event the NLRB declares the union the
winner, Harvard will work constructively with the union in the
interest of support staff and the university.''
   Henry Griggs, AFSCME spokesman, said Harvard's clerical workers
``have waited a long time for this. But they'll have a fight on
their hands. They'll have to negotiate a contract, but at least
this time they'll have a voice.''
   Rondeau didn't want to predict how long negotiations might last,
but Taylor estimated that based on the experiences of Yale and
other schools it would take eight months to a year to develop the
first contract.
   Taylor said university administrators are checking out
complaints from individual workers that union supporters
intimidated them during Tuesday's voting. University administrators
have five working days to file a motion with the NLRB if they
conclude the workers' allegations could be grounds for throwing out
the election.
   The union leveled a countercharge that department supervisors
sought to intimidate workers during the voting by pacing near
polling places.
   These were only the latest in a series of exchanges between the
university and the union.
   Harvard has blasted the union for calling its efforts
``anti-union.'' Taylor said on election day that the union failed
to offer any concrete gains to workers.
   And in a letter sent last month to the clerical workers, Bok
wrote that ``unions have typically resisted efforts to reward
superior achievement.''
   Even in victory, Rondeau refused to back down from her charge
that the university broke labor law by telling workers that if a
union was formed, they would lose all their benefits and have to
begin negotiating from zero.
   In fact, Rondeau said, negotiations will begin at current salary
levels, which the union says average about $18,000 per year and the
university puts at closer to $19,000.
   The union plans to seek increased pension benefits and an end to
the practice of job reclassification, which she called ``a
euphemism for getting rid of older workers.''
   Seven unions currently operate on the Harvard campus,
representing 1,300 workers in such fields as plumbing, building
maintenance, cafeteria work and communications. The AFSCME clerical
union would cover such jobs as librarians, secretaries, biomedical
assistants and copy center operaters.
   Bok, who holds graduate degrees in law and economics and has
been Harvard president since 1971, has published books and articles
in which he has often praised the U.S. labor movement. For example,
a 1971 Harvard law review article said that nowhere else in the
world but the United States ``can one find such an efflorescence of
collectively bargained experiments providing imaginative benefits
for workers.''
</TEXT>
