<DOCNO> AP880518-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DenverAirport     05-18 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denver Airport,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor, Mayor Jubilant Over Annexation Of Denver Airport Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Roy Romer and Mayor Federico Pena on
Wednesday went to the barren site of what could become the nation's
largest airport to celebrate voters' decision to allow the city to
annex 45 square miles of land for the project.
   ``There still are a lot of people asking questions and that's
fair,'' Pena said in a tent at the site. ``We are going to get the
project done and meet our goal'' to open the airport by the summer
of 1994.
   The proposal on Tuesday won the support of 34,070 voters in
suburban Adams County, or 55.9 percent, while 26,928, or 44.1
percent, voted against it. A total of 47.6 percent of the county's
voters cast ballots.
   Denver proposes a $3 billion replacement for Stapleton
International Airport, now the fifth-busiest in the country. The
new airport, 10 miles northeast of Stapleton and 17 miles from
downtown, could be the second-busiest in the nation by the year
2000, estimates show.
   Pena said construction now is virtually assured. ``This is the
rocket booster that pushes the airport project forward,'' he said.
   But some financial issues remain unresolved and an environmental
review and legal challenges are ahead. If those are resolved,
ground for the new facility could be broken in the summer of 1989.
   Denver has asked for $500 million over five years in federal
aid, and the city this summer will turn over its environmental
assessment to the Federal Aviation Administration for review.
   Opponents, who had expressed concern about increased air
pollution, jet noise and other environmental effects, vowed to
continue their fight.
   Hal Shroyer of suburban Westminster, one of the most outspoken
foes of the new airport, has filed a lawsuit contesting the wording
of the ballot issue.
   ``I think the courts will throw the election out because of the
faulty ballot title. They put those six words in, `For the benefit
of Adams County,''' Shroyer said.
   Stapleton, which is 59 years old, would be torn down and the
land converted for development and open space. Its replacement
would be the first major airport built from scratch in the United
States since the Dallas-Fort Worth airport was built in 1974.
   Nearly 35 million pasengers fly through Stapleton every year,
but officials say FAA projections indicate 50 million passengers
are expected through Denver by 1995. The new airport could
accommodate 100 million passengers a year.
</TEXT>
