<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OrthodoxPatriarch     05-18 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orthodox Patriarch,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patriarch Cancels Plans to Attend Russian Church Celebrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ecumenical Patriarch Dimitrios will not
attend celebrations in Moscow marking the 1,000th anniversary of
Christianity in Russia, Orthodox Church officials said Wednesday.
   Dimitrios, spiritual leader of the world's 180 million Orthodox
Christians, refused to join the celebrations next month because
they would include U.S. and other Orthodox leaders he doesn't
recognize as independent.
   ``The patriarch will not participate in a liturgy that includes
the leaders of the Russian Orthodox churches of Japan and North
America,'' said Yiannis Hadzifotis, spokesman for the Orthodox
Church of Greece.
   Metropolitan Bartholomew, private secretary to the
Istanbul-based patriarch, said only that patriarch would not attend
``because appropriate conditions for participation do not exist.''
   Dimitrios also decided not to send a delegation from the
patriarchate to the celebrations next month, church officials in
Athens and Istanbul said.
   The Orthodox Church in America is derived from the Russian
Orthodox church, which granted the U.S. church independent status
in 1970. It is fully recognized by other Eastern Orthodox bodies in
the United States. But U.S. church sources, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said there may be some difficulty with Dimitrios
recognizing its independence.
   The centerpiece of the 10-day anniversary celebrations is a June
5 service at Moscow's Patriarchal Cathedral. The service was
scheduled to be conducted by Dimitrios with Russian Patriarch Pimen
and other Orthodox patriarchs.
   The Communist Party is officially atheist, but Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev has backed the church's millennium
celebrations as part of his restructuring of society.
   Dimitrios made a publicized visit to the Soviet Union in August
and said earlier this year he would attend the Russian church's
millennium ceremonies.
   Hadzifotis said Russian clerics organizing the celebrations have
insisted that leaders of the Russian Orthodox churches of North
America and Japan take part in the June 5 service, along with the
head of the breakaway Orthodox Church of Macedonia.
   ``This is not correct. None of these churches has been
recognized as autocephalous (independent) by the ecumenical
patriarchate and their leaders cannot be regarded as equal to the
other patriarchs,'' he said.
   Among Orthodox patriarchs, Dimitrios is regarded as first among
equals as head of the oldest Orthodox church.
   The Russian church's decision to grant the American and Japanese
churches independent status is a considered a serious breach of
Orthodox practice, Hadzifotis said.
   Dimitrios also objects to the Russian church's claim that the
Patriarchate of Georgia should stand higher in the hierarchy than
those of Serbia, Bulgaria and Romania, he said.
   Normally, a pan-Orthodox conference would be required to upgrade
the status of smaller Orthodox churches.
   ``In the eyes of other Orthodox churches, the Russians'
unilateral actions are seen as an attempt to challenge the
ecumenical patriarch's authority and dominate the course of
Orthodox Christianity,'' said a senior Greek Orthodox churchman who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
