<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngryMourners     05-18 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angry Mourners,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mourners Walk Out After Bishop Asks For Forgiveness In Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry mourners walked out of a
funeral Mass for a shooting victim after a Roman Catholic bishop
asked forgiveness for the Protestant killers and denounced reported
IRA threats of retaliation.
   About 20 mourners left St. Patrick's Roman Catholic church after
the remarks by Bishop Cahal Daly at the funeral of Stephen McGahan,
27, one of three Catholic men killed in Sunday's shooting at a pub
patronized by Catholics.
   The Protestant Action Force, an outlawed extremist paramilitary
group, claimed responsibility.
   Daly said he prayed ``for the perpetrators of these murders as
well as their victims'' and urged them ``to be free from their
murdering hate.''
   He also denounced reported threats by the Irish Republican Army,
which is fighting to unite this mainly Protestant British province
with the Catholic Republic of Ireland.
   As the bishop finished speaking, some mourners walked out of the
church.
   ``We feel very, very bitter and he only makes us feel more
bitterness toward Protestants,'' said mourner Eddie Kane.
   After the shooting, Patrick McBride, whose 27-year-old brother,
Paul, was those killed, called for peace. ``I don't want any
innocent Protestants to be killed as a result of this,'' he said.
</TEXT>
