<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BankAgency     05-18 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Agency,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Offered to Abolish Asset-Disposal Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats on the House Banking Committee on
Wednesday introduced legislation that would dissolve a heavily
criticized agency created to dispose of property from insolvent
savings institutions.
   The bill, whose lead sponsors are Reps. Paul E. Kanjorski,
D-Pa., Thomas C. McMillen, D-Md., and House Banking Committee
Chairman Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I., would abolish the Federal
Asset Disposition Agency, or FADA, within 60 days.
   Its functions would be turned over to the Federal Savings and
Loan Insurance Corp., the government fund that insures S&L deposits
up to $100,000.
   St Germain told reporters he would attach the bill to
legislation granting banks new powers, including the ability to
underwrite certain securities. Kanjorski said he expected the
committee to act on that bill by June 15.
   McMillen said the 3-year-old FADA, which oversees $4.2 billion
in real estate and loans, has spent more than $100 million and has
managed to dispose of only $775 million in assets.
   ``FADA is a classic example of a government agency gone
haywire,'' Kanjorski said.
   M. Danny Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
which regulates federally insured savings institutions, has argued
that new FADA management installed in February is cleaning up the
agency and trimming waste. He said in a letter last week that
dismantling FADA would cost millions of dollars.
   The dissolution bill is sponsored by 24 of the 30 Democrats on
the Banking Committee and one other Democrat, Rep. James J. Florio
of New Jersey. It has no Republican support.
</TEXT>
