<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   05-18 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, Bjt,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Sees No Convention Fight; Bush Talks Tough on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said Wednesday he doubted Jesse Jackson would
pick a fight at the Democratic National Convention this summer, and
added he hopes to select a running mate before the session
convenes. Vice President George Bush visited a one-time drug
hangout to dramatize his opposition to drugs.
   Jackson met with Jewish leaders in California in hopes of
defusing suspicions over his candidacy. One rabbi spoke of a
reconciliation, but demonstrators outside booed Jackson and
chanted, ``Lose, Jesse, Lose.''
   Dukakis, fresh from Tuesday's landslide victory in the Oregon
primary, is the faraway favorite in public opinion polls in
California. He hopes to clinch a nominating majority by the time
the primary season ends in three weeks with elections in
California, New Jersey, Montana and New Mexico.
   The Massachusetts governor also has received good news in
nationwide polling matchups against Bush in recent days, and top
Bush aides were quoted as being particularly concerned over
indications that their man is viewed unfavorably by a large
percentage of voters.
   ``If those numbers are that way by election time, it's pretty
insurmountable,'' Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said in an
interview with the Boston Globe. But Fuller and other aides said
Bush's standing as measured by the polls could improve dramatically
virtually overnight.
   Bush, wrapping up a week-long West Coast campaign swing, spent
about 15 minutes in a storefront in Los Angeles that police said
had been a drug location. He said he would not ``bargain with drug
dealers'' as president, whether they were in the United States or
on foreign soil.
   Still, he refused once again to offer an opinion on reports of
Reagan administration plea bargaining with Panamanian leader Manuel
Noriega, who is under U.S. indictment on drug charges.
   In a speech before flying home, Bush said he would mount an
attack against drugs that would be ``nothing less than a modern
D-Day'' and urged his Democratic rivals to join him in calling for
tougher penalties for convicted drug dealers.
   Dukakis made no mention of Bush at a news conference in Boston.
   Instead, he said he doubted Jackson would mar the anticipated
tranquility at the party's nominating convention by challenging
delegate selection rules.
   ``I don't think we are going to have a fight with Mr. Jackson at
the convention,'' he said.
   Jackson has complained in recent weeks that his support among
``super delegates'' _ party leaders who will have voting rights at
the convention _ does not match his success in primaries. Dukakis
said Jackson ``has a perfect right to voice criticism,'' but noted
that Jackson knew the rules before entering the race.
   Even so, top aides to Jackson released the text of a letter they
sent to Democratic Chairman Paul Kirk, saying that ``the vote of
the people is distorted'' by Dukakis' overwhelming advantage in
super delegates.
   As for his vice presidential running mate, Dukakis said he would
not turn his attention to the search until the primary season is
concluded.
   ``If I'm the nominee I would hope that the decision will be made
before the convention, sure, or at least the recommendations,'' he
said.
   Paul Brountas, a law school classmate and close friend of the
governor, is expected to head the search effort.
   Dukakis made his comments before heading off to campaign stops
in New York and New Jersey.
   Jackson already was in California, where he is mounting an
intense primary campaign. He said his 90-minute session with a
dozen Los Angles area rabbis and other Jewish leaders was ``the
beginning of a meaningful and in-depth dialogue'' with critics of
his candidacy.
   He said the sesson was a ``step toward healing wounds.''
   One participant, Rabbi Allen Freehling said ``the litany of
complaints in the Jewish community with Jesse Jackson'' was aired,
and there was ``a reconciliation.''
   Outside the session, though, a dozen demonstrators chanted
``Lose, Jesse, Lose, and ``Jew hater.''
   Many Jews have been suspicious of Jackson in part because of his
1979 meeting with Yasser Arafat, the head of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, his 1984 reference to New York as
``Hymietown'' and other incidents.
</TEXT>
