<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-EthnicRiots     05-18 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Ethnic Riots,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12 Dead in Hindu-Moslem Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-India-Sikhs Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were ordered Wednesday to shoot
troublemakers on sight in the western city of Aurangabad, where two
days of Hindu-Moslem rioting have left 11 dead, a police official
reported.
   News of the riots spread and a 12th person was stabbed to death
in Poona, another city in Maharashtra state, officials said.
   Authorities imposed a curfew on Aurangabad, 350 miles east of
Bombay, but lifted it for four hours Wednesday so Moslems could
celebrate the end of Ramadan, the Islamic holy month.
   S. Ramamurthy, commissioner of the police intelligence
department, said more than 500 police officers had been deployed in
neighborhoods in Aurangabad.
   ``Stray incidents of stabbing ... are a major problem,'' he
said. ``We just can't have policemen in every lane to stop the
stabbing spree.''
   Three of the 11 victims were killed by police gunfire and the
rest died of stab wounds during fights between Moslems and Hindus,
Ramamurthy said. Nearly 100 people have been reported injured.
   The violence began after a court dismissed a petition filed by
Shiv Sena, a militant Hindu group, challenging the election May 6
of Mayor Shantaram Kale, a Hindu supported by a Moslem organization.
   Shiv Sena organized a rally outside the court and police said
the crowd turned into a mob after the petition was dismissed. They
said gangs of Hindus and Moslems attacked homes and businesses in
the city of 315,000 people.
   About 12 percent of India's 800 million people are Moslems and
82 percent are Hindus. The two ethnic groups have a long history of
conflict.
</TEXT>
