<NOTE>Eds: SUBS New York-dated first item to UPDATE with comment from
NBC President Brandon Tartikoff in 4th graf; SUBS Freehold,
N.J.-dated item with new material thruout from O'Toole's lawyer,
saying actor will temporarily defy court order.</NOTE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby was coy about whether 1988-89 would
be the final season for ``The Cosby Show,'' but he said he's going
all out next year.
   ``This is our fifth season, and it's supposed to be our last, so
I'm going to have my fun this year _ not in messing up, but in
doing things even better,'' said Cosby, who appeared at NBC's
unveiling of its fall schedule for advertisers.
   He has previously said he would only do the show five years. In
its four seasons so far, it has consistently been the top-rated
network show and is credited with making NBC the No. 1 network.
   ``If he's having fun and he's got stories to tell, we might
convince him to come back,'' said NBC Entertainment President
Brandon Tartikoff, adding that NBC had held no formal talks with
Cosby.
   Cosby gave a plug to the striking Writers Guild of America,
promising the show would be as good as ever ``once we get our
writers back.''
   ``They're asking for more money, and they're going to get it ..
. If they don't come back, it's all over for TV _ and you all have
no jobs.''
   The 2-month-old strike centers on creative control and royalties
from syndication.
   Cosby pleaded, mostly tongue-in-cheek, with the advertisers to
buy time on his show next season. A frequent pitchman for a number
of products, he added: ``Some of you have not called me to do
commercials for you. I have your names.''
   As for ``A Different World,'' the critically bludgeoned but
commercially successful spinoff of his show, Cosby said, ```A
Different World' is sort of a payback, a chance to see a child who
says, `I know what I'm doing,' go off and take care of him or
herself. We've gotten rid of all the people who didn't know what it
was about.''
   Debbie Allen, a former producer on ``Fame,'' has been brought in
to produce ``A Different World'' next year. Her sister, Phylicia
Rashad, plays Cosby's wife.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rock 'n' roll of ``Cousin Brucie,'' the
horror of the ``Inner Sanctum'' and Don Dunphy's fight
announcements were recognized at the first induction into the
Emerson Radio Hall of Fame.
   Eighteen radio legends, including the late Orson Welles and
Edward R. Murrow, were inducted in a ceremony that honored radio as
much as it paid tribute to the personalities.
   ``Radio is a vital, living immediate thing,'' said Himan Brown,
who was honored as producer of ``Inner Sanctum.''
   ``We are all a part of radio. It's not something that's in the
past. It surrounds us,'' he told the 250 people at the ceremony
Tuesday at the Empire State Building.
   ``Cousin Brucie'' Morrow, host of the oldies show, ``Cruisin'
America,'' was inducted in the radio personality category, and
Dunphy, a top fight announcer, was honored in the sportscaster
category.
   ``To be amongst names like Orson Welles and Arthur Godfrey, Alan
Freed and Martin Block, who I grew up with ... and all the people
like Don Dunphy and Himan Brown _ to think that I am to be walking
among these legends, these eagles one day, is way beyond my great
expectations,'' he said.
  
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnny Mathis reached the top of the
charts early in his career with songs like ``Chances Are'' and
``Wonderful Wonderful.''
   But the truth is, he has never liked his recorded versions of
the songs.
   ``Honestly, it doesn't bother me if I don't have another
million-seller,'' said Mathis, who is performing this week at
Bally's Grand Hotel and Casino.
   Mathis' debut album was released by Columbia records jazz
division and went nowhere. He was teamed with Mitch Miller,
producer of his top-ten pop hits, but Mathis said the musical
arrangements ``were frivolous and didn't require vocalization.''
   ``I sang the way he wanted me to sing,'' Mathis said. ``It was
what I needed for a hit record, but it was stifling and not
creative.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OK, already. Robin Williams is funny.
   On Tuesday, he dominated the American Comedy Awards by winning
four awards: funniest male performer of the year, funniest male
standup comic, funniest male performer in a comedy special, Comedy
Relief `87, and funniest male performer in a movie, last year's
``Good Morning, Vietnam.''
   British comedian Tracey Ullman scored as the funniest female
performer, and the ``Tracey Ullman Show,'' garnered her the award
for funniest female performer in a leading role in a TV series.
   Garry Shandling, host of ``It's Garry Shandling's Show,'' took
the award for funniest male performer in a TV series.
   The awards, staged by George Schlatter, were presented during a
two-hour ABC special.
   An annual Lifetime Creative Achievement Award was given to
producer Blake Edwards.
   Other winners were:
   Funniest female performer in a TV special: Roseanne Barr, ``On
Location: The Roseanne Barr Show.''
   Funniest actress in a motion picture: Bette Midler for
``Outrageous Fortune.''
   Funniest supporting female, TV or movie: Olympia Dukakis for
``Moonstruck.''
   Funniest supporting male, TV or movie: Albert Brooks for
``Broadcast News.''
   Funniest female standup comic: Lily Tomlin.
   Comedy club female comic of the year: Judy Tenuta.
   Comedy club male comic of the year: Jerry Seinfeld.
   Lifetime achievement, female: Imogene Coca.
   Lifetime achievement, male: George Burns.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Peter O'Toole will temporarily defy
a court order to return to New Jersey with his 5-year-old son
because he wants to do what's in the best interest of the child,
the actor's attorney said Wednesday.
   Monmouth Superior Court Judge Alexander D. Lehrer ordered
O'Toole to give his son, Lorcan, to his mother Tuesday or face a
$1,000-a-day fine and possible arrest.
   But O'Toole remained in London with the boy, said Jeffrey P.
Weinstein, a Roseland attorney representing the actor.
   Raoul Felder, attorney for the boy's mother and O'Toole's former
girlfriend, Karen Sommerville O'Toole, said he would seek O'Toole's
arrest shortly. Weinstein said neither he nor his client has been
notified of any arrest warrant.
   Weinstein would not specify why O'Toole's keeping the child was
beneficial but did say he believes O'Toole wants to be present at a
June 14 custody hearing before Lehrer.
   O'Toole and Ms. O'Toole met about six years ago but never
married. After the child was born, the mother began using O'Toole's
last name. A short time later, the couple split and have been
embroiled in a custody dispute.
