<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Claiborne     05-18 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Claiborne,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Court Reaffirms That Ousted Federal Judge Claiborne Can
Practice Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nevada Supreme Court issued an
opinion Wednesday reaffirming an order issued in November to let
ousted federal judge Harry Claiborne practice law despite
imprisonment for tax evasion.
   Justice Tom Steffen wrote the long-awaited formal opinion, which
concludes that no further punishment should be imposed on
Claiborne, 71, who spent 17 months behind bars after being
impeached as a U.S. district judge in October 1986.
   Claiborne was named a federal judge in 1978. He was impeached
following his conviction for failing to report $107,000 on his 1979
and 1980 tax returns. The impeachment was the first of its sort in
more than a half-century.
   Claiborne maintained he was a victim of a Justice Department
vendetta. He alleged misconduct by federal agents and bias on the
part of his trial judge, Walter Hoffman.
   The case against Claiborne started out as an investigation into
allegations that Claiborne took a $30,000 bribe to derail an FBI
probe into brothel owner Joe Conforte. A trial in Reno on bribery
and other charges resulted in a hung jury, and a retrial on the
bribery charge was thrown out.
   Claiborne, born in McRae, Ark., got his law degree from
Cumberland University and was admitted to the Arkansas Bar in 1942.
He was admitted to the Nevada Bar a few years later, worked two
years as a deputy prosecutor and also served as a one-term
Democratic state assemblyman.
   In his opinion, Justice Steffen outlined the history of
Claiborne's removal from office, the claims of investigatory
misconduct, the federal government's bargain with Conforte,
Claiborne's trial, his professional background and the tension
between federal agents and Nevada's federal judges.
   Steffen said it was regrettable that Claiborne was unable to get
evidentiary hearings into his claims of bias and misconduct, adding
that there was evidence within the federal Justice Department of
``appalling arrogance, contemptuousness, and a lack of decorum.''
   ``If our review of the record had enabled us to conclude, in
good conscience, that Claiborne had been fairly prosecuted and
convicted, we unhesitatingly would have imposed severe sanctions,''
Steffen said.
   He stressed that the high court's decision wasn't based simply
on legal technicalities and acknowledge that some critics would
disagree with the ruling.
   But Claiborne's felony conviction, while serious, ``was no
ordinary conviction,'' Steffen said. ``Questionable investigative
and prosecutorial motivations, as well as anomalous and arguably
unfair practices and procedures, pervade the record of this matter
from its inception.''
   The ruling included a separate 9-page concurring statement from
Chief Justice Al Gunderson, who said it was fortunate the Claiborne
case didn't end ``with his total annihilation.''
   Gunderson concluded that the federal government's pursuit of
Claiborne ``began with a fixed purpose _ but without any evidence
whatever _ that the U.S. District Court judge should be destroyed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
