<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugTesting     05-18 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Testing,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families of Chase Rail Crash Victims Lobby on Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families and friends of some of the 16 people
killed in last year's Amtrak crash in Maryland visited Capitol Hill
on Wednesday to urge lawmakers to approve a long-stalled
drug-testing bill.
   ``We can sit at home and cry about what's happened, or come down
here and tell these people to move ahead,'' said Dr. Roger Horn of
Hunt Valley, Md.
   Horn, whose daughter, Ceres, 16, died in the accident, and about
100 other people spent their day visiting the offices of the 432
members of the House.
   Their focus was legislation that would require random, mandatory
drug and alcohol testing for railroad, airline, bus and trucking
industry employees. The measure would affect about 3.3 million of
the nation's transportation workers.
   The proposal has been the subject of House-Senate negotiations
since the beginning of the year. It has been the major obstacle to
the completion of work on an airline passenger consumer protection
bill, into which it was inserted by the Senate. The version of the
bill passed by the House contains no drug-testing provision.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce Committee, has jurisdiction over bills affecting railroad
workers and has so far opposed the testing provision. He has
expressed fears about ``rampant incompetence and faulty procedures
of the nation's laboratories.''
   But Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., a leading sponsor of the testing
measure, said at a news conference Wednesday, ``The key to solving
the problem of drug and alcohol use by people in safety related
transportation jobs is testing, which includes mandatory random
testing.''
   According to the Department of Transportation, in the first 14
months after the Jan. 4, 1987, Amtrak accident at Chase, Md., there
were 37 rail accidents in which one or more workers tested
positively afterward for illegal drug use, and four accidents in
which alcohol use was detected.
   The National Transportation Safety Board has concluded that
marijuana use was the primary cause of the Maryland accident, in
which three linked Conrail engines passed a stop signal and ran in
front of a crowded Amtrak commuter train. Sixteen people were
killed and 175 injured.
   Also Wednesday, Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Dick
Stafford said 39 air traffic controllers and other agency workers
have been relieved from their duties after testing positive for
drug use since the FAA began the examinations last year.
   Of those, 31 are still employed by the FAA but may be undergoing
drug rehabilitation programs, five resigned and three have been
fired, according to Stafford's figures.
   During the period, 1,652 FAA workers received random drug tests
and 25,161 others were tested as part of their annual medical
exams, he said.
   Stafford presented the figures after Danforth cited similar
numbers at the news conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
