<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietChristians     05-18 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Christians,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Resolution Urges Soviets To Free Christians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday called on Soviet
leaders to grant general amnesty to imprisoned Christians on the
1,000th anniversary of Christianity in Russia.
   The resolution, sponsored by Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., was
adopted by a 394-0 vote.
   The resolution also calls on the Soviets to widen religious
freedom.
   Smith said he believes the strong support will have an impact on
Soviet leaders, who now control 219 known religious prisoners.
   ``It sends a clear signal about how Congress and the American
people cherish religious freedom everywhere,'' Smith said.
   Smith said the aim of the resolution was ``religious glasnost,''
using Soviet leader Michael S. Gorbachev's term to describe his new
policy of openness.
   The passage of the resolution was timed for the May 29-June 2
summit meeting between Gorbachev and President Reagan in Moscow,
Smith said.
   According to the resolution, this year marks the millennium of
the arrival of Christianity in the Ukraine, now part of the Soviet
Union. In the year 988, the grand prince of Kiev invited Byzantine
priests to teach the Christian faith in the region.
</TEXT>
