<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia-Guerrillas     05-18 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Guerrillas,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodians to Confer on How to Beat Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pro-Vietnamese government of
Cambodia has convened an unprecedented national congress to discuss
ways to fight guerrilla infiltration of villages.
   Representatives of about 500 model communes across the country
attended the opening of the congress in the capital, Phnom Penh, on
Monday, the official Communist Party newspaper Pracheachon said.
   The paper said while the Cambodian government has made advances,
guerrillas were conducting psychological warfare along the Thai
border area ``with impunity.''
   The paper said the party's ruling Politburo ``considers the
localities as a matter of life or death to the revolution ... as
the core battlefield, and the work of building and consolidating
localities, villages, communes, units and army bases as the key
task in 1988.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978, ousting the Khmer Rouge
rulers. The communist Khmer Rouge now forms the largest of three
guerrilla groups.
   Pracheachon said the guerrillas were moving into the interior of
the country to spread propaganda against the government and
encourage criticism of Vietnam. It said the rebels were planting
agents and preparing for 1990, when Vietnam has said it will
withdraw the last of its troops from Cambodia.
   The Cambodian government is trying to lure guerrillas and their
supporters back to the fold with promises of amnesty, jobs and
rewards.
   However, the paper said, ``the enemy is still able to conduct
his activities at a number of remote villages and communes along
the Cambodian-Thai border, frequently making unchecked entries
into, exits from, and passages through these localities and
intimidating the local people with impunity.''
   A text of the paper's editorial was obtained from a Western
embassy in Bangkok on Wednesday.
   Cambodians are torn between deep-seated enmity for Vietnam and
for the Khmer Rouge, which massacred hundreds of thousands of
people during its nearly four-year rule.
   On May 10, Khmer Rouge radio claimed that guerrillas smashed the
Vietnamese administrative network in more than 4,000 villages and
200 communes during the seven-month dry season that ended in April.
   Vietnam was forced to transfer important units from the
Thai-Cambodian border to the interior to defend against attacks, it
claimed.
   However, Khmer Rouge claims are widely regarded as exaggerated.
</TEXT>
