<DOCNO> AP880518-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CheckCashing     05-18 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Check Cashing,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Says Some Banks Won't Cash Government Checks for
Non-depositors</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social Security and welfare recipients in
urban areas have the most difficulty getting their government
checks cashed by banks where they do not have an account, the
General Accounting Office told Congress on Wednesday.
   ``Some individuals do not have depository accounts and are not
able to cash their checks at local banks or thrifts,'' Assistant
Comptroller General Richard L. Fogel told a Senate banking
subcommittee.
   Instead, he said, they cash their checks at check cashers,
grocery stores, liquor stores, bars and with relatives.
   Fogel released a preliminary report to the panel which found
that ``the unbanked population of the United States is at the lower
end of the income scale, relies relatively heavily on government
benefit programs, includes a significant percentage of the
unemployed, and most have 12 years or less of education.''
   Consumer groups argue that in 1987, anywhere between 71 percent
and 88 percent of the banks and thrifts would not cash checks for
non-customers at any price. The GAO indicated that in 1985, nearly
86 percent of banks and 55 percent of thrifts cashed Treasury
checks for non-depositors.
   Fogel said he saw no disparity between the statistics because
the consumer groups' studies targeted urban areas while the GAO
report was nationwide, including rural and suburban as well as
urban areas.
   Fogel said there is no current, nationally representative survey
of the check cashing experience. ``Nonetheless, it is our
impression that access is considerably more of a problem in urban
locations than in rural ones,'' he said.
   The report of the GAO, investigative arm of Congress, said banks
do not cash government checks for non-depositors because of the
costs involved in performing the service free of charge, congestion
of their facilities and potential fraud.
   Fogel testified before the Senate Banking consumer affairs
subcommittee on legislation, sponsored by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio, to require banks to cash government checks for
non-depositors once they have registered with the bank. A similar
measure has been introduced in the House.
   ``My bill would ensure that individuals do not have to chase all
over town to cash their government checks,'' Metzenbaum said. ``And
it would ensure that senior citizens and low income persons were
not charged exorbitant fees for the privilege of cashing such
checks.''
   Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, chairman of the House banking
committee, said he favored the Metzenbaum bill and a similar one
introduced by Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y. in the House.
   St Germain said any comprehensive banking bill passed by
Congress this year will contain a version of required check-cashing
legislation. Both Metzenbaum and Schumer have said they are willing
to modify their proposals but that the banking industry has opposed
any such effort.
   August Zinsser III, representing the American Bankers
Association, told the committee the legislation would subject banks
to large fraud losses and ``is premature, inappropriate and unfair
to depository institutions.''
   Zinsser said, ``This legislation presents a window of
opportunity for individuals to use banks to perpetuate fraud
through the pretext of cashing checks. Organized crime, in
particular, would find the bill particularly useful and
profitable.''
   However, in answer to a question by Metzenbaum, Fogel said the
GAO study found the actual dollar amount the Treasury Department
reclaims from banks and thrifts or refuses payment on to be smaller
than the claims of banking groups imply.
   Fogel said the final GAO report would be published in September
but doubted that there would be any major changes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
