<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RobertsReturn     05-18 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roberts Return,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Damaged Frigate to be Returned Aboard Another Ship</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy said Wednesday it had decided to
return the mine-damaged frigate Samuel B. Roberts from the Persian
Gulf aboard a commercial heavy-lift ship.
   The service said it hoped to award a contract for the ferry
operation in the next few days and then load the frigate in
mid-June for the trip back to the United States.
   The Navy announced April 29 the ship would be repaired at the
Bath Iron Works in Bath, Maine, where it was built.
   The alternative to having another ship carry the vessel back to
the United States would involve performing fairly extensive repairs
and then towing it home, the Navy said. The ship is currently in
dry dock in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
   According to the Navy, a number of companies that operate
heavy-lift ships were asked to bid on the job recently. There are
probably about two dozen such ships in the world capable of doing
the job, the service said. Such vessels are normally used to carry
huge oil-drilling rigs to new locations.
   ``With the exception of approximately 10 crewmen who will ride
the heavy-lift ship, the crew of the USS Roberts will fly to their
home port of Newport, R.I., when their ship departs for the United
States,'' the Navy said.
   The Roberts was badly damaged by a mine on April 14 shortly
after completing a convoy operation for a reflagged Kuwaiti tanker.
Navy officials have said the frigate almost certainly would have
sunk had it not been for the performance of its crew.
</TEXT>
