<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TVA-Organization     05-18 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TVA-Organization,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TVA Changes Organization Structure To Same As Private Companies'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tennessee Valley Authority voted
Wednesday to cut in half the number of top-level managers and
reorganize to resemble a private company.
   After the unanimous vote by the agency's three board members,
TVA Chairman Marvin Runyon said there will be layoffs but added
that it was not known how many because some managers would be
reassigned.
   He also declined to say how many ``top-level'' managers the
reorganization affects. The agency has more than a dozen offices
doing separate aspects of TVA work, such as power in general,
nuclear power, general counsel, natural resource and economic
development, and fertilizer research.
   ``A corporation the size of TVA must have a sound organizational
structure, one that can help ensure that TVA survives and prospers
in today's competitive business environment,'' Runyon said at a
news conference after the board meeting.
   The new organization goes into effect July 1. After that, it
will be clearer to agency officials which posts should be
eliminated and how many people will be laid off, he said.
   Currently, the agency has a dozen office managers who report to
General Manager William Willis. Willis reports to the board.
   Under the new structure, approved on the TVA's 55th birthday,
there are three main operating groups _ nuclear power, non-nuclear
power and resource development.
   As examples, Steve White, the TVA's current manager of the
nuclear power office, becomes senior vice president for nuclear
power. Willis becomes chief operating officer, and his former
position of general manager will be eliminated.
   The organizational change and recently announced layoffs at
nuclear power plants should help cut $300 million from agency
programs and personnel next year in an effort to keep electric
rates the same for three straight years, Runyon said.
   He said he did not know how much the reorganization could save
the utility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
