<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     05-18 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Orders Examination of Risky Training After Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The admiral who heads the Navy's training
program has ordered a review of possibly risky procedures after a
sailor drowned during a rescue course, a Navy spokesman said
Wednesday.
   ``Are we coming too close to the edge, are we too close to the
margin?'' Vice Adm. N.R. Thunman, chief of naval education and
training, asked, according to his public affairs officer, Lt. Cmdr.
Dennis Hessler.
   Thunman, who is based at Pensacola, asked commanders of more
than 200 training activities throughout the Navy to respond to that
question, Hessler said.
   The Navy scheduled a preliminary hearing May 25 for five
instructors and the officer in charge of the Navy Rescue Swimmer
School at the Pensacola Naval Air Station on charges in the March 2
death of Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.
   Thunman also said the Navy began investigating the suspicious
nature of Mirecki's death immediately after he drowned in a pool.
He denied allegations by the sailor's family that the Navy failed
to react until pressured by them, their congressman and the media.
   Three separate investigations eventually were launched, one by
the training command, one by the Naval Investigative Service and
the third by the Navy's inspector general.
   The Investigative Service, a police agency, filed a dereliction
of duty charge against Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, officer in charge of
the school, and involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy to commit
battery charges against each of the five instructors.
   According to the charges, the instructor forced Mirecki into the
pool against his will and held his head under water and broke his
grip on a rack and safety rope before he died.
   The preliminary hearing will be held by an officers' panel,
which will make a recommendation on a possible court-martial to
Rear Adm. David Morris, chief of naval air training, a subordinate
of Thunman based in Corpus Christi, Texas.
   The defendants have been relieved of duty and activities at the
rescue school have been suspended.
</TEXT>
