<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrickPunishment 1stLd-Writethru a0819 05-18 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brick Punishment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0819,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Orders School To Stop Practice of Brick Punishment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 13, `Among the...' to the end to update with
comment from boy's grandmother.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NACOGDOCHES, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hanging bricks around youngsters'
necks was just a gimmick so they'd remember their pencils and
supplies, school officials said Wednesday, but the state said the
school district should forget the whole practice.
   Four fifth- and sixth-graders were required to carry the bricks
in their hands or around their necks in late April if they
repeatedly forgot to take supplies from one class to another, said
Superintendent James Bogue.
   ``It was not a punishment. It was a gimmick _ an attempt to get
students to bring the proper supplies to school,'' Bogue said. ``We
needed some type of reminder.
   ``I would say it was unusual, but it wasn't unsafe,'' he added.
``It wasn't used to intimidate the children. I don't even consider
(the practice) to be bad.''
   The brick discipline worked, so officials in this district about
125 miles northeast of Houston stopped using it, Bogue said. But on
May 9, a parent called the Texas Education Agency to complain.
   ``We told the school that it was an inappropriate form of
discipline and to stop it,'' TEA spokeswoman Terri Moore said
Wednesday. ``But it's not illegal and it does not violate state
policies or rules.''
   No formal complaints, which would have led to an investigation,
were filed, she said.
   Bogue said the students were told they would have to carry the
bricks to class as reminders to take the proper supplies to the
next class.
   The students, one girl and three boys, had to have the bricks
with them for one day each, he said. They were told they could
either carry them or hang them around their necks.
   ``A string was provided, (but) they were not ordered to wear it
around their necks,'' Bogue said. ``It was long enough so it could
rest on the student's books.''
   Three white bricks were used, each 7\-inches long, 3{-inches
wide and 2\-inches thick. Bogue was not sure how much they weighed,
but said three holes in each made them lighter.
   One student had written, ``I forgot my books,'' on a brick. A
boy had autographed his brick and another brick appeared to have
the words ``I forgot my pencil'' on it, Bogue said.
   Among the students required to carry a brick was the 13-year-old
son of Houston firefighter James Barclay, who said his son has a
learning disability and takes the medication Ritalin, frequently
prescribed for hyperactive children.
   ``He's been diagnosed as being hyperactive and has mental
problems,'' the boy's grandmother, Annie M. Barclay said Wednesday.
``A child can't learn anything with a brick tied around his neck.
When he was in school, the other kids would call him and when he'd
turn, the brick would hit him in the face. It's pure humiliation.''
   But Bogue said the child, who lives with the grandmother in
Nacogdoches, has a behavior problem, not a learning disability, and
has been sent to the principal's office numerous times.
   Ms. Barclay said her son plans to attend a Central Heights
school board meeting Thursday to question the discipline.
   The superintendent said parents of two of the children involved
complained, while parents of the other two said they were not upset.
   ``It's just been blown way out of proportion,'' Bogue said. ``It
is unusual. I agree it would have been better if we had not done
it.''
</TEXT>
