<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Ethiopia     05-18 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Ethiopia,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expert Says 2.4 Million Ethiopians May Face Starvation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2.4 million Ethiopians living in two
northern provinces may be facing starvation because the Ethiopian
government has placed severe limits on deliveries of emergency food
provided by international donors, a U.S. government expert said
Wednesday.
   Dr. Frederick Machmer Jr., the top official of the Agency for
International Development in Ethiopia, said a food distribution
program run by Ethiopian authorities is reaching only about 780,000
persons in Eritrea and Tigray provinces _ less than a quarter of
their combined populations.
   Both provinces are wracked by drought and anti-government
rebellions. Government control in these provinces basically is
limited to their respective capitals and the authorities are not
allowing food deliveries beyond these areas, Machmer said.
   ``Every sign we have is that a bad situation is not getting any
better,'' Machmer told a small group of reporters.
   He said food availability is no problem, noting that
international donors have promised Ethiopia 1.4 million metric tons
of food for the rest of the year. In addition to restrictions on
food deliveries, the Ethiopian government ordered most foreign
relief workers out of the two provinces last month.
   Machmer said representatives of private organizations have
volunteered to deliver food by truck to the interior of the two
provinces but Ethiopian authorities have refused the offer,
contending they would be blamed if the volunteers were harmed.
   The United States has offered to donate just under 250,000
metric tons of food to Ethiopia. The Soviet Union, a close ally of
Ethiopia, has said it will donate 250,000 tons but has not
indicated it will pay for food transportation costs, Machmer said.
</TEXT>
