<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StateWaste     05-18 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Waste,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Official Issues Recommendation In North Carolina Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency should
back away from its attempt to strip North Carolina of the right to
operate its own hazardous waste disposal program, according to a
recommendation to EPA's administrator.
   ``The use of program withdrawal authorities under (federal
hazardous waste law) is not the most effective means'' to make sure
waste facilities are soundly operated, said J. Winston Porter,
assistant administrator for solid waste and emergency response, in
a letter to Administrator Lee M. Thomas.
   Porter's letter was dated Monday and obtained Wednesday by The
Associated Press.
   ``This is good news,'' said Velma Smith of the Environmental
Policy Institute, a Washington-based lobbying organization for
environmental causes that had been supporting North Carolina. ``You
have made my day.''
   Porter said EPA should use its authority under the ``Superfund''
waste dump cleanup law ``as the primary vehicle for addressing
capacity issues.''
   A 1986 amendment to the Superfund law requires states to show
that they have plans for handling all the toxic waste they
generate, at the risk of losing state grants under the Superfund
program.
   ``I would like for us to work cooperatively with the states to
develop necessary waste management capacity, and to make it clear
that the required (Superfund) capacity certification will be
considered very seriously by EPA,'' Porter wrote.
   Porter's letter reported findings of a special agency committee
considering the dispute with North Carolina, together with Porter's
own recommendations. The task force ``has not yet reached a
consensus recommendation'' but should do so within two weeks, he
said.
   The North Carolina dispute arose when GSX Corp. sought to put a
waste treatment plant on the Lumber River upstream of Lumberton,
whose 10,000 citizens get their drinking water from the stream.
   State law requires that any stream used for drinking water and
receiving discharge from such a plant dilute the discharge by a
factor of 1,000.
   Compliance would limit the plant to discharing 72,000 gallons a
day at the planned location. It had planned to discharge 500,000.
   EPA officials contended the state law in effect limited capacity
in such a way as to prevent other states from using the plant and
in effect to keep the plant from being built at all. Some officials
were reported as saying the agency wanted in effect to make an
example of North Carolina to warn other states against letting
parochial concerns hamper interstate commerce.
   State officials denied it, and Ms. Smith said North Carolina's
law would permit a plant of unlimited size 30 miles downstream.
   An EPA administrative law judge had been scheduled to hear the
agency's attempt to revoke North Carolina's authority next month.
   Federal hazardous waste law encourages states to operate their
own disposal programs under EPA oversight. State programs must be
``consistent'' with federal law and may be ``more stringent.''
   One of the findings of the task force reported by Porter was
that ``it will be increasingly difficult for EPA to determine the
difference between a state's `consistency' with the national
(waste) programs and the state's ability to be `more stringent'
than the national program.''
</TEXT>
