<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Fairness     05-18 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Fairness,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Complains To Party Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Jesse Jackson's campaign on Wednesday fired a salvo
in his bid to change what he considers the Democratic Party's
unfair system of delegate selection, writing to party chief Paul
Kirk that ``the vote of the people is distorted'' by the current
process.
   A letter signed by Jackson's campaign chief Willie Brown and
Jackson adviser Rep. Walter Fauntroy of Washington, urged Kirk to
consider the ``moral and political questions raised'' in an
attached delegate analysis compiled by Jackson's delegate counter
Steve Cobble.
   The letter was dated May 17 and copies were sent to Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis, who has benefitted from the system
Jackson is protesting, and to House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas.
   Jackson principally objects to the role of the so-called super
delegates, who are delegates by virtue of their elected offices of
party positions, because their allegiance is not related to the
popular vote. Most of them have been siding with Dukakis.
   Brown and other Jackson representatives have met with Kirk to
urge a more proportional system of allocating super delegates, but
have not decided whether to mount an official challenge at the
summer nominating convention in Atlanta, aides have said.
   ``As of now it is an appeal to conscience and to fairness,''
said Ron Brown, who is heading Jackson's convention team. He said
``all options are open'' on the matter of an official challenge,
but also said there are no plans to call for retroactive changes in
the party rules.
   Dukakis said Wednesday in Boston that he does not anticipate ``a
fight with Mr. Jackson.''
   ``I think Jesse has a perfect right to voice criticism of
whatever he chooses to criticize,'' he said, before repeating his
position that Jackson knew the delegate selection rules when he
entered the race.
   The Cobble analysis said Dukakis has 61 percent more delegates
than Jackson in early May, at a time that the two were separated by
a a popular vote margin of less than 30 percent, according to
counts by news organizations.
   Cobble cited four reasons for the inequity:
   _ In Puerto Rico, Jackson won the nonbinding popular vote but in
an internal political power war, the Puerto Rico governor awareded
all the island's 51 delegates to Dukakis.
   _ Super delegates have flocked to Dukakis rather than dividing
themselves up in a way that would more accurately reflect the
popular vote.
   ``The super delegates do not have to coronate a winner. They
could act on behalf of fairness. There is nothing in the rules
which mandates a lemming-like rush to the frontrunner's side,
particularly when he is in reality so far short of 2,081 votes,''
the number needed to secure the Democratic presidential nomination,
the letter said.
   The cover letter from Willie Brown and Fauntroy states: ``The
`party of fairness' is not well serviced in the candidate receiving
30 percent of the 1988 primary and caucus vote is virtually
excluded from the support of super delegates. The Democratic Party
is not well served if the vote of the people is distorted once the
polls are closed.''
   _ Direct election states, in which voters elect delegates on the
ballot rather than having the delegates awarded proportionately
based on how a candidate did in each district, have worked against
Jackson. In Maryland, according to Cobble's memo, Jackson would
have received 26 delegates under a proportional representation
system, but in the direct election, he got 20. Similar inequities
were evidenced in the direct election states of Illinois and
Pennsylvania, he wrote.
   _ The use of ``bonus elections'' in some states, has worked to
Dukakis' advantage and Jackson's disadvantage. In those states, the
first delegate in each district is awarded to the person who won
the district. Those states have cost Jackson some 22 to 27
delegates, while Dukakis gained 20 to 25, the letter said.
   If all of the Jackson objections were fixed, according to
Cobble, Dukakis' delegate lead of 562 on May 6 would have dropped
to a lead of 260.
   That would have put Dukakis in a different situation than ``the
coronation that is taking place today,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
