<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugRecall     05-18 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Recall,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Questran Recall Doesn't Apply to Supplies in Patient Hands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bristol Laboratories spokesman said
Wednesday that the voluntary recall of certain batches of the
cholesterol-lowering drug Questran does not apply to supplies
already in patients' hands.
   The company announced the recall after it learned that one of
the ingredients in the drug may have been contaminated by
agricultural chemicals.
   Scott Litherland, a spokesman for Bristol Laboratories, said the
low levels of these chemicals present in some batches of the drug
did not pose a health threat and that patients should continue
taking the medication.
   Litherland said the recall only involves certain Questran
supplies at the wholesale and retail level but not medication that
has already been sold to consumers.
   The voluntary recall involves cans and packets of Questran
bearing an expiration date between August 1988 and October 1991
(``USEBY 8 88'' through ``EXP 1 OCT 91'') or the following batch
codes: MKH81, MKH82, MLH46 and MLH47.
</TEXT>
