<DOCNO> AP880518-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ProtectingCandidates 1stLd-Writethru a0838 05-18 0944</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Protecting Candidates, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0838,940</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 5 bgng ``So far'' with 2 grafs to clarify reported
figure, add Jackson quote; adds attribution last graf to newspaper
bgng ``There are...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Secret Service, in keeping with its name,
doesn't like to discuss the details or frequency of threats against
Jesse Jackson, Michael Dukakis or George Bush. Neither do the
candidates and their staffs.
   Yet the specter of the candidate as a crackpot's target is a
fact of politics in America. And as a charismatic candidate, and a
black man with a ground-breaking presidential candidacy, Jackson
has become a magnet for death threats.
   ``Just like the Kennedys have had to wrestle long and hard with
running for president because of the risk, I have had to do the
same thing,'' Jackson once said.
   By his own count, Jackson was the object of 314 recorded threats
on his life during his 1984 presidential campaign. In 14 of those
cases, people were arrested.
   Jackson's campaign press secretary, Delmarie Cobb, said the
Secret Service would not give the number of threats against him for
this campaign. She said early Wednesday she had understood from
another staff member that there were at least 100, but later said
she could not confirm the figure, and that the Secret Service had
subsequently told her the number was wrong.
   Cobb quoted Jackson as saying that threats against him in 1984
were more numerous than for any candidate, and that ``Of course,
they're running high now.''
   Federal agents in St. Louis said this week they had arrested a
self-described white supremacist and his wife on charges of
conspiring to kill or harm Jackson. Londell Williams, 30, of
Washington, Mo., and his wife Tammy, 26, were being held without
bond.
   Authorities recovered a semiautomatic rifle said to belong to
the couple. An agent quoted Williams as saying Jackson was
``getting too close to being president of the United States.''
   Jackson, in California, thanked the Secret Service on Wednesday
and said, ``We will not surrender to the dream-busters.''
   Dukakis, who for a long time spurned Secret Service protection,
praised the agency as well and acknowledged the threats he has
received.
   ``All of us in public life have these threats,'' Dukakis said.
``I've had them, not recently to the best of my knowledge. These
things happen to you.''
   The Secret Service has been protecting most major presidential
candidates since ordered by Congress following the assassination of
Robert F. Kennedy in 1968, on the night he won California's
Democratic primary.
   Secret Service spokesman William J. Corbett said it is against
agency policy to discuss the protection accorded any of the
candidates, the methods that are used, or the nature of threats.
   ``The more hype we put on it, the more potential there is to
plant the seed in other people's mind,'' he said. ``We go out of
our way to downplay it.''
   He said the Secret Service works closely with other federal
agencies, and with state and local police, to monitor any potential
threats, including the possible threat posed by terrorists
overseas. While only a few threats result in arrests, all are
viewed with seriousness and are pursued, he said.
   ``Some of them fizzle out, luckily, and others don't, and we
keep monitoring to see what the potential is,'' Corbett said.
   The crowded 1988 presidential field, which earlier boasted more
than a dozen major party candidates, forced the Secret Service to
borrow agents from other Treasury Department agencies _ Customs,
Internal Revenue Service, and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms.
   Dukakis did not accept agents until last week, preferring the
freedom of movement and ability to circulate with crowds. He
resisted the urgings of some on his staff, and even his wife Kitty,
to accept protection sooner.
   ``I think Dukakis felt he wanted to run as close a campaign as
he could to the voters, and felt comfortable with the kind of
support he was getting form local police as he traveled,'' said
Leslie Dach, Dukakis' communications director.
   ``He tries to live as much of a private life as he can, and in
order for the Service to do their job it takes a bit away from
that. Dukakis likes to be able to go home and be by himself and
enjoy his neighborhood, and I think that was a large part of it,''
Dach said.
   Other candidates, particularly those struggling early in the
race, welcomed the protection. It meant a traveling entourage of
agents, as few as four or as many as nine or 10. It lends an air of
professionalism to a campaign and ``it helps to pay for the
airplane,'' as former Democratic candidate Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
once quipped.
   The government pays for each agent's seat on a candidate's
chartered plane.
   But the seriousness of the duty is often apparent.
   During the New York primary campaign, agents remained extremely
close to Jackson at all times. One agent confided he would be
greatly relieved when the campaign left the state.
   As with the president, the thought that some violent act could
erupt at any moment is always present with a presidential candidate
and his entourage.
   ``My mother tells me not to stand too close to Jackson,'' his
spokeswoman, Cobb, said _ adding that it was meant in a somewhat
joking way.
   ``You have to basically believe that nothing's going to
happen,'' she said. ``You can't operate in fear.''
   ``There are certain givens I must face every day,'' Jackson told
the Atlanta Constitution in an interview. ``Anxiety and fear can
become paralyzing. I cannot let myself become paralyzed with morbid
thoughts.''
</TEXT>
