<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShultzDisclosure     05-18 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz Disclosure,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoke-Hating Shultz Accepted Cigarette Boxes as Gifts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who hates
smoking so much he outlawed it on his official flights, accepted
gifts of silver cigarette boxes from leaders in India, France,
Guatemala and Mexico last year, according to a list issued
Wednesday.
   The secretary also kept caviar, chocolates, a tea set and a
lacquered painting, worth $175 in all, from Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   The gifts were on Shultz's annual financial disclosure
statement, which gives a bare-bones outline of assets and income,
plus his $99,030 salary as a cabinet officer.
   A blind trust established for Shultz when he took office July
1982 generated more than $100,000 in income in 1987; how much more,
he is not required to disclose under the rules of the Office of
Government Ethics. The trust executed purchases and sales totaling
more than $250,000 during the year.
   For most of his adult life, Shultz has been either a college
professor or government official, but during the Ford and Carter
presidencies and in the beginning of President Reagan's first term,
he was a high-ranking executive of the Bechtel Group, Inc., one of
the world's largest construction companies.
   All gifts from foreigners worth more than $100 must be reported
and anything over $180 must be turned in to the government.
   Besides all those cigarette boxes, Shultz kept six pounds of
coffee from Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, four yards of silk
from the wife of the South Korean ambassador, and a Danish ham from
the Danish foreign minister.
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police sent Shultz a wall mounting,
titled ``Mounties.''
   Shultz kept more gifts from Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze than from any other single source, which was not
surprising, considering the number of times they met during a year
of superpower summitry.
   The gifts included a book on Russian churches, a candle holder
``with some sort of semiprecious stone adornment,'' a small pill
box, two other boxes, a commemorative medal, vodka, dolls, a
lacquered picture and a soapstone necklace, the report said.
   Many leaders gave Shultz books. Israeli foreign minister Shimon
Peres sent a tome titled ``The Jewish People, 4,000 Years of
Survival,'' and Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte gave his
autobiography, ``My Story.''
   The costliest gifts Shultz accepted from American sources in
1987 were $633 in tennis clothes and equipment from the Community
Foundation of Greater Washington, which runs a charity-raising
celebrity tennis tournament Shultz plays in.
   Shultz certified that the statements in the form were ``true,
complete and correct to the best of my knowledge and belief,'' but
whoever filled in the secretary's telephone number in the heading
got it wrong.
   The State Department changed the numbers on most of its phones
in 1986, and Shultz's form, signed May 4, 1988, had the old digits.
Any member of the public who sees the form and calls Shultz at the
number on the form will hear a recording that says, ``you have
reached a disconnected U.S. government number.''
</TEXT>
