<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     05-18 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Sabotage Damages Power System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent attacks on the electric
power grid by leftist rebels have put seven of the 19 distribution
lines out of service and aggravated supply problems created by
drought, officials said Wednesday.
   Orlando Quiteno, public relations director of the state-run
Lempa River Hydrolectric Executive Commission, said in a telephone
interview about 40 percent of the nation has been affected by the
sabotage.
   Government reports show 75 percent of San Salvador and five of
the 14 provinces have been without service since Monday. An
emergency rationing system already in effect has been tightened
elsewhere.
   Guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, who
began fighting U.S.-supported governments 8{ years ago, said
Tuesday they had mobilized ``dozens of units of militia and
saboteurs throughout the national territory.''
   A broadcast by clandestine Radio Venceremos said the campaign
was ``placing the Christian Democratic military dictatorship in the
worst energy crisis of the war.''
   Col. Mauricio Vargas, operations director for the joint chiefs
of staff, told reporters the military command was studying ways to
increase security for the nearly 500 miles of primary cables in the
distribution system.
   The power grid has been a prime target in the guerrila program
of economic sabotage. Official reports say more than 2,000 attacks
since 1980 have done at least $51 million in damage.
   Quiteno said that, before the latest attacks, the power company
had begun a rotating system of daily four-hour power cuts because
of low water levels in reservoirs and a delay in the arrival of the
rainy season, which normally begins in May.
   An attack May 11 on the November 5th Dam in northern El Salvador
forced daily cuts of six to eight hours, he said.
   Raiders destroyed five transformers and a central control board
at the dam 50 miles north of San Salvador. Reports indicate the
generating facility will be down for two months and damage exceeds
$500,000.
</TEXT>
