<DOCNO> AP880518-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Jews     05-18 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Jews,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Leaders See Anti-Semitism in Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish leaders said Tuesday there are signs in Italy
of the same anti-Semitism that preceded enactment of racial laws 50
years ago by Benito Mussolini's fascist government.
   Chief Rabbi Elio Toaff and Jacob Sabban, president of the Jewish
community, told reporters it ``could be the prelude of things much
more vile, and not only against the Jews.''
   Toaff and Sabban accused the media of publishing reports from
the Middle East that compare Israelis to Nazis because of the
Israelis' policies toward Palestinians in the occupied territories.
They displayed bundles of threatening letters and dozens of photos
of swastikas painted on walls in Rome.
   They said an old man who survived Auschwitz was asked by a
doctor who saw the camp number tattooed on his arm: ``How many
Palestinians have you killed today in your extermination camps?''
   A Jewish university student was forced to remove the Star of
David he wore on a chain around his neck, the two men said.
   ``It seems to me the return of the climate that preceded, 50
years ago, the approval of the racial laws by the fascist regime,''
Toaff declared.
   Both said ``a deterioration of the value of civilization'' was
illustrated by recent acts of intolerance against Gypsies and
people of other races.
   Toaff said criticism of Israel is legitimate but journalists
should be careful not to use terminology that encourages
anti-Semitism. He said threats to the Jewish community made
recently had the pretext of condemning acts by Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
