<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Drugs     05-18 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Drugs,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>13 Arrested in Airport Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police rounded up at least 13
people Wednesday in a surprise airport raid conducted during a
follow-up investigation of drug smuggling.
   Rigoberto Regalado Lara, Honduran ambassador to Panama and
half-brother of the armed forces chief, was arrested Sunday on
arrival in Florida from Tegucigalpa and charged with trying to
smuggle nearly 26 pounds of cocaine into the United States in his
luggage.
   Police sources said privately the purpose of Wednesday's raid at
Toncontin International Airport was to determine how drugs could be
carried out of Honduras. They said those detained probably would be
interrogated and released.
   Retired Gen. Oswaldo Lopez Arellano, president of the Honduran
airline TAN-Sahsa, said he was advised of the raid in advance. He
said all those picked up had access to the baggage-handling and
runway areas.
   The airline's labor union declared an immediate protest strike,
forcing suspension of TAN-Sahsa's international flights.
   Gen. Humberto Regalado Hernandez told reporters Tuesday his
half-brother also would be prosecuted in this country. ``The law is
the same for everyone and, independently of the ruling in the
United States, we also will judge him in Honduras,'' he said.
   Regalado Lara, 49, a career military officer, was suspended as
ambassador after the arrest. He is being held without bond in
Miami, pending trial.
</TEXT>
