<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Guatemala-Tass     05-18 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Tass,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rightist Attack on Tass Correspondent's Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two grenade explosions shattered windows
Wednesday at the home of a Soviet journalist who earlier received a
threat from a rightist terrorist squad.
   No one was injured.
   Alejandro Trouchine, who opened an office of the Soviet news
agency Tass in the capital in January, said two grenades exploded
at 2:20 a.m. (4:20 a.m. EDT), damaging the door of the house and
his car.
   He said the blasts broke windows in his home, where he also has
his office, and in neighboring houses.
   Trouchine said he and his wife Elena were at home. Their
12-year-old son Eugenio left two weeks ago for Moscow, he said.
   He said he received a statement in the mail on May 9, signed by
Mano Blanca (White Hand), one of the main right-wing terrorist
squads active from the mid-1960s until around 1980.
   It was a copy of a communique dated April 14 that was published
last month in local newspapers. The communique also threatened
representatives of an exiled opposition organization who visited
Guatemala in April.
   ``The Mano Blanca rises again in the combative life of
Guatemala, raises its flags of western Christian civilization
against the new Marxist avalanche that keeps company with two
Communist espionage agencies, Tass and Prensa Latina, for whom we
have a surprise at the right opportunity,'' it read.
   Prensa Latina is the Cuban government news agency.
   A recent communique purportedly from another underground
rightist group, called Officials from the Mountains, also mentioned
the two news agencies in a barrage of accusations of leftist and
illegal activity against President Vinicio Cerezo and Defense
Minister Hector Gramajo.
   That communique was read by a local television news director on
his program two weeks before a coup attempt which the government
has blamed on a group of civilians and military officers.
   Five civilians and six military officers have been charged with
rebellion in connection with the coup attempt last week.
   Cerezo took office Jan. 14, 1986, as the first civilian
president since 1970.
   Mano Blanca has claimed responsibility for bombings and
assassinations of people it claimed were communists.
   A leftist insurgency has operated in Guatemala for more than a
quarter century.
</TEXT>
