<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-18 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Soaks East Coast, Scattered Showers in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A stubborn low pressure system stalled over eastern Virginia
Wednesday, bringing rain all day from southern New England to the
North Carolina coast.
   The rain extended west into the upper Ohio Valley, but was
heaviest over parts of central and eastern Virgina and eastern
North Carolina, where thunderstorm watches were issued for the
evening.
   Flash flood watches were in effect until early Thursday for
parts of central Pennsylvania and the Laurel Mountains.
   Newark, N.J.'s .65 inches of rain Wednesday set a rainfall
record for the date, breaking the mark of .63 set in 1963.
   Showers also were widely scattered from the central Missouri
Valley into parts of the central Rockies. Thunderstorms were dotted
across western and northeast Nebraska during the morning and later
formed over north-central Iowa. Light showers also were scattered
from Wyoming through northern New Mexico into the high Plains from
South Dakota into northwest Kansas.
   The rest of the nation enjoyed pleasant weather, with cloudy
skies over most of the Pacific Northwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 41
degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Thermal, Calif.
The morning low for the nation was 26 degrees at Marquette, Mich.,
and Hibbing, Minn.
   Thursday's forecast called for more rain from the upper Ohio
Valley through southern and central New England into the Middle
Atlantic states. Thunderstorms should be scattered across the upper
Ohio Valley and mid-Atlantic Coast, and from the upper Mississippi
Valley through the central Missouri Valley into the central and
southern high Plains and along the east slopes of the Colorado
Rockies.
   High temperatures should be in the 70s or 80s across most of the
nation, dipping into the 60s across northern and western Washington
into northern Idaho, over northern Minnesota and from eastern parts
of the Ohio Valley through the central Appalachians into much of
the New England. Highs should reach into the 90s from the valleys
of California into the desert Southwest and from the central Gulf
Coast region through eastern and central Texas into the Rio Grande
Valley.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
