<HEAD>Police Seek to Deport 66 After Car Bomb Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Wednesday they want to deport
66 foreigners viewed as security risks after a car bomb killed
three people last week in a bungled attack on the Israeli Embassy.
   In six days, 116 foreigners also have been refused entry to
Cyprus. Police turned them back at points of entry for failing to
give good reasons for their visits.
   A police statement said the records of 2,648 foreigners,
including 755 students, have been checked since the
explosives-laden car exploded near the embassy May 11.
   Nationalities were not disclosed. Police sources, however,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said most of those checked and
on the expulsion list were Arabs. Police have asked court officials
to issue expulsion orders for the 66, the statement said.
   A Lebanese man was arrested in connection with the explosion.
The driver of the car, who was killed, also was identified as
Lebanese.
   Among those refused entry were 26 people turned back at Larnaca
airport Wednesday, the police announcement said.
   This eastern Mediterranean island has a large Arab community.
Many of the Arabs are Lebanese who come on business or to escape
the 13-year-old sectarian civil war in their country.
