<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wedtech-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0922 05-18 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wedtech-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0922,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Attorneys Say Senate Report on Wedtech `Seriously Wrong'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after pvs 2nd graf bgng ``In addition ...'' to
include Levin response; picks up pvs 3rd graf bgng ``The report
...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee report is ``seriously
wrong'' in accusing Attorney General Edwin Meese III of violating a
White House policy by assisting scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.,
Meese's private lawyers said Wednesday.
   In addition, Meese's counselor at the Justice Department,
William Bradford Reynolds, claimed subcommittee chairman Carl
Levin, D-Mich., did not give subcommittee members an opportunity to
vote on the report.
   ``The subcommittee report was issued following standard
committee procedures. The report was circulated to every member of
the subcommittee for comment. ... Release of the report was
approved by the subcommittee members,'' said Levin in a response
statement.
   The report issued earlier this month says then-White House
counselor Meese and his deputy violated a White House policy
barring contacts with procurement officials, resulting in
favoritism toward Wedtech.
   Wedtech in September 1982 got a $32 million no-bid federal
contract to build small engines for the Army, after an intense
lobbying campaign by former White House political director Lyn
Nofziger and longtime Meese friend E. Robert Wallach.
   Meese's private attorneys, Nathan Lewin and James Rocap, said
the subcommittee report was incorrect because the White House
policy permits contacts with procurement agencies when the White
House has a legitimate interest in information about procurement
matters.
   ``Mr. Meese's direction to his staff to ensure that Welbilt,''
which was then the firm's name, ``received fair treatment was
consistent with that widely recognized interest and was permitted
under the White House policy,'' Lewin and Rocap's said in an
18-page rebuttal.
   President Reagan had campaigned in the South Bronx, N.Y., area
where Wedtech was located and had expressed an interest in
promoting jobs to the area.
   ``The report appears to us to be seriously wrong in its
finding,'' Lewin and Rocap concluded.
   In a cover letter with the rebuttal sent to Levin, Reynolds said
he understood that members of Levin's subcommittee on oversight of
government management were not provided an opportunity to vote on
the panel's report.
   However, the panel's five Democrats or four Republicans were
given an opportunity to file dissenting views, and none did.
</TEXT>
