<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama     05-18 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Forces Announces Closing of Offices in Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces announced Wednesday
it was eliminating the office of military attache in Washington and
closing the Defense Forces offices there.
   Capt. Jose Santos Mota, military and navy attache in Washington
since 1983, advised U.S. officials of the decision, said a
communique read to The Associated Press by telephone.
   It said Panama did not recognize the U.S. Southern Command,
which is based in Panama, and ``there are no channels of liaison or
communication with the armed forces of the United States.'' It did
not elaborate.
   The intelligence group of the Defense Forces chiefs of staff has
suspended meetings with a U.S. intelligence panel because ``that
counterpart has parallel organizations in the embassy as well as
other new ones assigned to the psychological war for the search for
information in the national territory,'' it said.
   It did not identify the other groups. But Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, who controls the government, has accused the United States
of waging psychological and economic warfare against Panama.
   Noriega, the head of the Defense Forces, was indicted in
February on narcotics charges in Florida. The United States has
applied a broad range of economic sanctions in an effort to oust
him.
   Lt. Col. Arnie Williams, a Pentagon spokesman in Washington,
said late Wednesday the Defense Department would have no immediate
reaction to Panama's announcement.
   Williams also said he could not immediately confirm that the
Panamanian attache had advised U.S. officials of the decision to
close the Defense Forces office.
</TEXT>
