<HEAD>South African Farm Experts Expelled Under Pressure From Nigeria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Equatorial Guinea has expelled seven
South African farm experts, Nigeria's government Lagos Radio said
Wednesday.
   The radio, monitored in Abidjan, quoted External Affairs
Minister Mamman Anka as saying that ``the racists left Equatorial
Guinea.''
   Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation with more than 100
million people, had been pressing its West African neighbor to
order the South Africans out. A vocal opponent of apartheid,
Nigeria claimed the South Africans were building a satellite relay
station and expanding an airfield on one of Equatorial Guinea's
islands off Nigeria's coast.
   Apartheid by law and custom establishes a racially segregated
society in South Africa in which the 26 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   South Africa said the aid team was helping build roads, working
on medical projects and running an experimental cattle-breeding
ranch in the impoverished nation of 300,000.
