<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PortlandMayor 2ndLd-Writethru a0903 05-18 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portland Mayor, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0903,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clark First In Mayor's Race But Runoff Likely</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to note that write-in votes as well as absentee
ballots need to be counted; SUBS 5th graf, bgng `Clark needed' and
8th graf, `Clark's 59,810' to UPDATE with later percentage and vote
totals. Note this combines material on Denver airport vote and
Oregon helmet law, to serve as roundup of Tuesday non-presidential
elections.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portland Mayor Bud Clark is heading for a
November runoff after falling just short of the number of votes
necessary to win a second four-year term outright.
   Write-in votes and about 6,500 absentee ballots remained to be
counted, but Clark said Wednesday that it was unlikely he would
pick up enough votes to avoid a runoff against a former police
chief, Ron Still.
   ``It looks like we're going to have to do it,'' Clark said.
   ``It's just frustrating to me,'' he said. ``All I want is the
job and to get the job done.''
   Clark needed one vote more than 50 percent of the total votes
cast in the non-partisan election Tuesday to win re-election
outright, but final unofficial results showed he had 49.92 percent.
   Also in Oregon, voters statewide approved by a 2-to-1 margin a
law requiring drivers and passengers of motorcycles and mopeds to
wear helmets.
   And in Colorado, voters in a Denver suburban area approved a
plan to let the city annex land for a new $3 billion airport that
would be the first major U.S. airport since 1974 and ease
congestion at the existing airport.
   Clark, with 59,981 votes, was followed by Still with 40,352, or
33.6 percent, and former city commissioner Lloyd Anderson with
12,733, or 10.6 percent. Former police chief Jim Davis was a
distant fourth, with 4,848, or 4 percent. The remaining seven
candidates split 2,251 votes, or just under 2 percent.
   Charles Duffy, Clark's press secretary, said the absentee
ballots would be counted Thursday and Friday. The mayor fell about
170 votes short of avoiding a runoff in the final, unofficial
tally, Duffy said.
   Clark, a tavern owner, scored a stunning victory four years ago
over incumbent Frank Ivancie and held a big lead in pre-election
polls in the non-partisan race this year despite a series of crises
that plagued the first half of his term.
   Asked how a runoff election would affect his ability to function
as mayor, Clark said: ``We have to limit the number of things that
we have on our agenda anyway and this just adds one more item and
takes energy out of my life. But we have plans for the city going
forward and the city is going to work.''
   Still, confident of a runoff, was one of two police chiefs who
resigned during Clark's first two years in office. Clark also fired
a third police chief, Davis.
   Clark's most famous and controversial appointee, Penny
Harrington, resigned after 16 months as the first female police
chief of a big U.S. city. Her resignation came a day after a
commission that Clark appointed issued a report sharply criticizing
her management and recommending her replacement.
   Portland's high crime rate was a major issue in the campaign.
Still said Clark's policies helped cause the problem, but Clark
vowed to make fighting crime his top priority.
   Clark, 57, has been criticized for his eccentricities, but there
were few campaign attacks on his personality. His trademark
``whoop, whoop'' cry is a staple of civic functions, and the
bicycling mayor has chronicled his political career with an
ever-present camera.
   In Colorado on Wednesday, Gov. Roy Romer and Denver Mayor
Federico Pena went to the barren site of what may become the
nation's largest airport and hailed Tuesday's land annexation
decision by Adams County voters.
   County residents approved the city's plan to annex the
45-square-mile site northeast of Denver by a 56 percent to 44
percent margin. The move cleared a major hurdle for the city to
build a replacement for crowded Stapleton International Airport.
</TEXT>
