<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BigCypress-Oil     05-18 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Big Cypress-Oil,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Explorers Plot Next Move After Expulsion From Big Cypress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil drillers have been told to tear down
their equipment and get out of Big Cypress National Preserve after
conservation groups protested that exploration would damage the
sensitive lands.
   The preserve covers cypress swamp, hardwood hammocks and grass
prairie in southwest Florida adjacent to the Everglades National
Park.
   The order, issued last week by the U.S. Justice Department,
resulted from a suit filed by the Wilderness Society, the Sierra
Club and five other environmental groups arguing that the federal
government pushed for drilling despite unresolved environmental
concerns.
   Shell Western Energy and Petroleum, a subsidiary of Shell Oil
Co., began exploration this month inside the 570,000-acre preserve
by drilling holes for seismic testing.
   Shell spokeswoman Mary Dokianos has said the government decision
will put 100 employees out of work and $1 million worth of
equipment will have to be dismantled.
   The company will probably continue to apply for rights to
explore for oil north of the preserve on land that will eventually
become part of the preserve under legislation signed by President
Reagan last month, Ms. Dokianos said.
   Until the government actually buys the land, the National Park
Service can't regulate oil companies wanting to explore there.
   But representatives of the Sierra Club say they will fight to
keep Shell from exploring in the expansion area too.
</TEXT>
