<HEAD>IRA Suspect Rearrested, Backers Battle Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities seized a suspected bomber for
the Irish Republican Army on Wednesday as he was released from
prison on other charges, and his angry supporters scuffled with
soldiers, police said.
   Patrick McVeigh fled when authorities tried to arrest him as he
was released from Portlaoise Prison, 50 miles from Dublin, after a
seven-year term for weapons possession. Police fired warning shots
and caught him.
   About 35 supporters, who had turned up expecting McVeigh to be
freed, surged forward and clashed with police. One man was
arrested, but injuries were reported, police said.
   The new warrants accused McVeigh of involvement in terrorist
bombings in mainland Britain from 1981-83. Authorities had to
release him Wednesday because he completed his term, but they
figured on seizing him as soon as he stepped outside the prison
gates.
   The IRA is fighting to force the British to leave Northern
Ireland. The outlawed organization wants to unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the overwhelmingly Roman
Catholic Irish Republic to the south.
   After his arrest, McVeigh was driven to nearby Carlow and
ordered held for 48 hours pending a court appearance on moves to
extradite him to Britain.
   In London, Scotland Yard said the latest warrants were issued on
Friday, when Britain and Ireland resolved a legal dispute over
extradition of suspected terrorists.
   The extradition warrants allege that McVeigh had control of
explosives and conspired to cause explosions at unspecified
locations in Britain between 1981 and 1983.
   The British domestic news agency Press Association said he was
believed wanted for questioning in connection with bombings in
London in 1981 which resulted in three deaths.
   McVeigh was also wanted for questioning in the bombing of
Harrods on Dec. 17, 1983, which killed six people and injured 93,
the agency said. McVeigh was in prison then, but authorities may
believe he helped plot the bombing from behind bars.
</TEXT>
