<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Toronto-Herbig     05-18 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toronto-Herbig,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Herbig Leaves Troubled Detroit Symphony To Take Over In Toronto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conductor Gunther Herbig said Wednesday he will
resign as music director of the troubled Detroit Symphony Orchestra
to take over the same job with the Toronto Symphony.
   The announcement was seen as a serious blow to Detroit's
cultural community and a coup for Toronto's.
   Herbig, 56, has been music director in Detroit since 1984.
During that time, he appeared as guest conductor with major
orchestras in Europe and the United States.
   He said lack of money for expansion, recordings and tours was
the factor leading him to leave Detroit, where the orchestra went
on strike last year.
   The Toronto Symphony promised him three recordings a year, an
ambitious series of world tours, an expanded orchestra of 105
players, television and radio broadcasts and acoustical
improvements at the orchestra's home, the Roy Thomson Hall. He will
step up as music director in Toronto in 1990 with a renewable
contract ending in 1992.
   At a news conference, the silver-haired conductor described
Toronto as a city that ``really cares about the arts.''
   ``The situation in Detroit is such that they could not come back
with a counter-offer,'' he said.
   Herbig was born in Czechoslovakia of German parents and made his
name with the Dresden Philharmonic and Berlin Symphony Orchestra.
   He succeeds the British conductor, Andrew Davis, who ended his
13-year tenure in Toronto to take over the British Broadcasting
Corp. Symphony Orchestra in London.
</TEXT>
