<2ND_LINE>AM-Stano-Death Appeal, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0930,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Issues Stay Of Execution For Confessed Serial Killer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 2nd and three grafs after 5th graf pvs
``I explained'' to UPDATE with details of appeal ruling; reax from
Florida officials. DELETES outdated 8th graf pvs ``Mark Olive'' and
10th graf pvs ``If he.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confessed serial killer Gerald Stano, who
claims to have slain 41 women, got an indefinite stay from a
federal appeals court Wednesday, less than 24 hours before he was
scheduled for execution.
   Attorneys for Stano turned successfully to the 11th Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta after a federal judge here refused a
stay of execution. The district judge had rejected arguments that
his defense counsel was ineffective.
   The appeals court, however, ruled that Stano was entitled to a
hearing on the claim.
   Stano, 36, who has been convicted of 10 murders, was scheduled
to die in Florida's electric chair at 7 a.m. Thursday.
   After hearing eight hours of legal arguments over two days, U.S.
District Judge Patricia Fawsett ruled Wednesday that Stano's lawyer
had correctly informed him of the consequences of pleading guilty
to the murders of two women, but that ``Stano rejected this
advice.''
   ``I explained to Mr. Stano that he was at risk, that there were
no deals, and Mr. Stano understood that,'' the former lawyer,
Howard Pearl, had testified.
   In issuing the stay, a three-judge panel of the 11th Circuit
ruled that it remained unclear whether Stano understood what his
lawyer meant when the attorney told Stano he had not examined all
the evidence.
   Carolyn Snurkowski, director of death-penalty appeals in the
office of Attorney General Bob Butterworth, said the state likely
would not appeal the stay, but she reserved final judgment until
she had a chance to review the order.
   ``We still have to look at it more carefully,'' she said.
   After giving him life sentences on guilty pleas in other cases,
Volusia Circuit Judge James Foxman sentenced Stano to death in 1983
in the killings of Susan Bickrest, 24, in 1975 and Cathy Muldoon,
23, in 1977.
   ``Counsel followed the instructions of his client,'' who had
been found mentally competent by five experts, Fawsett said.
   Stano, who was brought from death row to Orlando for the
district court hearing, showed no emotion when Fawsett issued her
ruling. He was relaxed and attentive and often smiled and joked
with defense counsel.
   The exact number of Stano's victims may never be known, said
Assistant Attorney General Belle Turner. ``With so many murders,
there has understandably been confusion over some cases and
details,'' she said.
   Although Stano has been sentenced on only 10 of the crimes _
receiving seven life sentences and three death penalties _ Florida
investigators say they have documented 25 of the murders claimed by
Stano in this state and that there may have been others.
   There is less known about the cases in the New
Jersey-Pennsylvania area which Stano admitted to, but authorities
in those states have linked him to a number of unsolved murders
over the years.
   Daytona Beach Police Sgt. Paul Crow, the chief investigator who
arrested Stano in 1981, has testified that Stano provided crucial
information about burial sites, victims' clothing, appearance,
methods of death and other minute details that only the killer
would know.
   He has been jailed since the 1981 arrest.
   Ann McMillan of Ocala, a psychologist who has done extensive
studies of Stano's life, says he fits into the classic pattern of
multiple killers such as Charles Manson and David ``Son of Sam''
Berkowitz.
   In 1982, she estimated Stano's death toll at 35.
   Stano's death warrant is his second for the Bickrest-Muldoon
murders. Both women, who worked as cocktail waitresses, were forced
into his car at gunpoint, driven to remote areas and killed,
according to trial testimony.
   Besides the issues of inadequate defense counsel and of mental
incompetency by Stano, Olive accused police interrogators of
misleading Stano into a series of ``bogus confessions'' by
promising that he would not receive the death penalty. Those
arguments have been heard and rejected by various courts in the
past.
   ``All that happened here was that a guilty man pleaded guilty
and was appropriately sentenced,'' prosecutor Turner argued.
</TEXT>
