<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SharpevilleSix     05-18 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville Six,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Agrees To Reopen Controversial Murder Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has agreed to reopen
the trial of the so-called ``Sharpville Six'' to hear defense
arguments against the death sentences imposed on the black
defendants, court officials said Wednesday.
   The six _ five men and a woman _ were scheduled to hang March 18
for complicity in the 1984 mob killing of a black town councilor in
Sharpeville, south of Johannesburg. A stay of execution was granted
March 17.
   Pretoria Supreme Court Justice W.J. Human set June 6 for a
hearing on the case, which has attracted international attention.
Defense lawyers had applied to reopen the trial so they could
present evidence that a key state witness was coerced into giving
false testimony.
   President P.W. Botha has said he will not intervene in the case,
despite widespread appeals for clemency.
   The case has sparked debate in part because the six were not
convicted of contributing physically to the death of councilor
Jacob Dlamini. Instead, they were convicted under the doctrine of
common purpose, which held them responsible because they allegedly
were active participants in the mob which set out to kill the
councilor.
   The killing occurred during riots provoked by a rent increase in
Sharpeville and neighboring townships.
</TEXT>
