<HEAD>Harrisburg Legislative Leaders Urge Tighter Security After Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT time of arrests to Tuesday sted
Wednesday in 1st and 5th grafs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men were arrested in the theft of a
car belonging to a state lawmaker who was beaten to death, but they
have not been charged in the slaying, a district attorney said
Wednesday.
   At the Capitol, meanwhile, officials called for heightened
security throughout the building and grounds after the body of a
severely beaten woman was found at a nearby construction site
Wednesday.
   A 12-member task force of state and local police has been
working round-the-clock gathering information on the slaying of
Rep. William Telek, said Dauphin County District Attorney Richard
A. Lewis.
   Telek, a Cambria County Republican, was found dead Tuesday
morning on a side street about three miles north of the Capitol,
his wallet and state-leased car missing. Officials said he died of
injuries from repeated blows to the head.
   Three men arrested Tuesday in the theft of Telek's car remained
in custody but were not charged with the slaying, Lewis said.
   ``The task force is sifting through all the information coming
in,'' he said.
   About 24 hours after Telek's body was found, the body of a
Harrisburg woman was found a block from the Capitol.
   ``You can't dismiss the possibility, but there doesn't appear to
be any obvious connection'' between the two slayings, Lewis said.
   In the wake of the two deaths, House and Senate leaders urged
tighter precautions throughout the Capitol complex.
   Senate President Pro Tem Robert Jubelirer said Telek's death has
rekindled previously voiced concerns, especially about a recently
constructed parking garage.
   Jubelirer said some have speculated that Telek's killer might
have entered his car while it was parked in the underground garage,
later surprising him.
   The Department of General Services had begun looking into adding
security personnel patroling the Capitol garage before Telek's
death, said spokeswoman Pam DiSalvo.
   She said the upgraded security plans included boosting the
number of Capitol police officers patroling the two-level garage,
installing a card entry system into the garage and putting camera
surveillance throughout the Capitol complex.
   Charged with theft by receiving stolen property were the driver
of Telek's car, Bernard Williams, 17, of Harrisburg, and John
Wesley Anderson III, 19, of Susquehanna Township. The third person,
a juvenile, was turned over to the juvenile authorities. His
identity was withheld.
   Despite his age, Williams' name was made public because of a
prior conviction on adult charges. A hearing for the men is
scheduled for next week.
   Lewis identified the woman whose body was found by security
guards at the construction site as Ann Landis, 39, a former nurse
at Harrisburg State Hospital.
</TEXT>
