<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PeresVisit     05-18 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peres Visit,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Says More Soviet Jews Will Be Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said
Wednesday that he has been assured that 1,400 Jews would be allowed
to emigrate from the Soviet Union this month, continuing the upward
trend of recent months.
   Peres, in an appearance at an Israeli Bond luncheon in
Manhattan, said he had learned of the increased emigration on
Tuesday when he met with President Reagan, Secretary of State
George Shultz and Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin.
   Later, Peres reiterated his remarks before the Conference of
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations.
   ``I must admit we do live in a changing world,'' he told the
group of about 100 presidents. ``Things that looked impossible a
year ago, three years ago' are now becoming reality.''
   He said it was also agreed that 10 Jews who had been refused the
right to emigrate on national security grounds would now be allowed
to leave.
   And he said there was agreement that Soviet psychiatric
hospitals _ long accused of housing and maltreating dissidents _
would allow doctors from outside the country to examine their
patients.
   Peres also said an agreement would be signed at this month's
Reagan-Gorbachev summit to enlarge the cultural life of Soviet
Jewry.
   The National Conference on Soviet Jewry had reported Tuesday
that 1,086 Soviet Jews emigrated in April, the highest monthly
total in nearly seven years. That figure is far less than the
emigration totals for 1979, when the monthly average was more than
4,000.
   Soviet officials claim that only 15,000 of the country's 1.8
million Jews want to leave, though others claim the number is more
than 400,000.
   Peres also said Dubinin read a Soviet proposal for an
international peace conference on the Middle East in which the
Soviet Union would play a part. Peres said the new proposal was an
improvement upon previous Soviet suggestions, but Israel still
could not agree to it.
</TEXT>
