<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Media     05-18 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Media,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists Hit Allegations Of Reporter-Financed Rebel Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Correspondents'
Association of the Philippines said Wednesday that allegations that
foreign journalists financed a rebel ambush could hurt the
country's press freedom.
   Also Wednesday, a military official denied the British
Broadcasting Corp. was named as the foreign media group that
reportedly paid New People's Army rebels to stage an ambush in
February in which a general's son and 10 other soldiers were killed.
   The correspondents' group urged President Corazon Aquino's
government to investigate the matter and make the results public
quickly.
   ``We fear that such unsubstantiated charges may constitute a
potential assault on freedom of the press. We believe that coverage
of both sides of a guerrilla conflict is essential to responsible
journalism,'' the group said in a statement.
   Col. Marino Filart, deputy constabulary commander of Bicol where
the ambush occurred, presented a captured rebel Wednesday who said
``Caucasian'' journalists gave her group a wad of 100-peso ($5)
bills and three M-16 Armalite rifles to stage the ambush for
filming purposes.
   Filart said the woman did not identify the journalists involved.
He added that Manila reporters may have concluded that it was the
BBC because of a letter with the company's letterhead seized by the
military from the rebels.
   Filart said the letter, signed by a certain Mina Daum, requested
video coverage of rebels training but he added that ``we are not
sure if the intent of the letter was pushed through.''
   His superior, Brig. Gen. Eduardo Taduran, was quoted by Manila
newspapers Monday as saying that the letter showed the BBC was the
group involved. The military has provided no further evidence to
substantiate the charges.
   The BBC has denied the allegation and said it had no crew in the
Philippines when the ambush occurred.
   Rep. Gregorio Andolana urged the Philippine House of
Representatives Wednesday to enact measures that would protect
journalists' right to cover events related to the insurgency, the
government-run news agency reported.
   Andolana, a former human rights lawyer, also asked his
colleagues to stop the military from carrying out surveillance of
journalists who maintain contact with rebel sources for their work,
the Philippine News Agency said.
   On Tuesday, Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre, chief of the Capital
Regional Command, said the military had seized rebel documents with
the names of 112 foreign and Philippine journalists who had been in
touch with the guerillas since 1987.
   Aguirre said no legal action would be taken against the
reporters but some would be placed under surveillance.
   He did not release any names of the reporters.
</TEXT>
