<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0921,0748</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Declares Day Of Mourning For Bus Crash Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 2nd with developments from Cleveland
and New York bus accidents to serve as a bus crash rdp. Pickup 3rd
graf pvs, `Wilkinson ordered...' May stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Wallace Wilkinson, saying he wished
``it were possible to turn back the clock,'' declared an official
day of mourning for Thursday for the 27 victims of the Radcliff
church bus disaster, coinciding with the first five funerals.
   Grief counselors from the National Organization for Victim
Assistance conducted a seminar in Radcliff on Wednesday for school
counselors, military personnel and others dealing with the victims'
families. A separate seminar open to the public was scheduled
Wednesday night at Radcliff Middle School, where 16 of the dead
were pupils.
   Meanwhile, four people remained hospitalized Wednesday from a
public transit bus accident in Cleveland that killed a teen-age
passenger, and police were checking reports that the bus
accelerated after striking a car.
   The Tuesday accident was triggered when a motorist tried to make
a left turn in front of the bus. The bus struck the car and then
lurched out of control, striking a tree, a utility pole and a fence
before grazing a building and another pole, said Patrolman Emil
Cielec.
   And in Clinton Corners, N.Y., a National Transportation Safety
Board inspection found no structural or mechanical problems with a
bus that overturned Monday, killing three people and injuring 20
others, police said Wednesday.
   However, mechanical failure has not been entirely ruled out as
the cause of the accident, said state Police Sgt. Dennis Cody. The
driver of the bus remained hospitalized and was unable to talk to
investigators Wednesday, Cody said.
   Wilkinson ordered flags flown at half-staff across the state
Thursday in memory of the 24 children and three adults who died
when their bus was struck head-on Saturday night by a pickup truck
being driven in the wrong direction on Interstate 71 in Carroll
County, 100 miles northeast of Radcliff.
   The truck driver, Larry Mahoney, still hospitalized in
Louisville, was charged with 27 counts of murder, one for each of
those who died in the accident. Authorities said he was intoxicated
at the time of the crash. Thirteen other people also were still
hospitalized Wednesday.
   National Transportation Safety Board officials also continued to
study the crash.
   Jean Fasone, in charge of the probe, said investigators are
comparing buses similar to the one involved in the crash to
determine whether 1977 safety standards requiring a caged fuel tank
would have prevented the fire that enveloped the bus after the
accident. The bus was built shortly before the standards went into
effect.
   In a statement released Wednesday by his office, the governor
said: ``If it were possible to turn back the clock, we would.''
   ``Whatever consolation we can give will never make up for the
loss of friends and loved ones. We will make this day (Thursday) as
an official day of mourning, but the memory of the victims of this
tragedy will be with us always.''
   The governor planned to attend a memorial service Thursday
evening at North Hardin High School in Radcliff. Most of the
victims were military dependents or had ties to nearby Fort Knox,
and the service at the school's 2,400-seat football stadium was to
include hymms and a performance by the post military band, said
Lelia S. Haddle, secretary to Mayor Joseph Hutcherson.
   It wasn't known how many of the victims' families would attend
the service, Ms. Haddle said. ``We've got familes that say they
can't handle another service,'' she said. ``But everybody wants to
do something, and this is one way to handle it.''
   Four of the victims _ Mary Catherine Daniels, 14; Julie Ann
Earnest, 12; Denise Ellen Voglund, 13; and Amy Wheelock, 14 _ were
to be buried at Radcliff on Thursday. A fifth, 14-year-old Tina
Michelle Mustain, was to be buried in Tyler, Texas. All attended
the middle school.
   Most of the funerals were scheduled for Friday, including a
joint service for six of the victims at Radcliff First Assembly of
God, the church that owned the bus.
   Members of the church's youth group, with more than a dozen of
their invited friends, used the bus for an all-day outing Saturday
at the Kings Island amusement park north of Cincinnati.
</TEXT>
