<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0909,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Says Paraguay Suffers From Putting Profits, Power Above
People</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ASU3</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with papal speech at airport,
departure; picks up 9th graf pvs, ``John Paul ... with minor
editing to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II completed a South
American tour Wednesday by calling for a ``reconciled and brotherly
Paraguay'' but the ruling party blasted his meeting with opposition
leaders, calling them ``a grab-bag of society's destroyers.''
   In a nighttime farewell address at Asuncion's airport, the pope
urged citizens to build ``the Paraguay of tomorrow'' based on
Christian values.
   ``I have happily witnessed the dream that moved you to launch in
unity a reconciled and brotherly Paraguay,'' he said.
   The country's authoritarian president, Gen. Alfredo Stroessner,
told the pope his visit was ``unforgettable.''
   Stroessner, widely regarded as a dictator, described Paraguay as
``pluralistic and democratic ... without violence, without
terrorism.''
   The pope departed in an Alitalia Boeing 747 for Rome, where he
was to arrive Thursday afternoon.
   During his 12-day trip, the pope visited four nations _ Uruguay,
Bolivia, Peru and Paraguay. It was his ninth visit to the region.
   Earlier in the evening at a youth rally in a muddy field near
the airport, more than 100,000 teen-agers sang ``Happy Birthday''
to the pontiff in Polish, his native language. It came at the end
of a busy day that included visits to the Parana River port city of
Encarnacion and Caacupe, site of the national Catholic religious
shrine.
   During a Mass in Caacupe, John Paul II repeated a call for
special attention to the rights of the country's largely landless
peasants and Indians.
   Today's church ``wants to strongly support their demands that
their legitimate rights be respected, without allowing them to
forget their duties,'' the pontiff said.
   In Encarnacion, on the border with Argentina, John Paul said
Paraguay suffers from a concept of life that puts ``profits and the
thirst for power above the human person and his needs.''
   ``I call on you to construct a society of love,'' said the pope.
   John Paul urged his audience to participate in ``a new
evangelization.'' He paid homage to the missionary priests who
sowed the seed of Catholicism among the native tribes of
present-day Paraguay, Argentina and Brazil in the 16th and 17th
centuries.
   Encarnacion is in the heart of the area where Jesuit priests
founded 30 missions in an effort to convert Guarani Indians from
1608 until 1767, when the Spanish crown expelled the order from
Latin America.
   Among those attending the prayer meeting were several thousand
Argentines, many from Polish immigrant communities who crossed a
recently completed bridge linking Argentina and Paraguay.
   The Asuncion daily newspaper Patria, run by Stroessner's
Colorado Party, criticized a papal meeting Tuesday night with a
church-picked group of cultural and civic leaders that included
opposition activists. The group is known as the ``Builders of
Society.''
   ``There is no doubt about the opposition ideologizing,
politicizing and manipulation of everything concerned with the
meeting,'' Patria declared. ``It would be better to call them a
grab-bag of society's destroyers.''
   In an editorial, Patria labeled Rene Recalde, an organizer of
the meeting, ``an ideologized element from the extremist sector of
radicalization.''
   Government officials and Colorado Party members boycotted the
meeting, which Paraguayan authorities originally canceled but later
permitted after the Vatican protested.
   At the meeting, the pope heard denunciations of political
oppression and then told his cheering audience, ``It is impossible
to speak of true liberty, and even less of democracy, where there
is no real participation by all citizens.''
   Stroessner, 75, took power in a 1954 military coup and recently
was elected to an eighth term in voting his opponents say was
rigged. The local church has regularly criticized his human rights
record and authoritiarian style, pressing for a more pluralistic
form of government in this landlocked nation of 3.8 million people.
   Wednesday marked the second time John Paul had celebrated his
birthday outside Rome since becoming pope nearly 10 years ago. He
celebrated his 65th birthday in Belgium.
   About 1,000 well-wishers serenaded him in the morning at the
Vatican envoy's residence in Asuncion. The pope emerged to greet
the crowd and told them, ``I still feel young, especially when I am
with young people.''
</TEXT>
