needed some type of reminder.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WRIGHTWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pines dot snowy peaks outside as Tom
Pinard sits in his rustic office in a peach cowboy shirt, crusading
to carve away 90 percent of the nation's largest county to create
Mojave County.
   At 18,160 square miles of mostly desert north of the San Gabriel
and San Bernardino mountains, the new county would still be the
nation's largest, bigger than Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode
Island and Delaware combined.
   Both it and what remained of San Bernardino County would have
better-focused government if voters agree to a ``divorce'' by
passing Measure A, said Pinard, who publishes a local newspaper
from this 6,000-foot-high ski resort town.
