<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the U.S. trade deficit for March improved
beyond all expectations, many economists and big investors
responded with a chorus of ``Bah, humbug.''
   Funny they should pan what would seem like fabulous news. But
they've done it before and most likely they'll do it again.
   They responded that way to news of a lower jobless rate, to
increases in factory use, even to the dollar's new stability.
   It is a strange, discomfiting world in which good is bad, happy
is sad, up is down, square is round, best is worst, last is first,
strong is weak, bottom is peak, rich is poor and less is more.
   And if the sages are being spooked by the ``good'' news _ news
for which they've waited months and which they deemed necessary for
economic survival _ it's no wonder they're exaggerating ``bad''
news, of which they've found plenty.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers are replacing their
crash diets of the early '80s with more lasting changes to prepare
for challenge of the next decade: overproduction.
   By 1990 there could be 5.6 million more new cars and trucks than
buyers worldwide, according to industry estimates.
   ``First, obviously, cost-cutting was the major concern ... But
in the long term it's the products they're coming out with'' that
will determine who survives, said Kathleen Heaney, an analyst with
Nikko Securities in New York.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few youngsters are likely to answer ``actuary''
to the question of what they want to be when they grow up, but a
new book rates it as the best job of all.
   Typical children's choices like doctor and astronaut ran far
behind less glamorous professions such as computer programmers,
statisticians and parole officers in ``The Jobs Rated Almanac,''
published by American References Inc. of Chicago.
   Actuaries _ who interpret statistics to determine expected
personal losses due to sickness or disability and material losses
from disasters _ emerged No. 1 overall, as determined by the
almanac's six criteria.
