<1ST_LINE>a a PM-GamblingonSurgery Adv25 APPhotoPkg 05-18 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gambling on Surgery, Adv 25, AP Photo Pkg,0562</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, May 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Corrective Surgery Pays Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Photo Package</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the last of four operations was
completed, the surgeon reminded his young Guatemalan patient that
she owed him a dinner of black beans and rice.
   ``We agreed upon that fee,'' Dr. John Johnson told Nicolasa
Menchu, a 27-year-old student who came to the United States on a
scholarship and ended up having surgery to correct a 142-degree
curvature of the spine.
   Johnson had warned Ms. Menchu that without surgery, the
curvature would eventually choke off her vital organs, resulting in
death.
   The procedure that Johnson proposed carried no guarantees.
``There's a 60 percent chance of success, a 20 percent chance of no
improvement, and a 20 percent chance that you won't survive,'' he
told her.
   Ms. Menchu made her decision in mid-February. ``I decided to
gamble on an operation even though I'm accustomed to the way I
am,'' she said.
   At the time, she was 3 feet, 11 inches tall and weighed 64
pounds. Today, she is 2{-inches taller, the curvature has dropped
to 90 degrees and she is gaining weight.
   She also is preparing to return to classes at the University of
Louisville under a United States Information Agency scholarship.
The agency brought 154 students to this country in January 1986 in
an effort to offset Soviet influence in Central America.
   While swimming last fall, Ms. Menchu developed breathing
problems and was turned over to Johnson, co-director of the spine
clinic at Norton Hospital and assistant professor of orthopedic
surgery at the university's medical school.
   In the hospital, Johnson bolted a metal band to her skull and
attached weights to stretch her spine.
   ``That's your halo,'' he told her, ``because you've been so good
about everything.''
   Two more operations removed bone chips from her spine.
   The final step came in March when Johnson hooked up a set of
rods to his patient's spine for more straightening and stability.
   His team used a magnet ``doughnut'' attached to Ms. Menchu's
head to warn it when the surgery threatened the spinal cord.
   ``The magnet sends a discharge into the arms and legs, causing
them to react,'' he explained. ``At first, Niko could move only one
leg or the other. We must have started and stopped seven times
before both limbs worked in unison.''
   Ordinarily, the surgery and hospital stay would cost $89,000,
but Johnson is donating his services and Norton expects to cover
the remainder.
   Because of the long recuperative period, the USIA extended Ms.
Menchu's scholarship.
   ``Hopefully, I'll get my bachelor's degree in education by
Christmas and be ready to go home,'' she said.
   Her family lives in Totonicapan, where she once made and sold
pottery to help finance her education.
   Although she still has some pain and cannot yet sit in a chair,
Ms. Menchu said, ``It's been worth it a thousand times, and I've
grown a lot.''
   She was close to tears, however, on May 9 when the university
graduated the 12 other foreign students who had accompanied her to
the Louisville campus.
   ``My turn is coming, I guess.''
   End Adv for Wed PMs, May 25
</TEXT>
</DOC>
