<1ST_LINE>a i AM-SouthAfrica-Party Adv23-2Takes   05-18 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Party, Adv 23-2 Takes,0748</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, May 23, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>South Africa's National Party Marks 40 Years of Unbroken Rule</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: In 1st graf, ``this week'' is May 22-26.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Party, which made
apartheid law in South Africa, this week marks 40 years of unbroken
rule. In that time, it has helped create Africa's most modern state
and one of the world's most divided and ostracized nations.
   On May 26, 1948, to the surprise of its own Afrikaner faithful,
the party won a narrow majority in the whites-only Parliament. Its
subsequent hold on power is one of the longest ever among countries
with multiparty elections.
   The party's tactics and constituency have changed over the
years, but its primary objective remains constant _ to preserve the
white minority's political and economic paramountcy.
   ``Forty years of National Party rule have brought us to a sorry
state indeed,'' wrote Joyce Harris, former president of the Black
Sash civil rights group, in a recent article.
   ``It has pursued its blinkered apartheid policy with no regard
to its effects on the country and the vast majority of its people.
... It has successfully followed a policy of divide and rule.''
   President P.W. Botha, the National Party's leader since 1978,
says apartheid is ``an outdated concept'' now and is being
dismantled in phases. He and his loyalists depict the party as a
proponent of racial reform, using rhetoric that would have been
heretical to Nationalists 20 years ago.
   The party still stresses, however, that its vision of
power-sharing does not include any scenario where blacks, who make
up 75 percent of the population, could overrule whites on matters
of vital national interest.
   People officially classified as being Asian or of mixed races
now have their own Parliament, but all the major legislation
resides with the white Parliament.
   The policy of slow-paced, limited reform has induced large
numbers of English-speaking South Africans to desert more liberal
parties and support the National Party.
   But the talk of reform has driven an even larger number of
pro-apartheid Afrikaners into the ranks of the far-right
Conservative Party, which emerged from the 1987 white election as
the main opposition in Parliament.
   ``The National Party is no longer the political arm of Afrikaner
nationalism,'' says Harald Pakendorf, a moderate Afrikaner
political columnist. ``It and the Conservative Party have an almost
equal share of support from Afrikaners.''
   When the National Party was formed in 1914, it was intended
solely as a vehicle for promoting the interests of Afrikaners, the
descendants of the Dutch, French and Germans who settled in South
Africa in the 17th century.
   Today, Afrikaners make up 60 percent of the 5 million whites,
and their economic and educational levels are largely comparable to
English-speaking South Africans. But after losing to the British in
the Boer War (1899-1902), many Afrikaners felt dominated culturally
and politically by English-speakers, who as a whole were richer and
better educated.
   The hardcore Nationalists stuck with the young party in 1934
when many of its leaders formed a broadbased alliance with
English-speaking politicians under the banner of the United Party.
   Entering the 1948 election, the National Party had 49 seats in
the 153-member Parliament. It campaigned on a platform of strict
racial segregation, and few experts believed it could oust the
United Party.
   South Africa broke away from the British-led Commonwealth and
declared itself a republic May 31, 1961. This was a major issue for
the National Party, and it narrowly won a referendum in October
1960, with 52 percent of the voters supporting the breakaway.
   But, in what The Star newspaper of Johannesburg described at the
time as a ``political convulsion,'' the Nationalists won a
five-seat majority. D.F. Malan, a stern former pastor, became prime
minster and established the first all-Afrikaner Cabinet.
   Over the next few years, the new government consolidated its
powers through the allocation of civil service jobs to Afrikaners
and laid the legislative groundwork for apartheid.
   By 1950, interracial sex and marriages had been banned, and two
of the laws that today form the cornerstones of apartheid had been
enacted. These are the Group Areas Act, which mandates segregated
residential districts, and the Population Registration Act, which
requires racial classification of all South Africans _ white,
black, Asian or ``colored'' (mixed race).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-SouthAfrica-Party Adv23-1stadd   05-18 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Party, Adv 23-1st add,0561</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, May 23, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>JOHANNESBURG: (mixed race).</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The goal, explained National Party policymakers, was to
eliminate friction between the races. A separate education system
was created, and hundreds of thousands of blacks were forcibly
moved to homelands where, in theory, they could practice limited
self-government.
   ``The calling of this small nation is to give to the world the
basis and pattern on which different races can live in peace and
safety in the future, each within its national circle,'' said Daan
De Wet, a Cabinet minister, in 1959.
   Even before 1948, non-whites' freedoms were limited. For
example, they could not vote or own farmland in ``white'' areas.
But only after 1948 were they restricted by a vast array of major
and minor discriminatory laws that changed the siutation from de
facto to legalized segregation.
   In addition to the Group Areas Act, Population Registration Act,
Mixed Marriages Act, the new government took numerous other steps.
Under the Separate Amenities Act of 1953, separate entrances were
provided for whites in railway stations, post offices and other
government buildings. Special hospitals and beaches were set aside.
Whites and non-whites were forbidden to sit on the same benches in
parks and at bus stops.
   Other National Party laws formalized the segregation of trains
and buses. In the past five years, there has been a trend toward
desegregation, affecting restaurants, cinemas, hotels, but
segregation, both enforced and de facto, remains pervasive.
   Edward Perkins, who in 1986 became the first black U.S.
ambassador to South Africa, has remarked that apartheid, which in
Afrikaans means ``separateness,'' has achieved its purpose.
   ``The sad fact is that the policy of apartheid has been all too
successful,'' Perkins said in December. ``It ranks as one of this
century's most disastrous feats of social engineering.''
   Critics of the National Party acknowledge that
government-sanctioned racial discrimination was pervasive in South
Africa long before 1948. But Joyce Harris, the former Black Sash
leader, argues that the Nationalist takeover came at a time when
Western countries were becoming increasingly conscious of
individual rights.
   ``It was precisely then that South Africa parted company with
the Western world and turned its face in the opposite direction,''
she wrote. ``At that time, our country was a respected member of
the Western world and South Africans could hold up their heads and
walk with pride anywhere.''
   Politically, the high-water mark for the National Party came in
1977 when it gained 64 percent of the vote in the white election.
Last year, its share of the vote dropped to 52 percent, but a
favorable districting system enabled it to win 123 of the 166
contested Parliament seats for its 10th consecutive general
election triumph.
   Despite the far-right's extensive gains, few political experts
are predicting an early end to the National Party's reign. There is
a widespread sense of irony in the perception that the party's
future now hinges on its ability to co-opt blacks, rather than
isolate them.
   Botha himself touched on this matter in April when he proposed
black participation in Cabinet-level policymaking.
   ``If the white people do not wish to follow my way, it is their
responsibility,'' he said. ``If they follow the way of
confrontation, it is their problem.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs May 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
