<1ST_LINE>s a BC-FishWars Adv22-2Takes   05-18 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fish Wars, Adv 22-2 Takes,0820</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Illegal Foreign Fishing in Bering Sea Strains Coast Guard Patrols</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OVER THE BERING SEA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The view from the flight deck had not
changed all day: mile after mile of gray sky, gray water, and not a
fishing boat in sight.
   The four-engine C-130, its huge fuel tanks running low, finally
turned and headed for land.
   ``That was a perfectly boring patrol,'' said Joseph Koczur Jr.,
a National Marine Fisheries Service agent.
   ``Well, we learned where they aren't,'' the co-pilot, Coast
Guard Lt. Cmdr. Mike Flood, said with a shrug.
   Chalk up another frustrating day for the ``fish cops'' of the
Bering Sea, who fight a losing battle guarding the nation's richest
deepwater fishery against raids by an elusive foreign fleet.
   This first leg of a two-day patrol covered a slice of ocean half
the size of Kentucky _ and, for the number of foreign vessels seen,
that's where the patrol may as well have been. Keeping the C-130
airborne for the day cost taxpayers $27,000.
   ``It's a big ocean,'' Adm. Paul Yost, the Coast Guard's
commandant, said from his Washington office. ``It's like searching
for a needle in a haystack.''
   This year, it's like searching with one eye closed. Deficit
reduction measures have cut back on fishery patrols. Four years
ago, a C-130 would take off daily from the Coast Guard's base on
Kodiak Island; now it's more like once a week.
   American fishermen say the cuts come at a bad time, just as
they're finally claiming an area Congress made theirs in 1976 by
extending U.S. jurisdiction to 200 miles offshore. And foreign
fleets are not being polite about leaving the fishing grounds they
pioneered decades ago.
   By some estimates, foreign boats in the Bering Sea are illegally
catching up to $1 billion in fish each year, twice the amount
caught legally by Americans. Biologists worry that such poaching,
combined with unregulated fishing just outside the U.S. zone, may
threaten fish stocks.
   If a scale big enough could be found, the Bering Sea's hoard of
fish would weigh in at more than 30 billion pounds, a huge,
swimming feedlot that is 65 percent Alaska pollock and 35 percent
Pacific cod, yellowfin sole, sablefish and a smattering of other
species. Collectively known as bottomfish, they provide an annual
catch worth more than all other U.S. deepwater fisheries combined.
   For years, bottomfish were ignored by American fishermen seeking
salmon and crab. Foreigners, mainly Japanese, Koreans, Soviets and
Poles, valued the fish more highly. Starting in the 1940s, they
fished these distant waters with huge trawlers, depleting stocks of
some slow-growing species by the early 1960s.
   Management improved in 1976, when the U.S. Fishery Conservation
and Management Act established the 200-mile zone. The act also
created the North Pacific Fishery Management Council to regulate
harvests.
   Americans were given first shot at the bottomfish, but they had
neither the capital needed to build processing plants nor a market
for the finished product. By 1981, foreign boats still accounted
for 93 percent of the Bering Sea bottomfish harvest.
   Recently, more Americans have joined the bottomfish boom. Some
are drawn by a keener U.S. appetite for fish and by worldwide price
increases. Others, their crab boats idled by a drop in Alaska crab
populations, just want to stay in business.
   The fishery council has doled out progressively smaller catch
quotas to the foreign fleet. This year, for the first time,
American fishermen will catch all the fish within the 200-mile
limit, although 60 percent are still sold to foreign processing
ships.
   Foreign fishermen have been relegated to a triangle of high seas
known as the ``doughnut hole,'' a 45,000-square-mile pocket formed
by the boundaries of the U.S. 200-mile zone on the east and south,
and the Soviet convention line on the west.
   The foreign catch of pollock in the doughnut hole has soared,
from just over 4,000 metric tons in 1982 to an estimated 1 million
tons last year. That's close to the pollock catch allowed in the
rest of the Bering Sea.
   In addition to producing this legal catch, the doughnut hole has
become, in the words of Alaska Republican Sen. Ted Stevens, ``a
haven for bandits.''
   Just as fish ignore political boundaries, so do some foreign
fishermen. ``They've been fishing the Bering Sea since the end of
World War II,'' said NMFS agent Koczur. ``If they want to come in
and find fish, they know where to go.''
   On the second day of Koczur's mission, the C-130 reached the
patrol area and descended to 1,500 feet. Cockpit radar showed a
bright green dot 40 miles beyond the limit, dead ahead. Soon the
radar screen filled with dots.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-FishWars Adv22-1stAdd   05-18 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fish Wars, Adv 22-1st Add,0686</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>OVER THE BERING SEA: with dots.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The plane descended to 600 feet, and the boats became visible,
dozens crowded into a few square miles. It dropped still lower, to
200 feet, and roared by the rigging of a rusty old boat with its
net in the water.
   Koczur recorded the vessel's call number, and fellow NMFS agent
Kenneth Hansen snapped a picture. It was a large Soviet stern
trawler, Koczur said.
   For 90 minutes, the pilots yanked and banked the plane, lining
up one boat after another for photographs, information collected
for files and future patrols. On some turns, it seemed a wing might
dip into the ocean.
   The navigator said he felt ill. The reporter turned pale. Pilot
and co-pilot chatted about eating raw fish. And Hansen and Koczur
kept snapping away. They counted 56 boats in all, a mix of
Japanese, Soviet and Polish trawlers.
   The boats continued to fish, knowing they were perfectly legal,
40 miles into the international waters of the doughnut hole.
   Koczur wondered aloud where the boats had been hours earlier.
Officials suspect foreign vessels use cover of darkness and storms
to sneak into U.S. waters. Fishermen have been known to duck into a
squall when they know the law is close, and boats have been spotted
with canvas tarps over their identifying numbers.
   Coast Guard efforts in this cat-and-mouse game have had limited
success. Since August 1986, 15 foreign vessels have been detected
fishing illegally in the 200-mile zone, Yost said. Patrols have
spotted hundreds more, but unless a boat has its net in the water,
it is considered legal.
   ``That is frustrating,'' Koczur said. ``We don't know they're
fishing, but why else would they be out there?''
   Why indeed, an angry Sam Hjelle asked last winter. Hjelle, the
Seattle-based owner of a Bering Sea trawler, met with the Coast
Guard last December to discuss illegal foreign fishing. He left the
meeting in disgust, and shortly afterward, he and other fishermen
tried their own remedy.
   On Jan. 12, Hjelle and Ted Evans, executive director of the
Alaska Factory Trawlers Association, chartered a twin-engine plane
for a two-day ``fishing expedition.''
   The fish vigilantes came back $17,000 poorer, but they got what
they were looking for: videotapes of seven Japanese vessels
allegedly fishing in U.S. waters.
   The tapes created an uproar, just as Hjelle and Evans had hoped.
The Senate passed a resolution condemning illegal fishing and
urging a moratorium on doughnut hole fishing. The State Department
demanded an explanation from the Japanese government, and the
Commerce Department fined three Japanese companies $100,000.
   Soviet and American negotiators last month renewed talks to
consider closing the doughnut hole to fishing _ a delicate issue
involving international law since neither country has jurisdiction
over the area.
   The negotiators have asked other fishing nations to consider a
moratorium. But the response has been weak, especially from Japan,
a fish-hungry nation that's seen traditional worldwide fishing
grounds shut off by nations declaring 200-mile limits.
   ``Japan has a long history in the Bering Sea, long before the
economic zone was claimed by Americans,'' said Katsuo Jodai of the
Japan Fisheries Association. ``... The doughnut hole is high seas.
It does not belong to any country.''
   So the cat-and-mouse game continues, and the mice have a greater
advantage than ever.
   In March, Yost announced that C-130 patrols from Kodiak would be
cut by 35 percent; cutter patrols by 55 percent. Yost he hopes an
interim funding measure working its way through Congress will boost
patrols this summer, but there's no guarantee of funding for next
year.
   The State Department, meanwhile, awaits a reply from the
Japanese on January's illegal fishing. The companies fined by the
Commerce Department have yet to pay. And their troublesome boats,
after dropping off their catch in Hokkaido, returned to fish the
Bering Sea.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
