<DOCNO> AP880518-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1953EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-GoingDutch Adv22   05-18 1098</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Going Dutch, Adv 22,1131</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Remote Aleutian Village Struggles to Keep Up With Fishing Boom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fish Wars</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUTCH HARBOR, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunched over the steering wheel,
dressed in rubber boots and jeans, Paul Fuhs guided his bouncing,
mud-spattered truck along a rutted road past docks crowded with
fishing vessels.
   ``It's the most highly sophisticated fishing fleet in the
world,'' he boasted, waving toward the boats. ``There's nothing
like this anywhere else.''
   Fuhs, 39, an expert in underwater explosives, is the unpaid
mayor and chief booster of Unalaska _ a hotbed of high technology,
high finance and high hopes.
   The Aleutian village, with a permanent population of about
1,900, is awash in a wave of Bering Sea bottomfishing boom time.
U.S. vessels, along with cargo and processing ships from at least
14 other nations, crowd 80 square miles of harbor, jockeying to get
to 15 docks.
   ``In the first two weeks of the year we turned away 114 ships,''
Fuhs said. ``This has got to be the most exciting place in the
world right now.''
   Most of the bustle is centered on Dutch Harbor, located about
800 miles southwest of Anchorage on tiny Amaknak Island; it is part
of the town of Unalaska on the larger, sheltering Unalaska Island.
   Fuhs spends much of his time trying to persuade the state to
pump money into his wind-swept community _ to cash in on the boom
instead of asking, ``Dutch where? Bottom what?''
   The entire state would benefit, he says, if the fishing
industry's focus shifted north from Pacific Northwest ports.
   ``The state has no policy on bottomfishing,'' Fuhs said.
``Seattle has a strategy. Japan has a strategy. Everybody has a
strategy but us. Here we are, a tiny little town in the middle of
nowhere, and it's fallen in our laps. ... The Bering Sea could be a
perpetual Prudhoe Bay if we manage it properly.''
   Fuhs says state officials urge Unalaska to seek private
investment. But private investors, while indicating willingness to
build $60 million in warehouses, cold storage and processing
plants, first want the town to upgrade its sewer and water lines
and build a bigger dock.
   For that, Fuhs says, the town needs state money. ``We want
grunt-level infrastructure. We don't want a performing arts
center.''
   City Manager Nancy Gross says needed improvements in the World
War II-era water system alone could cost an estimated $30 million.
Much of the system is built of wood-stave pipes, which leak an
estimated 80 percent of the water pumped through them.
   ``The needs are just enormous,'' she said. ``Ten years ago, this
was a town of 500 to 600 people with very little industry.''
   Unalaska, unfortunately, needs money at a time when slumping oil
prices have squeezed the budget. Gov. Steve Cowper managed to find
$1.7 million for Unalaska sewer improvements in the last days of
the legislative session.
   Harbormaster Gary Daily believes the problem may be Unalaska's
remoteness. ``The same thing that gives us our advantage works
against us,'' he said. ``There's a lot of ignorance about what's
going on out here.''
   ``Out here'' is a frontier of sorts, where fists, brains and
hard work win respect. Unalaska has no full-time dentist, no
plumber, no appliance repair service, no doctor and no veterinarian
to deal with scores of free-roaming mutts.
   Milk costs $4.99 a gallon. A bottle of Jack Daniels sour mash
whiskey that sells for $20 in Anchorage goes for $39.50 here.
Softball and basketball are serious pursuits, and eagles are as
plentiful as vultures, fighting for space in the rigging of docked
vessels.
   Almost any language can be heard on the street.
   The Soviets are a favorite because they spend buckets on
stereos, gum, solar-powered watches and (nobody knows why) plastic
baby bottles. And they are enthusiastic merrymakers. ``They get
down and boogie,'' Daily said.
   Thirty-five Soviet vessels docked at Dutch Harbor last year; 40
are expected this year.
   Men outnumber women 5-1. Drugs, liquor and brawling are problems.
   ``These guys make a lot of money, and there is nothing to do
here,'' said 48-year-old Pete Davis, chief of the eight-man police
force. ``If they're so inclined, they can stick it up their nose or
pour it down their throats. Eighty-five percent of our work is
because of booze or drugs.''
   On the islands, the mountains wade into the sea; flat land goes
at a premium. There are 30-odd miles of car-killing dirt roads and
a 3,900-foot, heart-stopping gravel runway for planes.
   If it rains, there is mud. If not, choking dust.
   And there is money _ lots of money.
   The Bering Sea fisheries _ salmon, crab and bottom fish _
generate $1.3 billion to $2.3 billion a year. Fishermen get about
$400 million of that, with the rest going for the myriad services
needed to keep boats afloat.
   Only a few years ago, Unalaska was dead in the water. In 1982,
for reasons still not understood, stocks of red king crabs were
decimated. The harvest plummeted to 3 million pounds from a 1980
peak of 130 million. The 1983 season was canceled.
   The bottomfishing industry was then mostly in foreign hands, but
American fishermen turned to these less-valued fish to make a
living, aided by Congress' 1976 act establishing a 200-mile U.S.
coastal zone.
   Some say the crab crash may have been a blessing in disguise for
Unalaska. ``King crab was real seasonal,'' said Kathy Grimnes,
president of Ounalashka, the Aleut regional ative corporation.
Workers labored 14 hours a day, seven days a week.
   ``It was so busy you didn't have time to think,'' she said.
``The crash sort of put things on hold and allowed people to
evaluate their community.''
   Since then, Unalaska has put in parks and sponsored cultural
events. There is a bookstore. The school, with 150 students from
kindergarten through senior high, boasts an Olympic-sized swimming
pool.
   But the boom makes some residents fear that part of Unalaska is
dying.
   Jim Bacus drives a battered taxi. ``We can't drive our
three-wheelers anymore,'' he said. ``They used to let this dog
sleep on the floor of the Elbow Room. Now when dogs wander in they
chase them out. There's too many rules now.''
   Grimnes' corporation, a land development company, is busy
planning a 50-acre industrial park and may build a $5 million,
900-foot dock. But Grimnes admits something may be fading.
   ``It used to be that everybody used to wave to each other,'' she
said. ``Now we don't.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 22</NOTE>
