<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Ryder Adv27-29 1stLd-Writethru 05-18 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Ryder, Adv 27-29, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0892,0835</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27-29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 27-29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Kym throughout</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Performing Is a Good Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Kym Ryder sipped on her tea and squirmed
in her seat. She was discussing her childhood, her days on the
road, her debut record. But she would rather have been in front of
an audience.
   ``My idea of a good time is performing,'' said Ryder. ``The
closer I am to the people, the better. I want to sit on their
table.''
   Ryder, whose new LP is ``Angel Arrive,'' does not need a stage
to attract attention. She stands 5 feet 9 under a wave of blond
hair. She is outgoing and curious about the people around her. She
likes to talk. She has a lot to say.
   She knew from an early age she did not want to spend her entire
life in Minneapolis, where she was born in 1965 and adopted by a
UPS employee and his wife. Her first live performance was a
rendition of ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer,'' sung in front of a
collection of aunts and uncles. She was 4 years old.
   In junior high school, she got involved in acting. In high
school she joined her first band and was impatient to pursue a
career in music.
   ``I was kind of a rebel in high school,'' she said. ``I thought
it was a stupid setup. School was just holding me down. It was a
very frustrating time.''
   A week after graduating, she hit the road. ``I followed bikers
and things like that. I got down and dirty for a while,'' she said.
   Three years on the road, frequently changing bands, living out
of a trunk and suitcase did little to discourage Ryder.
   ``You learn whether you want to do this for the rest of your
life. You like it or you don't. It cuts the men from the boys,''
she said, laughing. ``I loved it, even when I was broke and
starving.''
   Two years ago, performing in Wyoming, she caught the attention
of a vacationing New York lawyer.
   ``He saw me play and liked the energy,'' Ryder said. ``He
followed me 100 miles and saw me the next day. He left roses in my
hotel room; I didn't see the roaches anymore.''
   The lawyer left a business card and suggested Ryder look him up
if she came to New York. Ryder came East and met David Werner, who
produced the record and wrote the songs. ``Shatter the Glass'' is
the first single.
   ``Everything is so perfect, then something happens and shatters
the reality,'' she said. ``I'm like the devil, the temptress. I
pull you in. I shatter the fantasy.''
   The music on ``Angel Arrive'' is straight ahead pop-rock.
Ryder's singing shows the influence of the music's best known
female vocalists.
   ``I loved Pat Benatar. I looked like her in high school,'' she
said. ``Singers like Debbie Harry and Belinda Carlisle, that's who
I sound like. I have a pure voice, very strong.''
   Rock 'n' roll has always appealed to nonconformists, and Ryder
is no exception. ``I was always the black sheep; I always liked to
dress weird,'' she said. ``People think I'm so outrageous. My
friends were just paralyzed by me.''
   Ryder sees live performing as a way of breaking down barriers
between herself and the audience. She describes herself as a tomboy
growing up and admits to feeling more comfortable around men. On
stage, she has had trouble, almost to the point of violence, with
women who feel threatened by her presence on stage.
   ``Sure I flirt on stage, but I try to make it for fun. I don't
do that dripping kind of sex thing,'' she said.
   But occasionally, she can connect. One time was in Salt Lake
City.
   ``After one of my ballads, a girl took off one of her earrings
and handed it to me,'' she remembered. ``It's still in my jewelry
box. Things like that nail me.''
   Although Ryder must face the problems of being a woman in the
music industry, she considers herself relatively fortunate.
   ``It (sexism) is around all the time, but I haven't had to deal
with it in a bad way,'' she said. ``I've found very good people and
stuck with them.''
   If she's had any disappointments, it's been with the pace of her
career.
   ``I don't like having to wait. I don't like depending on other
people. I'm after the next thing.''
   But even if Ryder has been frustrated by the lengthy process of
getting her first album released, she has lost none of her
determination to succeed.
   ``I never want to wake up and say, `I wish I would have.' You
just go for it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 27-29</NOTE>
