<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-18 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0496</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record level of export sales gave the United
States its lowest monthly trade deficit in three years during
March, the government has reported.
   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the deficit shrank
dramatically in March to $9.7 billion, a drop of 29.5 percent from
the February imbalance of $13.8 billion.
   The improvement came from a 23 percent surge in American
exports, which rose to a record monthly high of $29 billion, as
demand for U.S. machinery, aircraft, computers and chemicals picked
up sharply. This offset a smaller rise in imports, which climbed
3.6 percent to $38.7 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dramatic improvement in the nation's trade
deficit bolstered the dollar, but has intensified the gloom of
pessimists in the stock and bond markets.
   The news of a $4 billion drop in the March trade gap catapulted
the dollar higher against other major currencies.
   But after a short-lived rally, stock and bond prices fell, with
traders seeing the deficit news as confirmation of nagging fears
that strong economic growth could rekindle inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industry operated at 82.7 percent of
capacity in April, the highest level in more than eight years, the
government says.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Tuesday the operating rate at
factories, mines and utilities last month jumped by 0.3 percentage
point from 82.4 percent a month earlier. It was the highest since
March 1980, when the operating rate was 83.7 percent.
</TEXT>
