<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have shown little change
after another session of apathetic trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, June contracts for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, rose 10 cents to
settle at $17.76 per barrel on Tuesday.
   Among June contracts for refined products traded on the
exchange, wholesale prices for unleaded gasoline rose 0.01 cent to
52.74 cents per gallon, while heating oil fell 0.20 cent to 47.78
cents per gallon.
   Trading was quiet for most of the day, with with no news having
any lasting impact on the market, said Peter Beutel, assistant
director of the energy group at Elders Futures Inc.
   He said many traders have decided to limit their activity until
they see what happens at the next meeting of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The conference, which begins June 8 in Vienna, Austria, is
expected to focus on another round of efforts to limit production
in order to bolster prices.
</TEXT>
