<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LuckyStores Bjt   05-18 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucky Stores, Bjt,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Stores Ups Bid For Lucky Stores To $65 A Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bidding war for Lucky Stores Inc. has
continued with a new $2.5 billion takeover offer by American Stores
Co., which is trying to beat out an investment firm for ownership
of the nation's sixth largest supermarket chain.
   American Stores on Tuesday increased its tender offer to $65 a
share to counter a $61 per share, or $2.2 billion, leveraged buyout
plan that Lucky accepted last month from New York-based Gibbons,
Green, Van Amerongen Ltd.
   The new offer had been expected following Lucky Stores'
disclosure of confidential information to American, made with the
stipulation that American either boost its price or end the hostile
takeover bid.
   If accepted, the combined stores would become one of the biggest
supermarket companies in the nation. American, which owns the Alpha
Beta grocery chain, is based in Salt Lake City, Utah.
   Shares of Lucky, based in Dublin, Calif., closed down 25 cents
at $61.12{ on the New York Stock Exchange. American Stores stock
fell 75 cents to $57.
   American, which initiated the bidding in March at $45 a share
and later indicated it would offer at least $60 a share, extended
its tender offer's expiration from Tuesday to June 1.
   Lucky Stores spokeswoman Lissa Perlman said the company's board
of Directors and independent financial and legal advisors would
review the offer and respond shortly. No date or time for the
meeting was set, she said.
   American chairman L.S. Skaggs, in a letter to Lucky's directors,
wrote that the sweetened offer was based on the confidential
information from Lucky ``and the very favorable impression we
received in the course of meetings with your management last
Friday.''
   Skaggs said in his letter that in connection with the proposal,
American Stores was prepared to enter into an agreement and plan of
merger substantially similar to merger plan executed by Gibbons,
Green, van Amerongen.
   He said American also was prepared to enter into incentive
compensation arrangements with selected key personnel.
   Skaggs said it would be in the companies' mutual interest to
enter the merger agreement by the close of business on Friday.
   ``As we have indicated in the past, we believe that substantial
business advantages would accrue from the combination of Lucky's
operations with those of Alpha Beta and we view Lucky's management
as a vital ingredient to the combination of the two companies,''
Skaggs wrote.
   Morgan Guaranty Trust Company of New York has committed $500
million in financing for the transaction, said Skaggs.
</TEXT>
