<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RubberStrike Bjt   05-18 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rubber Strike, Bjt,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone Walkout Continues; Goodyear Settles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4-day-old strike by the United Rubber
Workers union against Firestone Inc. moves back to center stage
following a tentative agreement that averted a walkout at 11
Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. plants.
   Union and Goodyear negotiators reached an amended contract
settlement shortly before a noon strike deadline on Tuesday,
forestalling a strike by 15,000 Goodyear workers.
   Some 4,700 Firestone workers in six states went on strike Sunday
after union negotiators decided Firestone's offer didn't match an
earlier agreement with Goodyear, which the union intended to serve
as a pattern for Firestone.
   URW International President Milan Stone said the union would
notify Firestone of the changes made Tuesday in Goodyear's new
contract proposal.
   ``They (Firestone) weren't willing to follow the pattern as it
was on Saturday night at midnight. So I don't know what their
response will be now,'' Stone said. ``We have not heard from
Firestone since the strike began.''
   Firestone officials said Saturday the company believed its offer
was equal to Goodyear's. Firestone spokesman Bob Troyer said
Tuesday the company would review the revised Goodyear contract.
   ``For the past two days, the union's attention has been focused
on Goodyear,'' Troyer said. ``Now that they have reached a
tentative agreement, we hope they will get back with us and we can
begin negotiating again.''
   The URW represents workers at Firestone plants in Noblesville,
Ind.; Des Moines, Iowa; Decatur, Ill.; Russellville, Ark., and
Oklahoma City as well as maintenance workers and technicians in
Akron.
   Goodyear workers are to hold a ratification vote before a new
strike deadline of May 24.
   Stone said three key changes were made in the three-year
agreement reached April 21 by the company and the union. A majority
of the membership at the 11 Goodyear locals rejected the proposed
pact on May 2.
   Added to the agreement was a 25 cents-per-hour wage increase;
however, cost-of-living increases will be reduced by 25 cents in
three steps.
   The amended contract restores a requirement that all locals
approve any wage concessions accepted by any single local, Stone
said. It also provides for a wage reopener in March 1990 that
hinges on the company's recovery from the financial impact of an
attempted takeover in 1986.
   Akron-based Goodyear ended the takeover attempt by financier Sir
James Goldsmith when it bought Goldsmith's 11.5 percent share of
the company for $619 million.
   Eleven of Goodyear's 42 plants nationwide would have been shut
down by a strike. The plants are in Akron, Marysville and St.
Marys, Ohio; Lincoln, Neb.; New Bedford, Mass.; Sun Prairie, Wis.;
Topeka, Kan.; Union City, Tenn.; Danville, Va.; Madisonville, Ky.;
and Gadsden, Ala.
   J.W. Battles, president of Local 12 in Gadsden, Ala., said he
would recommend the new package to his 3,000 members, who rejected
the first proposal.
   ``It's an improvement to what we had,'' he said. ``At least,
it's money up front.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
