<DOCNO> AP880518-0318 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0759EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MediaGeneral-Sugarman     05-18 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Media General-Sugarman,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media General Says It Rejected Sugarman Offer to End Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media General Inc.'s board of directors has
rejected an offer by California investor Burt Sugarman to end his
takeover bid in exchange for a large share of the company's cable
television operation in northern Virginia, Media General officials
say.
   The company's board turned down the offer as ``greenmail of the
most egregious sort,'' President James S. Evans said Tuesday night.
Greenmail occurs when a company gets a potential acquirer to end
the chase by agreeing to buy back its own shares at a premium not
available to other stockholders.
   Jeffrey Taufield, a spokesman for Sugarman, would not confirm
the terms of the purported offer or even that an offer was made on
Sugarman's behalf.
   Taufield quoted Sugarman as describing Media General's version
as a ``last-minute desperation move to turn around a proxy
contest'' that he contended Media General is losing. ``It just
won't work.''
   J. Stewart Bryan III, vice chairman of Media General, said the
offer was made Monday afternoon by Sugarman's financial advisers to
Media General's financial advisers.
   Sugarman proposed withdrawing his nominees for three of the nine
seats on the company's board in balloting that ends Friday and
exchanging his group's 10.1 percent share of Media General publicly
traded stock for about 43 percent of a new company that would own
the cable system in Fairfax County, company officials said.
   Media General is seeking the re-election of its three directors,
and the family of Chairman D. Tennant Bryan opposes the sale of the
Richmond-based communications company at any price. Sugarman,
chairman of two companies that produce cement and television game
shows, has offered $1.8 billion for Media General, or $70 a share.
   Sugarman was seeking to buy the cable system ``at a bargain
basement price,'' Evans said. Sugarman's investment adviser valued
the system at $300 million, while the company values it at $450
million to $600 million, according to Stewart Bryan.
   That prompted the charge of greenmail.
   Sugarman couldn't be reached for comment, but Taufield said
Sugarman ``said he never made Media General an offer.''
   Taufield declined comment on whether Sugarman's financial
advisers at Bear Stearns & Co. forwarded a proposal for spinning
off the cable system and letting Sugarman obtain a 43 percent stake
in it.
   Legal and investment banking advisers for both Sugarman's group
and Media General ``have been communicating throughout the
process,'' Taufield said.
   He said Sugarman reiterated his pledge not to accept greenmail
and that a proposal to pay shareholders $70 per share in a $1.8
billion transaction remains on the table.
   Bear Stearns executives went to the offices of Goldman Sachs &
Co, Media General's financial adviser, in New York Monday afternoon
and made the offer. ``I don't think it was in writing,'' Stewart
Bryan said.
   Asked what the company's next move would be, he said, ``I don't
know what to expect from people of his type. There is no next move,
as far as I'm concerned.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
