<HEAD>London Shares Off 12.3 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Wednesday as a
gloomy mood settled into the market.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was off 12.3
points, or 0.7 percent, at 1,776.9 at 12:30 p.m. local time.
   Volume was 255.3 million shares at midday compared with 203.5
million shares at the same time Tuesday.
   The inability of Wall Street to set an upbeat tone after
Tuesday's narrower-than-expected U.S. trade deficit for March
prompted a markdown in prices, dealers said.
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed more than 20 points
lower Tuesday as traders focused on the bearish side of the $9.7
billion trade shortfall, saying a rise in imports coupled with an
expanding export sector meant inflation was on the horizon.
   The deficit compared with a shortfall of $13.8 billion in
February.
   ``We couldn't muster any enthusiasm after Wall Street didn't
perform too well'' on Tuesday, one equity salesman said.
