<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HarvardUnion 1stLd-Writethru f0025 05-18 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Union, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0025,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Workers Vote To Unionize In Narrow Margin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to recast, bring higher reference to NLRB.
Picks up in 4th graf, `We're all ...; also moving on general news
wires</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard University's clerical and
technical workers narrowly approved a bid to unionize, but the
fight that set an Ivy League faculty against an administration
accused of strong-arm tactics may not be over.
   Tuesday's vote, which the president of the parent union called
an important step in organizing white-collar workers, ended with
the union winning by 44 votes.
   The unofficial count Tuesday night was 1,530 to 1,486, but 41
ballots were challenged, said Allison Chisolm, a university
spokeswoman. The university has asked the National Labor Relations
Board to investigate the conduct of the union in the election.
   ``We're all ecstatic,'' said Kristine Rondeau, the union's chief
organizer and a former Harvard employee. ``We want to make this a
model for women everywhere.''
   Harvard's 3,300 clerical and technical workers have always
bargained on their own, a practice organizers say has resulted in
lower pay for women, who comprise 83 percent of the group.
   Rondeau maintained the union was victorious, saying, ``Whenever
you have a big and powerful and sophisticated employee like this
one, you always have a close vote.''
   The prestige of Harvard and the publicity generated by the union
effort increased the importance of Tuesday's voting. Gerald
McEntee, president of the 1.1 million-member American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees, called it ``the premier test
of our union in 1988.''
   AFSCME would be the parent union of the Harvard Union of
Clerical and Technical Workers.
   ``As goes Harvard,'' McEntee said, ``so goes the unorganized
white-collar sector of the economy.''
   The struggle to unionize, reminiscent of a 1985 campaign that
led to a bitter strike by clerical and technical workers at
Harvard's Ivy League rival, Yale University, went on for more than
a year and became increasingly public as union representatives
accused the university of strong-arm, anti-union tactics.
   The university argued that the union offered workers no
substantive promises.
   ``I don't think we're anti-union,'' said Anne Taylor, who
directed Harvard's response to the organizational effort. ``We have
run an extremely fair, fact-based campaign.''
   Last month, 27 faculty members signed a full-page advertisement
published in the campus newspaper calling on the administration to
stop interfering in the union campaign.
   Last Sunday, 350 faculty members, religious leaders, actors,
elected officials and civil rights activists signed an
advertisement supporting the union under the headline, ``We're with
you.''
   Taylor said the outcome of the election could be affected by an
investigation into reports that the union may have engaged in
conduct prohibited by the national labor law.
   ``Until the NLRB has certified the results, they are not
final,'' she said. ``In the event the NLRB declares the union the
winner, Harvard will work constructively with the union in the
interest of support staff and the university.''
   Henry Griggs, spokesman for AFSCME, said Harvard's clerical
workers ``have waited a long time for this. But they'll have a
fight on their hands. They'll have to negotiate a contract but at
least this time they'll have a voice.''
   University President Derek Bok told the workers in a letter that
he believes in the union movement but feels it is inappropriate for
their type of work.
   ``Unions have typically resisted efforts to reward superior
achievement with greater compensation or to allow supervisors and
employees to vary the way they work in response to their special
needs and capabilities,'' Bok wrote.
   A clerical union would cover 110 job descriptions, Rondeau said,
including librarians, secretaries, biomedical assistants and copy
center operators. She said typical annual salaries for clerical
workers at Harvard are around $18,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
