<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0004 05-18 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0004,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Export Sales Slashed U.S. Trade Deficit in March</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS new grafs 1-5 to UPDATE with housing starts for April,
edit to conform; picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng, While the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction edged up 0.5 percent in April, the third
monthly gain in a row after a sharp slump at the end of last year,
the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said the increase pushed construction
activity to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.56 million units.
   The increase last month followed a gain of 2.3 percent in March
and 9.9 percent in February. But housing activity was still 4.5
percent below last year, in part because of declines in December
and January.
   Many economists now believe rising mortgage interest rates could
choke off housing growth later this year.
   The government's report Tuesday that the March trade deficit
fell to the lowest level in three years helped the dollar but
failed to inspire other financial markets.
   While the dollar climbed against most other currencies after
Tuesday's report, stock and bond prices sagged.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 21.22 points
to 1,986.41, erasing its 17.08-point gain on Monday. Broader stock
market indices also fell. In the credit markets, yields on the
bellwether 30-year Treasury bond rose to 9.21 percent from 9.11
percent late Monday.
   The Commerce Department said a record level of exports helped
reduce the trade deficit to $9.7 billion in March compared with the
February imbalance of $13.8 billion.
   American exports rose 23 percent to an all-time high of $29
billion in March, as demand for U.S. machinery, aircraft, computers
and chemicals picked up sharply. That offset a 3.6 percent increase
in imports, which rose to $38.7 billion.
   For the first quarter of 1988, the trade deficit totaled $36
billion, an annual pace of $144 billion. Last year, the merchandise
trade deficit hit a record $171.2 billion, but as expected to
decline by about $20 billion this year.
   Analysts said some investors are worried the export boom will
spark another round of inflation in the United States as factories,
many already operating at peak capacity, begin to raise prices.
   The Federal Reserve Board said in a separate economic report
Tuesday that American industry operated at an eight-year high of
82.7 percent of capacity in April, a 0.3 percentage point rise from
March.
   The high operating rate was solid evidence of the boom in export
sales, economists said, but they cautioned that the country wais
approaching a danger zone in which tight labor markets begin
pushing prices higher. Unemployment fell to a 14-year low of 5.4
percent last month.
   ``You would have to read the trade number as evidence supporting
the view that wages and prices will be firming up and there will be
further inflationary pressures later this year,'' said Jerry
Jasinowski, chief economist of the National Association of
Manufacturers.
   That view was echoed in a survey indicating the nation's
purchasing managers have become more optimistic the economy will
continue growing this year, but also expect higher inflation.
   In their latest semiannual forecast, 73 percent of the
purchasing managers predicted the economy would be better in 1988
than it was in 1987, compared with 57 percent in their December
report.
   They forecast a net average increase in prices of about 5.8
percent for the year, the report said, compared with their December
forecast of a 3.6 percent price rise for all of 1988.
   The latest survey was released by the National Association of
Purchasing Management, an education and research organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
