<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 0922EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Taiwan-U.S.Trade     05-18 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Taiwan-U.S. Trade,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Welcomes Lower U.S. Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sharp decline in the U.S. trade
deficit in March was welcomed Wednesday by Taiwan, which has been
under pressure from U.S. officials to reduce its huge trade surplus.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Taiwan's trade surplus
with the United States was $531.8 million in March, down from $1.34
billion the month before.
   ``That's really exciting news,'' said Lin Chien-shan, economics
professor at Fu Jen University.
   Lin said the narrowing trade imbalance would help alleviate U.S.
pressure on Taiwan to appreciate its currency against the U.S.
dollar. A stronger Taiwan dollar makes the island's products less
competitive in the American market and helps U.S. goods sell in
Taiwan.
   The U.S. dollar gained slightly against the Taiwan dollar in the
foreign exchange market Wednesday. The Taiwan dollar traded at
28.62 per U.S. dollar, compared with the 28.61 rate maintained for
the past 14 days.
   The Taiwan dollar has appreciated 39 percent since January 1986,
largely under U.S. pressure.
</TEXT>
