<HEAD>Bell & Howell Shareholders Approve Buyout by Bass, Management</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Bell & Howell Co. have
voted to approve a $702 million buyout led by Texas financier
Robert M. Bass and members of Bell & Howell's management.
   The approval cleared the way for the information services
company to become a subsidiary of Bell & Howell Group Inc., which
was formed by an affiliate of Robert M. Bass Group Inc., Acadia
Partners L.P. of Fort Worth, Texas, and certain Bell & Howell
executives.
   The executives include Gerald E. Schultz, Bell & Howell's
chairman and chief executive officer.
   Under the buyout, shareholders will receive $64 a share for
their common and preferred stock, Bell & Howell said in a statement
Tuesday.
   Financing arrangements for the deal were consummated shortly
after the shareholder approval, the company said.
   The financing includes $200 in senior subordinated debt, of
which Acadia Partners is buying $30 million; $344 million in bank
financing; $100 million equity participation in the form of cash
and Bell & Howell stock; and $58 million of Bell & Howell's cash on
hand.
   Schultz said Bell & Howell would concentrate on its core
international businesses of mail handling systems, microfilm
products and services, textbook publishing and private database
publishing.
   ``Bell & Howell's new investors and existing management are
committed to moving forward and providing unique and challenging
opportunities for its employees and customers,'' he said.
   Bell & Howell is based in Skokie, Ill., a suburb of Chicago.
</TEXT>
