<HEAD>GE, Carbide Combine Silicone Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. and General Electric
Co. have announced an agreement to form a new joint venture
company, GE-Carbide Silicones, combining their worldwide silicone
businesses.
   The two business currently have combined annual sales of about
$750 million, the companies said in a joint statement Wednesday.
   ``This new company will bring together two complementary
silicone business, building on strengths of both and expanding
their capability to serve diverse global markets,'' Gen H. Hiner,
senior vice president at General Electric Plastics, and H. William
Lichtenberger, president of Carbide's Chemicals and Plastics
Business Group, said in a joint statement.
   ``The combined businesses will not only be able to offer a wide
variety of products, but will be positioned to compete more
effectively and to rapidly increase worldwide market for
silicones,'' they said.
   The deal is expected to be completed in the third quarter of
this year, subject to required goverment review and final approval
by both companies.
   Philip M. Gross, currently vice president and general manager of
GE Silicones, has been designated president of the new company,
which will be based in Waterford, N.Y.
   Carbide is a recognized leader in organofunctional silicones,
specialty fluids and surfactant copolymers. GE Silicones leads in
heat-cured rubber, RTV elastomers and resin systems.
