drop in the trade deficit reported Tuesday by the Commerce
Department. Although the $9.7 shortfall for March was the lowest
monthly level in three years, the shrinkage was regarded on Wall
Street as further evidence of a resurgent economy.
   ``You're seeing a market that is a little confused,'' said Hank
Striefler, senior vice president on the trading floor at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``People are interpreting good news
as bad news.''
   Many investment professionals said the stock market was strongly
influenced by rising interest rates in the bond market, a sensitive
barometer of inflation and the economy.
   The key 30-year Treasury bond was yielding 9.22 percent by
midmorning, its highest level of the year. To many investors, that
makes bonds more attractive than stocks.
