<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rainy Forecasts Pressure Grain, Soybean Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade with soybeans leading the way as
meteorologists predicted rain in most crop-growing areas.
   Showers were developing over the central Great Plains this
morning and were expected to move slowly eastward, bringing badly
needed moisture to most of the Midwest by this weekend.
   The prospects of precipitation pressured the soybean and grain
markets from the opening bell. Soybean prices have soared in recent
weeks due to a lack of moisture, which is needed to get newly
planted seeds to sprout.
   Soybean prices held above Tuesday's lows in early trading, which
could encourage some buying, said Joel Karlin, an analyst in
Chicago with Research Department Inc.
   ``But I look for the market to be on the defensive for most of
the day,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.16} a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 3 cents lower with May at $2.06} a bushel; oats were \ cent to
1\ cents lower with May at $1.60 a bushel; soybeans were 5\ cents
to 7{ cents lower with May at $7.43 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .45 cent higher with June at 73.62
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .27 cent higher with
May at 81.12 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to .40 cent
higher with June at 52.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.12 cent to .18 cent lower with May at 53.65 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
