<1ST_LINE>u f PM-HousingStarts 2ndLd-Writethru   05-18 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Starts, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Straight Gain After Earlier Slump</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Removes extraneous words in last graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction edged up 0.5 percent in
April, the third monthly gain in a row after a sharp slump at the
end of last year, the government said today.
   The Commerce Department said the increase pushed construction
activity to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.56 million units.
   But all of the strength came in apartment construction, which
often has wide month-to-month swings. Construction of single-family
homes, a closely watched category, posted a decline, which analysts
blamed on rising interest rates.
   ``In the single-family, it's a little bit discouraging to see
starts fall off like that, but at the same time we've started to
see interest rates drift up,'' said Thomas M. Holloway, senior
economist for the Mortgage Bankers Association of America.
   ``Our outlook is for interest rates to continue to drift up over
the year and for ... starts to continue to decline modestly,'' he
said.
   The overall increase last month followed a gain of 2.3 percent
in March and 9.9 percent in February. But housing activity was
still 4.5 percent below last year, in part because of declines in
December and January.
   Housing starts plummeted 15.8 percent in December and then fell
another 1.2 percent in January. Analysts attributed the slump to
builders' fear that the October stock market crash would dampen
home buying. Since then the economy has proved to be robust and
interest rates have emerged as the new threat to housing activity.
   Housing permits, considered a good sign of future economic
activity, fell 4.1 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 1.42 million units.
   The strength in starts last month came entirely in construction
of multi-family units, which soared 23.3 percent to 466,000 units.
That more than offset a 6.9 percent decline in single-family units,
which fell by 6.9 percent.
   It was the reverse of the usual pattern. Apartment construction
has been depressed since early 1987 because the new tax law removed
many of the benefits of investing in real estate.
   The overall increase in April was paced by a 22.4 percent rise
in the Midwest and a 5.2 percent climb in the South.
   Housing starts fell 8.9 percent in the Northeast and 13.0
percent in the West.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0335 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SoybeanPrices     05-18 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soybean Prices,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tight Reserves, Weather Could Cause Wild Fluctuations in Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soybean market is likely to fluctuate
wildly this summer in response to factors ranging from weather
conditions to the amount of U.S. soybean exports to the Soviet
Union, several economists say.
   The market already is more sensitive than usual because of tight
U.S. reserves, the economists said.
   Iowa State University extension economist Robert Wisner says
prices could drop sharply by September after reaching a peak. He
based the prediction on market performance during six previous
years with tight soybean supplies and barring a widespread drought.
   Higher spring prices during those years prompted farmers to
plant more soybeans, pushing prices down, he said. The scenario
could be repeated this year.
   The years 1973, 1977, 1978, 1979, 1982 and 1984 were marked by a
tight soybean supply, a strong price rally in the spring,
larger-than-indicated plantings and a sharp decline in prices by
Sept. 1, he said.
   ``This year, we have the tight bean supply and the spring price
rally, we could have the increased acreage, so the market pattern
could be very similar,'' Wisner said in a telephone interview with
the Omaha World-Herald from his Ames, Iowa, office.
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower Wednesday on the Chicago
Board of Trade with soybeans leading the way as meteorologists
predicted rain in most crop-growing areas.
   Concern over dry conditions in the Midwest and a
smaller-than-expected South American soybean crop are responsible
for the recent high prices, said Roger Hoskin, agricultural
economist with the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   The National Weather Service's mid-May to mid-June outlook
predicts dry conditions for most of the soybean-producing states,
including Missouri, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio.
   The U.S. soybean supply, now estimated at 1.1 billion bushels,
is expected to drop to 145 million bushels by Sept. 1, 1989. Stocks
at that level represent 7 percent of the annual use, Wisner said.
   When stocks drop below 10 percent of annual use, he said, the
market has traditionally been volatile.
   Another factor is uncertainty over soybean exports to the Soviet
Union. Since September, that country has bought 831,000 metric tons
from the United States, said Tom Bickerton, a USDA economist.
   The Soviets expect to buy about 1 million more metric tons by
Aug. 31, but, Bickerton said, ``anything is possible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
