<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Macmillan-Bass 1stLd-Writethru   05-18 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan-Bass, 1st Ld-Writethru,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Gets Buyout Proposal on Eve of Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-8 new with stock soaring, chairman's statement. Picks
up 7th graf pvs, In a filing ..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. common stock rocketed higher
today following an unsolicited $1.5 billion takeover proposal from
a group led by Texas financier Robert M. Bass.
   The chairman of publishing concern, addressing shareholders at
the company's annual meeting this morning, said Macmillan's board
had not had a chance to discuss the proposal but said the company
was not for sale.
   The $64-a-share proposal was disclosed after the stock market
had closed Tuesday. By midday today, Macmillan stock had soared $20
a share to $70.62{ on the New York Stock Exchange.
   As the shareholder's meeting convened today, Chairman Edward P.
Evans noted he had received an unsolicited inquiry about the
possible sale of the company. He said company management felt
confident about Macmillan's growth potential, and added that the
company ``is not for sale.''
   But he also said that since the offer was disclosed so recently,
Macmillan's board had not had a chance to discuss it and declined
further comment.
   Bass, who heads the Robert M. Bass Group Inc. in Fort Worth,
Texas, disclosed Tuesday that he had sent a letter to Evans in
which he proposed paying acquiring all of Macmillan's stock.
   Bass said the offer was ``intended to be consensual'' and was
conditioned upon approval by the Macmillan board of directors and
on Macmillan not issuing any additional equity securities.
   A proposal to authorize issuance of new preferred stock was on
today's meeting agenda, and the company said shareholders approved
it.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Bass
said his group owned about 2.4 million Macmillan shares, or about
9.1 percent of the company's 26.1 million common shares outstanding.
   In the letter to Evans, Bass said the $64-a-share price was
based on publicly available information and could be increased if
non-public information indicated a higher price is warranted.
   He said he hoped Evans and Macmillan senior management could be
persuaded to participate in the transaction.
   Bass said the offer also was conditioned on obtaining the
necessary financing, and said his group has about $250 million
available to purchase equity and subordinated debt of Macmillan.
   Acquisition of Macmillan would not be the Bass Group's first
venture into publishing.
   The proposal came as shareholders of Bell & Howell Co., a
publishing and information services company based in Skokie, Ill.,
approved a buyout offer valued at about $700 million from an
affiliate of the Bass group and senior management.
   Macmillan, based in New York, publishes educational textbooks
aimed at elementary through college grade levels as well as books
of general interest.
   It offers information services, such as Who's Who listings and
demographic information, and has interests in instructional
services including the Katherine Gibbs business schools and Berlitz
language training.
   For the year ended Dec. 31, Macmillan reported a profit of $70.7
million, or $2.74 a share, compared with earnings of $59.5 million,
or $2.47 a share, a year earlier.
   Annual revenue rose to $955.8 million from $817.8 million in
1986.
   For the first quarter, Macmillan reported a loss of $2.7 million
in contrast to a loss of $2.5 million a year earlier. Revenue for
the quarter rose to $182.6 million from $165.1 million a year
earlier.
   The first quarter normally is weak for Macmillan because of the
seasonality of its textbook business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
