<HEAD>London Shares Close Off 11.6 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed lower Wednesday amid trader
concern about the U.S. trade deficit.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed off
11.6 points, or 0.6 percent, at 1,777.6.
   Volume was 536.1 million shares, compared with Tuesday's 425.9
million. Dealers said two large computer-generated trading programs
involving the purchase and disposal of several stocks accounted for
about 275 million shares of the total volume.
   Several dealers said the market was concerned about the
underlying increase in U.S. imports contained in Tuesday's report
of a $9.7 billion U.S. trade deficit for March, saying that
increase in conjunction with rising exports could prove to be
inflationary.
   One dealer said the market ``looked at some trends in the
figures and saw some very disturbing exceptions.''
   The market ``isn't convinced that the worst is over...,'' said
Michael Howell, an equity strategist at Salomon Brothers
International Ltd.
