<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Hutton-Laundering     05-18 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hutton-Laundering,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Disclosures Could Bring More Money Laundering Charges Against
Hutton</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New disclosures by the Securities and Exchange
Commission could widen the scope of money laundering charges
against E.F. Hutton & Co., a major brokerage firm that was absorbed
by Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The SEC disclosed in documents it made public Tuesday that
Shearson has uncovered possible instances of money laundering at
several New York branch offices of Hutton.
   Shearson, a giant investment firm which acquired Hutton in
December 1987, pleaded guilty on Hutton's behalf Monday to three
criminal counts of money laundering and conspiracy at Hutton's
branch in Providence, R.I. Shearson was fined $1.01 million for the
offenses, which occurred between 1982 and 1984.
   Also Tuesday, the SEC granted Shearson a temporary exemption
from securities laws that would bar it from acting as an investment
adviser in Providence because of its guilty plea.
   The SEC documents, based on information supplied to the agency
early this year by Shearson, said an internal investigation
conducted by Shearson turned up possible cases of money laundering
at several Hutton retail branches in the New York City area.
   The documents did not disclose how much money may have been
laundered through the Hutton branches, the period in which it may
have occurred, or how many branches may have been involved.
   The new disclosures will not have any impact on Shearson's
continuing business operations, said a Shearson spokesman who
declined to be identified.
   According to the documents, Shearson's internal investigation
covered 24 Hutton branches in the New York metropolitan area; four
Hutton branches randomly selected in the financial districts of Los
Angeles, Dallas, Chicago and Miami; and the administrative
departments at Hutton's New York headquarters that were responsible
for the branches concerned.
   The investigation revealed evidence of money laundering, in the
form of unreported currency transactions, at some of the New York
branches prior to Shearson taking over Hutton.
   No such transactions were found in the branches outside New York
that were reviewed, the documents said.
   Cash transactions over $10,000 must be reported to the Internal
Revenue Service. In the Providence case, Hutton and two of its
former brokers were charged with helping clients hide about $1.5
million in cash from the IRS.
   One of the brokers, Brian Lareau, pleaded innocent on Tuesday.
The other broker died of cancer two years ago.
   Shearson said its outside attorneys are studying the possible
involvement of any individuals in these branches. The firm said it
will take appropriate action against any current Hutton employee
involved in violations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
