<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Media,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Corp. Reports Gain for Nine-Month Period</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News Corp. Ltd., the media conglomerate
controlled by financier Rupert Murdoch, said Wednesday that its
profit in the nine months ended March 31 rose 28.8 percent over the
same period a year earlier.
   The company, which is based in Sydney, Australia, did not
provide figures for the latest quarter.
   A statement said News Corp.'s earnings rose to 300.5 million
Australian dollars, or about $231 million, in the first three
quarters of its 1988 fiscal year. That compared with a profit of
233.3 million dollars in the 1987 period.
   Revenue rose to 4.44 billion Australian dollars, or about $3.2
billion, up 13 percent 3.92 billion Australian dollars in 1987.
   The company's primary businesses include newspaper, magazine and
book publishing, along with motion picture and television
production and distribution. It has operations in the United
States, Britain, Australia and Pacific Basin countries.
   Media Corp. attributed its gains to ``income from acquisitions
in Australia and Pacific Basin, increased profits from Australian
and United Kingdom publishing operations and foreign exchange
trading gains.''
   ``These gains were partly offset by reduced earnings in the
United States, lower dividend income and higher interest expense,''
the statement said.
   The company said its U.S. operating earnings were 8 percent
lower in the latest nine-month period, at 291.7 million Australian
dollars, or about $225 million.
   It said fiscal 1987 U.S. earnings were buoyed by two very
profitable movies releases by Twentieth Century Fox Film Corp. This
year's performance reflects the ``difficult comparisons for motion
picture operations and results for the television stations that
were below expectations,'' it said.
</TEXT>
