<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed higher Wednesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade after some meteorologists modified
their forecasts for badly needed rain in crop-growing areas.
   But most forecasters continued to predict weekend showers in the
Midwest.
   Wheat futures turned in an unusually strong performance as talk
circulated that dry weather had damaged enough of the maturing soft
red winter wheat crop to significantly affect yields, analysts said.
   ``Some people are disappointed in the yield prospects as some
dryness continues to persist during this critical growing peroid,''
said Steve Freed, an analyst in Chicago with the investment firm
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Soybean futures have been extremely sensitive to weather and
other supply factors because U.S. stockpiles are declining.
   Talk that Congress may approve a measure allowing soybean
planting on corn set-aside acreage next year prompted some
spread-type activity by traders who sold soybean contracts for
November delivery while buying contracts for near-term delivery,
Freed said.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 5} cents higher with May at
$3.23 a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1 cent higher with May at $2.09
a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2\ cents higher with May at $1.63\
a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 8\ cents higher with May at
$7.56{ a bushel.
