<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     05-18 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0451</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks stumbled badly this afternoon in active
trading, wrenching the Dow Jones average down more than 30 points
in a selloff that brokers blamed on investor fear of inflation and
rising interest rates.
   The slide accelerated when large institutional investors such as
pension funds sold stock, as yields on the key 30-year Treasury
bond flirted with the 9.3 percent level, the highest since the
October crash.
   ``Today's the first day I've seen some real institutional
liquidations,'' said William King, head trader at Nikko Securities
Co. International in New York. ``You're getting some
acknowledgement from institutional investors that there's a
problem.''
   The Dow average of 30 industrial stocks, which fell 21.22 points
Tuesday despite good economic news, was down another 36.64 points
as of 3 p.m. EDT to 1,949.77. Broader market indices also fell
sharply.
   Brokers said many investors still were reacting to the drop in
the trade deficit reported Tuesday by the Commerce Department.
Although the $9.7 billion shortfall for March was the lowest
monthly level in three years, it was regarded on Wall Street as
further evidence of a resurgent economy and therefore higher
inflation.
   ``You're seeing a market that is a little confused,'' said Hank
Striefler, senior vice president on the trading floor at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``People are interpreting good news
as bad news.''
   Many investment professionals said the stock market was strongly
influenced by rising yields in the bond market, a sensitive
barometer of inflation and the economy. Higher yields are making
bonds more attractive than stocks, especially during times of
investment uncertainty.
   Losers outnumbered gains by about 4-to-1 on the NYSE, with 1,276
down, 258 up and 408 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 188.44 million shares with an
hour of trading left, though the figure was inflated by
dividend-related trading strategies in Philadelphia Electric, down
[ to 18 on volume exceeding 64 million shares.
   MacMillan soared 17{ to 68[ following disclosure late Tuesday
that a group led by Texas financier Robert M. Bass offered to buy
the company for $64 a share.
   Other notable takeover-related stocks included Lucky Stores,
which jumped 3[ to 64\ after American Stores Inc. sweetened its
offer for the rival grocery chain to $65 a share.
   Among prominent blue-chips, IBM fell 1[ to 109, General Motors
fell 1} to 75\, Merck fell 2} to 148|, DuPont fell 3[ to 80 and
Coca-Cola fell 1\ to 35\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all listed issues was down 2.21 to
142.44. The American Stock Exchange's market-value index fell 3.70
to 292.87.
</TEXT>
