<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OilImports     05-18 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Imports,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Petroleum Imports Up 22 Percent in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. imports of crude oil rose 24.1 percent in
April from year-earlier levels while total domestic production
registered a 2.7 percent decline, a trade association reported
Wednesday.
   And, the American Petroleum Institute said, unlike previous
months, the latest domestic production figure did not include a
year-to-year increase in Alaskan output to partially offset a
decline in the lower 48 states.
   In its Monthly Statistical Report, Washington-based API said
U.S. imports of crude oil and petroleum products averaged 7.04
million 42-gallon barrels a day in April, up from 5.77 million
barrels daily in April 1987.
   Domestic crude production averaged an estimated 8.17 million
barrels a day in April, compared with 8.4 million barrels daily
last April, while deliveries of domestic refined products slipped
by 0.1 percent, it said.
   The report said demand for petroleum products in April, as
measured by domestic deliveries from primary storage, was not much
different from that of last April.
   But over the first four months of this year, it was a different
story, with deliveries increasing to 17.44 million barrels daily _
a ``surprisingly high'' 4.6 percent gain over the 1987 period, said
Gene Johnson, an API spokesman.
   ``In previous years, 1 percent or 2 percent was considered high,
so a 4.6 percent was very, very unexpected. It's a significant
increase,'' he added.
   The report said this April's inventories rose by 22 million
barrels because of higher imports and below-trend deliveries,''
although April's totals, on average, ``have historically shown
little direction during the month.''
   ``Crude oil stocks accounted for half of the increase. Gasoline
stocks held nearly steady, while distillate inventories, in a
contraseasonal move, rose slightly,'' it added.
   Distillates refer to diesel oil and heating oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880518-0352 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f WhytheSeersSay`Bah Humbug'toStrongEconomy   05-18 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Why the Seers Say `Bah, Humbug' to Strong Economy</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the U.S. trade deficit for March improved
beyond all expectations, many economists and big investors
responded with a chorus of ``Bah, humbug.''
   Funny they should pan what would seem like fabulous news. But
they've done it before and most likely they'll do it again.
   They responded that way to news of a lower jobless rate, to
increases in factory use, even to the dollar's new stability.
   It is a strange, discomfiting world in which good is bad, happy
is sad, up is down, square is round, best is worst, last is first,
strong is weak, bottom is peak, rich is poor and less is more.
   And if the sages are being spooked by the ``good'' news _ news
for which they've waited months and which they deemed necessary for
economic survival _ it's no wonder they're exaggerating ``bad''
news, of which they've found plenty.
   Late last year, for instance, the pessimists said consumers
would reduce spending, forcing the economy into recession. It
didn't happen. Then they said an inventory glut might produce
recession in 1988. But the glut disappeared.
   ``It is ironic that the pessimistic crowd see a boom just as
bloated inventories are starting to cool things off,'' said
economist Edward Yardeni of the Prudential-Bache investment firm,
who fears neither a boom nor a bust.
   Throughout, there has been wide disagreements among economists,
some of whom believed the biggest threat was from recession, others
that inflation would turn out to be the big problem.
   Whatever the interpretation, however, the conclusion has been
the same, i.e., bad news. If the economy expanded it would strain
production facilities and produce inflation. Should expansion
cease, recession would follow.
   The dramatic improvement in the nation's trade deficit _ a $4
billion reduction to $9.7 billion in March _ provides the most
vivid example of the syndrome.
   Nothing economic has been more eagerly awaited in recent months,
since a shrinkage of the deficit means U.S. goods, especially
manufactured items, are becoming more competitive abroad.
   In fact, many economists and investors made the latest trade
figures the fulcrum of their analyses. When the deficit grew in
February, the stock market plunged. Would a gain in March make the
market rise?
   It didn't happen. Once again the news, though opposite to that
of February, produced a negative reaction. Both the bond and stock
markets interpreted the news as indicative of an economy about to
overheat and produce inflation.
   ``It seems the better things get, the worse they're going to
be,'' quipped Malcolm Forbes, the publisher, who was addressing a
business luncheon group shortly after hearing the news.
   Why the mood?
   Economists themselves have been asking that question, and most
have defended their positions with data and theories that to the
layman seem thorough, reasonable and even sagacious.
   While recognizing that pessimism may be justified _ and that
inflation, high interest rates and perhaps recession lie ahead _
some economists believe there is a large psychological element
involved.
   In fact, with so many disproportions and dislocations in the
economy _ big budget and trade deficits, uncollectable Third World
loans, and the crash of the securities markets in October _ no
matter how poor or inaccurate an analysis might be, a negative
forecast stands a chance of being correct.
   There are also the awful memories of the 1970s to contend with.
Economists back then couldn't believe what was happening _ that
inflation and interest rates were not just high but in the double
digits. They cannot forget.
   And, finally, anxiety is produced by the very expansion itself.
Now in its 66th month, it has lived far beyond the usual lifespan
of expansions, and inevitably will turn down. But when? And will
inflation or recession end it?
   H. Erich Heinemann, chief economist for Ladenburg, Thalmann&
Co., a securities broker-dealer, remains optimistic, at least about
inflation. He notes that major inflation indicators rose less in
the first quarter of 1988 than in the final quarter of 1987.
   His forecast contrasts with that of most economists.
   ``We're convinced that with just a little bit of luck, the
expansion could continue into 1991 or 1992,'' he says, adding the
caveat:
   ``However, this will be a respite, not a reprieve. If Washington
cannot deal with its problems (mainly the budget deficit), we will
all have to live with the consequences.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: John Cunniff has covered business and economic
issues for The Associated Press since 1964.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
