<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MediaGeneral     05-18 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MG Says Sugarman Offers Deal for Cable TV Holdings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California investor Burt Sugarman on
Wednesday denied he had offered to end his attempt to name three
directors of Media General Inc. in exchange for control of the
firm's cable television franchises.
   Media General officials said the offer was made through
Sugarman's financial advisers.
   But Sugarman said, ``I do not make offers through advisers.
Media General knows that all my offers are made in writing to the
company.''
   Sugarman has offered to buy Media General for $70 per share, or
a total of $2 billion.
   James S. Evans, president and chief executive officer of Media
General, and J. Stewart Bryan III, vice chairman of Media General
and publisher of the Richmond News Leader and the Richmond
Times-Dispatch, said the proposal to end the proxy contest was made
Monday.
   Evans said Sugarman offered to sell the Class A common stock he
owns or controls _ about 2.8 million shares, or 10.1 percent of the
Class A stock _ ``in exchange for equity _ at a bargain-basement
price _ in our 163,000-subscriber cable systems'' in Fairfax County
and Fredericksburg.
   Evans said the offer, which was rejected, also included a
provision by which Sugarman would agree to drop his attempt to have
himself and two business associates, Harold Simmons and David
Gotterer, named Class A directors at the company's annual
stockholders' meeting Friday.
   The company has recommended re-election of three directors at
the meeting.
   Sugarman, in a release from his Beverly Hills, Calif.,
headquarters, called the Media General statement ``a desperate move
to make it appear as though we are losing the proxy contest. In my
opinion, this last-minute trick just won't work.''
   Sugarman's proposal called for him to exchange his stock
holdings for about 43 percent of a new company formed from the
cable TV operations, while other shareholders could trade their
shares, on a pro-rata basis, for the cable company's remaining
equity, Evans said in a statement.
   Media General employees who own stock in the company would not
be permitted to own stock in the cable TV company, nor would
members of the Bryan family, who control Media General through
their Class B common shares.
   Company employees own nearly 10 percent of Media General Class A
stock, and the Bryan family owns 12 percent of the Class A stock.
Bryan family members also own 70 percent of the Class B stock,
which can elect seven directors.
   ``Sugarman's proposition is that we value Fairfax Cable at $300
million, which would clearly be undervaluing that asset by 50 to
100 percent,'' Evans said. According to Evans, Sugarman's proposal
would grant him ``working control of the system and treat various
shareholders inequitably.''
   The Media General board saw the offer as ``greenmail of the most
egregious sort and quickly rejected it,'' he said.
   New York media analyst Curtis L. Alexander, who has followed the
Media General-Sugarman takeover fight, said he would not be
surprised to see Sugarman's per-share offer go up to $75 before
Friday's meeting.
   ``Why not? He knows he can pay that much and still break up the
company for a profit,'' Alexander said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
