<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Service500     05-18 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Service 500,0508</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Biggest Service Companies Had Rough Time in 1987, Fortune Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailing was one of the few bright spots last
year in the service sector of the economy, according to a new
survey released Wednesday.
   Fortune magazine, in its annual survey of the nation's 500
largest non-industrial companies, found most service companies had
a rough time in 1987. The October stock market crash brought a
slump in the brokerage business, while savings institutions
continued to suffer from a rash of bad loans and major commercial
banks continued to sustain losses on loans to developing countries.
   Total profits for the 500 biggest service companies dropped 22
percent in 1987 to $50.8 billion, Fortune said. By contrast, the
annual Fortune 500 survey of the leading industrial companies,
released last month, showed a 41 percent jump in profits, to $91
billion.
   Recent economic statistics _ such as the U.S. trade deficit for
March and factory use data for April released on Tuesday _ have
indicated a resurgence of traditional ``smokestack'' industries.
The trade figures included a jump in exports to an all-time high of
$28.97 billion, which factories have been running at full capacity
to produce.
   Service industries, on the other hand, had few successes in 1987
other than retailing, life insurance and transportation, the
Fortune survey found.
   ``Shoppers supplied most of the oomph in the service economy
last year,'' the magazine said. ``By keeping cash registers ringing
even after many economists thought they would be immobilized by the
stock market crash, consumers carried the 50 largest retailers to a
9 percent jump in total profits'' to $8.28 billion.
   Top retailers riding the crest of the consumer wave included
first-ranked Sears, Roebuck, followed by K Mart, Safeway Stores,
Kroger and Wal-Mart Stores.
   The companies in the service survey, like Fortune 500 firms,
were ranked by sales.
   American Express became the largest diversified financial
company for the first time in 1987, displacing Federal National
Mortgage Association which slipped into second place, followed by
Salomon, Aetna Life & Casualty and Merrill Lynch.
   BankAmerica, once the nation's biggest commercial bank, dropped
to third place behind Citicorp and Chase Manhattan. Chemical New
York was fourth and J.P. Morgan & Co. placed fifth.
   Savings institutions were led by Financial Corp. of America,
H.F. Ahmanson, Great Western Financial Corp., Calfed and Meritor
Financial Group.
   Among diversified service companies, Super Valu Stores was
first, followed by Fleming Cos., McKesson, Hospital Corp. of
America and Ryder System.
   Allegis, the parent of first-ranked United Airlines, was the
leading transportation company, followed by United Parcel Service
of America; Texas Air, the parent of Eastern Airlines and
Continental Airlines; CSX and AMR, the parent of American Airlines.
   The biggest utilities were GTE, Bellsouth, Nynex, Pacific Gas &
Electric and Southwestern Bell.
   Leading life insurance companies were Prudential of America,
Metropolitan Life, Equitable Life Assurance, Aetna Life and
Teachers Insurance & Annuity.
</TEXT>
