<HEAD>Dart Group Buys Half Of Small Supermarket Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. said Wednesday it acquired
half the stock of Jumbo Food Stores Inc., which operates 18
discount grocery stores in Maryland and Virginia.
   Jumbo management, however, will retain operational control of
the chain of Shoppers Food Warehouses, Dart spokesman Stanley
Rubenstein said.
   Kenneth Herman, Jumbo executive vice presient, did not return a
reporter's calls for comments Wednesday.
   Jumbo stock is privately held by the Herman family, Rubenstein
said.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   Dart has unsuccessfully tried to acquire some of the largest
retailers in the country in the past several years.
   The Landover-based company owns Trak Auto Corp., a chain of
discount auto parts stores; Crown Books Corp., a chain of discount
book stores and Dart Group Financial Corp., a financial business
which purchases bankers' acceptances.
   Dart acquisition targets have included May Department Stores in
1985, Jack Eckerd Corp. in 1985, Safeway Stores in 1986,
Supermarkets General Corp. in 1987, Dayton Hudson Corp. in 1987 and
Stop & Shop Co. this year.
   In April the Haft family, which controls Dart, said they
intended to buy up to $15 million in F.W. Woolworth Co. stock.
</TEXT>
