<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-18 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Prices Surge On Outlook For Inflation, Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures surged about $10 a troy ounce Wednesday and
helped rally the other precious metals as the markets digested new
indications of inflation and economic growth.
   In other trading, energy futures were sharply higher; grains and
soybeans advanced; stock-index futures sank; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Fears of inflation have been supporting precious metals futures
prices since the October stock market crash. Fresh indications of
economic vitality, such as Tuesday's government report of a
dramatic narrowing of the trade deficit, are viewed as especially
constructive for platinum and silver, which double as industrial
metals.
   ``The inflationary scenario is moving the precious metals higher
and the scenario of an expanding economy is moving the industrial
metals higher at a faster clip than gold,'' said Bette Raptopoulos,
metals analyst in New York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Lower Treasury bond prices _ indicating higher interest rates _
and higher prices for grain, soybean and energy futures, also
supported the metals, said Sharon Ziemian, an analyst at Citibank
in New York.
   Ms. Ziemian said fears of recession have also reawakened on the
metals markets.
   ``There's a fear that you could get a sudden push up in prices
and interest rates across the board, get a quick, sharp pop, and
then you'll get a recession,'' she said.
   Platinum settled $9.90 to $10.10 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange with the contract for delivery in July at
$563.30 a troy ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold settled $1.70 to
$2.80 higher with June at $458.10 a troy ounce; silver was 14.5
cents to 15.4 cents higher with May at $6.685 a troy ounce.
   Oil futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange in
reaction to an industry report showing an unexpected buildup last
week in inventories of distillates, including heating oil.
   The re-establishment of diplomatic relations between Paris and
Tehran also weighed on the markets as traders anticipated an
increase in exports of Iranian crude oil to France, said Nauman
Barakat, energy analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents to 33 cents
lower with June at $17.43 a barrel; heating oil was .35 cent to .71
cent lower with June at 47.07 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.26 cent to .51 cent lower with June at 52.23 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished higher Wednesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade after some meteorologists modified their
forecasts for badly needed rain in crop-growing areas.
   But most forecasters continued to predict weekend showers in the
Midwest.
   The National Weather Service, in its six-to-10 day forecast,
predicted normal precipitation in the northern half of the United
States and below-normal precipitation in the southern half from May
24 through May 28.
   Wheat futures turned in an unusually strong performance as talk
circulated that dry weather had damaged enough of the maturing soft
red winter wheat crop to significantly affect yields, analysts said.
   Soybean futures, which are extremely sensitive to weather
factors because U.S. stockpiles are declining, also finished
sharply higher.
   Wheat settled 4{ cents to 6 cents higher with May at $3.23{ a
bushel; corn was { cent to 1 cent higher with May at $2.09 a
bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2\ cents higher with May at $1.63\ a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 8 cents higher with May at $7.56{ a
bushel.
   Stock index futures followed Treasury bond futures lower in a
second consecutive day of steep losses.
   The contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 4 points lower at 251.10 on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange. On the Chicago Board of Trade, the June T-bond contract
settled 24-32 point lower at 85 18-32.
   Most cattle futures moved higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange as the futures market continued to chase strong cash
prices, which are running about 3{ cents above futures, analysts
said.
   Hog futures advanced in anticipation of a seasonal cash rally
but frozen pork-belly futures fell on expectations that a
government report due out Friday will show near-record stocks, said
Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington
Heights, Ill.
   Live cattle settled .15 cent lower to .80 cent higher with June
at 73.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .42 cent
higher with May at 81.27 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent lower to
.32 cent higher with June at 53.25 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .43 cent lower to .35 cent higher with May at 53.37
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
