<2ND_LINE>AM-GE-Carbide-Silicones,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE, Carbide Combine Silicone Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp. and General Electric
Co. on Wednesday announced a joint venture to combine their
worldwide silicone businesses.
   Philip M. Gross, currently vice president of GE Silicones, will
become president of the venture, which will be called GE-Carbide
Silicone Inc.
   The two business currently have combined annual sales of about
$750 million, the companies said in a joint statement.
   The deal is expected to be completed in the third quarter of
this year, subject to required government review and final approval
by both companies.
   GE is headquartered in Fairfield and Union Carbide is based in
Danbury. The new company will be based in Waterford, N.Y., where GE
has major manufacturing and compounding facilities.
   Gross said GE's silicone business has been second to industry
leader Dow Corning, a joint venture between Dow Chemical and
Corning Glass.
   ``We'll still be smaller but we feel we will have enough of a
larger size to be able to have more resources and more investment
in product development and new market development,'' Gross said.
``The silicone business grows by inventing new products and the
greater the size, the more products you can work on.''
</TEXT>
