<HEAD>Interest Rates Rise As Bond Prices Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates climbed higher as the value of
bonds declined Wednesday, largely because of continued fears of
inflation.
   The yield on the Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue soared to
9.29 percent, up from Tuesday's close of 9.21 percent and the
highest level since the stock market crash seven months ago. Its
price fell about } point, or $7.50 per $1,000 face amount.
   Elizabeth G. Reiners, an economist at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,
said fears of higher inflation once again dominated the markets,
following Tuesday's release of better-than-expected trade figures.
   The Commerce Department said the nation's trade gap shrank more
than $4 billion in March to $9.7 billion, the lowest monthly
deficit in three years.
   Bondholders, though, view a sharp jump in exports as a sign the
economy could overheat and generate higher inflation, which erodes
the value of fixed-income investments.
   Adding to bondholders' worries Wednesday were reports that the
Federal Reserve took between $2 billion and $3 billion out of the
system, Mrs. Reiners said.
   She said, however, it was unlikely the Fed was tightening its
credit policies. ``It just looks like it was technical,'' she said.
   The closely watched federal funds rate, the interest on
overnight loans between banks, closed at 6 percent, down from 6}
percent late Tuesday.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments fell about 1-16 point, intermediate maturities declined
from \ point to 7-16 point and long-term issues were about } point
lower, according to figures provided by the business information
concern Telerate Inc.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, lost 0.30 to 108.63. The Shearson Lehman Hutton
Daily Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, stood
at 1,137.02, down 3.55.
   Corporate bonds also declined. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 0.26
to 276.30.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds was down about } pont at 18 29-32 as of 3
p.m. EDT. The average yield rose to 8.24 percent from 8.16 percent
late Tuesday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were down 11 basis points
to 6.19 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage
point. Six-month bills were down 2 basis points at 6.53 percent and
one-year bills were up 1 basis point at 6.89 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
