<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EasternNegotiations     05-18 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Negotiations,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern, Machinists Begin Daily Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After several months of contract talks, Eastern
Airlines and its machinists union will start daily negotiations May
31 in a bid to resolve pay and work rule issues at the heart of
their bitter dispute.
   ``We've got a couple of issues that need further
clarification,'' said federal mediator Harry Bickford. ``And within
a matter of days, I'm going to be taking them out of town to attack
the core issues.''
   The parties will meet at an undisclosed location and negotiate
daily until June 12.
   Eastern has pledged to keep its highest level negotiators at the
talks in an effort to reach a deal with District 100 of the
International Association of Machinists. The union represents
12,000 mechanics and other ground workers at the Miami-based
carrier.
   Although strike talk has been pervasive on both sides, each side
issued carefully crafted statements saying they want a negotiated
deal.
   ``We're going there with the full intention, hopefully, once and
for all, putting something to bed and getting a settlement,'' said
Thomas Matthews, Eastern vice president of human resources. ``Our
goal is to see if we can get an agreement with the IAM.''
   Charles E. Bryan, president of the IAM District 100, said he
also was hopeful that an agreement could be reached, but he
cautioned, ``I've never jumped to any conclusions.''
   ``We're not trying to set the world on fire or establish any new
standards above anybody,'' Bryan said. ``We're just trying to get
what's fair and equitable in the industry.''
   Ever since Texas Air Corp. acquired Eastern, management has
battled the IAM and two other unions over concession demands,
employee treatment and even airline safety. The company recently
sued the IAM and the pilot's union for $1.5 billion, claiming the
unions were trying to drive down the price of the company so they
could buy it.
   Labor has campaigned for investigations of Eastern's safety. The
government just concluded a plane-by-plane inspection of Eastern's
fleet, and is probing Texas Air management.
   Eastern, trying to save $200 million a year, wants to cut the
top hourly pay of mechanics, but the union, citing pay raises at
USAir and Northwest is demanding raises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
