<FILEID>AP-NR-05-18-88 2200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Sasson-Judge 1stLd-Writethru f0265 05-18 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sasson-Judge, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0265,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sasson Jeans Head Charged with Threatening Judge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 3rd graf to UPDATE with Guez being
held without bail after marathon court hearing, his denial. Picks
up 4th graf pvs ``It wasn't.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents arrested the former head of the
collapsed Sasson Jeans empire Wednesday for allegedly threatening
the life of the federal bankruptcy judge handling his company's
reorganization.
   Paul Guez, the majority shareholder in Sasson Jeans Inc.,
allegedly threatened the life of U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R.
Lifland who was presiding over the Chapter 11 reorganization of the
apparel licensor in Manhattan.
   According to a criminal complaint, Guez, 43, threatened to kill
Lifland and other parties involved in the bankruptcy proceeding on
Monday ``if a result contrary to his interest were to be reached.''
   ``I did not threaten anybody. I am astonished to see I have been
accused of this,'' Guez told U.S. Magistrate Barbara A. Lee during
a marathon hearing in which prosecutors sought to have him detained
without bail and Guez sought his freedom in order to attend another
bankruptcy hearing on Thursday.
   He claimed the charges were ``part of a conspiracy'' to block
his attendance at the confirmation hearing on Sasson's
reorganization plan.
   Ms. Lee ordered Guez held overnight pending a detention hearing
scheduled to take place before the afternoon bankruptcy hearing.
   It wasn't the first time Guez has gotten into hot water over his
combative antics since taking over as his own lawyer in bankruptcy
court.
   Lifland has cited Guez twice for civil contempt and referred the
matters to the district court level.
   Guez is also under indictment for allegedly assaulting a federal
marshal over bankruptcy proceedings.
   The criminal complaint said Guez is currently ``undergoing
psychiatric evaluation concerning his fitness to stand trial'' in
the assault case.
   The complaint was based on information supplied by a
confidential informant described as a lawyer with ``a privileged
professional relationship'' with Guez.
   The complaint further stated that ``due to the tone and
demeanor'' of Guez, the informant believed he was ``fully capable
of carrying out his threat.''
   Sasson has been in bankruptcy proceedings since October 1986. On
Wednesday Lifland approved the sale of the company's name for $8
million to Stanwich Partners of Stamford, Conn.
   The Tunisian-born Guez arrived in this country in 1976 with $74
and a new style of French cut jeans. Through clever advertising he
took the market by storm and made millions by licensing the Sasson
label for watches, lingerie and luggage as well as jeans.
   But the company began to unravel due to internal feuds and
Sasson was swamped by lawsuits leading to the Chapter 11
reorganization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
